<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VEEP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHOM WILL BUSH, GORE
 PICK?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 BY KRIS MAYES 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush had just swept the Republican
primaries on Super Tuesday and was about to make the speech of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   Standing at a lectern with the network cameras rolling,
surrounded by a pack of cheering teenagers who had been invited
onstage by his daughters, Bush noticed that a fellow governor whom
he had invited to Austin to share the spotlight was being pushed
out of the camera shot.
</P>
<P>
   With the camera strobes flashing, Bush plucked Jane Hull from
the pack of teens standing at his side.
</P>
<P>
   It was at that moment that a rumor was born.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that a certain red-haired governor from Arizona
might need to begin measuring the drapes in the Naval Observatory
in Washington, home of the vice president?
</P>
<P>
   This question was born a half-second later: If Hull was on
Bush's mind as a possible vice president, what other women might
also be dancing in his calculations?
</P>
<P>
   The national nominating conven tions are still more than four
months away, but speculation about who might be the actual
candidates in the Republican and Democratic veep stakes is hot and
won't cool down until the summer conventions. LOOKING FOR SOCCER
MOMS
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans are actively push ing for a woman vice
presidential candidate because they think the party needs to
attract women voters.
</P>
<P>
   Potential female picks include New Jersey Gov. Christine Todd
Whit man, Maine Sen. Olympia Snowe, former GOP presidential
candidate Elizabeth Dole, Washington Sen. Jennifer Dunn, Texas Sen.
Kay Bai ley Hutchison, Florida Rep. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, and Hull,
who has scored points with the Bush crowd for her willingness to
defy Arizona Sen. John McCain in his home state.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of columnists have even dropped the name of Lisa Graham
Keegan, Arizona superintendent of public instruction, though she is
mentioned more often as a possible Bush Education secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Hull, for one, is pleased at the mentioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very, very flattered that my name even comes up,'' Hull
said in an interview. ``But I love being governor of Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull, who insists she is not interested in the No. 2 post and is
not considered by most observers to be a top-tier candidate,
nevertheless ex pects to play a role in Bush's selection process.
The advice she intends to offer Bush: Persuade Colin Powell to run,
and if he turns the post down, as expected, choose a woman as a
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's time, and I think it would be a good pick, a
good balance,'' Hull said. ``And you've got more and more women
rising up to seniority. You've got three or four women Republican
senators.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some political experts are less than enthusiastic about
the field of female candidates. According to Dennis Goldford, a
political scientist at Drake University, Hutchison is a redundant
choice because she is from Texas; Hull is out because she governs a
small state and is per ceived as McCain's enemy; Dole has never
held elective office and, thus, has no geographic constituency and
Dunn and Ros-Lehtinen are too new to the political scene. Snowe and
Whitman are more likely possibili ties, but they are both
abortion-rights supporters, which could give Bush heartburn among
party faithful at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   For Gore, the pickings are even slimmer if he wants a woman as
his running mate. Sen. Diane Feinstein is the most obvious choice,
an experi enced politician with the added benefit of hailing from
California. But other female candidates seem to require time to
mature politically or are from minuscule states, including Maryland
Lt. Gov. Kathleen Ken nedy Townsend and New Hampshire Gov. Jeanne
Shaheen. MCCAIN LOOK-ALIKES
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates believe their tickets to ride could be punched
by Inde pendents. For Bush, that could be accomplished by
persuading McCain to join the ticket, or Powell, who declined to
run in 1996 and who is not expected to accede this year.
</P>
<P>
   Short of that, the candidates may look for a suitable
substitute, what Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a political scientist at the
Claremont Graduate University in California, calls the search for a
``viable McCain clone.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, the best option may be one of McCain's best friends,
Ten nessee Sen. Fred Thompson, a me dia-savvy early proponent of
campaign finance reform who took the lead in investigating the cam
paign funding scandals of the Clin ton-Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are Bush, it's as close as you can get to John McCain
without having the annoyance of having John McCain on the ticket,''
Bebitch Jeffe said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Gore may be looking for a McCain-like candidate, which, ac
cording Bebitch Jeffe, could be ac complished by tapping McCain's
partner in campaign finance reform, Sen. Russell Feingold of
Wisconsin or Sen. Bob Kerry, an independent-minded Vietnam War hero
from Nebraska. BATTLEGROUND STATES
</P>
<P>
   Other potential contenders come from large battleground states,
in cluding Ohio, where Rep. John Kasich, an early GOP presidential
contender, and Sen. George Voinov ich have both been mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Concern for big swing states could divert Bush's attention north
to New York Gov. George Pataki, a Catholic Republican and
abortion-rights sup porter. Also looming on the radar screen is
Pennsylvania, where Gov. Tom Ridge resides. Ridge, socially
moderate and a Vietnam War hero, has the added benefit of being a
McCain clone, according to Gold ford.
</P>
<P>
   Gore could aid his chances in New York by tapping someone as
young and fresh to the scene as Secretary of Housing and Urban
Development Andrew Cuomo, the son of former New York Gov. Mario
Cuomo and a Catholic Italian-American. Or the vice president could
focus on New Jersey, another key state, by mending fences with his
former rival, Sen. Bill Bradley, and placing him on the ticket,
though this is viewed as highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Bush may also be looking to diver sify the ticket by choosing a
minority running mate. If that is his priority, the odds favor J.C.
Watts, an ener getic and youthful member of Con gress from Oklahoma
or Rep. Ros-Lehtinen from Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Gore may be looking at several minority candidates, including En
ergy Secretary Bill Richardson from New Mexico, former HUD
Secretary Henry Cisneros from Texas or New Jersey Rep. Robert
Menendez, who has ties to the Cuban-American community in southern
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But even those political experts who mention the possibility of
a minority candidate are skeptical. Cisneros was tinged by scandal
during his time with the Clinton administration and Richardson,
also a Latino, once offered Monica Lewinsky a job at the United
Nations and was criti cized for his handling of a security breach
at a U.S. nuclear lab in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't see it. They are pandering on this one,'' Bebitch
Jeffe said. Moreover, she added, ``in the battleground states
(Ohio, New Jer sey and Pennsylvania) the Latino vote isn't
critical.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bush would each like to force the other to pour
resources into territory they once took for granted. For Bush, this
could be accomplished by choosing a running mate from California or
a woman. For Gore, it could be accomplished by giving the nod to a
prominent politician from Florida, where Jeb Bush, the Sunshine
State's governor, is expected to lock things up for his brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``The head games may win out, and Gore may go with Senator Bob
Graham of Florida,'' Bebitch Jeffe said. COVERING THE BLEMISHES
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and Bush have glaring flaws they would like to paper
over, which could be done by choosing someone with the kind of
credentials they lack. For Bush, that may mean finding someone with
an unimpeach able record on foreign policy, such as Powell, McCain
or former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney. Or Bush could look no
further than his foreign-policy campaign adviser, Condoleeza Rice,
a Stanford Univer sity professor hired to help Bush overcome his
knowledge gap on foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Criticism of Gore's involvement in the campaign finance scandals
of 1996 may convince him of the need to tap someone with a
reputation for purity on that matter. Bradley would help, as would
Feingold. Gore may also want to choose someone with a little more
charm, such as Indiana Sen. Evan Bayh, to counterbalance his own
reputation for woodenness.
</P>
<P>
   Until the conventions, the candidates are expected to hold their
short lists close to the vest. But they also do not mind the months
of speculation about candidates that will occur between now and the
conventions, a process that rewards their friends and leaves the
impression that every swing group under the sun is impor tant to
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``What that does is let each candi date enjoy all these trial
balloons for which they have to take no responsi bility; they can
just sit back and get a sense of how that plays,'' said Goldford of
Drake University. ``Ev erybody becomes a great mentioner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
