<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNWANTED BOY BLOOMS IN THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's mid-May in the year 2019 and the smart-alecky columnist for
``The Arizona Republic'' (yeah, still me) has tracked down the
21-year-old son of Ruth Ann Burns to ask if he'll be sending his
mom flowers for Mother's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's it to you, old-timer?'' asks the young man, whose name
is Nicholas.
</P>
<P>
   It has to do with what happened in court back in 2000, he's
told.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get lost,'' Nicholas says.
</P>
<P>
   Kids these days. No respect. (I'm nearing retirement age by this
time. I'm supposed to spout off about youngsters.)
</P>
<P>
   I've been waiting for you to become a grown-up, Nicholas is
told. There are things no one could ask you back in 2000, when you
were only 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like what?''
</P>
<P>
   Like, did the court case ruin your life?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's old news.''
</P>
<P>
   Your mother sued her doctors for not diagnosing her pregnancy
sooner so she could have had an abortion. She claimed her life
would have been a lot better.
</P>
<P>
   ``That had nothing to do with me,'' Nicholas says.
</P>
<P>
   Sure it did, he's told. In Maricopa County Superior Court, your
mother's lawyer said, ``This is a major imposition.'' He meant you.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just talk for the lawsuit,'' Nicholas says. ``It wasn't
personal.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but he was speaking for your mother and father. A lot of
frustrated parents wonder if they'd have been better off without
kids. Some even say it out loud. But I don't recall anyone swearing
an oath to it in open court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 2{,'' he says. ``I don't remember any of it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's good. You should have heard some of the things people
said about your mom. The trial brought up other abortions she'd
had, her lifestyle. I took calls at the paper from people who said
her children should be taken away from her. They couldn't believe a
mother would file such a lawsuit. They were sure it would destroy
your life.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's hasn't happened.''
</P>
<P>
   What about when you were a kid? Back in 2000, people figured
you'd be scarred forever by all the teasing you'd take at school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Not at all?
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened once or twice. All kids get teased,'' Nicholas
says.
</P>
<P>
   But, your mother used you as a pawn in a sleazy money grab. Her
lawyer put an economist on the stand to say your life was worth
$143,214. Then, when the opposing lawyer asked your mother if she
was ``damaged'' by the fact you were born, she answered under oath,
``Yes.'' And she said so a week before Mother's Day 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Don't you hate her for that?
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not? I can't imagine a worse thing a parent could say about
her child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in 2000,'' Nicholas says, ``did anyone claim my mother
had abandoned me?''
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was she accused of physically abusing me?''
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did she fail to give me clothes or food, or to put a roof over
my head?''
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did she also say that, after I was born, she loved me?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, what was your original question again?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   Will you be sending your mom flowers next Sunday?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   (Hey, I'm an old man. I'm supposed to dream.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
