<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8075 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-PATTON-NYT &LR;      05-07 0398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-PATTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAROLD LLOYD PATTON, 71, NOTED FOR HIS COLLECTION OF BOOKS BY BLACK
AUTHORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC COPAGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harold Lloyd Patton, a stage manager for Ray Charles who is said
to have amassed one of the largest private collections of black
literature in the United States, died April 19 at a hospital in
Burbank, Calif. He was 71.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, said his wife, Emily.
</P>
<P>
   Patton assembled an archive of more than 20,000 rare books and
first-edition volumes by African-American authors like James
Baldwin, Zora Neale Hurston, Jean Toomer and Langston Hughes. An
important aspect of the collection was its representation of
unknown authors, said Leon F. Litwack, the Pulitzer Prize winning
historian and author of books about the black experience in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not limited to the recognizable names in
African-American literature,'' said Litwack, who was Patton's high
school classmate. ``His decision to buy extensively from vanity
presses indicated his belief that these authors deserved to be
recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   James Fugate, an owner of Eso Wan Books in Los Angeles, which
specializes in books by black authors, said, ``If we had a notable
author who was in town for a signing, Harold would stay until
everyone else had left, just to have a discussion with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Patton would have the author sign his or her book, then
autograph a scrapbook he had titled ``Authors I Have Known,'' which
included the signatures of James Baldwin, Alice Walker, Ossie Davis
and more than 200 others.
</P>
<P>
   Patton was born in San Bernardino, Calif., and attended a
community college in Ventura, Calif. His father, Dave L. Patton,
who owned a general store and was politically active, encouraged
his devotion to books and collecting.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1960s, Patton was stirred by the growing black
consciousness movement, and began collecting contemporary authors.
The 16 years he spent traveling the world with Ray Charles enabled
him to track down rare editions.
</P>
<P>
   In time, Patton expanded his property in Studio City to house
his collection.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Patton is survived by seven children,
13 grandchildren and 10 great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Patton said his family would try to establish a nonprofit entity
to keep the collection intact and maintain it as a research
resource for scholars and the public. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
