<HEADLINE>
CEDENO HAPPY BUT STRUGGLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ No boos, no cheers. Roger Cedeno is just another
visiting player.
</P>
<P>
   He once was the Los Angeles Dodgers' top prospect, but after two
years and two trades, Cedeno is the starting center fielder for the
Houston Astros.
</P>
<P>
   After eight years in the Dodgers organization, Cedeno had a
breakout season for the New York Mets in 1999, batting .314 with 90
runs and 66 stolen bases. Last season, Cedeno was critical of the
Dodgers organization for its unreasonable expectations, but now he
says that all seems long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I've been traded again, and I look at it as one of the
things you can't control,'' Cedeno said. ``I enjoyed New York,
enjoyed the chance to play every day and not worry when I didn't
get a hit. But coming here has been great. We have a great team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros won the NL Central the past three years but are
struggling this season. Cedeno, who was acquired with Saturday's
starter, Octavio Dotel, for 20-game winner Mike Hampton, also has
gotten off to a slow start. He entered Saturday's game batting
.202, although he does lead the league with 10 stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Cedeno's success last year was credited to nurturing by
Mets manager Bobby Valentine and coach Mookie Wilson. Valentine
refused to play Cedeno in center because of problems with the
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said he hoped Cedeno would be his center fielder.
Astros manager Larry Dierker said Cedeno is still struggling
defensively, and it showed in the third inning when he misplayed
Mark Grudzielanek's catchable fly ball into an RBI ground-rule
double.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't always been good,'' said Dierker, who is batting
Cedeno second behind Craig Biggio. ``Maybe adequate. But he can
cover a lot of ground, and we expect him to improve. It's the same
with his hitting. He's gotten off to a slow start, but we project
him as a .280 hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Lasorda: Former manager Tom Lasorda met Saturday with
heads of the U.S. Olympic baseball program, a day after being named
to coach the team at the Summer Games in Sydney, Australia. The
team is run by former Yankees and Astros general manager Bob Watson
and ex-Angels GM Bill Bavasi.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, professional players will be used, although
major-leaguers will not participate because the Olympics will be
during the final two weeks of September.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers Triple-A outfielder Shawn Gilbert, who has 36 games of
big-league experience, was a member of last year's U.S. team at the
Pan Am games.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers GM Kevin Malone said he is not opposed to sending
players who might be involved in minor-league playoffs, but manager
Davey Johnson is a little skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a great experience for any player,'' he said.
``But what happens if someone gets injured and you need him?''
</P>
<P>
   Quick hits: Results of an MRI on the elbow of reliever Mike
Fetters were negative, and he could be back by Monday in Arizona.
Fetters has not pitched since Wednesday, when he experienced
inflammation in his elbow. ... Astros right fielder Richard Hidalgo
robbed Shawn Green of a home run in the second inning. He also was
hit by a pitch in the same inning after Ken Caminiti hit a home
run. Hidalgo tied a major-league record April 19 when he was hit
three times by Orel Hershiser. On the way to first, Hidalgo
exchanged words with Dodgers starter Darren Dreifort, who hit him
with an 0-2 fastball on the left forearm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
