<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-A'S-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS STAGE ANOTHER COMEBACK TO BEAT A'S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ After coming back from an eight-run deficit
on Friday, the five-run hole in the third inning last night looked
like nothing. Neither did the two-run one in the seventh. Or the
one-run in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers overcame them all, the final one on Luis Alicea's
one-out single off T.J. Mathews in the ninth to drive in Jason
McDonald, to defeat the Oakland Athletics, 11-10, at The Ballpark
in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game \RFriday\S night translated into confidence, and it
carried over into tonight,'' Rangers shortstop Royce Clayton said.
``Hopefully they won't all be like this, but it's good to know the
team's capable of putting together runs late in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The winning run scored when Alicea hit a sharp grounder into
right field, foiling A's manager Art Howe's strategy of playing an
extra infielder.
</P>
<P>
   With runners at first and third and one out and Alicea batting
left-handed against Mathews, Howe brought right fielder Jeremy
Giambi in to play between first baseman Jason Giambi and second
baseman Frank Menechino in a drawn-in infield.
</P>
<P>
   Alicea's grounder, though, got between the two Giambis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fortunate,'' Alicea said. ``That's not what I wanted to
do. I wanted to get the ball up in the air. But he was keeping the
ball down and fortunately enough, it got through a hole.''
</P>
<P>
   The game ended much like the one on Friday did. The Rangers
players streamed out of the dugout to first congratulate the player
who scored the winning run _ Ivan Rodriguez on Friday, McDonald
last night _ and then went to first base to maul the player who
drove it in _ Mike Lamb on Friday, Alicea last night.
</P>
<P>
   The games differed in how the Rangers got to that point,
however.
</P>
<P>
   The comeback on Friday was amazing in its magnitude. The one
last night was incredible because it actually was a series of
comebacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now there's a feeling that they're never out of it, and
they keep battling,'' manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Battle No. 1 came after the A's got to Rangers starter Kenny
Rogers early, forging a 6-1 lead after the top of the third.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers erased that with McDonald's homer in the bottom of
the third and an opportunistic three-run fourth built on a hit, an
error and four walks.
</P>
<P>
   Battle No. 2 came after the A's went ahead on Jason Giambi's
two-run homer in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers overcame that with three runs in the eighth. Lamb
started it with a leadoff single off reliever Jeff Tam, forcing
Howe to summon closer Jason Isringhausen into the game to attempt a
two-inning save.
</P>
<P>
   Isringhausen almost got out of the inning with the lead, but
David Segui lined a two-out, bases-loaded single past a diving
Menechino to give the Rangers a one-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers then gave the ball to closer John Wetteland, who had
a chance to grab a piece of baseball history. He was three outs
away from becoming the 12th reliever to save 300 games.
</P>
<P>
   The three outs didn't come, however, until the A's had scored
twice.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Giambi followed Miguel Tejada's leadoff single with a
mammoth, 421-foot homer to center field, and the A's led again,
10-9.
</P>
<P>
   For the Rangers these days, though, a one-run deficit is
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to get known as a team that's not going to give
up,'' McDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Curtis got the inning started with a single, and after Lamb
struck out he went to third on a single by McDonald. Clayton
followed with a bouncer to third that Eric Chavez threw away.
Curtis scored and McDonald went to third.
</P>
<P>
   Alicea then singled to cap another comeback.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
