<HEADER>
A8099 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-OFFENSE-T     05-07 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-OFFENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS PLAN TO SPREAD THEIR WINGS _ AND DEFENSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Cowboys receivers coach Wes Chandler played in
this offense under Don Coryell at San Diego in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Although the offense has evolved, and is still evolving, the
Cowboys are resuscitating the basic principles that helped win
three Super Bowls in the 1990s. After two seasons of Chan Gailey,
the Cowboys are returning to a system with roots stemming to Air
Coryell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just tweaked it,'' said Chandler, who played for the
high-powered Chargers of the '70s, with its multiple weapons of
Charlie Joiner, John Jefferson and Chandler at wide receiver,
Kellen Winslow at tight end and Dan Fouts at quarterback. All but
Jefferson and Chandler are in the Pro Football Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty of this offense is that you never know where the
ball is going to go,'' Chandler said. ``In fact, every eligible
receiver on the field is considered `alive' on every route. There's
no lax period. This is exciting for a receiver, because there's a
chance that the ball is coming to him on every play.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones has put a lot of faith in new
offensive coordinator Jack Reilly who, with the help of Ernie
Zampese in a consulting role, will add a few wrinkles and dust off
a few more aspects of the pre-Gailey offense, run by Norv Turner
(1991-93) under Jimmy Johnson and by Zampese (1994-97) under Barry
Switzer. Reilly previously served as Cowboys quarterbacks coach in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack is real imaginative, a good communicator, and, while he's
well-schooled in this offense, he doesn't limit himself to
\Rcopying\S one philosophy,'' Jones said. ``You can be sure that
Jack will put his own stamp on this offense. For one thing, he
understands that an offense is really a product of your
personnel.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Reilly pointed out when asked how all the pieces will fit,
``No matter what different personnel groups we use, we must be able
to run and pass out of all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, all five \Religible receivers\S on the field, in some
way, should be involved in the passing game,'' Reilly said. ``It's
similar to basketball strategy. You have five different guys who
can do five different things out there. Each is a role player.''
</P>
<P>
   But this won't be Air Reilly. The Cowboys still have Emmitt
Smith, who is on track to break the NFL career rushing record in
2002, if not sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to always have Emmitt in there, or else Chris
\RWarren\S ... that's a key to this offense,'' Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly expects Smith's presence will force opposing defenses to
keep a minimum of two linebackers on the field, even when the
Cowboys go with their three- or four-receiver sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emmitt will be involved more in the passing game this year,''
Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   No one is more pleased than Smith. He felt too one-dimensional
in Gailey's offense, catching only 27 passes each of the past two
seasons. During the Cowboys' Super Bowl years (1992-93, 95), Smith
caught 59, 57 and 62 passes. Those Turner/Zampese offenses provide
much of the blueprint for what Reilly is bringing back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I was utilized to my potential the last two
years,'' Smith said. ``Even when Chris was in there on third down
the last two years, he wasn't thrown the ball very often.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren had 13 (in nine games) and 34 catches in Gailey's offense
the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Smith saw this as a license for opposing defenses to play
eight-man fronts on first and second downs, and to load up
secondaries on third down.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly has tried to find concepts being used in Washington and
St. Louis that may best fit his personnel in Dallas. The biggest
misconception about the return of Reilly and Zampese to the Cowboys
is that they are here to clone what was done in their first tour of
duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different from what we used to do, and it's not different
from what Norv \RTurner\S is doing in Washington or what Mike Martz
is doing in St. Louis,'' quarterback Troy Aikman said. ``The system
has evolved quite a bit since we last ran it. Those \RRedskins and
Rams\S teams have had tremendous success offensively over the past
couple of years, and we hope to duplicate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zampese said that because of Smith, the Cowboys more closely
resemble the Redskins with 1999 NFC rushing leader Stephen Davis, a
``downhill-style runner'' much like Smith, than they do the Rams
with Marshall Faulk, whose forte is getting the ball in ``space.''
Then again, the speed of Joey Galloway, Rocket Ismail, et al., make
the Cowboys' passing attack similar to the Rams'.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very good offense for Troy,'' Zampese said. ``He's
so accurate. Plus, he's the most mechanically sound quarterback in
football.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense has the Cowboys already thinking about September ...
in May.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
