<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-UCLA-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA TOP USC AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The UCLA-USC men's dual meet was typically
untypical.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins upset USC, 88-75, to win their 22nd consecutive meet
over the Trojans before 5,463 at UCLA's Drake Stadium on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA defeated USC in the women's competition, 86-68, to win for
the eighth consecutive year paced by Seilala Sua's victories in the
javelin, shot put and discus.
</P>
<P>
   After losing by a point last season in the closest score in the
67-meet history, the USC men were heavily favored to knock off the
Bruins for the first time since 1977.
</P>
<P>
   The form chart for both squads, however, went awry.
</P>
<P>
   No event proved more pivotal than a 1-2 finish by Damian Allen
and Bryan Harrison in the 200 meters with UCLA behind 71-60 with
four events left.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, a senior who had been battling knee injuries for the past
two seasons, won in 20.97 in his first 200 of the season with
Harrison in second in 20.98.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first career victory in the crosstown rivalry for
Allen, a former cornerback on the football team competing in his
last home meet.
</P>
<P>
   USC was projected to pick up big points from Andre Ammons and
Sultan McCullough, a decisive winner over Allen in the 100 in
10.25. McCullough, however, pulled up with a groin strain at the
top of the curve, and Ammons finished third in 21.01.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like I have not really been happy in a race for two
years ,'' Allen said. ``Just to be healthy is a wonderful feeling.
To come out with a victory to keep the streak alive, I am elated. I
can stand here with scores written on paper and say how great their
team is but you show up to run on the day of the track meet.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1-3 finish by Scott Moser and Scott Wiegand in the discus to
put the Bruins to within 75-74. UCLA clinched the meet in the 5,000
meters with a 1-2-3 sweep by Paul Muite, Dan Brecht and Bryan Green
for an 83-75 advantage heading into the final event, the
1,600-meter relay.
</P>
<P>
   Amid rhythmic clapping from a large group of teammates on the
homestretch, Muite, Brecht and Green pulled away from USC's Bryan
Livingston with three laps to go. Muite raised both arms as he
crossed the finish and into a waiting mob of teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole team was the hero,'' said Muite, a junior from North
Hollywood High who also finished second in the 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sprinters got it done we just went out and did what we had
to do. It is great to have great times on paper but when it comes
down to it. Heart and team effort is what wins this kind of
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's prospects did not appear promising when Malachi Davis,
the Bruins' top 400-meter runner, strained a hamstring in the 400
relay, the meet's first running event, and 1-2-3 USC sweeps in the
hammer, triple jump and 110 high hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA coach Art Venegas had already tabbed his team as a 15-point
underdog prior to Davis' injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we were going to give them a battle,'' Venegas said.
``But could we win it? Every way I looked I did not see how. We
needed a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins received a break in the pole vault when Dennis
Kholev, the USC school-record holder and Pacific-10 leader at 18-3,
no heighted to pave the way for a 1-2 finish by Brian McLaughlin
(17-3) and Jared Drake (16-8).
</P>
<P>
   In the women's meet, UCLA's Sua and Tolson set meet records in
the discus (208-4) and hammer (206-2), respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Darnesha Griffith and Quartz Hill graduate Michelle Perry were
other notable Bruins winners with personal-best efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith, the niece of Jackie Joyner-Kersee and the late
Florence Griffth-Joyner, won the high jump at 6-0 for the
fourth-best mark in school history. Perry edged USC's Natasha
Danvers to win the 100 high hurdles. Both were credited with
identical times of 13.20.
</P>
<P>
   USC sophomore Angela Willians, the defending NCAA 100 champion,
turned back UCLA's Shakedia Jones, the 1998 World Junior 100
champion, to win the 100 (11.1) and 200 (23.32).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
