<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS MUST COPE WITH SHAQ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Luc Longley is no Vlade Divac. Clifford Robinson
is a former All-Star, but certainly no Chris Webber. But could the
Phoenix Suns take a cue from the Sacramento Kings on how to
illegally double-team, er, defend Shaquille O'Neal?
</P>
<P>
   Considering Longley was abused by O'Neal all season, giving up
33.3 points a game, and considering the Kings' strategy managed to
thoroughly fluster O'Neal for two games, and a pair of wins, it
wouldn't be surprising if the Suns at least tried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're going to be able to do it, because I
don't think they have the bodies,'' the Los Angeles Lakers' Glen
Rice said. ``Their size really doesn't compare to the size that the
Kings had. And if we move the ball around the way we know we're
capable of doing, it's going to be pretty easy to get it inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Harper said the Lakers learned a bit in the Kings series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq needs to use his size and move around some,'' he said.
``So we know that we just can't tell Shaq to sit there on that same
damn side he likes to be sitting on. He has to move around more.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings also had athletic, 6-foot-11 Scot Pollard behind
Divac. The Suns have rotund Oliver Miller. Robinson, meanwhile,
lacks Webber's strength. Phoenix might just decide to use all of
its fouls, with Miller, Longley and ex-Laker Corie Blount taking
turns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They found some defensive resolve against San Antonio; they
fronted the post,'' Lakers coach Phil Jackson said. ``They did some
things against David Robinson I think they might feel is effective
against us. And they help very well. They have good team defensive
help, so we have to honor that fact. But they have yet to really
figure out how to cope with Shaq.''
</P>
<P>
   Denied: It was subtle, but there was at least a hint of
disappointment among the Lakers that they didn't get a shot at the
Spurs, who the Suns defeated in four games. San Antonio swept the
Lakers out of the playoffs a year ago and was the only team to beat
them three times this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers would have liked another shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, because it would have been a nice challenge,'' Kobe
Bryant said. ``It would have been a nice payback to beat the
champions. But Phoenix is here, they deserve it, they beat the
world champs, so we have to try to take it out on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Second best: When the Suns acquired Penny Hardaway last summer
and paired him with Jason Kidd, they marketed the pair as
``Backcourt 2000'' and started comparing them to the all-time great
guard tandems, including Jerry West and Gail Goodrich.
</P>
<P>
   Harper said Kidd and Hardaway aren't even the best tandem of the
present.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His choice? New York's Latrell Sprewell and Allan Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can make a good case for that, I think,'' Harper said.
``Those two guys can shoot the ball. Those two guys have the ball
all the time. I mean, they've got two good guys on that team, the
Suns do. Yes, they may have two great All-Stars, as y'all say, but
when they step on that floor, they're going to have the same kind
of shoes that my shoes are going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's opinion of Kidd-Hardaway as tops in the league: ``On
paper, it could be.''
</P>
<P>
   No time to be tired: The Lakers had just one day to recover from
their grueling five-game series against the Kings, but Bryant said
fatigue won't be a factor in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's playoff basketball,'' he said. ``We fought all year long
to have homecourt advantage, and we're not going to let it slip
away because of tired legs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
