<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MAGIC LEFT BETWEEN SHAQ, PENNY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Theirs was an arranged marriage that everybody was
certain would go on happily ever after, as all fairy-tale unions
naturally do.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal and Penny Hardaway, two very different
personalities bonded by a similar goal, were brought together by
the Orlando Magic in the early 1990s 'til retirement do them part.
</P>
<P>
   The union started out rocky, with Orlando fans booing Hardaway
when the Magic traded the rights to Chris Webber for Hardaway in
the 1993 NBA draft. But O'Neal, whom Orlando had drafted the
previous year, warmly embraced the 6-foot-7 point guard.
</P>
<P>
   And together, the two players quickly set about building a
legacy that would last.
</P>
<P>
   They were going to be the next Kareem Abdul-Jabbar and Magic
Johnson. Largely because of Hardaway and O'Neal, Orlando looked
like the rightful heir to the dynastic Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   The first ripe fruit of their union was a runner-up finish to
Houston in the 1995 NBA Finals. To everybody's surprise, it also
would be their last.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1996 season, O'Neal left the Magic in a lurch to take
up with the closest thing the NBA has to a trophy team.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the glittery, glamorous, coquettish Lakers, who
threw $120 million at O'Neal's feet in lieu of a lace handkerchief
and watched the 7-feet-1 center bolt across country, leaving behind
Hardaway, who felt helpless and betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers brokered the union of O'Neal and Kobe Bryant, the
latter a younger, more dashing version of Hardaway, and that became
the NBA's hot, high-profile ``It'' pairing; the Jennifer
Aniston/Brad Pitt of pro basketball, if you will.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway, the Gwyneth Paltrow character in this triangle that
Tex Winter wouldn't touch, much less teach, fell on hard times. He
underwent two separate surgeries on his left knee and weathered a
couple of seasons of discontent in Orlando before he was sent to
Phoenix in a sign-and-trade deal last August.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix just happens to be the Lakers' second-round opponent in
the playoffs. So O'Neal is going to have to confront his past in
order to move forward, starting with Game 1 today at the Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   This, the Big Guy said, is no big deal.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal claims to be cordial with Hardaway. He talked with his
former teammate last summer when Hardaway was trolling the
free-agent waters. Hardaway subsequently dined with Lakers
executive vice president Jerry West, but the Lakers didn't have the
cash to be a serious contender for his services.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never a feud between me and Penny,'' O'Neal said.
``I went my way. Penny went his. We're still good friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but don't look for O'Neal to make like Magic and kiss
Hardaway at midcourt before today's opening tip. About the only
thing they really share these days besides a history is a hint of
regret.
</P>
<P>
   They now know that in basketball, same as in life, the rarest
relationships sometimes are recognized as such only in retrospect.
</P>
<P>
   If O'Neal has played like a man possessed this season, it's
because he knows his union with Bryant can't be counted on to last
forever (or even five years). Stuff happens.
</P>
<P>
   The sense of urgency O'Neal feels to win an NBA title now is the
surest sign that he has not only grown older, but wiser.
</P>
<P>
   Laker reserve Brian Shaw, who played with O'Neal and Hardaway in
Orlando, said, ``I think they both missed playing with each other
once they weren't on the same team. It's one of those things that
you take for granted. They probably did think they were going to be
together for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   After practice on Saturday, O'Neal admitted, ``At first, I had
regrets.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged the obvious; that the Magic, with O'Neal and
Hardaway as fixtures, ``could have been something really special.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's as far as O'Neal will follow that story line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in ifs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brooding is not in O'Neal's nature. He lives in the here and
now, not in the ifs and buts. The eighth-year veteran loves being
not just the NBA's best center but the center of attention.
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old is a human welcome mat, inviting everyone to
join him in the mother of all parties that is life.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway, also 28, is more introverted. In temperament as well
as in talent, he is very similar to Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   He is a screen door that swings open to only a precious few. So
you can see how O'Neal's ``strictly business'' decision to dump
Orlando for L.A. could have been processed differently by Hardaway.
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing four years have helped frame for O'Neal the bigger
picture of his ``strictly business'' decision. His perspective has
broadened so he can see the ripple effect it had on others and on
the league, in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only bad thing about professional basketball,'' O'Neal
said Saturday, ``is the business side. We're all
mini-conglomerates.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers loom over their competition like Microsoft. If the
scrappy Suns are going to topple the giant, Hardaway is going to
have to be a huge help. Indeed, to the victor of the mini-war
between Hardaway and Bryant will go the games' tone and tempo.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, 21, studied Hardaway long before he knew O'Neal. When he
was in high school in Philadelphia, Bryant attended a couple of
Orlando games with his father Joe. He was so impressed by
Hardaway's skills, he bet on the Magic to beat Houston in the 1995
NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets swept Orlando, costing Bryant $10.
</P>
<P>
   Starting today, you can bet there's a lot more at stake for both
Bryant and O'Neal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-00 0249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
