r s BC-BB0-BASEBALL-REPORT-T     05-07 2760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB0-BASEBALL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL HAS DONE PEDRO WRONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez is a special pitcher precisely because he knows
how to pitch. The Red Sox ace augments his impressive physical
talent with a remarkable knowledge of his craft.
</P>
<P>
   He knows how to change speeds, how to set up hitters, how to mix
his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   If a batter has success against him, he's smart enough to figure
out why and talented enough to do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   Usually it's simply a matter of changing his pitching pattern.
If a hitter is sitting on a fastball, he'll throw a changeup.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Indians catcher Einar Diaz, he took more drastic
measures.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz had doubled in his first two at-bats against Martinez in a
game last Sunday. Both hits came on changeups on the outer part of
the plate that Diaz was able to hit with authority by doing what
batters typically do these days, leaning over the plate as eagerly
as a teen-ager after loading up at the CiCi's buffet.
</P>
<P>
   When Diaz next came up, Martinez did what pitchers used to do
with regularity. He busted him up and in with a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was diving out and got me twice on the outside,'' Martinez
said. ``I had to try something different.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball historians tell us this used to be called a brushback
or a knockdown pitch. It was an accepted part of the game, a weapon
in a pitcher's arsenal to keep the batter from getting too
comfortable or taking liberties at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The intent isn't to inflict pain; Martinez didn't hit Diaz. The
purpose is to keep the hitter from leaning over the plate to look
for the outside pitch, to send a message, and, yes, to intimidate.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, any pitch remotely close to a batter is seen as
an act of war. The benches cleared in a game Thursday between the
Mets and Giants when Mets reliever Dennis Cook hit Marvin Benard
with an 0-1 sinker. To load the bases. In the eighth inning. Of a
tie game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like it's getting to the point that every time you
pitch someone in, it's like you're testing their manhood,'' Cook
said.
</P>
<P>
   When Martinez knocked down Diaz, the Indians, typically,
overreacted.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland starter Charles Nagy responded by throwing at Jose
Offerman in the eighth inning, hitting him in the hip.
</P>
<P>
   Retaliation also used to be an accepted part of the game, and to
a certain extent _ benches-clearing incidents notwithstanding _ it
still is.
</P>
<P>
   But what was Nagy retaliating for? Martinez throwing a brushback
pitch? Ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   The benches cleared, naturally, although no punches were thrown.
</P>
<P>
   Now Martinez had to do some retaliating of his own. He hit the
first batter in the bottom of the inning, Robbie Alomar. Again, the
benches cleared.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez and Red Sox manager Jimy Williams were ejected because
warnings were issued after Nagy hit Offerman. Three days later,
discipline czar Frank Robinson suspended Martinez for five days, a
punishment that's on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension is understandable, given the warning as well as
Robinson's goal of doing what he can to put a stop to the silly
practice of milling around on the field at the slightest
provocation.
</P>
<P>
   It's also misguided, because Robinson got the wrong guy.
</P>
<P>
   The way to exact revenge on a pitcher who knocks a batter off
the plate is to get a hit, preferably one that clears the fences.
The Indians have trouble doing that against Martinez, though. He's
7-0 in his career against them, including the playoffs, and hasn't
allowed them to score in 20 innings.
</P>
<P>
   So instead, Nagy blatantly threw at Offerman.
</P>
<P>
   Nagy, who was fined but not suspended, escalated the incident.
He's the one who was out of bounds, and should be sitting for five
games.
48 wide, 36 vince has picture on dye Spotlight
Ed Zurga A healthy cut, after a siege of injuries, helps explain
why Kansas City outfielder Jermaine Dye is putting up big numbers.
With enchanted April, Dye cast as star, not fluke
</P>
<P>
   A short list of candidates to become the first player ever to
hit double figures in home runs and doubles before May 1 likely
would include the likes of Barry Bonds, Ken Griffey Jr., Alex
Rodriguez and Vladimir Guerrero. Chances are, it wouldn't have
included Jermaine Dye.
</P>
<P>
   Dye had a nice season in '99, when he hit .294 with 44 doubles,
27 homers and 119 runs batted in. But there was the suspicion that
the Royals outfielder might have enjoyed his career year. After
all, there was nothing in his career to hint at such a season.
</P>
<P>
   But now, his '99 numbers look like a breakthrough season rather
than being a fluke or a career year.
</P>
<P>
   Dye did become the first player in major-league history to hit
double figures in homers (11) and doubles (12) in April. He went
into May leading the American League in homers, doubles, total
bases (83), slugging percentage (.847) and extra-base hits (23).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just confidence,'' Dye said. ``I played pretty good in
the minor leagues coming up. I always knew I could play this
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Dye didn't play that well in the minors. He was
drafted by the Braves in the 17th round of the 1993 amateur draft
and batted .347 in the Gulf Coast League, but after that never
topped .300 or hit more than 15 homers.
</P>
<P>
   He was traded to the Royals for Michael Tucker before the '97
season, and while Tucker contributed to a couple of NL East
champions in Atlanta, Dye spent most of his time on the sidelines
nursing various injuries. He played in just 135 games in two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ate him up inside,'' Royals general manager Herk Robinson
said. ``He even got to the point where he had freak \Rinjuries\S,
hurting his knee getting out of a car at a Wal-Mart parking lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Dye finally was healthy last year, and showed what he's capable
of. In addition to the fine offensive numbers, he tied for the
league lead with 17 outfield assists.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he's even better.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really matured as a player,'' Robinson said. ``He's
really taken his job as a player and a leader in his own hands.
He's really risen and become a real fine, fine prototypical right
fielder that has been invaluable to this club.''
\Nsubheds: Short hops Clark hurt again Nothing much has changed for
Will Clark since leaving the Rangers and signing with the Orioles
as a free agent before the '99 season. Just as he was in Texas,
he's still effective when healthy. But he has trouble staying
healthy.
</P>
<P>
   He went on the disabled list Wednesday because of a strained
left hamstring, his third trip to the injury list since signing
with the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Clark appeared in only 77 games last season because of a broken
thumb and bone chips in his left elbow that required surgery on
Aug. 26. He reported to spring training early to make up for lost
time, and was encouraged by having full range of motion in the arm.
</P>
<P>
   Before injuring his hamstring he was hitting .367 with a
league-leading .524 on-base percentage. He only had three RBI, but
had scored 18 runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disappointing's not the word,'' Clark said. ``For as much work
as I put in this off-season and spring training, and to get off the
start I'm off to and the team's off to, disappointing's not near a
bad enough word.''
\Nsubheds:Suspensions slow Sox Frank Robinson accomplished
something AL pitchers had a difficult time doing, slowing down the
White Sox. They set a major league record with 181 runs in April,
but scored only 19 runs in their first six games after Robinson
levied his suspensions for the brawls with the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Lee missed three games in Detroit last weekend, and
Magglio Ordonez began his five-game suspension Monday. At the same
time, Frank Thomas is hampered by foot and hamstring injuries.
</P>
<P>
   However, hitting instructor Von Joshua thinks there's more to
the power outage than absences and injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the fight, I've watched a change,'' he said. ``That took
a little sting out of them. Some players aren't as aggressive. I
think we went into the Detroit series and several guys changed the
way they were playing. They were tentative. We have to get back to
being aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:New Reds struggling When the Reds added Ken Griffey
Jr. and Dante Bichette in off-season trades, their lineup appeared
to be as strong as any in the majors. Instead, the team and the new
guys have struggled.
</P>
<P>
   Through Thursday, the Reds were a game under .500 and 41/2 games
behind the Cardinals in the NL Central. Griffey was hitting .198
(20-for-101) while Bichette was at .206 (21-for-102) with no homers
in his last 80 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   At least Griffey is driving in runs. He had 24 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know he's a good ballplayer,'' manager Jack McKeon said.
``He's going to hit. I wish we had four or five guys with 24 RBI. I
think we'd be in good shape.`
</P>
<P>
   Bichette, on the other hand, has only six RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hitter's nightmare, to dig yourself a hole early in the
season,'' he said. ``It takes so long to get your numbers back to
normal. What you have to do is grind, get your hits, try to get big
hits and help the team win. Don't even look up. Hold your breath,
go hard and keep working at it.`
\Nsubheds:Indians' offense missing The Indians found out over the
past five seasons that you can slug your way to a division title,
but not to a World Series championship. So they upgraded the
pitching staff by signing free-agent starter Chuck Finley.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the pitching's just fine, but the offense is dragging them
down.
</P>
<P>
   They hit .219 (42-for-192) and scored 16 runs in losing four
times in a six-game homestand against the Red Sox and Yankees.
After leading the league with 1,009 runs last year, they're on pace
to score 836.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept saying, `We need pitching,' '' shortstop Omar Vizquel
said. ``Well, we got the pitching and now we can't hit.''
\Nsubheds:Injuries slow Gwynn Padres outfielder Tony Gwynn finally
went on the disabled list after having fluid drained from his left
knee for a fifth time since the start of spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only thing they could do,'' Gwynn said. ``I couldn't
keep going out there for two days, then have it drained and sit for
three or four days, come back, have it drained again and sit again.
It's too hard on them and it's too hard on me. I can't play this
way, and \Rmanager Bruce Bochy\S can't make the moves he wants to
make.''
</P>
<P>
   The best pure hitter of his generation is batting just .186 with
no homers and seven RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to fight my way through it but, offensively, I
can't do what I need to do,'' Gwynn said.
</P>
<P>
   The injury could cost him a lot of money. The contract extension
he signed in the spring guarantees him a $6 million salary in 2001
if he gets 502 plate appearances this year. But he has played in
just 13 games because of the knee problems and an elbow injury
after being hit with an Al Leiter pitch on Opening Day.
\Nsubheds:Around the NL Mike Hampton pitched like an ace for the
Astros last season, leading the league with 22 wins and posting
career bests in innings (239), strikeouts (177) and ERA (2.90). But
he has been a bust since his trade to the Mets. He leads the major
leagues with 36 walks, and walks-per-nine-innings (8.4). He
admitted he's suffering from ``a little lack of self-confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Bonds hit the first ball completely out of Pac Bell Park
and into San Francisco Bay with a blast off Mets reliever Rich
Rodriguez on Monday night, but he doesn't expect there to be many
more. ``There's going to be some guys who can do it,'' he said.
``\RBut\S the ball doesn't carry here like everybody thought it
would. I hit that ball pretty good and it barely got in that
water.''
</P>
<P>
   The offensive explosion hasn't reached Milwaukee. In their past
nine games going into a weekend series against the Expos, the
Brewers scored 22 runs (2.4 per game) and batted .176 (49 for 278).
``We haven't found an answer yet,'' rookie manager Davey Lopes
said. ``When you're not hitting, everything else is magnified. You
look like you are kind of dead, collectively.`
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs played perhaps their best game of the season in Kerry
Wood's first start. They scored 11 runs, with reserve infielder
Willie Greene getting four hits and driving in four runs. Sammy
Sosa made a diving catch. Reliever Brian Williams pitched three
scoreless innings for a save. ``It's not like we play better for
Kerry, but the emotion gets higher because of this kid,'' Mark
Grace said. ``He's special. You don't really elevate your skill,
but it does seem to work out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston's Enron Field yields a lot of homers and runs, but it
still takes a back seat to Denver's Coors Field in the launching
pad category. In a six-game homestand that ended Wednesday, the
Rockies gave up 8.83 runs a game, yet went 4-2 by scoring 10.83
runs a game. The winning team never scored less than 12 runs in any
of the six games.
</P>
<P>
   The ``go figure'' game of the year: The Dodgers ended the
Braves' 15-game winning streak when troubled left-hander Carlos
Perez outdueled multiple Cy Young award winner Greg Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks reliever Mike Morgan has saved for the cycle this
season, preserving victories by going four innings, three innings,
two innings and one inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds finished 12-12 in April, ending five consecutive years
in which they had posted a losing record in the season's opening
month.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Around the AL Tampa Bay manager Larry Rothschild has a
solution if baseball wants to curb the offensive explosion: widen
home plate from its current 17 inches. ``It would give the pitchers
more room to work with,'' Rothschild said. ``It would make hitters
more aggressive. And it would lead to quicker games.''
</P>
<P>
   White Sox manager Jerry Manuel, who was handed an eight-game
suspension after the brawl between his team and the Tigers, said a
uniform set of rules covering such incidents might cut down on
their frequency. ``Guidelines would be nice,'' he said. ``This is
what's going to happen if you pitch inside, this is what's going to
happen if you charge the mound. If you know what's going to happen,
it might eliminate some of these things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had a starting outfield of Brian Hunter, Ken
Griffey Jr. and Jay Buhner when Butch Huskey left Seattle last
August. When they played the Twins, Huskey's current team, last
week, the outfield was Mark McLemore, Mike Cameron and Stan Javier.
``I didn't play with any of those guys, and I've only been gone
since last August,'' Huskey said.
</P>
<P>
   The trade that sent Jaime Navarro and John Snyder from the White
Sox to the Brewers for Cal Eldred and Jose Valentin is looking
awfully one-sided. Navarro was released and Snyder has been on the
DL all season, while Eldred was 2-0 going into his start against
the Royals on Friday and Valentin was hitting .283 with five homers
and 18 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have the best record in the league, even though they
have the lowest batting average and the lowest fielding percentage
in the East, one win out of David Cone and two RBI out of Chuck
Knoblauch. How? Perhaps because of a bullpen that was the first
ever to go through April without sustaining a loss, that leads the
AL with a 2.52 ERA and is first in saves (11) and fewest hits (67)
and homers (2) allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Twins president Jerry Bell met for two hours with commissioner
Bud Selig on Tuesday to discuss the club's concerns about being in
baseball's only six-team division if Selig's favored realignment
proposal is approved. The Twins are concerned that the addition of
the large-revenue Rangers further would damage their chances of
making the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Bordick not only led the league with 29 RBI in April, he
also set a club record. The previous mark was 24, set by Hall of
Famer Frank Robinson in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' Alex Rodriguez won't turn 25 until July 27 but
he's already sixth on the career home run list by shortstops with
156, 12 behind Barry Larkin.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:The week ahead The Dodgers, second in the NL West,
could get an idea this week of whether they're really contenders or
just pretenders. They travel to West-leading Arizona for a
three-game series beginning tomorrow, then head to St. Louis for a
three-game series against the Central-leading Cardinals.
\Nsubheds:The final word ``I'm against everything he said. I don't
think they should throw him out of baseball, but he does deserve to
get booed and mooned. I think everyone should be allowed to speak
their mind, and that's what I did.'' _ Andrew Tellers, the Dodgers
fan who mooned Braves reliever John Rocker
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
