<HEADLINE>
GALAXY, WIZARDS BATTLE TO DRAW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ With all the anticipation of a championship
fight - two unbeaten teams, two scoring machines and defensive
weapons to make both teams complete - Kansas City and the Los
Angeles Galaxy did nothing to enhance or damage its reputations
after 90 minutes and two sudden-death overtime periods.
</P>
<P>
   No knockdowns, no big flurries, just a handful of
counter-punches that left the only two unbeaten teams in Major
League Soccer still unbeaten. As they say overseas, this was
nil-nil, which kind of describes the action of Saturday's 0-0 draw
in front of 17,098 at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Wizards (6-0-2, 20 points) were on the road and
without Danish Striker Miklos Molnar (ankle strain), the
psychological edge goes to the Wizards for keeping a slight edge in
the Western Division standings.
</P>
<P>
   But if there was any advantage between the lines, the Galaxy
(5-0-3, 18 points) deserves credit for constantly challenging the
organized shape of Kansas City's 4-4-2 alignment.
</P>
<P>
   K.C. goalkeeper Tony Meola recorded his league-leading sixth
shutout of the season, making two big one-handed saves in the last
20 minutes to keep the game scoreless.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy striker Clint Mathis nearly broke free in the 80th
minute, but was pulled down by Wizards defender Nick Garcia,
spoiling the Galaxy's last good scoring opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City had its chances in the first half, but nothing as
dangerous as the Galaxy's scoring opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Using plenty of give-and-go's to break K.C.'s flat four in the
back, Mauricio Cienfuegos left a pass wide for Roy Myers cutting
toward the goal in the 31st minute. Cienfuegos followed the play,
getting a pass back from Myers a few yards in front of the Wizards
net, but Cienfuegos couldn't hammer home the one-touch finish as a
Wizards defender slid to angle his shot wide.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the half, Danny Pena slipped behind Kansas City's
defense to the left side. With everyone shifting right, Simon
Elliott sent a pass the other direction to Pena, unmarked 10 yards
in front of Kansas City's net. Meola rushed out, hurrying Pena's
shot, which skidded of Meola's hand and away from the goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
