<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 02:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8107 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-ASTROS-LA     05-07 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-ASTROS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDLEY LIFTS DODGERS TO VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Todd Hundley was living right Saturday night.
About the only thing he couldn't control was his pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley hit his sixth career grand slam and threw out his first
baserunner of the season in the Los Angeles Dodgers' 9-6 victory
over the Houston Astros. But every time it appeared Hundley had
done enough, Darren Dreifort needed more.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley's grand slam capped a six-run third inning and gave the
Dodgers a comfortable lead. But Dreifort opened the next inning by
allowing a leadoff double to Jeff Bagwell.
</P>
<P>
   When Bagwell tried to steal third, Hundley threw him out, the
first time he has done that in 19 attempts this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that play I turned to (home plate umpire) Gerry (Davis)
and said, `that's the first one all year,' ``He said, `You're
kidding.'' I wish I was. It felt great to finally get it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the next inning, Dreifort was back in trouble, allowing two
RBI singles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think he pitched that bad,'' Hundley said of
Dreifort, who allowed five hits and four runs in 5 innings. ``We
kind of got in a bad groove, throwing too many fastballs. I'm not
worried about him.''
</P>
<P>
   But after Eric Karros made it 8-3 with a two-run homer in the
bottom of the fifth, Dreifort opened the sixth by allowing a single
and a walk. Hundley didn't help the inning with a passed ball that
put runners at second and third. But Dreifort allowed both to score
and was pulled after walking Craig Biggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you need to win a sloppy game when you don't have
your best stuff,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``I've been
very pleased with him this year. You don't want to see your pitcher
let the other team back in, but sometimes it happens and you move
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Dodgers held on to win for the sixth time in eight
games on the homestand, and Hundley hit the club's third grand slam
this season, Dreifort (2-1) remained a puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   In his last start, Dreifort had took a 10-2 lead into the fifth
inning, but left with a no decision in the Dodgers 13-12 victory
over Florida. Errors by Adrian Beltre and Mark Grudzielanek led to
seven unearned runs in the fifth, but Dreifort also walked two and
gave up back-to-back homers to Mike Lowell and Derrek Lee.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that game I just couldn't stop the bleeding,'' Dreifort
said. ``Tonight, I made some good pitches and some bad pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   None of that seemed critical, even after a second-inning home
run by Ken Caminiti.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, Houston starter Octavio Dotel (1-3) walked three,
hit a batter and gave up a double to Grudzielanek. But Hundley
dropped the big bomb, hitting a line drive into the lower stands on
a 2-2 fast ball.
</P>
<P>
   It was his sixth home run of the season. His last grand slam
came July 19 at Pittsburgh. Karros and Kevin Elster have the
Dodgers' other slams this season.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, Hundley did something even more rare. He was 0
for 18 throwing out runners this season, although three runners
were picked off first, which counts as a caught stealing Backup
Chad Kreuter was 0 for 4.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell, who entered the game batting .333 with nine homers and
24 RBI, had 30 stolen bases last season. He was not in a running
situation. But with the Astros trailing 6-1 and struggling early
this season, Bagwell tried to shake things up against Hundley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was his first of the year, but actually he has done well,''
Johnson said. ``Our pitchers need to be better holding guys on.
Todd is having a hell of a year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
