<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 03:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8108 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN     05-07 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE WILL MOISO, RUSH GO IN DRAFT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As interpreted by the socially stalwart watchdogs of college
basketball, the NBA may be the scariest place outside the range of
Janet Reno's mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the young men in this league are drafted, just like in
war.
</P>
<P>
   So if war is hell and the draft is like war, then it can be
concluded that the NBA Draft is hell.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask any UCLA fan. See, last week, the NBA Draft claimed two
promising Bruin sophomores - 6-foot-10 Jerome Moiso and 6-6 JaRon
Rush, whose name is scrawled in pencil on the NCAA's Most Wanted
List.
</P>
<P>
   But while USC baseball fans didn't burn precious cell phone
minutes waiting to howl with the gods of talk radio over Sean
Burrough's skipping from Wilson High to the minor leagues, the
departure of Moiso and Rush has become a scream.
</P>
<P>
   The counter scream should be ``Grow up!''
</P>
<P>
   For those who refuse to pass judgment and would gladly kiss off
academia for the chance to pocket $4 million in three years
(Moiso's estimated value), we offer the opportunity to accept it
and move on.
</P>
<P>
   When can you expect these rascals to be drafted?
</P>
<P>
   After browbeating five scouts and two NBA personnel executives,
we conclude Moiso could be selected anywhere from 10 to 16 in the
June 28 draft. Sure, he may get bruises and hemorrhoids next
season, but two semesters of NBA 101 will better prepare him for
NBA 2001-2002 than another college campaign with virtually any
coach you can name.
</P>
<P>
   Things are trickier for Rush, a small forward in a two-guard's
body.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll have to show something special in Chicago just to get
near the first round,'' said one scout, referring to the pre-draft
camp June 6-12. ``If he had stayed at UCLA another season, he might
have been top 20 next year.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has a $6,000 tab, based on his celebrated relationship
with a (sit down for this) shady AAU coach.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Jason Kapono has admitted to kicking around the notion
of declaring for the draft, but the same talent snoops advise
against this. The former Artesia High standout is a longshot to go
in the first round, prime territory that includes the coveted prize
of a guaranteed three- year contract. &QL; 
Back on Planet Clipper
</P>
<P>
   Donald T. Sterling's little ship of horrors sails on with
interim coach Jim Todd still on board, while Mike Fratello's name
continues to be the favorite that's run up the mast.
</P>
<P>
   According to team sources, the Clips owner really digs the idea
of having his team mentioned in the same paragraph with Fratello,
the ex-Hawks and Cavaliers coach, who now makes a living as a game
analyst for TNT and studio guru for NBC. The cheerfully eccentric
Sterling even has gone as far as to seek opinions from members of
the team's support staff in regard to the possible hiring of
Fratello.
</P>
<P>
   In 14 seasons as an NBA head coach, the ``Czar of the
Telestrator'' has a .552 winning percentage with one division title
and nine playoff appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Contact has been made with the Clips by Fratello, who probably
is seeking a deal in the $5 million-per-year range. While it may
seem nutty to think Sterling would approach that figure, he did
throw some market-value loot at Larry Brown a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Todd, assistant coach No. 2 Kareem Abdul-Jabbar and
assistant coach No. 1 Dennis Johnson - considered a solid and
affordable candidate - have been reporting to their event-level
offices at Staples Center for draft and off-season preparation.
Just in case it involves them.
</P>
<P>
   As for free agent shooting guard Derek Anderson, don't bite on
any sign-and-trade stories involving the Clippers and free agent
Denver guard Tariq Abdul-Wahad. Sure, Anderson would like to play
in Denver, but his price tag (in the $6 million per year ballpark)
is about double the market value for Abdul-Wahad. For the Nuggets
to clear Anderson's contract under salary-cap rules, they'd have to
send back a players whose deals would be of equal value. Simply
put, they'd add a garbage-time all- star (or two) the Clippers
won't want. By the way, Clipper personnel man Elgin Baylor would
prefer a sign-and-keep deal with the eager-to-leave Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson still has a grip on San Antonio's interest, but if the
Spurs re-sign Tim Duncan (seems very likely now), they'd be capped
out and would need to offer the Clips a sign-and-trade deal
involving their own garage-sale bench warmers.
</P>
<P>
   On deck in this Clipper review is free agent power forward
Maurice Taylor, who - according to league sources - isn't exactly
as coveted by Orlando as he and agent David Falk had hoped. That
goes double for the hometown Detroit Pistons, who - thanks to the
rehiring of George Irvine and front-office rise of Joe Dumars may
be able to keep Grant Hill, severely limiting their spending money.
</P>
<P>
   A recently published rumor unveiling an interest in returning to
the Clips by Kings reserve point guard Darrick Martin (UCLA, St.
Anthony's High) was just plain silly. Darrick, that ship has
sailed.
</P>
<P>
   Shot-clock violations: Indiana assistant coach Rick Carlisle
remains a solid prospect to replace Larry Bird on the Pacers' hot
seat. Other teams interested in Carlisle should realize that one of
his coaching cronies is Miami assistant Mark Iavaroni. Iavaroni
wasn't much of a player, but the Pete Newell coaching disciple is
considered one of the best teachers of post play in the NBA. It's
no cinch that Iavaroni would leave the Heat to join Carlisle, but
teams with young, raw inside players should think about it. ...
After Darrell Walker left Rockford of the CBA to become interim
coach of the Wizards, ex-Detroit Bad Boy Rick Mahorn scooted over
one seat and did quite well with the Lightning. This doesn't figure
to yield an NBA head-coaching gig this year, but a source said
Larry Brown would like to have Mahorn as an assistant in Philly.
...
</P>
<P>
   ESPN has reported that high school quantum leaper Darius Miles
(East St. Louis, Ill.) will be represented by Falk. But a source in
Falk's office says the report was bogus. Miles, who could be
selected in the 5-8 range of the June 28 NBA Draft's first round,
has been wooed by rising agent star Bill Duffy, but he may be
leaning toward Eric Rudolph, who represents athletes on behalf of
an entertainment crossover group fronted by rap star Jay-Z. Worked
well for Master P, right? ... Missouri sophomore point guard Keyon
Dooling will stick with his decision to ride the draft - if
pre-draft buzz puts him in the top 20. According to three NBA
scouts, the swift Dooling will go in the 15-20 range. ... Despite
frequent demonstrations of limited court savvy, at least two league
personnel directors believe DeShawn Stevenson (Washington Union HS,
Fresno) has enough two-guard promise to be chosen midway through
the first round. ... An NBA assistant with head-coaching chops is
the Lakers' Jim Cleamons. According to a league source, Cleamons -
one of the hardest-working, no-nonsense coaches in the business -
is content as Phil Jackson's understudy and not interested in the
Clippers job. ... Shaquille O'Neal, proving his movie-watching
tastes are as sophisticated as those he stars in, recently added
his own personal copy of the Keith Closs beat-down film. O'Neal
used a portable DVD player to screen it with Chris Webber in a
Staples Center hallway after Game 1 of the Kings-Lakers series.
O'Neal, a source reports, enjoyed the action, but thought the Closs
premise was derivative. Working title? ``Closstrophobia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
