<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8191 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-COX-RUSSIA-PUTIN-0508     05-07 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-RUSSIA-PUTIN-0508 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PUTIN SWORN IN AS RUSSIA'S PRESIDENT
 &HT;    550 words &AMP; ADD
 &HT;    By Margaret Coker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW -- Vowing to rebuild the country, safeguard human rights
and work ``openly and honestly'' to serve the people, Vladimir
Putin on Sunday became the second democratically elected president
of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, the 47-year-old former head of Russia's Federal Security
Service, the successor agency to the KGB, thereby assumed immense
and unrivalled authority as leader of the world's largest country.
</P>
<P>
   Just three hours after the inauguration, Putin named 42-year-old
Mikhail Kasyanov as acting prime minister. Kasyanov, the outgoing
first deputy premier and finance minister, is almost certain to
gain parliamentary approval. He is well known in the West as a
financial expert and foreign debt negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   The relative youth of the two top men also marks a clear move to
a new generation of Russian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-minute ceremony took place in sumptuous St. Andrew's
Hall, a wing of Grand Kremlin Palace, in the heart of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   In a 10-minute acceptance speech marking his meteoric
eight-month rise to power, Putin promised to usher in a new era for
the nation impoverished by a decade of political upheaval,
corruption and botched economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure you that in my actions I will be guided only by
national interests,'' Putin said, flanked by a frail Boris Yeltsin,
the former president, and Marat Baglai, chairman of the
Constitutional Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I will not avoid mistakes but what I promise, what I can
really promise, is that I will work openly and honestly,'' he said,
adding:
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider it my holy duty to consolidate Russian society, and
every day and every hour to remember that we have one nation, one
state, one common future together.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin's campaign message centered on the need to revive Russia,
what he calls a ``rich country of poor people.'' But he did not
disclose any details of his yet-unpublished economic plan.
</P>
<P>
   Putin took over as acting president when Yeltsin, 69, abruptly
resigned on New Year's Eve. Since then, his detractors have accused
him of committing human rights abuses in the seven-month Chechen
conflict and have voiced concern over how a career KGB officer
could govern democratically.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the judo black-belt and avid swimmer who rose from
relative obscurity last summer to become prime minister and
Yeltsin's chosen successor as president has enjoyed approval rating
above 70 percent. He won the March 26 presidential election with a
clear 52 percent majority of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   A Kremlin spokesman said the symbolism behind the ornate
ceremony was aimed at highlighting the peaceful transfer of power
and the rise of a new era, as well as codify a sense of tradition.
For instance, Putin took his oath of office using the same red,
leather-covered copy of the constitution that Yeltsin once did.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, dressed in a dark gray suit and gray tie, spoke in the
Kremlin Throne Room, a spacious place with walls and pillars
covered in gold leaf and polished parquet floors in front of about
1,000 guests for the closely choreographed ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The palace's restoration was overseen by the former head of the
Presidential Property Management, Pavel Borodin, and is the subject
of an ongoing embezzlement scandal involving him and an estimated
80 other former Kremlin officials. Swiss authorities are currently
investigating the case. Putin served under Borodin before being
appointed FSB chairman.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story can end here. Optional add follows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Muscovites interviewed Sunday on a bright but blustery day in
the Russian capital expressed a hopeful mood about the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to have such a young, energetic president. I hope
that he does everything that he promises. I want a better country,
like he says he does,''
</P>
<P>
   said Ludmila Vladimirova, 50.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting Russia's young democratic tradition, the inauguration
ceremony took on weighty symbolic value. The final event schedule
was approved only on Friday, leaving a last minute rush for
organizers.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts judged the results as mixed at best, with some
television commentators likening the event to a Czarist coronation
and others discussing the irony of a president who ran on an
anti-corruption campaign standing in a room surrounded by more
wealth that most Russians could imagine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they (the organizers) were trying not to imbue the event
with to much connection to (the past administration), which is
associated in the Russian public mind with corruption and mistakes,
then they didn't quite succeed,'' said Lilia Schvetsova, an analyst
at the Moscow Carnegie Endowment Center, a think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Cost-wise, the event itself was quite modest, with the Kremlin
spending only around $214,000, compared to nearly $30 million for
President Clinton's second inauguration in 1997. Putin said he
wanted less pomp than Yeltsin's inauguration so that it would not
overshadow the popular May 9 holiday to mark
</P>
<P>
   the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Few, if any, of the regular people Putin thanked in his speech
for supporting him were in attendance. Putin did not make any
public appearances during the day.
</P>
<P>
   After the ceremony, Putin left the Kremlin Palace to a 30-gun
salute by soldiers flanking the palace grounds. He inspected a
squadron of troops, laid a wreath at the nearby Tomb of the Unknown
Soldier and received a blessing by Russian Orthodox Church leader,
Patriarch Alexiy II.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the newly inaugurated president and his wife Ludmilla
attended a concert at the Kremlin's Soviet-era theater and presided
over a gala
</P>
<P>
   reception -- with an invitation list that was even more
selective than the swearing-in ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian president is the formal head of state and
commander-in-chief of the armed forces, controls the government,
names most top officials and has the last word in most state
affairs. He can be impeached only with great difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB: Official English-language site of the Russian
Federation -www.gov.ru/page8.html
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Coker's e-mail address is megc(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
