<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8193 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-COUPON-LADY0508-COX     05-07 1353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUPON-LADY0508-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Above and beyond the call of duty
 &HT;    By Stephanie Allmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ It's 7:30 p.m. on a weeknight and the usual
post-work crowd of customers at the H-E-B is lined up to check out.
</P>
<P>
   In Lane 6, parents entertain small children in baskets,
bachelors hold cases of brew and professionals loosen ties and
remove jackets while they thumb through magazines.
</P>
<P>
   No one in Lane 6 seems to mind that they're waiting in the
longest line in the store.
</P>
<P>
   That often happens when Jacklynn Adams is on the other side of
the register.
</P>
<P>
   ``How ya doin', ma'am? Is there anything else I can get you
before I get started?'' Adams asks, smiling, as a middle-age woman
steps up to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Adams quickly swipes the groceries across the scanner, paying
attention to nearly everything the woman buys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ooh, Ben and Jerry's has it goin' on. I love that,'' she says
as she scans a carton of ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   When she scans a package of frozen vegetables, she stops and
looks at the customer to offer her a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have a coupon for this, honey? 'Cause if you don't, I
got one for you,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She takes out a coupon from a zipper pouch next to the register,
scans it and puts it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you interested in some toothpaste for 99 cents? This is a
great deal,'' she says, pointing to a basket full of Colgate tubes.
</P>
<P>
   The woman politely declines and hands over a check for $89.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, honey,'' Adams says and reaches across to shake the
customer's hand. ``Ma'am, you have a good day. Take care, ya hear?
God bless you.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman nods and walks out with a smile on her face.
</P>
<P>
   Adams has once again accomplished two of the goals she sets
every day: She's made a customer happy and she's saved her money.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandmother used to say, 'If you keep your fist closed, you
can't receive any blessings and you can't give anything out,'' the
46-year-old cashier says.
</P>
<P>
   That philosophy has H-E-B customers asking for ``Miss Jackie''
by name, her bosses singing her praises and other grocery stores
trying to woo her away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people blend into the woodwork, and Jackie stands out,''
says H-E-B store manager Brent Ackors. ``I've been in the grocery
store business for 26 years, and I've never had (an employee) that
excited, that energetic. It's not normal. It's not anywhere close
to normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides being a cashier, Adams is ``the coupon lady,'' a
responsibility she created herself and a title she works hard at
every day. After her ``graveyard'' shift as a cashier ends each
night, she spends two to three hours clipping coupons and taping
them to food displays. Then, when inspiration hits, she opens a
black book of jingles and pens a ditty or two about an upcoming
sale item.
</P>
<P>
   Adams uses her own sense of humor and musical talent to compose
her jingles. Every night on the hour, she clicks on the intercom
and serenades customers with one of her catchy songs. On a recent
night, her 9 p.m. jingle was ``Get Ready for H-E-B,'' which
advertised a program that lets customers earn money toward gas with
their groceries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never knew shoppers who make me feel the way that you do,
you're all right/You come in her each and every day, yes you do
dears, you're outta sight.'/So fe-fi-fo-fum, look out shoppers,
cause here we come/And we're bringing good sales to you/So get
ready, get ready for H-E-B.''
</P>
<P>
   After she announces the fuel rewards program, she signs off
with, ``As always, thanks for shopping your super-Texas friendly
H-E-B store.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if customers have never had Miss Jackie as a cashier, they
probably know her voice from the jingles she sings over the
intercom, Ackors says.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are her regular customers, like Jerry Lassetter,
who gets a hug from Adams when she sees him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only live a couple blocks away, so I come in and see her
about every day,'' Lassetter says as Adams helps him find the
Cheese Nips.
</P>
<P>
   Adams says her natural tendency to help people and to save money
both come from her upbringing. She grew up in Philadelphia, the
youngest of seven children.
</P>
<P>
   She remembers playing ``grocery store'' with her siblings when
they were young. Her first real job at a supermarket came in
Philadelphia in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to the manager, 'If you'll give me a chance, I'll be
the best worker you've got,''' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said she attended Penn State in the early 1970s but cut
her academic career short when she married and had the first of six
children. Adams pursued her interests in music, entering vocal
contests, writing gospel songs and directing a local children's
choir in Philadelphia. She also worked as a seamstress, at a pizza
parlor and at a grocery store when her children were growing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving money and taking care of us was always important to
her,'' says Adams' 25-year-old daughter Kiante Davis. ``She loves
to work and loves working with people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I was like my mom,'' Davis says.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Adams decided to leave Philadelphia for a warmer
climate. She picked Phoenix first, but she says she wanted to live
in a place where the people were friendlier. So, in the spring of
that year, she went to the library, opened a map and picked Waco.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she never wants to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waco's got the friendliest people in the world,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said she started working at a Save-a-Lot grocery store and
worked her way up to manager. After the store closed, she was
offered a management position at H-E-B in 1997. But she chose to
become a cashier instead to stay closer to her favorite people, the
customers, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Now she has a full calendar. Besides working full-time at H-E-B
at night, she delivers pizzas for Pizza Hut part-time during the
day. (She has to keep both her uniforms close by so she can change
quickly from one to the other.) In her spare time, she runs errands
for house-bound senior citizens, and she gives food to homeless and
needy people.
</P>
<P>
   Adams sometimes takes advantage of H-E-B sales to give food to
others. Recently, she bought $130 worth of Easter candy to
distribute to needy children. And last Christmas, she piled 120
jugs of holiday punch into her 1995 Corsica and gave them to
homeless people.
</P>
<P>
   Her altruistic gestures extend to the animals in the community,
too. She takes in homeless dogs and cats, feeds them and gives them
shelter. Right now, she has 10 dogs and 12 cats, but she's had as
many as 22 dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're my babies,'' she says. ``I go home and sing to them,
and they sing with me.''
</P>
<P>
   She says her motivation to work hard and to give to others comes
from her 16 grandchildren. Besides wanting to save money to help
them with college, she wants to set a good example for them, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we keep our kids motivated, they keep us rejuvenated,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Her service at H-E-B and in the community has not gone
unnoticed. She has a cupful of customer service buttons, and she
was honored as the H-E-B Partner of the Year in 1998. She has also
received a Waco City Works Award.
</P>
<P>
   Several local grocery stores, including Wal-Mart and Winn Dixie,
have tried unsuccessfully to woo her away from H-E-B, Ackors said.
He wouldn't say whether he offered her more money to stay at the
store. But he acknowledges that when it's time to dole out raises
for merit, her name is high on the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say I would do whatever I needed to keep her
here,'' Ackors says. ``The best compliment I could give her is to
say that I have 340 (employees) at H-E-B, and I wish I had 340
people just like Jackie.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, though, Adams will leave H-E-B, she says. She wants
to open her own restaurant in Waco in the next five years or so.
The cuisine will consist of recipes _ from German to Mexican _ that
she has learned from her customers over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Success comes at all levels, but I won't feel successful until
I open my own restaurant,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   And when she does, you can bet she'll offer coupon specials.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
