<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN0508-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Governor is right to seek clarification on blind trust
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Warning: This column could be hazardous to people
infected with political cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   A politician in hot water for trying to do the right thing? It's
a rarity. But that's what happened to Gov. Roy Barnes recently.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes doesn't always do the right thing. Not on gun control.
Not on changing the state flag. Not so far, at least. But on
anything to do with openness in government, you can pretty much
count on Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   Consistent with his legislative record on sunshine in
government, Barnes' first act as governor was to ask the General
Assembly to tighten requirements relating to open records and
meetings so the people's business can't be hidden from the people.
But when the governor and his lawyers asked the Secretary of State
how to report Barnes' blind trust for his annual financial
disclosure, Barnes looked at first as if he were trying to hide
something.
</P>
<P>
   If the governor had kept quiet and reported the blind trust in
the same manner former Gov. Zell Miller did, the issue might never
have arisen. It's a good thing he didn't because the law needs
fixing.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes and his wife Marie, who have a net worth estimated at
$9.6 million, created the blind trust shortly after the governor's
election. They released the trust document and a list of the assets
placed in it. Wealthy office holders, especially at the federal
level, often use blind trusts to prevent perceived or real
conflicts of interest. The idea is to keep public officials from
knowing how their assets are being managed. That prevents
politicians or their cronies from using inside information for
personal enrichment.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia law is silent on reporting blind trusts, but demands
that an office holder disclose the ``name, address, and principal
activity'' of any ``business entity'' (including a trust) in which
he or she has more than a 10 percent ownership. But another section
of the state law says officials must disclose real estate holdings
in excess of $20,000 in which they have ``a direct ownership''
interest. The law also demands disclosure of annual payments in
excess of $20,000 from a business interest. If such reporting is
applied to a blind trust, however, the purpose of the trust would
be defeated and the legal requirements of the trust violated.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes was so concerned about the muddle that he called on the
state's foremost legal ethics expert, Randolph Thrower, to help
him. Thrower is best known for having resigned as Commissioner of
the Internal Revenue Service when President Nixon tried to misuse
the agency for political purposes during Watergate. Thrower advised
Barnes that a blind trust legally removes the governor from a
``direct ownership'' interest in trust assets. So a literal
interpretation of the state law would only require disclosure of
the trust's existence, and the name and address of the trustee. But
Thrower asked Secretary of State Cathy Cox to request a formal
Attorney General's opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Teddy Lee, a lawyer who heads the State Ethics Commission,
disagreed with Thrower's interpretation. He said it would render
the state's personal financial disclosure law ``impotent and
meaningless.'' Every asset in the trust which meets the threshold
amount or ownership percentage for reporting should be disclosed,
Lee said _ although he conceded that such an interpretation defeats
the purpose of a blind trust.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Barnes said simply that the public should
know everything he knows about the blind trust. Thrower said the
governor planned to disclose the trust's tax return, its annual
worth and any additional assets placed in it _ all of which could
probably be done without violating the terms of the trust.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the Attorney General decides about this legal
quagmire, two things are clear: State disclosure laws need to be
amended to address blind trusts; and the governor has tried to do
the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
