<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, May 8:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   EURO (Frankfurt, Germany) _ The euro was supposed to unify the
economies of 11 European nations and be a symbol of stability to
rival the dollar, the yen and even the British pound. But so far it
has been a boon to the very currencies with which it was supposed
to compete. Now Americans brandishing dollars are finding bargains
from Amsterdam to Vienna. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   PUTIN-INAUGURATION (Moscow) _ Vladimir Putin is inaugurated as
Russia's president and names Mikhail Kasyanov, 42, as his acting
prime minister three hours later. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE (Freetown, Sierra Leone) _ Developments in the U.N.
hostage drama. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   RWANDA-CONGO (Dateline TK) _ The Rwandan president promises a
U.N. delegation that he will end the involvement of his country's
30,000 troops in the war in neighboring Congo. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   CZECH-GYPSIES (Prague, Czech Republic) _ On Gypsy activists who
have made it to prominent positions. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-BOWLING-ALLEY (Los Angeles) _ For the last five years,
Jacqueline Sowell has loved to go to the Holiday Bowl, a faded
bowling alley on a faded street in a faded district of Los Angeles.
Walking into the Bowl renewed her faith. It showed her day after
day just how well people of diverse backgrounds and races can get
along. But early Saturday morning, after 42 years, the Holiday Bowl
was closed. And a few hours after the last balls thundered down the
lanes, a group of Sowell's neighbors, co-workers and friends were
standing outside, holding signs, declaring the Bowl ``A Landmark of
Diversity'' and urging the new owners and the city to ``Preserve
Not Destroy.'' By Don Terry.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCHEDULE (Washington) _ There are fewer than 6,000 hours
left in the Clinton presidency, a dwindling block of time that many
people want to share. Putting together Clinton's schedule in these
final months is a delicate balancing act that involves squeezing
together fund-raising dinners, presidential speeches and photo ops
with golf games, foreign trips and overnight stays in Chappaqua,
N.Y. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   SHALIKASHVILI-PROFILE (Washington) _ Gen. John Shalikashvili,
former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, works on the
administration's behalf to lobby for arms control on the hill. By
Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded p)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-POLITICS (Washington) _ This week offered a stunning
contradiction in numbers: a 3.9 percent unemployment rate, the
lowest in 30 years, and two major national polls showing Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas leading Vice President Al Gore by 5
percentage points. To put that contrast in perspective, the last
time a president's party lost the White House in good times was
1920. So why isn't the booming economy blowing Bush away? By Adam
Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   UTAH-REPUBS (Salt Lake City) _ Utah is one of the most
Republican states in the country. But in Utah, there are
Republicans and there are Republicans. At the Republican state
party convention, even Sen. Orrin Hatch was greeted with a healthy
mix of boos and jeers. So was Gov. Michael Leavitt, who is running
for a third term against three challengers and failed to reach 60
percent in any of three ballots, putting him in a primary for the
first time since 1992. ``These conventions are the political
version of hazing,'' Leavitt said. ``You have to expect it as a
two-term incumbent.'' By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
