<DOCNO> NYT20000507.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8261 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TIMEWARNER-ASSESS-MED     05-07 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMEWARNER-ASSESS-MEDIA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECONSTRUCTING THE GENESIS OF A BLUNDER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM RUTENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What, exactly, was Time Warner thinking?
</P>
<P>
   When the next history of public relations is written, the
company's decision to block the ABC television network in 3.5
million homes last Monday will surely be a prominent chapter.
</P>
<P>
   In just 39 hours _ the time it took for it to restore the ABC
signal _ Time Warner managed to anger many of its customers, rile
local and national politicians, provoke a tough editorial in The
New York Times, draw the ire of the Federal Communications
Commission, give its satellite competitors a rare opening to grab
customers and upset what had looked like smooth sailing on the way
to approval of its merger with America Online.
</P>
<P>
   And it made ABC's parent, Walt Disney, no media midget itself,
look, in many eyes, like a helpless victim.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner executives now acknowledge that they erred. This
came about, they say, through a legal miscalculation and a
conviction that Disney would back down. It is also clear that
judgments may have been clouded by emotion. For months, tension had
been building as negotiators tried to resolve how much Time Warner
should pay Disney for the use of three of its cable channels and
whether Disney would renew Time Warner's right to carry the ABC
network.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone agrees that the atmosphere of the bargaining was
poisonous. Five months of negotiating had gone nowhere. Deadlines
were extended seven times. Time Warner accused Disney of blackmail
for threatening to pull its ABC signal if Time Warner did not meet
its demands. Disney accused Time Warner of shortchanging it on its
valuable ABC programming.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, two Disney executives were asked to leave the Time
Warner offices, and by late April face-to-face talks had ceased.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Wednesday, April 26, five days before the latest
negotiating deadline, when Time Warner's rights to carry the ABC
network were to expire. ABC faxed a terse letter to Time Warner
notifying it that Disney expected Time Warner to continue carrying
the ABC signal through May 24, after the end of the sweeps period,
when stations measure audiences to determine what to charge
advertisers. Time Warner had been insisting on an eight-month
extension.
</P>
<P>
   The tone of the fax set off the tempers of some Time Warner
executives, who felt ABC was negotiating by fiat. Previously,
before the other deadlines, ABC had faxed polite requests for
signatures on proposed extension agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, they were saying, `We give you the right to
carry our signal,' '' said Mike Luftman, spokesman for Time Warner
Cable. ``We felt that clearly things had changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner executives began to prepare for the worst. They
ordered an advertising agency to create a blaring message to
replace the ABC signal, the dramatic sentence ``Disney has taken
ABC away from you.''
</P>
<P>
   But still, they expected no Armageddon. For one thing, they
thought ABC would never allow its programming to be pulled during a
sweeps month, especially because it would jeopardize its chance to
finish the season as the No. 1 network for the first time in five
years.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, both sides were interpreting the law differently.
ABC maintained that an FCC regulation stipulated that its signal
could not be pulled in a sweeps month. Time Warner's lawyers argued
that, barring mutual agreement on an extension, it had to do just
that.
</P>
<P>
   Within Time Warner, executives debated what to do if Disney
stood its ground. Some saw blocking the network signal as a real
risk. A cable company _ an institution about as popular as a
parking violations bureau and often the target of accusations of
monopolistic practices _ was more likely to take the blame than a
network, these people argued.
</P>
<P>
   But others saw advantages. Assuming the law was on Time Warner's
side, ABC would potentially face big advertising revenue losses _
up to $3 million a day, according to some estimates. And perhaps
Disney, a huge conglomerate, would take just as much blame, if not
more, if Time Warner put its message out effectively. And then
there was also the resentment at play.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point you have to put your foot down and be a man and
stand up and say `Look,''' Fred Dressler, Time Warner's senior vice
president for programming, later told a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, April 30, came, and still no agreement had been reached.
More terse faxes went back and forth that afternoon. Neither side
budged. By around 8:30 p.m., Disney executives began to sense that
Time Warner's threat to pull the ABC signal was real, though they
still found it hard to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Was Disney playing the bullfighter taunting the bull? There is
no evidence that this was the corporate plan, though pulling the
singal clearly played into Disney's strategy of painting Time
Warner as a monopolist that would become even bigger should its
merger with AOL win approval.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner executives were convinced, meanwhile, that they had
Disney cornered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear they didn't think we would drop, and we didn't
think they would let us drop,'' said Dressler, who led the Time
Warner negotiating team.
</P>
<P>
   Luftman, the Time Warner Cable spokesman, said, ``Right up until
the last minute, we were hoping to get something acceptable on the
table.''
</P>
<P>
   But Preston R. Padden, the Washington lobbyist for Disney, who
had become increasingly involved in the negotiations, said: ``All
we could do was sit in front of the TV and wait until midnight to
see what they were going to do. I didn't think they were going to
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   With no compromise offer from Disney, Time Warner executives
felt there was no turning back. Not long before midnight, Time
Warner Cable's president, Joseph J. Collins, alerted Gerald M.
Levin, the Time Warner chairman, that he was about to order his
engineers to block the ABC signal. Levin supported the decision.
Executives said Stephen M. Case, the America Online chairman, was
also apprised of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   At 12:01 a.m., the ABC screen went briefly to static before the
accusation against Disney appeared on a blue screen in bright
yellow letters. Padden was in his room at the Four Seasons Hotel in
Manhattan. ``I had a very sick feeling in the pit of my stomach,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Where things stood for Time Warner were pretty clear within 24
hours. In New York, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani attacked Time Warner as
a predatory monopoly. ``This is an example of what happens when you
let a monopoly get too big,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   Disney dispatched its lawyers to the Washington offices of the
FCC, where they requested that the commission force Time Warner to
transmit its signals based on the sweeps regulation.
</P>
<P>
   In the same building, Time Warner representatives made their
case. They thought they were getting positive signals. But later in
the day, during a meeting with the commission's cable bureau, Time
Warner had a different feeling.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, The New York Times published an editorial that said
the threat to Disney by a combined America Online and Time Warner
was real.
</P>
<P>
   At about 10 a.m. that day, Dressler said, Time Warner executives
decided it was time to try a resolution. It was becoming rapidly
clear that Time Warner was badly losing the public relations war,
though both sides were suffering to some degree. ``We certainly
knew at that point that our customers weren't happy,'' Dressler
said. ``We thought it was in our interest, certainly in theirs as
well, to extend the olive branch.''
</P>
<P>
   At a hastily called news conference, Collins announced that he
had offered Disney an extension of the negotiations until October.
During the news conference, Robert Iger, the Disney president, sent
a fax to Time Warner officials proposing July 15 as the next
deadline. Collins accepted immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, the FCC ruled that Time Warner had indeed violated
the law by blocking ABC from its systems during a sweeps month. The
company received a strong rebuke from FCC Chairman William E.
Kennard, who declared, ``No company should use consumers in a
private contract dispute.''
</P>
<P>
   The question now is how much the dispute will hurt Time Warner
as it tries to conclude its merger with America Online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did we decide to take a stand now?'' Dressler said. ``We
thought it was the right time. They were just pushing us and
pushing us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
