<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, May 8, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another hot afternoon is expected from interior southern New
England to the Southeast coast. Readings will reach above 90
degrees in many urban areas from New York to Charlotte. Hazy
sunshine and balmy winds from the southwest will dominate this
region. The boundary with a cooler air mass over Quebec will become
active with afternoon thunderstorms developing over central New
York and the higher terrain of New England.
</P>
<P>
   The remnants of the disturbance that brought downpours from
Dallas to St. Louis last week will move into the central
Appalachians with considerable clouds and scattered thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   Hot, humid air from the southern Plains will reach into the
lower Great Lakes, aiding in the development of strong to severe
storms. Cooler air will cover most of the northwestern third of the
nation with patches of showers.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: MILES AND YEARS
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa, Okla., was inundated on Saturday with a daily record 2.83
inches of rain falling in 24 hours. This amount occurs on a
frequency of once every five years at the airport where it was
measured. About 10 miles away at the Riverside airport in Jenks, a
total of 6.31 inches was measured on Saturday. While daily records
are not kept at this smaller airport, this quantity of rain only
falls once every 50 years during a 24-hour period. The frequency of
such rainfalls provides valuable information to engineers who
design water catchment systems for cities. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
