<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PUBLIC RELATIONS, 25 PERCENT ADMIT TO LYING  
 `MILLIONAIRE' MAKES SORTIE INTO `E.R.' ZONE 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pity the public relations industry. It has long battled its
image as a cadre of hired guns who distort the truth, exaggerate
and sometimes even lie.
</P>
<P>
   And that part about the lying _ it may actually be true for one
quarter of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Leyland, the editor in chief of PR Week, a trade journal of
the public relations industry, surveyed some 1,700 public relations
executives about ethics in their industry. The survey, which was
published in the May 1 edition of PR Week, revealed several things,
not least of which was the statistic that turned into the article's
doom-and-gloom headline: ``One of out of four pros admits to lying
on job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry is deeply concerned with ethics and
truth-telling,'' Leyland said. ``And yet it has a reputation for
spinning and hype and straight out lying.''
</P>
<P>
   In the survey, 25 percent of the executives admitted they lied
on the job, 39 percent said they had exaggerated the truth, and 44
percent said they felt uncertain of the ethics of a task they were
asked to perform. And 62 percent said that they had felt
compromised in their work, either by being told a lie by their
client or by not having access to the full story.
</P>
<P>
   ``That statistic is the most significant contribution to
conflict with journalists,'' Leyland said. ``But I would really
like to survey the world of businesspeople, or the world of
journalists, and find out how many of them have lied.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of reactions from public relations executives to the
survey have poured in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them have said they just want to resign from the
industry and lie on a beach, examining their navel,'' he said. ``I
say, look at the bright side. If 25 percent told a lie, that means
75 percent did not.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Alex Kuczynski
</P>
<P>
   `Millionaire' Makes Sortie Into `E.R.' Zone
</P>
<P>
   With a week of celebrity contestants, ABC had already found a
new way to use ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' to hammer its
competitors in a sweep month. But then last Thursday the network
managed to pile on some additional torment for its main rival, NBC.
</P>
<P>
   ABC quietly let the Thursday edition of ``Millionaire'' run
eight minutes long, just enough to blunt the start of NBC's
strongest series, ``E.R.'' It blunted it enough for ABC to beat
``E.R.'' in its first half-hour, something no regularly scheduled
ABC show had done in the seven-year run of the hit medical drama.
</P>
<P>
   At 10 p.m., ``E.R.'' flew into an air pocket as viewers remained
hooked into the actor Ray Romano's efforts to answer questions on
``Millionaire.'' The game show had a huge 40.6 million viewers
watching from 10 p.m. to 10:08 p.m. By the time the ABC news
magazine ``20/20 Downtown'' finished out the half-hour, that number
was down to 22.5 million. But ABC's average for the half-hour of
27.3 million easily beat the 24.6 million viewers tuned into
``E.R.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC executives said it had not been a formal plan to run
``Millionaire'' long to damage ``E.R.'' But because the show had
committed to allowing every celebrity who participated in the week
of games to have a shot on the air, it had less editing flexibility
than normal. This was the case, ABC executives said, even though
the celebrity shows were taped about a month in advance.
</P>
<P>
   About a week ago, ABC's program executives were informed the
show would run long. They simply ordered the extra eight minutes to
be cut out of the coming news program.
</P>
<P>
   Having seen what a little extra ``Millionaire'' can do to the
previous prime-time ratings champ, will there be more occasions of
run over? One senior ABC executive said, ``It has not gone without
notice.''
</P>
<P>
   But another ABC program executive said, ``I really don't think
it's in the best interests of `Millionaire' to regularly tick off
fans of `E.R.'''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Bill Carter
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
