<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8287 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ISRAEL-TAXES-NYT &LR;      05-07 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-TAXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI CABINET APPROVES TAX-REFORM PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This story is also being filed in ``i'' category.) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israel's Cabinet voted to overhaul the country's tax
system for the first time in a quarter century, backing a Finance
Ministry proposal for lower income tax rates balanced by new levies
on inheritances, foreign earnings and capital gains.
</P>
<P>
   The national labor federation staged a one-hour warning strike
Sunday to protest provisions in the proposed tax package, which
will be submitted to the parliament next month. But in a rare show
of cohesion, Prime Minister Ehud Barak's coalition Cabinet endorsed
the long-awaited tax plan with a 17-0 vote with two ministers
abstaining.
</P>
<P>
   Overall tax payments for most Israelis would decline under the
new rules, the government said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest benefits, though, would accrue to those who earn the
most. The threshold for the highest tax rate _ 50 percent _ would
be raised from about $55,000 to slightly more than $100,000. The
prime minister blocked an effort Sunday by several of his ministers
to raise the highest tax rate to 60 percent, contending that level
of taxation would unfairly penalize ``people who are investing
their best resources in Israel and aiding in its development and
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The most significant change in tax policy would be the
introduction of a 25 percent capital gains tax on local stock
sales. Currently, only earnings from stocks in foreign companies in
international markets are taxed. The Tel Aviv Stock Exchange rose 4
percent Sunday _ an indicator, analysts said, that investors were
resigned to the capital gains tax even though it would eliminate
one of the few advantages of listing shares locally.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed 25 percent capital gains tax would also apply to
earnings on interest from securities and savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The package eliminates other loopholes, among them long-standing
exemptions from taxes on rental income and the partial
classification of many salaries as ``training funds'' rather than
taxable earnings. All earnings from foreign sources would be taxed
for the first time, ending special treatment for recent immigrants
and international business consultants. Salaries earned by married
women would no longer be taxed half a percentage point less than
men's wages.
</P>
<P>
   Inheritance taxes would be reintroduced after a lapse of two
decades _ but would apply only to estates of $500,000 or more.
Corporate tax breaks for capital investments would be reduced or
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Temporarily overshadowing the constant preoccupation here with
peace talks and national security issues, the tax package
galvanized national attention last week. Thousands of Israelis
quickly tried to transfer funds abroad, deed gifts to children and
open untaxed long-term savings accounts in hopes of avoiding estate
taxes and capital gains assessments. All for naught, though. The
Cabinet said the new package, if passed, would apply retroactively
to last Thursday, the day the reform proposal was first officially
announced.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition Likud Party, sounding a populist note, vowed to
join the labor movement in fighting the tax initiative. ``We object
to the inheritance tax, to a tax on long-term savings, taxes on
pension funds and training funds and canceling the tax credit for a
working woman,'' said Ariel Sharon, the party's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the near-unanimous Cabinet endorsement appears to ensure the
passage of most of the complex package, which is widely considered
the Barak government's most significant economic policy measure.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the proposed changes would have a negligible
effect on the government's overall tax collections, with new taxes
compensating for a projected decline in income tax receipts.
</P>
<P>
   David Klein, the governor of the central bank, suggested Sunday
that the reform initiative should seek to reduce the gross tax
burden here, which is comparable to that in Northern European
countries, which have average incomes nearly twice as high as in
Israel. In addition to income and social security taxes, Israelis
pay a 17 percent value-added sales tax on most goods and services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-00 1744EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000507.0058 </DOCNO>
