<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000507.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8290 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RIVER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     05-07 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIVER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BALLAD OF LITTLE RIVER': FACING LIFE WITH A SIX-PACK  
 BY RICHARD BERNSTEIN  
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is a mournful ballad of rural life in the South that Paul
Hemphill chants in his new book, ``The Ballad of Little River.'' It
is a ballad that brings to mind many cultural references, James
Agee's ``Let Us Now Praise Famous Men'' and Walker Evans' haunting
photographs of rural poverty and what Hemphill himself calls ``a
Faulknerian huddle of fairly exotic proportions.''
</P>
<P>
   Little River is an undistinguished place in southern Alabama
where in 1997 five local white youths, bored and drunk and, it
would seem, prone to racist incitement, burned down one small,
bedraggled black church, and some of them vandalized another one.
Hemphill rented a cabin in town and chronicled it for a year. His
purpose was to get to know the inhabitants, half of them black,
half white, to understand the place from which the five miscreants
had emerged.
</P>
<P>
   The result of his investigation is a melancholy and savory story
of a kind of forgotten America where people face dead-end jobs and
despair with six-packs of beer, the occasional joint and a kind of
heedless self-justification. Almost nobody has a happy story in
Hemphill's instructive and finely tuned portrait, which serves as a
reminder that the world of Agee, Evans and Faulkner is not entirely
behind us.
</P>
<P>
   Hemphill structures his story along familiar narrative lines,
portraying Little River as the kind of place where nothing much had
happened since a famous Indian massacre of the early 19th century,
until things began to unravel publicly early in 1997. A young black
man was shot and killed breaking into a white-owned home late at
night. A white grocer liked by everybody, black and white, was
savagely beaten by a black ex-convict. Then a newcomer to town held
a Ku Klux Klan rally on his five-acre spread, and two days after
that the five white youths struck at the tiny St. Joe Baptist
Church and at the somewhat larger Tate Chapel just down the country
road.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks on the churches brought an unwelcome prominence to
Little River, which lies alongside Alabama Highway 59, running
through one of the poorest counties in the United States. The
church burnings, which reflected similar incidents taking place
elsewhere in the South, were aggressively prosecuted, with the
local district attorney trying to use new hate-crime legislation to
get enhanced sentences for the defendants.
</P>
<P>
   What Hemphill succeeds in doing in his casual, understated,
almost aw-shucks way, is get under the skin of a troubled
community. And the images of American gothic life that emerge from
his piquant pages indicate that the phrase ``hate crime'' doesn't
quite explain things. A deeply rooted racial hostility certainly
existed in forlorn Little River, where one supposedly enlightened
white man accounted for the success of a local black woman by
explaining she had some white blood in her.
</P>
<P>
   But the relations between the races had always been peaceful, if
distant. The church-burning seemed more a consequence of a sort of
moral disintegration _ family violence, divorce, chronic feuding,
infidelity, heavy drinking and welfare cheating _ that was a good
deal more pronounced among Little River's whites than among its
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a gaggle of about two dozen of them out there on the
20-mile stretch of road between Little River and Uriah: white kids
who were about to graduate from high school, sons and daughters of
dysfunctional families, kids with few hopes and dreams beyond
finding some menial job or marrying within the clan, kids who had
not even been given a road map about how to live a noble life,''
Hemphill writes.
</P>
<P>
   His narrative has as much to do with getting to know the
denizens of Little River as with tracing the course of the events
that took place there. He captures the minds and mentalities of men
whose entire lives have taken place in isolated trailers parked in
steamy, piney woods, or in jail. There were, to take one example
among many possible examples, Tommy and George Boone, members of
Little River's largest white clan who, as Hemphill puts it, ``were
in a competition to see which one could get the most ink.''
</P>
<P>
   Tommy got 20 years for burglarizing fish camps and homes
throughout the area. George lived ``alone in an old trailer down a
dirt road behind the cafe run by his ex-wife and her common-law
husband, his brother Leroy.'' One morning he got taken to jail
after firing at the cafe because two other members of the Boone
clan who had denigrated him were in it. He told Hemphill:
``Attempted murder? Hell, I was just trying to get their
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Hemphill has a good ear for the vernacular, and he allows his
dramatis personae to reveal themselves without comment. But he
clearly has a good deal of sympathy for the struggling blacks of
Little River even as he avoids the temptation to sanctify them. The
pastor of St. Joe Baptist Church, Joe Dees, is the main black
figure portrayed in this book, and he is a complicated figure. He
was mentally disturbed for years; his behavior was erratic and
sometimes irresponsible, and his wrecked church, to tell the truth,
was in an advanced stage of dilapidation.
</P>
<P>
   But Dees raised five children who were doing well in life, and
his instability was a matter of chemical imbalance. An interesting
fact about Little River is that many of the town's black children
went to college while very few of the whites did. ``They had to try
harder, and they and their parents knew it,'' Hemphill concludes of
the blacks. Most of the white parents, by contrast, ``assumed that
everything would work out fine in their favor, just like it always
had, simply because of the color of their skin.''
</P>
<P>
   The events of 1997, which resulted in the imprisonment of five
white youths, showed the fatal flaw in that reasoning. Hemphill, in
demonstrating this, did not, by his own description of things, earn
great popularity among Little River's whites. Still, he has held up
a mirror to them, and to the rest of us in the complicated American
racial diorama, and it is well worth our attention.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE BALLAD OF LITTLE RIVER'
</P>
<P>
   A Tale of Race and Restless Youth in the Rural South
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Hemphill
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 235 pages. The Free Press. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
