<HEADER>
A8291 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-DIMAGGIO-REVIEW-NY     05-07 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DIMAGGIO-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JOE DIMAGGIO: THE HERO'S LIFE': GLIDING IN CENTER FIELD, SLINKING
IN THE DARK 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consider the life of Joe DiMaggio, who was such a graceful
success on the baseball field and such a miserable failure off it,
and you may wonder if he sold his soul for that 56-game hitting
streak. But after viewing the fascinating biography Monday night on
PBS' ``American Experience'' series, you might conclude that
DiMaggio had no soul to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Zwonitzer's film ``Joe DiMaggio: The Hero's Life'' paints a
damning portrait of a man who was inarticulate, proud, vain and
cheap; a man who cheated at cards, took gifts from crooks and
failed miserably as a husband (twice) and father (once). But he was
most of all a thrilling performer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We strove for more than 60 years to give Joe DiMaggio the
hero's life,'' says the narrator, Richard Ben Cramer, who wrote the
film with Zwonitzer. ``From his debut at Yankee Stadium in 1936
until his death in 1999, DiMaggio was, at every turn, one man we
could look at who made us feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   The documentary may make you feel bad. But you'll be glad you
watched it, or rather, listened to it. With its newsreel clips,
file photos and talking heads, this film looks no different from
the historical fare offered nightly on a half-dozen cable channels.
</P>
<P>
   But pay attention to the words, chiefly those spoken by Cramer
and Maury Allen, the veteran sportswriter and DiMaggio biographer,
and you'll be touched by an American tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed he was walking on air,'' Allen says of DiMaggio.
``He would glide through a stadium. He would glide through a
restaurant.'' But despite appearances, he slinked darkly through
much of his life.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio, the son of a San Francisco fisherman, found baseball
by a process of elimination. He didn't want to follow his father
onto the boat. An indifferent student, he dropped out of school at
15. From semipro ball he progressed to the minor league San
Francisco Seals. He was making money. This was worth an effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe bent his life to the game,'' Cramer says. ``He'd never had
any coaching, but now he learned like Mozart learned the piano: all
at once and instantly.''
</P>
<P>
   He tore up the Pacific Coast League; and the Yankees, at sea
since the departure of Babe Ruth, pinned their hopes on this
prospect. New York and DiMaggio took to each other. He became a
regular at Toots Shor's. And while the team never paid him what he
thought he was worth, he quickly learned that ``there was money in
just being Joe.'' He piled up endorsement fees and accepted favors,
including a Cadillac just for showing up at a Newark, N.J.,
banquet.
</P>
<P>
   His first marriage, to the movie starlet Dorothy Arnold, brought
the couple pain and Joe DiMaggio Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Father and son would never have any kind of relationship. But in
the summer of 1941, while Americans shuddered over news of a war
that was soon to envelop them, the public was happily diverted by
DiMaggio's record-setting hitting streak. ``The entire country
seemed to be emotionally involved,'' Allen says.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, though, war trumped baseball. DiMaggio became a
reluctant volunteer and spent the duration safely playing ball for
an Army team. Back with the Yankees in '46 he was beginning to feel
his age. In 1951 he saw history repeated as a kid named Mickey
Mantle showed up to claim the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   His teammate Jerry Coleman recalls DiMaggio's pain at ``watching
this halo around his shoulders sort of slip away.'' He retired and
embarked on 48 years of living on his past glories.
</P>
<P>
   His second brief and tragic marriage, to Marilyn Monroe, almost
cost DiMaggio his standing with the public. He could not bear
living in her shadow, and when she left him, she had bruises on her
face.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio retreated, appearing now and then to sign autographs or
pitch products. He had no real friends and was estranged from his
family. But somehow his legend flourished in that vacuum. ``The
more he retreated, the more our hunger for him grew,'' Cramer says.
``His blankness allowed us to make him perfect in our eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Joltin' Joe is rendered most imperfect by this cold-eyed
documentary. But his tale is worth your attention. Despite his
flaws, he is still revered. To understand why, do two things. First
watch this film. Then talk to someone who remembers the summer of
'41.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE AMERICAN EXPERIENCE'
</P>
<P>
   `Joe DiMaggio: The Hero's Life'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Monday on PBS (Channels 13 and 49 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   A production by Lennon Documentary Group for ``The American
Experience.'' Mark Zwonitzer, producer and director; Richard Ben
Cramer and Zwonitzer, writers; Bruce Shaw, editor. `The American
Experience' is a production of WGBH, Boston. Margaret Drain,
executive producer; Mark Samels, senior producer; David McCullough,
series host.
</P>
</TEXT>
