<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8292 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-UNILEVER-AD-COLUMN-NY     05-07 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNILEVER-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: THERMASILK COMMERCIALS ENTER THE BIG-BUDGET REALM 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the world of advertising, the big budget commercials with
brand name directors and fancy special effects usually go to
products like automobiles, soft drinks and sneakers. Think Nike.
Think Pepsi. Think Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Now Unilever _ a company known for its household and personal
care products _is jumping into the fray with a multimillion-dollar
extravaganza for a shampoo line.
</P>
<P>
   The British-Dutch conglomerate is staking millions in production
costs and more than $40 million in media buys to promote the
two-year-old ThermaSilk shampoo, conditioner and hair care line.
The campaign goes on the air on network television beginning
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign follows a successful introduction for ThermaSilk,
which achieved more than $120 million in sales in its first year on
the market. The benchmark for a successful product line is about
$100 million in sales. Unilever says the brand was a major reason
the company was able to overtake Procter &AMP; Gamble's longtime
leadership in the $3.7 billion hair care market.
</P>
<P>
   Created by J. Walter Thompson USA, the three new commercials are
lush, dreamlike settings of mythical places: In each one, a
princess-like woman tames a dragon or beast, and in so doing also
transforms her hair into beautiful locks. To create the lush spots,
Thompson used some 90 special effects and animation experts, and
employed a digital artist on the set.
</P>
<P>
   The fantastical settings tap into the popularity of fantasy and
magic, as witnessed by books like the Harry Potter series; in TV
shows like ``Charmed'' and ``Queen of Swords''; and even in the
newest women's fashions, which have a ``princesslike prettiness''
about them, said Cathy Lennox, management director for ThermaSilk
at Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   But the settings also dramatize an insight into the 25- to
39-year-old female audience the company is trying to reach: that
each morning women undergo a transformation when blow-drying their
hair, Lennox said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of advertising in this category talks at women; it's not
emotionally based,'' Lennox said of the campaign's approach. ``We
found heat-styling is an emotionally charged time, when a woman is
transformed. Another reason the campaign resonates with women is
that it recognizes the appeal of fantasy to escape the emotional
world.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercials cost several million dollars to produce, said
Andrew Gross, hair care category director for Unilever Home and
Personal Care USA. The average national 30-second spot costs
$295,000 to produce, according to the American Association of
Advertising Agencies in New York, a trade group.
</P>
<P>
   In one spot, a young woman is lost in a forest in medieval times
and comes upon a huge fire-breathing dragon, which she embraces,
rather than fears; his flames make her hair gorgeous. That spot,
shot in a subtropical jungle in Mexico, required a flamethrower to
light the trees in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   In another spot, a snake-haired Medusa is seen in a celestial
ballroom amid other figures from Greek mythology. To the delight of
the crowd, she dances the tango with another creature and her
viper-filled tresses are transformed into beautiful hair. An
80-piece orchestra performed the tango from an original score.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign was directed by Bruno Aveillan, known in France for
his Perrier and Galeries Lafayette commercials. Even though
Thompson used American-style special effects, the creative
directors in charge at Thompson _ Chris D'Rozario and Ed
Evangelista _ wanted the campaign to have a low-key, European
sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want a Hollywood feel, which is more obvious and
very packaged and canned,'' said D'Rozario. ``The Europeans have a
more artistic sensibility. With Bruno, each frame looks like a
painting.''
</P>
<P>
   Evangelista believes the less commercial feel of European-style
advertising is beginning to catch on here. ``The Europeans are less
literal and give the consumer more credit, and we're starting to
see more of that here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Unilever, what is significant about the campaign is that it
is based on the brand's main attribute, that its formula works with
heat to improve the hair, Gross said. Hence the campaign's slogan:
``Heat is beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What intrigued us about the idea is that it linked with the
brand proposition, which is taking heat from bad to good in a
dramatic way,'' Gross said.
</P>
<P>
   ThermaSilk's success, paired with a restaging of Unilever's
Suave brand, helped increase Unilever's market share last year to
23.9 percent of the $3.7 billion overall hair care market, edging
out P&AMP;G, which had a 22.5 percent share, according to A.C. Nielsen
Co., which tracks product sales in supermarkets, drugstores and
other outlets. This is the first time Unilever has led in the
category, Gross said.
</P>
<P>
   ThermaSilk fits in with the trend in the industry toward premium
brands with product benefits beyond smelling nice, said Wendy
Nicholson, a personal care analyst with Salomon Smith Barney in New
York. ThermaSilk retails for about $3.50 a bottle, a price that is
roughly 20 percent more than an average shampoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are more concerned about using products that are
good for them and have more therapeutic benefits,'' Nicholson said.
``No one is using the basic, just-smell-good stuff anymore;
consumers are willing to pay more for perceived product benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Nicholson noted that while P&AMP;Gs market share has eroded a
bit, it remained the leader last year in the $2.7 billion market
that includes shampoo and conditioner only. P&AMP;G had a 27 percent
share last year compared with Unilever's 20 percent, according to
Information Resources Inc., which tracks sales of packaged goods.
P&AMP;Gs Pantene is the market leader, with a 14 percent share.
ThermaSilk has a 5 percent market share and is ranked fourth,
Nicholson said. The market is highly competitive, with dozens of
new products introduced every year.
</P>
<P>
   And P&AMP;G isn't standing still. Just this year it introduced
Physique, a premium styling line with formulas that are promoted as
helping women to get and keep their hairstyles. It's a complete
line of products from shampoo to gels, priced at about $7 each. P&AMP;G
is aggressively promoting Physique, which Nicholson said was
designed to reinvigorate P&AMP;Gs hair care business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
