<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESBY-PASTOR0508-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former NASA chaplain named pastor of nation's largest
Presbyterian church
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Peachtree Presbyterian Church, the nation's largest
Presbyterian congregation, Sunday called as its new senior minister
a man whose influence has extended beyond the planet: the Rev.
Victor Pentz, pastor of First Presbyterian Church in Houston and
chaplain for three NASA mission crews.
</P>
<P>
   An almost electric buzz crackled Sunday as a standing-room-only
crowd packed the sanctuary for the vote. The 11,000-member church
has been without a senior pastor since the death in March 1999 of
the Rev. Frank Harrington, who had held the job for 28 years.
</P>
<P>
   With a photograph of Pentz projected onto large screens on both
sides of the sanctuary, Frank Skinner, chairman of the 11-member
pastor nominating committee, named Pentz as the committee's choice.
Pentz, 52, who goes by ``Vic,'' first caught the nominating
committee's attention because of the ``strength and vitality of his
sermons'' and impressed the panel with his record of community
service and his appreciation of music as a part of worship, Skinner
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pentz did not seek out the committee, Skinner said, ``we sought
him. Oh, how we sought him!''
</P>
<P>
   ``The thought of leading the Peachtree congregation takes my
breath away,'' Pentz said in a letter to the church. ``Any person
not in awe of following Dr. Harrington into the Peachtree pulpit is
not thinking clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentz was one of the founders of Presbyterians for Renewal, an
organization formed in 1989 with the mission of reinvigorating the
2.6-million-member mainline Presbyterian church. Among the group's
positions on social issues is support for maintaining the
Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) ban on ordaining sexually active
homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Pentz identifies his theology as ``ecumenical in its scope,
conservative in the sense that it is Biblically grounded, liberal
in the sense that it is open to fresh insights and new expressions.
. .''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
