</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROOKS-AUCTION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER SOTHEBY'S OFFICIAL IS IN LIMBO INSTEAD OF IN THE SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  BY CAROL VOGEL and RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In other times, this would have been Diana D. Brooks'
moment.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the multimillion-dollar spring auctions of
Impressionist and modern art at Sotheby's in New York, it was
always Brooks' striking presence and booming voice that
predominated.
</P>
<P>
   As the auction house's president and chief executive, she
cropped up on ``Charlie Rose'' or ``Today,'' talking up the
forthcoming sales. She greeted the thousands of visitors who
thronged Sotheby's York Avenue galleries to view the art coming up
for auction. Brooks, six feet tall with distinctive curly blond
hair, presided over cocktail parties, dinners and brunches in the
United States and abroad for Sotheby's big-money collectors. When
the selling began, sometimes she even wielded the auction gavel
herself.
</P>
<P>
   But as experts finish preparing for the two weeks of auctions at
Sotheby's and Christie's that begin Monday night _ hundreds of
millions of dollars' worth of art will change hands _ there is an
uncomfortable silence on York Avenue. Brooks, who had become
something of a celebrity in the 13 years since Sotheby's made her
the first woman to head an auction house, resigned under fire on
Feb. 21, along with A. Alfred Taubman, the company's chairman and
its biggest shareholder, in connection with a federal antitrust
investigation. Allegations center on whether the two colluded with
their counterparts at Christie's, Sotheby's archrival, in setting
the commissions charged to buyers and sellers. Between them
Sotheby's and Christie's dominate the multibillion-dollar auction
market.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of financial ruin or even prison has taken a toll
on Brooks and her family, friends and associates say. ``She is
extraordinarily upset and terrified about the consequences,'' one
friend said, speaking on condition of anonymity. She recently cut
her hair short and straightened it to be less recognizable. But the
friend also described her as resilient and physically fit, still
devoted to morning runs of several miles.
</P>
<P>
   Except for one visit to Sotheby's since her resignation _
several hours that employees described as painful in their
awkwardness _ Brooks, 49, has kept to herself, spending
considerable time at her mother's house in Hobe Sound, Fla., but
returning periodically to a luxury apartment on the East Side of
Manhattan and a Connecticut home.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, Michael C. Brooks, a venture capitalist,
recently bought a house in Jupiter, Fla.; Florida protects homes
from seizure in bankruptcy proceedings. The week she resigned from
Sotheby's, the couple put their 7,262-square-foot Colonial house in
Greenwich, Conn., on the market for $4 million, along with an
additional two-acre plot for $1.5 million. They also own a
residence in Lawrence, on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks turned away numerous requests for interviews, made
through one of her lawyers, Stephen E. Kaufman, and Sotheby's chief
spokeswoman, Diana Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, a longtime confidante of Brooks, said that they had
spoken from time to time since Brooks' resignation and that ``she
sounded fine.''
</P>
<P>
   As Brooks' lawyers maneuver to negotiate a settlement with the
Justice Department, her life is in limbo. If charged and found
guilty, she could be heavily fined and sentenced to up to three
years in prison. But the Justice Department could still determine
that the evidence is insufficient to warrant prosecution, or it
might offer her lenience or even immunity in exchange for her
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the case said she was prepared to testify that
Taubman had directed her to meet with her counterpart at
Christie's, Christopher M. Davidge, to discuss price-fixing
arrangements. But they said she would give such testimony only in
exchange for favorable treatment from prosecutors. Such a statement
would support one made by Davidge, who has told the government that
a former chairman of Christie's, Sir Anthony Tennant, devised the
price-fixing scheme in meetings with Taubman and then instructed
Davidge to carry it out on behalf of Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's turned over documentation from Davidge to the
government and has received immunity dependent on its continued
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Through their lawyers Taubman and Sir Anthony have disputed the
accounts and denied any wrongdoing. The chief Justice Department
antitrust prosecutor in New York, John J. Greene, has consistently
declined to discuss the case.
</P>
<P>
   Life at Sotheby's is not going on entirely without Brooks.
Although she is no longer a company officer _ she and Taubman are
now listed only as board members in Sotheby's catalogs, and even
those references will soon disappear as neither is standing for
re-election _ she remains on her full salary of $600,000, people
close to her said.
</P>
<P>
   William F. Ruprecht, Sotheby's new chief executive, who joined
the company in 1980, confirmed only that she was still getting paid
for helping with what he called the transition. Art dealers say
that she has been calling their clients, hoping to win business for
Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   So big was her role at Sotheby's that it was impossible for her
simply to walk away, officials at the company say. It was Brooks
who shaped relationships with the company's most important clients,
often pre-empting other Sotheby's specialists. It was Brooks who
brokered every important deal, whether for a highly valuable
Picasso or for a giant canary diamond.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a very smart, innovative thinker,'' said George Goldner,
chairman of the department of prints and drawings at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, who negotiated complicated deals with
Sotheby's while curator of paintings and drawings at the J. Paul
Getty Museum in Los Angeles. ``She was not restricted by the boring
ways most people buy and sell art.''
</P>
<P>
   Collectors and dealers say they do not believe the Justice
Department investigation will hamper a serious collector who covets
a Monet or a Matisse. But in an auction world governed by the
``three D's'' _ death, divorce and debt _ the robust economy is
such that collectors who don't have to part with their artworks are
holding on to them. Since no big collectors died this past winter,
experts at both Sotheby's and Christie's were left to scramble for
property.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Brooks was Sotheby's most powerful business getter.
</P>
<P>
   The first daughter of a family of six children, Brooks was
brought up comfortably on the North Shore of Long Island. She once
said she remembered her father, Martin, telling her she could do
anything her two older brothers did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believed him,'' she said years ago. ``When I was 8, I
announced I wanted to go to Yale.'' She graduated from Yale in
1972.
</P>
<P>
   The man she would marry, Brooks, was also a Yale graduate. Their
eldest child, a daughter, graduated from Yale last year.
</P>
<P>
   Her father controlled the only private water company covering a
part of New York City, the Jamaica Water Co. After he died in 1977,
Brooks' brother, Andrew, took over the company, then called Jamaica
Water Properties, and through rapid acquisitions built it into the
nation's largest computer reseller, a multibillion-dollar public
company renamed JWP Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks later joined the board of JWP but left before December
1993, when the company collapsed in bankruptcy and litigation
charging fraud in bookkeeping. JWP later re-emerged as the Emcor
Group. A lawsuit by insurance companies seeking to recover $148
million from Ernst &AMP; Young, JWP's accounting firm, was recently
reinstated by the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New York.
Brooks was not a defendant in the actions.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks got to Sotheby's by accident. In 1979, while taking a
leave from Citibank, where she was a lending officer, to spend more
time with her infant daughter, she was told by a friend that
Sotheby's was looking for a business person. She was hired part
time as director of financial planning and soon assumed the job
full time.
</P>
<P>
   For four years Brooks, who is known to her friends and
colleagues as Dede (pronounced DEE-Dee), concentrated on the
business side of the company. Then she moved into a more
administrative position. That was in 1982, when the company's
profits were down and its staff bloated. Through buyouts and pink
slips, Brooks reduced the staff by 90. The move earned her praise
from some outside financial analysts, but some inside the company
called her ``the hatchet woman.''
</P>
<P>
   As a boss Brooks was known for putting a premium on the
company's profitability and seeking out new business opportunities,
for instance, using the Internet and offering clients insurance.
She stressed that the company's future depended on reaching beyond
the traditional deep-pocketed buyer.
</P>
<P>
   But her management style lacked subtlety and got mixed reviews.
``Dede is an extremely smart person, effective in putting teams
together in every imaginable project and creative in bringing
people together, often outside their regular expertise,'' her
successor, Ruprecht, said. ``We had a full and frank relationship
with each other, and `warm' needs to get added to that.''
</P>
<P>
   But some colleagues and former Sotheby's employees, who signed
confidentiality agreements in exchange for lucrative financial
settlements but who agreed to speak on condition of anonymity, said
she displayed a temper and willfulness, sometimes directed even at
Taubman, the chairman, who himself is strong willed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing happened without her knowledge or say-so,'' said one
former employee. ``She micromanaged everything.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ruprecht made light of such accounts, saying, ``She
deconstructed some things and put them back together.'' He called
her ``a conciliator and provocateur, as any boss needs to be,''
adding, ``We worked all the time in concert _ not all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, despite occasional frictions, Brooks won the
support and respect of Taubman. ``I think they worked closely with
each other for a long period of time,'' Ruprecht said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990 she was elected to the board of the Yale Corp., on which
she still serves. She and her husband have contributed generously
to the university.
</P>
<P>
   She was asked to leave another board, however, that of Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, after she resigned at Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   She supports various charities, including a juvenile outreach
program in Baltimore that she and two friends started after Brooks'
godson, a 19-year-old high school student, committed suicide two
years ago. A sportswoman who runs nearly every day and was known to
have whipped male employees on company golf outings, Brooks
frequently spends vacations tackling challenging pursuits like
helicopter skiing.
</P>
<P>
   Her competitive side was just as visible in the office. When the
company arranged with Amazon.com last year to create a new Web site
called Sothebys.Amazon.com, which sells collectibles online, Brooks
was all over the airwaves once more. The company has poured tens of
millions of dollars into that site and a sister one, and once more
Brooks was not only Sotheby's champion, but also its
personification. Promotions for the Amazon venture featured a
picture of Jeff Bezos, chairman and founder of Amazon, and Brooks
posed together in a gilt frame.
</P>
<P>
   That was only last summer, but in many ways it was a long time
ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
