<HEADLINE>
ACADEMY ANNOUNCES WINNERS OF ROME PRIZE  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Calif., Texas, Mass., Wash., D.C., N.J., Ind., Ill.,
Pa., Va., England)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The winners of the annual Rome Prize Competition have been
announced by the American Academy in Rome, a center for independent
study, research and creative work in the arts and humanities.
</P>
<P>
   The prizes are administered by the academy at its headquarters
in New York City and include stipends and living and working
accommodations on the academy's Rome campus for six months to two
years.
</P>
<P>
   The winners will join the art historian Areli Marina and the
classicist Ann Marie Yasin, who will complete the second and final
year of their fellowships.
</P>
<P>
   The academy is supported by private donations and by the
National Endowment for the Arts, the National Endowment for the
Humanities and the United States Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   These are the 2000-01 winners:
</P>
<P>
   ARCHITECTURE
</P>
<P>
   Michael Goorevich, Cleveland
</P>
<P>
   Richard Taransky, Haddonfield, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   DESIGN ARTS
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Krohn, Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   Michael Palladino, Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   HISTORIC PRESERVATION AND CONSERVATION
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Walmsley, Washington
</P>
<P>
   Deirdre Windsor, Dover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   LANDSCAPE ARCHITECTURE
</P>
<P>
   Mark Klopfer, Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   David Meyer, Berkeley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   LITERATURE
</P>
<P>
   Sigrid Nunez, New York
</P>
<P>
   MUSICAL COMPOSITION
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hersch, Forest Hills, Queens, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Jalbert, Stafford, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   VISUAL ARTS
</P>
<P>
   Dara Friedman, Miami Beach and New York
</P>
<P>
   Lyle Ashton Harris, New York
</P>
<P>
   Gary Hill, Seattle
</P>
<P>
   Donald Lipski, Sag Harbor, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL STUDIES AND ARCHAEOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Dossey, Chicago
</P>
<P>
   John Curtis Franklin, London
</P>
<P>
   Karen E. Klaiber, New Brunswick, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos F. Norena, Philadelphia
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Zissos, Austin, Texas
</P>
<P>
   HISTORY OF ART
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer R. Bethke, Berkeley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Charles M. Rosenberg, South Bend, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Stefanie Walker, New York
</P>
<P>
   POSTCLASSICAL HUMANISTIC/MODERN ITALIAN STUDIES
</P>
<P>
   Joanna H. Drell, Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Michael R. Ebner, New York
</P>
<P>
   H. Darrel Rutkin, Bloomington, Ind.
</P>
