<HEADER>
A8300 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MILLION-DOLLAR-KID050     05-07 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLION-DOLLAR-KID0508-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: Fix includes student's first name.
 &HT;    Student awarded scholarships to five U.S. military academies
 &HT;    By Mary Ellen Flannery
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE WORTH, Fla. _ Maybe in these days of tech stocks and
teenage millionaires, it's not so unusual to hear about a kid worth
just over $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   But at Lake Worth High School, there's a senior who earned it in
the old-fashioned way. He studied his calculus, volunteered in the
town's parks, and applied to all five American military academies _
and was accepted.
</P>
<P>
   There's $250,000 from West Point, the U.S. Army's academy;
another quarter-million from the U.S. Naval Academy in Annapolis,
Md.; not to mention the money from the Air Force, Coast Guard and
Merchant Marines, and the Navy's scholarship to University of San
Diego _ worth more than $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Petty Officer Ron Spellman, a public affairs officer at the U.S.
Coast Guard Academy, didn't have specific numbers on how many
students get accepted into all five military academies. But, he
said, ``It's far from a common thing.''
</P>
<P>
   On July 1, Matt Tanguay will report to the U.S. Coast Guard
Academy in New London, Conn., for his new haircut and dress whites.
He will study naval architecture and prepare for a career as a
Coast Guard officer. It was his first choice all along, fulfilling
his desire to spend his life near the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   And still, Tanguay is as calm as a flat sea in the sunshine _
years and years of waiting for the right wave on a surfboard off
Lantana Beach will do that to you _ as he explained the work that
went into his recent success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've sacrificed a lot of parties to work on school projects or
get my homework finished, but I think it'll work out in the long
run,'' said Tanguay, who has a career 3.9 grade point average. ``I
think most of my friends would say first that I'm a nerd. I like to
read, I like to do my homework, I'm happy when I'm doing my
calculus _ that's my personality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to learn,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But after they thought about it a little, I think they'd say _
Matt's a leader, because I'm the guy who's always making plans for
them, telling them where to go. And they'd say I have good morals,
I'm trustworthy, that I'm a good person. There was this day when
the soda machine was unlocked and everyone was saying _ Free Sodas!
_ and I said, 'That's all right. If I want a soda, I'll pay for
one.' ``
</P>
<P>
   There also was the night that Tanguay stopped a carful of
friends because an elderly woman on the sidewalk was getting
hassled by some kids, he said. They were on their way back from
``Fiddler on the Roof'' rehearsals two years ago _ Tanguay played
the rabbi's son, a minor part, he said modestly _ when they saw the
woman poking her cane at her antagonizers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be (upset) if I saw my grandmother getting hassled,''
Tanguay recalled. ``So I said 'Hey, stop the car' and we chased the
kids away.''
</P>
<P>
   Tanguay is the perfect kid, Cotter said. He competed on the high
school's wrestling and golf teams; he's taking three advanced
classes this semester; and he's won the school's Most Spirited
award four years running. He also helped rebuild a local park and
rang a Salvation Army bell at Christmas, and he's held high-ranking
positions in ROTC since the summer after his freshman year. Back
then, Cotter asked him to take on public affairs duties for the
unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got everybody but Dan Rather and Tom Brokaw to show up,''
Cotter said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Tanguay said ROTC has given him leadership skills,
taught him how to lead by example, and feel comfortable in a
uniform. And he said he knows it sounds corny, but it has made him
feel part of a team or brotherhood _ one where it's actually cool
to do well in school _ and he hopes he has the same feeling in the
Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
   West Point is better known. Annapolis is right on the Chesapeake
Bay. But Tanguay doesn't want to spend his life preparing for war,
he said, and the Coast Guard has a peacetime mission. After a
summer at the Coast Guard's Academy Introductory Mission program,
which simulates the first few weeks of a typical freshman year,
Tanguay knew he wanted to go there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't walk away saying it was fun, but I said it was
something I want to be part of,'' he said. ``Honestly, I want to be
a Coast Guard officer. It's not like I just want the free
schooling, and then I'm going to ditch them.''
</P>
<P>
   Tanguay hopes one day, one perfect day, to be somewhere in
Hawaii, commanding a Coast Guard cutter making its way to yet
another spectacular rescue, or another day of environmental
clean-up, or just another day of sea and sun.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
