<HEADER>
A8305 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TAVENER-MUSIC-REVIEW-     05-07 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAVENER-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERMONS PUNCTUATE AN EVENING OF TAVENER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JON PARELES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The concert of Sir John Tavener's music at the Church
of St. Ignatius Loyola last Thursday night included minisermons
from the composer. He spoke about the power of Jesus, about the
``metaphysical subtext'' of his own music and about summoning the
divine imagination to go ``beyond the realm of our contemporary
scientific mass-genocidal world.'' That same mixture of humility
and grandeur informs his compositions. Nearly every piece on the
program was an elegy or a prayer; the music quietly contemplated
death, then turned triumphal as it invoked resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   Tavener's music has a neomedieval aura. He reaches back to the
modality of Renaissance music and outward to non-Western music,
particularly the sound of liturgical music from the Russian
Orthodox Church, which he has joined. Along with such mystical
minimalists as Arvo Paert, he stands aside from Europe's last 400
years, as if seeking purity through asceticism. The music rejects
the bustle and compromises of everyday life; it's a pristine
sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   The program was performed by the Tallis Scholars, a vocal
ensemble directed by Peter Phillips that usually sings Renaissance
music. Using a minimum of vibrato on Tavener's stately legato
phrases, they sustained the music's otherworldly calm.
</P>
<P>
   At its best Tavener's music projects simplicity without turning
simplistic. ``Song for Athene,'' which was sung at the funeral of
Diana, Princess of Wales, set out what could almost be a cozy
Anglican hymn, then moved through modernist dissonances before
resounding organ chords proclaimed an entrance into paradise. ``In
the Month of Athyr'' sets a poem by C.P. Cavafy, musing over a
worn, ancient tombstone. The chorus sings the few words _
``tears,'' ``grief'' _ that can be read in clear parallel lines
over a drone, while a narrator describes the scene. Last Thursday
night the somber narrator was Sir Paul McCartney, who drew some
Beatles fans to the sold-out concert.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the pieces on the program were modeled after antiphonal
church music, with a chantlike solo voice answered by choral
polyphony in which Tavener takes modern liberties. Some chorales
had austere modal harmonies; in others, independent lines wandered
toward impassive dissonance. Occasionally women's voices floated
upward in chromatic harmonies out of Debussy, like sirens in a
Hollywood epic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lament of the Mother of God'' generated drama with an
elementary strategy: as Mary poured out her grief, the key moved
upward with every verse. Patricia Rozario sang the demanding part
with sorrowful concentration. She was also the soloist in ``A New
Beginning,'' commissioned for Britain's Year 2000 celebration. The
music ended gently after the inevitable trumpets and drums.
</P>
<P>
   When the Flux String Quartet performed ``The Hidden Treasure,''
a lengthy, episodic piece based on earnest cello melodies (with
some Slavic inflections) and ghostly high chords, the music grew
threadbare. It needed text, not subtext. But tied to human voices,
Alleluias and words about death and transcendence, Tavener's music
was filled with serene reverence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
