<P>
   FAIRBANKS-OBIT _ Douglas Fairbanks Jr., a star of stage, screen
and television, a friend to royalty, a real-life war hero who spent
many years in Palm Beach, died Sunday. He was 90. Mr. Fairbanks
died from natural causes at Mount Sinai Medical Center in New York.
He had suffered from Parkinson's disease for years, said his former
personal assistant, Kay Hutchins. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-CIRCUIT _ ATLANTA _ The federal appeals court in Atlanta,
in recent years, has consistently sided with the government in
matters of immigration, much to the chagrin of immigration and
civil rights lawyers. A look at the court's recent major
immigration rulings, with an eye toward their influence over the
case of Elian Gonzalez, as well as the three judges presiding over
the matter. One judge is considered the court's most conservative _
and influential. Another is a former Alabama state judge and the
third is the court's only African-American, a conservative
appointee of President Clinton's. (Rankin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-COURTBOX _ ATLANTA _ Just what does the 11th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals do? How many judges does it have? Who are they?
How does it operate? Explainer box. (Rankin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON _ CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. The all-white Monticello
Association presents an interim report Sunday on what
qualifications it will require of slave Sally Hemings' relatives to
become members. Members of the association are entitled to burial
in the Monticello graveyard of Thomas Jefferson, a privilege sought
by some Hemings' descendents. Coverage of the Jefferson family's
annual business meeting. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   PRESBY-PASTOR _ ATLANTA _ Peachtree Presbyterian Church, which
is the largest mainline Presbyterian Church in the country with
12,000 members, votes on a new pastor at a congregational meeting.
(GWhite, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MENSA _ ATLANTA _ Mensa is the high-IQ society, a serious group
of people. From Friday through Sunday, though, they'll be doing
something that seems out of character: Mensans from around the
country will gather at a College Park hotel to play board games.
They do have a serious purpose, though, as you might expect:
They'll be rating the board games, all new releases, for the Mensa
seal of approval. (MacDonald, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   MILLION-DOLLAR-KID _ LAKE WORTH, Fla. _ Maybe in these days of
tech stocks and teenage millionaires, it's not so unusual to hear
about a kid worth just over $1 million. But at Lake Worth High
School, there's a senior who earned it in the old-fashioned way. He
studied his calculus, volunteered in the town's parks, and applied
to all five American military academies _ and was accepted.
(Flannery, Palm Beach Post). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLES
</P>
<P>
   COUPON-LADY _ It's 7:30 p.m. on a weeknight and the usual
post-work crowd of customers at the H-E-B is lined up to check out.
In Lane 6, parents entertain small children in baskets, bachelors
hold cases of brew and professionals loosen ties and remove jackets
while they thumb through magazines. No one in Lane 6 seems to mind
that they're waiting in the longest line in the store. That often
happens when Jacklynn Adams is on the other side of the register.
(Allmon, Waco Tribune-Herald). WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   VIRUS-BIZ _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Some companies were spared the full
wrath of the ILOVEYOU virus because of lessons learned a year ago
when Melissa struck. The lesson from them and others: As Internet
use becomes more and more prevalent, companies that have spent more
time and money on security will be the ones still doing business
when viruses strike. (Pletz, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIALEZZARD-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Warning: This column
could be hazardous to people infected with political cynicism. A
politician in hot water for trying to do the right thing? It's a
rarity. But that's what happened to Gov. Roy Barnes recently.
(Ezzard, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
