<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8311 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-VIENNA-MUSIC-REVIEW-N     05-07 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIENNA-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FRAU OHNE SCHATTEN': FREUDIAN OVERTONES FOR A SHADOWLESS BRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ In a highly charged political atmosphere, it
was the performance of Beethoven's Ninth Symphony on Sunday evening
at the site of a Nazi camp in Mauthausen that caught the attention
of the larger world.
</P>
<P>
   Yet everything about this past weekend was unusual for the
Vienna Philharmonic: even the workload, substantial as that
typically is. The orchestra, which is drawn from forces of the
Vienna State Opera, played the Beethoven on Friday evening and
Saturday afternoon, with another performance to follow Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday evening most of the same players worked in the opera
pit for Strauss' ``Frau Ohne Schatten,'' beginning a second round
of Robert Carsen's new production _ the first production of the
work here in 35 years _ which played briefly in December. (Bizet's
``Carmen,'' on Sunday evening, was assigned to another contingent
of the opera orchestra.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet clearly nothing was held back in the Strauss opera, which
was given its premiere here in 1919 and depends heavily on
orchestral power and brilliance. Giuseppe Sinopoli conducted with
good pacing, generally giving sufficient quarter to singers who
needed relatively little.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Voigt was especially fine as the mythical Empress,
tortured by her lack of a shadow, not to say her inability to have
children. As at the Metropolitan Opera, Voigt's clear,
well-supported tone carried over the orchestra with apparent ease.
</P>
<P>
   Her effort was rivaled in strength and staying power, and at
times in sheer tonal beauty, by Falk Struckmann as Barak, the Dyer.
Ben Heppner, as the Emperor, appeared to be working harder to put
across his finely honed sound. And Gabriele Schnaut, as the Dyer's
Wife, though stentorian through two acts, seemed to weary in the
third, shading flat and sounding a bit stressed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, all rose well to their big moments, as did Jane Henschel,
the Nurse, to hers at the end of Act 2.
</P>
<P>
   To two favorite sons of Vienna, Strauss and his librettist here,
Hugo von Hofmannsthal, Carsen's concept added a third: Freud. The
production made much not only of shadows but also of doors and
mirror images, and the program book followed course with essays
like ``Barak, Dyer and Psychotherapist.''
</P>
<P>
   The mythical realm went by the board _ or to stick to the
conceit, was sublimated _ in Carsen's set, which, centering on the
bedroom where the Empress spent so much time twisting and turning
in agony, resembled nothing so much as a hotel room left shortly
before, a block away on the city's famous Ring.
</P>
<P>
   The Dyer's lair, where couplings grew confused, was a recessed
version of same, disheveled as if in dream, with a place up front _
again, back in my hotel room, it sometimes seemed _ to sit around a
primitive fire.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even by the standards of the subconscious, some images
proved ludicrous. Not soon will one forget the sight of Heppner,
stuffed into a three-piece suit, standing on the Empress' bed,
hovering precariously over Voigt while grasping for reasons not to
shoot her with his pretended bow and arrow.
</P>
<P>
   To compensate for such oppressive drabness, Carsen supplied
lighting design that was often brilliant, if occasionally
self-consciously so. Aided by the costumes of Michael Levine, he
managed to leave the Empress largely shadowless in a world of
looming silhouettes.
</P>
<P>
   And in Strauss' actual dream scene, in Act 2, he showed the
Empress in bed as if from above, superimposing film projections on
a scrim in front of her: an imaginative yet unobtrusive use of
technology to startling effect.
</P>
<P>
   But the image that proved most haunting on this occasion was a
hackneyed one: a sea of corpses surrounding the Empress as she was
coming to accept responsibility for human misery. For a viewer on
his way to Mauthausen, the scene, however stagy, was too literal
for comfort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
