<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8312 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TODD-MUSIC-REVIEW-ART     05-07 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TODD-MUSIC-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SWEENY TODD': SPLENDID PERFORMANCE, POWERFUL THEATER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT18 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The question is boring, but one is obliged to ask it.
Is ``Sweeney Todd'' an opera? Here are three definitive answers: 1)
I don't care. 2) It doesn't matter. 3) No.
</P>
<P>
   No, at least as applied to Friday night's splendid performance
at Avery Fisher Hall. Maybe we are wrong to look for the label in
the garment. Maybe the name of the thing is in the eye of the
beholder: different onlooker, different measurements. (Einstein,
take note). Stephen Sondheim's grimly funny blood bath of a show,
which opened on Broadway in 1979 and has been much in our thoughts
ever since, is opera for those who expect it to be. But it was
certainly American musical theater for the wildly enthusiastic
audience that came to this, the second of the New York
Philharmonic's three performances.
</P>
<P>
   Describe Friday's event as ``semi-staged'' or an ``oratorio with
movement,'' a crisply managed version, directed by Lonny Price and
conducted by Andrew Litton. It was in the end a hybrid that drew
its elements from the place it was in and the materials with which
it was presented. The customary threat to operas-in-concert is an
orchestra not recessed in a theater pit but onstage, where its
members can cheerfully douse all but the mightiest singers in a
high tide of sound. Confronted by voice amplification, the mighty
Philharmonic offered only docile background to Sondheim's intricate
wordplay.
</P>
<P>
   To innocent ears this quasi-public-address system sounded
ghastly, but Broadway has found such electric tools useful in
combatting the challenged attention spans and hearing-impaired
spirits of the theater's new audiences. Amplification serves words,
and what separates Sondheim's art from grand opera is its literacy.
In ``Sweeney Todd'' words drive music. In Puccini music smothers
language, helpfully rescuing us from a lot of execrable melodrama.
Why else those printed librettos, supertitles and back-of-the-seat
television screens, bearing messages that in the end we wish we had
never read. (Ignorance can be bliss.)
</P>
<P>
   The Philharmonic's cast was evenly split between two art forms:
George Hearn, Patti LuPone, Audra McDonald, Davis Gaines and Neil
Patrick Harris drifting in and out of operatic voice but mainly
articulating texts as Broadway has taught them to do; Heidi Grant
Murphy, Paul Plishka, John Aler and Stanford Olsen working very
hard to make their big voices serve words.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Choral Artists, more accustomed to delivering Verdi
and Beethoven from a standing position, were prodded admirably by
their guest conductor, Grant Gershon, to march, writhe and
generally turn themselves into actors. They also sang very well.
</P>
<P>
   Broadway or opera? Again, the audience made that decision.
Murphy and Plishka, both first rate, received polite enthusiasm,
while Hearn and LuPone were engulfed in delirious ovations.
</P>
<P>
   Just as opera has its cults of the voice, musical theater
enthusiasts like those in Fisher Hall have their icons, too. Hearn
in the title role was splendid: self-possessed, clear of speech and
manipulating a cavernous voice to good effect. LuPone's Mrs. Lovett
exuded energetic charm but made this set of ears work very hard to
distinguish everything she said and sang.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's Beggar Woman was flat-out, concentrated emotion.
Harris' patter sounded admirably distinct. Gaines' throbbing
sentimentality bordered on overkill but was bearable in small
doses.
</P>
<P>
   At the end the original question comes back, and in reflection
it may not be so boring after all. Naming things _ opera, musical,
oratorio, symphony concert _ is after all how we make sense of the
world. One person walks through a forest or a flower bed and sees
masses of green, yellow, purple and white. Another identifies
spruce, oak, peonies and azaleas. The names are like eyeglasses;
they turn the vague into the specific; they sort out experience for
the senses.
</P>
<P>
   All this, I think, is true, but it still doesn't help me in
naming ``Sweeney Todd.'' I know that Sondheim has created powerful
and lasting theater, but that is about all I know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
