<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8318 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     05-07 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE DEAN OF DISCIPLINE IS ON THE CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One hundred and ninety eight times in his career,
Frank Robinson was either plugged, plunked, clipped, grazed,
drilled or beaned by a baseball, the third-highest total in Major
League Baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, however, says only once was he provoked to take a step
or two toward the mound, and that was against San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a reputation, and there were circumstances,'' he
explained the other day, adding that the Giants had whacked him in
the same arm five days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, when a pitcher throws the ball on the inside of the
plate, hitters see it as an insult that must be avenged on the
spot.
</P>
<P>
   In charge of sorting all this out is Robinson, baseball's vice
president of on-field operations, who brings the instant
credibility of a Hall of Fame hitter who later managed three teams
and maybe, a time or two, ordered a knockdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dynamics have changed,'' Robinson said the other day.
``There was no warning rule when I played. You had to protect
yourself. If a pitcher wanted to hit you five times in a game, he
could. Today, if the umpire feels a pitcher deliberately hit
somebody, he can eject him from a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week Robinson suspended Pedro Martinez, one of the best
pitchers in the universe, for five games for hitting a batter after
having been warned by an umpire not to retaliate for a previous hit
batter. Robinson will not discuss the specifics but will discuss
the nasty borderline between professional intimidation and flat-out
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   As a card-carrying member of the hitters union (586 homers, .294
career average), he gives the impression the hitters are even more
out of control than the pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A: The other day, Dennis Cook of the Mets hit Marvin
Benard of the Giants in the back _ tied score, eighth inning, one
out, runners on second and third. Benard stepped in front of home
and glared at Cook, long enough to empty both benches, just one
hothead short of a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the score,'' Robinson said. ``Benard's a lefty, Cook's
a lefty, he wants to get him out. It's times like that when batters
should realize pitchers don't have perfect control.''
</P>
<P>
   In these expansion days, when many great athletes are out trying
to be the next Michael Jordan, baseball is stuck with untrained
pitchers who can't work inside and hitters who flail at everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an art to pitching inside,'' Robinson said. ``There
is an art of brushing back a hitter. There is also an art of
getting out of the way of a pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledges the tradition of headhunters: ``There are always
guys who are not good enough to get people out. If you have to
resort to that, it's pretty bad.''
</P>
<P>
   And he talks with reverence about Don Drysdale, who at least
smiled in a vicious sort of way, and Bob Gibson, who was downright
tetchy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did they call Sal Maglie the Barber?'' Robinson added, in
homage to the glowering New York presence of the 1950s. ``Because
he knew how to shave you.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said today's hitters rarely think: ``Hey, it was my
fault. I didn't react.'' He added, ``The hitters today are all
looking for the ball away. The pitcher has the right to pitch
inside, but if they throw at the head or the shoulder, they should
be penalized.''
</P>
<P>
   He has his theories on why tempers are up.
</P>
<P>
   ``A whole generation has come up,'' Robinson said. ``Maybe it's
the aluminum bats they use as kids. Pitchers don't get used to
pitching inside because they are not rewarded for it. Now you get
into pro ball and the pitchers try to reclaim the inside of the
plate and they don't know how to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said he once managed a hitter who said, ``Hey, tell
them to get the ball over the plate.'' He had to explain to his
hitter that it was part of the game to run the ball inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk like that, they look at you like you're from
another era,'' Robinson said, ``which maybe I am.''
</P>
<P>
   He set an example for Don Baylor, the career-leading hit batsman
with 267, who would take one on a meaty part of the body, smart
enough to know he had just made the equivalent of a single. Ron
Hunt, second with 243, had lesser talents and wore baggy uniforms,
hung over the plate, and smirked as he trotted down to first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today it's just like the NBA,'' Robinson said, referring to
the sport that hangs around far too long into baseball weather.
``Today you have players dunking on people, jawing at people. It's
the same thing in baseball. The pitcher throws inside, he's staring
at the hitter, the hitter is jawing back at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm trying to get across to pitchers is that they don't
have to retaliate,'' added Robinson, who took the feistiness of the
National League to the placid Brother-in-Law League back in 1966.
``There are other ways to settle things. You can slide hard into a
base.''
</P>
<P>
   Some players are hard to miss because of their lunging habits
and their miscellaneous armor, said Joe Torre, the manager of the
Yankees: ``Mo Vaughn, you can't pitch inside to him with all that
equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the mandatory helmets, players now wear elbow
guards, shin guards, wrist guards that theoretically protect
against injury but also bulge out a an inch or three, thereby
making it easier for them to get hit and escalate the cycle of
resentment.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers of hit batsmen are up slightly from 278 to 300 in
the first 412 games of both 1999 to 2000, which may be
statistically meaningless. Home runs are surely up. The balls are
tightly wound _ and so are the players. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-00 1833EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
