<SLUG> BC-RUN-MARATHON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEHAVEN FINISHES FIRST ON AN OLYMPIC TRIALS SURVIVAL COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ In the brutal heat and humidity, legs cramped and
blisters bled through shoes and some of the runners left the finish
line on stretchers instead of on their feet. Rod DeHaven reached
the tape first Sunday after 26.2 miles at an Olympic trials that
became more about survival than speed. It also left American
marathoning at a state of utter depletion.
</P>
<P>
   DeHaven's winning time was 2 hours 15 minutes 30 seconds,
respectable for a day in which the temperature on a hilly course
hit 77 degrees by mid-morning with 57 percent humidity. But because
he did not achieve the Olympic ``A'' qualifying standard of 2:14,
DeHaven will be the lone American representative in the men's
marathon at the Summer Games for the first time since 1896.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Clark will also be the lone American in the women's
marathon at the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia, in
September. In the past, when stringent time requirements were not
imposed, the United States sent three male and female marathoners
to the Games. But the situation has grown dire as the rest of the
world has gotten faster and international Olympic officials have
begun to restrict the number of athletes competing in the
ever-growing Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's race left even the winner curiously downcast, and left
track and field officials to contemplate significant changes in the
way the Olympic marathon trials are conducted, as well as the way
American marathoners are trained.
</P>
<P>
   ``The win is pretty significant,'' said DeHaven, who is a
33-year-old computer programmer from Madison, Wis., and who earned
$75,000 for his victory. ``But being the only one going doesn't
leave me with the best taste in my mouth. Maybe this is the low
point for marathoning in the country. Maybe we can go up from
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh was awarded the 2000 trials in the spring of 1998
when it was the only city to offer to pay air fare, per diem and
prize money to the elite marathoners. Organizers could not have
known that the weather would be this awful. To prevent a recurrence
of unexpected heat, slow times and minimal representation in the
Olympics, officials and runners have suggested putting future
marathon trials on cooler, flatter courses.
</P>
<P>
   Also, officials said, ways must be found to make American
runners faster. The methods may include programs that identify
potential marathoners at an early age, group training camps and
financial support in the years between the end of college and the
late 20s, an age when many distance careers begin to blossom. Such
an assistance effort would cost $1 million a year, said Craig
Masback, the chief executive of USA Track and Field, the sport's
national governing body.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never been able to raise that money,'' Masback said.
</P>
<P>
   But, everyone agrees, something has to change if the Americans
are to regain their international competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's safe to say we will never again have an Olympic
trials that will be this hot or this slow,'' said Danny Grimes,
chairman of USA Track and Field's long distance-running committee.
</P>
<P>
   DeHaven's winning time was the slowest at the American Olympic
trials since 1972. Peter De La Cerda, who had been the pacemaker
the past two years at the Pittsburgh Marathon, took the lead
between Miles 12 and 13 and held it until the patient DeHaven took
the lead after 22.5 miles. On a slight downhill, DeHaven ran Mile
24 in 4:56 and put the race out of touch. De La Cerda finished
second in 2:16:18. Mark Coogan, a 1996 Olympian, took third in
2:17:04.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to say I had a grand plan, but it was totally a race
of attrition,'' DeHaven said.
</P>
<P>
   Only nine of the 99 starters ran under 2:20. Another 21 runners
dropped out during the race. David Morris, the American
record-holder in 2:09:36, began suffering from abdominal cramps at
Mile 2 and briefly stopped in the 15th mile. He finished 38th in
2:29:36. Morris said he had become anxious over the 2:14 Olympic
standard and uncertainty about whether Khalid Khannouchi, the
Moroccan-born world-record holder who got his American citizenship
last Wednesday, would compete. He did not because of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't sleep at all this week,'' Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   DeHaven, who was able to train more efficiently after reducing
his work in the computer business to part-time, said the heat and
humidity were not as bad as he had expected. The conditions were
worse at the 1999 world championships, held last August in Seville,
Spain, where DeHaven was the top American finisher in 24th place.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a couple areas, the cigarette smoke was so thick I could
hardly breathe,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
