u s BC-RAC-PEGASUS-NYT &LR;      05-07 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PEGASUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE DERBY WINNER FUELS GREAT EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ For the $4 million he spent to buy Fusaichi
Pegasus as a yearling, Fusao Sekiguchi of Tokyo is reaping racing's
richest rewards. His horse has won five straight races in four
months and he won the Kentucky Derby with an awesome display of
speed and power on Saturday while conquering one of the strongest
fields in Derby history. He also broke the ``jinx'' that for 20
years has kept the favorite from reaching the winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, Fusaichi Pegasus has endowed the sport of
thoroughbred racing with the thing it needs most: great
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The last three colts to win the Derby _ Silver Charm, Real Quiet
and Charismatic _ went on to win the Preakness. But, on the edge of
sweeping the Triple Crown, they lost the Belmont Stakes. Still,
they brought huge crowds to Churchill Downs, Pimlico and Belmont
Park to see if racing would unveil its 12th Triple Crown winner,
and the first since Affirmed in 1978 to sweep all three classics.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus is a third of the way there, and rarely has a
Derby winner looked so imposing. Perhaps not since Secretariat in
1973 has any horse so captured the public's fancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very talented horse,'' said his English trainer,
Neil Drysdale, still speaking conservatively from his pulpit
outside Barn 41 at Churchill Downs on the morning after the Derby.
``And he looks like he's got a very bright future in front of him.
So, it was very rewarding to watch the talent come through, and for
him to show that talent.''
</P>
<P>
   The jockeys and trainers who tried to outrun Drysdale's star
were less restrained. They sounded as though they had lost to sheer
brilliance on the race track, to an animal who lived up to his
name, Pegasus, the flying horse of mythology.
</P>
<P>
   With a quarter of a mile to go, Richard Migliore thought he was
riding a winner with Wheelaway, who had been first in the Tampa Bay
Derby but on Saturday finished fifth. ``The winner,'' Migliore
testified, ``might be a great horse.''
</P>
<P>
   With an eighth of a mile to go, John Velazquez thought he had
beaten the favorite with his mount, More Than Ready. But he
finished fourth, and Velazquez put it succinctly: ``The winner went
by me, and I knew I couldn't catch him.''
</P>
<P>
   D. Wayne Lukas, who trained the Derby winner three times in the
last five years, tried to outrun Fusaichi Pegasus with three
horses, but they finished up the track: Exchange Rate (12th), High
Yield (15th), Commendable (17th). Lukas, the only trainer with
purse winnings of $200 million, got nothing for his labors in his
20th straight Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed with Fusaichi Pegasus,'' he said. ``All the
fears about him were put to rest when he went over there, and he
did what he had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   What Fusaichi Pegasus had to do was win with command, something
that racing likes to remember in great horses and longs to see
again. He has regal breeding (son of Prospector, grandson of
Danzig), he has high spirits that were kept under control in the
Derby, he has horse sense _ he switches inside or outside, he flows
with the traffic, he closes with breathtaking drama.
</P>
<P>
   So, for his investment of $4 million, Sekiguchi has bought
himself a bundle of success, a mighty horse who is delivering the
kind of theater that racing has been searching for. And his
investment certainly looks more promising than the $60 million
spent so far by the National Thoroughbred Racing Association on its
cosmetic changes, its ``commissioner'' and his six vice presidents,
the television time they buy to increase public awareness of racing
and the cable television station they have established to send the
message.
</P>
<P>
   But they are sending a narrow message. They are serving the
hard-core bettors and handicappers who gamble on the product but
don't necessarily define it in terms of remarkable animals bred and
trained to race. The racing association is charged with
``marketing'' the business of racing. But it is traveling the low
road, trying to drum up people's interest in commercial solutions
like simulcasting and home betting.
</P>
<P>
   Poetry can't pay the bills, that's true. But when you have a
``product'' as classic as Fusaichi Pegasus, with a compelling story
line and rivals like 88-year-old Harold Rose and Jenine Sahadi and
the young Todd Pletcher with his four horses and Lukas with his
three and Sheik Mohammed bin Rashid al-Maktoum with his pair _ why
try to manufacture drama when it's already there?
</P>
<P>
   How can you beat the flying horse winning the Kentucky Derby and
reviving the great expectations of a sport that desperately needs
them?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-00 1853EDT &QL; 
