<HEADER>
A8328 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RAC-DERB-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-07 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERB-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FUSAICHI PEGASUS TAKING ONE STEP AT A TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ There was good reason to predict a Triple
Crown sweep for Fusaichi Pegasus after his seemingly effortless
performance in the Kentucky Derby on Saturday. But his trainer,
Neil Drysdale, will wait to see whether there may be a better
reason for not running him at all in the second leg of racing's
most coveted and grueling series.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the cautious and conservative horseman, Drysdale offered
only that his $4 million superstar is a possible entry in the
Preakness, the second leg of the Triple Crown, on May 20.
</P>
<P>
   After moving seven horses wide under the jockey Kent Desormeaux
and rocketing down the stretch to finish with the seventh-fastest
time in the 126-year history of the Derby, the strapping colt took
only a short walk Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was fine this morning,'' said Drysdale, who capped a week
that included his induction into the Hall of Fame by winning the
Derby on his first try. ``Somebody dropped something and he
bounced. So he was nice and bright this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to see how he comes out of this race first before we
go on to the next. As you well know, they're fragile animals and
sometimes things look easy and sometimes something shows up in the
wash, whatever it might be. So, literally, we'll just go one step
at a time. We've got to just see how he is the next few days.''
</P>
<P>
   In nearby barns along Churchill Downs' backside, Fusaichi
Pegasus' contemporaries _ most of them tired, a few bandaged _ were
being prepared to leave. They had come here considered one of the
deepest crop of 3-year-olds in years and carried the Triple Crown
aspirations of their trainers and owners.
</P>
<P>
   Now, those have been run over by the $4 million colt with the
obstinate and rambunctious personality, leaving many of them unsure
what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   The runner-up, Aptitude, will bypass Baltimore and Pimlico Race
Course to run in the Belmont Stakes on June 10 in New York.
Aptitude's trainer, Bobby Frankel, certainly did not sound
overwhelmed by the winner's performance and said it might have made
a difference if his jockey, Alex Solis, had kept Aptitude on the
rail instead of taking the colt wide at the half-mile point. While
Solis and Aptitude swung four wide around the final turn,
Desormeaux crept up the inside and saved ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong, Alex rode a good race,'' Frankel said.
``But Desormeaux took the gamble, and that was the difference of
maybe winning or losing. I'm not saying I would have beaten him,
but maybe that was the difference. I take my hat off to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The third- and fourth-place finishers, Impeachment and More Than
Ready, are doubtful for the Preakness, though the trainer Todd
Pletcher will wait until the Tuesday before the race to make his
decision. The brawny, late-running Impeachment has a better shot at
winning the one-and-a-half-mile Belmont, said Pletcher, than
excelling over the shorter course in Baltimore that favors
speedsters with its tight turns.
</P>
<P>
   More Than Ready may fit that profile, but the small, hard-trying
colt, who had the lead briefly in the stretch in the Derby, is
coming off two taxing efforts. He finished second by a head three
weeks ago in the Blue Grass; Sunday his legs were wrapped with
bandages to soothe a handful of minor cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tries too hard and probably needs the rest,'' Pletcher said
of More Than Ready. ``I'm inclined to wait for the summer for him.
He has nothing left to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   Pletcher saddled four horses in his Derby debut, and the other
two _ Trippi (11th) and Graeme Hall (19th and last) _ are off the
trail.
</P>
<P>
   Only D. Wayne Lukas with High Yield and Bob Baffert with Captain
Steve seemed intent on trying Fusaichi Pegasus again in the
Preakness. High Yield finished a disappointing 15th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have an explanation,'' Lukas, a four-time Derby
winner, said about High Yield. ``I wish I did, and I am seldom at a
loss for words. I never felt better about a horse three weeks prior
to the Derby since Winning Colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas also finished 12th with Exchange Rate and 17th with
Commendable.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Steve's owner, Mike Pegram, said his colt would make the
trip to the Preakness after being bumped in the stretch by
Wheelaway and finishing eighth. The fifth-place finisher,
Wheelaway, lugged into Captain Steve in the stretch, but by then
both horses were beaten.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he stubs his toe,'' Pegram said of Fusaichi Pegasus.
``Maybe somebody will impede him before he takes off. He was real
impressive. But the thing about this business is that you can't be
afraid to get beat. If you're not willing to reload and fire again,
then get out.''
</P>
<P>
   At least two new, speedy challengers will take a shot Fusaichi
Pegasus if he heads to Baltimore: Red Bullet and Snuck In.
</P>
<P>
   The Joe Orseno-trained Red Bullet finished second to Fusaichi
Pegasus in the Wood Memorial. Snuck In was the runner-up in the
Arkansas Derby and withdrew from the Derby late in the week after
the trainer Steve Asmussen decided the horse was too fractious to
relax in a big field. ``That Pegasus is a freak,'' said Scott
Blasi, Asmussen's assistant. ``He's just super, but our horse is
pretty fast, too.''
</P>
<P>
   New challengers or not, new surface or not, Drysdale says he
will wait to see if his colt's health coincides with his owner's
plan. Fusao Sekiguchi, a Japanese venture capitalist, says he wants
to pursue the Triple Crown but will leave it up to his trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very talented horse and he looks like he's got a
very bright future in front of him,'' Drysdale said of a colt who
has won 5 of 6 races. ``So we'll keep our fingers crossed and go
from there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
