<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8332 &Cx1f; tth-z
r d BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      05-07 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN FISH PRICES SINK THE BUDGET, LEAN BEEF MAKES THE CUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's difficult to read the recipe on the card because of the
splotches and food stains. You can barely make out my wife's
evaluation of the dish. Upon close scrutiny it reads,
``Marvelous!''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not positive all of our guests agreed. It's also true that
``marvelous'' in those days meant a dish we could afford that was
also edible.
</P>
<P>
   Every young reporter on the staff of the Bismarck Tribune had
his or her ``marvelous'' recipe. More often than not it was a
hamburger-noodle casserole. A few sliced green olives in the
casserole raised it in rank to ``superb.''
</P>
<P>
   We weren't paid a lot, but employees of that small, North Dakota
daily were distinguished by history. One Bismarck Tribune reporter
accompanied Gen. Custer on an expense-paid cruise to the Little Big
Horn. Needless to say, the scribe was not killed by a casserole.
</P>
<P>
   But we thought ours was ``marvelous.'' It contained potatoes, a
package of frozen Brussels sprouts and a can of corned beef.
Sprouts are good for you, which is one reason most young Americans
today would rather eat rattlesnake eggs. But in our house, in that
day, you shut up and ate your Brussels sprouts.
</P>
<P>
   We had better corned beef than you are liable to find in cans
today. You could actually slice the meat. Open a can of corned beef
today and it collapses into a sodden pile of cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   So we made a quick adjustment when we recently pulled out the
recipe for old time's sake.
</P>
<P>
   A Marvelous Casserole
</P>
<P>
   slab of lean, deli corned beef
</P>
<P>
   4 medium potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 package frozen Brussels sprouts
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of marjoram
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 cup beef bouillon
</P>
<P>
   Thaw the sprouts. Peel and quarter the potatoes then boil in
salted water until you can stick a fork in without the spud
hollering, ``Ouch!'' Cut the meat into bite-size hunks.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the meat, spuds and sprouts into a casserole. Sprinkle with
the salt, pepper and herbs. Pour bouillon over all. Cover the
casserole and shove into a 350-degree oven for 30 minutes. This
serves two to three but is easily doubled in case Bill Gates and
Paul Allen are coming for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   OK, we can afford a slightly better company meal today.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly enough, one of the quickest and cheapest meals you
can serve today is a steak dinner.
</P>
<P>
   In the rookie-reporter days, beef steak was an unattainable
delicacy. Fish was cheap, but nobody bought it or served it unless
it came out of a tuna can. Recently I bought a nice top sirloin for
two and it cost me $2.29. The same day halibut was going for eight
bucks a pound.
</P>
<P>
   The trick in serving steak is to avoid the expensive cuts that
are marbled with fat. Choose a lean slab of meat and marinate it
all day.
</P>
<P>
   Marinade for Steaks
</P>
<P>
   1 cup red wine
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon marjoram
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon rosemary
</P>
<P>
   2 sliced onions
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 splats of Tabasco
</P>
<P>
   You can use anything from a round bone chuck roast to thick-cut
top sirloin. Lift the meat from the marinade, drain, then broil or
barbecue. When done, top with:
</P>
<P>
   Beefsteak Mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   8 large mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 large clove garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fennel seed
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Mash together in a mortar the garlic, fennel, oregano and salt.
Stir in the olive oil and let this potent puddle sit for an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Wipe but do not wash the mushrooms. Cut them in half and lay out
flat-side down in an oven pan or dish. Spoon the olive oil mixture
over the top and bake for 20 minutes in a 400-degree oven. This is
enough for two servings.
</P>
<P>
   After a splurge like that, you'll be back to the tuna casserole
by Friday. If you add a few sliced almonds, it'll be marvelous.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-00 1929EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000507.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8333 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-PUTIN-INAUGURATION-92     05-07 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUTIN-INAUGURATION-925(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN INAUGURATED IN RUSSIA'S FIRST DEMOCRATIC TRANSFER OF POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Beneath a gilded sunburst in a gilded palace, his hand
on a red leather-bound copy of the constitution, Vladimir Putin
swore an oath Sunday to ``respect and guard the human and civil
rights'' of Russia and became, officially at last, its second
president.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Russia _ and the world _ now waits to see what he will
do with the title. Many expect a quick push to overhaul Russia's
inscrutable tax code and economy and to reassert Kremlin rule over
its 89 provinces _ goals supposedly too risky to chase when he was
but an acting leader.
</P>
<P>
   But Putin, who has dropped only the broadest hints of an agenda
since he abruptly succeeded President Boris Yeltsin last New Year's
Eve, revealed nothing more Sunday. Predictably, he reappointed as
acting prime minister Mikhail Kasyanov, 42, a financial expert
known to the West for his dealings on rescheduling Russia's foreign
debt who is widely expected to be Putin's nominee to head the
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief speech after his swearing-in, Putin said he would
perform his duties openly, ``guided only by the interests of the
state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider it my sacred duty to unite the people of Russia, to
gather citizens around clearly defined tasks and aims and to
remember, every minute of every day, that we are one nation and one
people,'' he said. ``We have one common future.''
</P>
<P>
   Although known as prosecutor of a war in Chechnya that has
brought fresh accusations of Russian trampling on human rights,
Putin on Sunday made much, oratorically and symbolically, of the
step toward democracy that his inauguration represented. The
ceremony, he noted, completed the first legal and democratic
transfer of executive power in Russia's 1,100-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring that, Yeltsin stood beside him, on a
flower-bedecked podium in the Kremlin Grand Palace, throughout the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can be proud that this is being done peacefully, without
revolutions and putsches, in a respectful and free way,'' Yeltsin
said in remarks to the crowd. ``This is possible only in a new
Russia, one in which people have learned to live and think
freely.''
</P>
<P>
   Four months after his stunning early resignation, Yeltsin
appeared healthy but spoke slowly and with one pause so long that a
handful in the audience applauded, thinking his speech was over.
</P>
<P>
   The tightly scripted ceremony called for Yeltsin to hand over to
Putin the symbol of Russian leadership, a gold medal and chain
called the Order of Service to the Fatherland, First Degree. Either
by deliberate omission or forgetfulness, the transfer did not take
place.
</P>
<P>
   Watching from a VIP seat was the former Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev, a bitter Yeltsin enemy who was barred from the 1996
inauguration. He was invited this time, officials said, as a
gesture to his role in creating a democratic Russia and to stress
the continuity of Russian leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Also present was Vladimir Kryuchkov, Gorbachev's KGB chief and
one of the leading conspirators in a 1991 coup against Gorbachev
that sought to return the Soviet Union to hard-line Communist rule.
That coup helped to speed the break-up of the Soviet empire by the
end of that year.
</P>
<P>
   The invitation-only audience of legislators, jurists and
diplomats _ heads of state were not invited _ also included Putin's
favorite schoolteacher and his judo instructor.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bittersweet and, for Putin and many in the audience of
1,500 people, a largely unexpected moment. When Yeltsin began his
second term in office four years ago, most people would have
considered it unthinkable that any head of Russia's long-feared
espionage apparatus would be freely elected president in the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   When Yeltsin plucked Putin from the relative anonymity of a
senior Kremlin post last August and named him prime minister and
preferred successor, still others snickered. Putin had no political
experience. Worse still, he was so bland in appearance and demeanor
that at many gatherings he seemed almost to fade into the walls.
</P>
<P>
   But Putin, 47, a former KGB agent who rose to head its domestic
successor, the Federal Security Service, surprised almost everyone.
His war against secessionist rebels in Chechnya _ and his
well-advertised fondness for judo, jet fighter rides and submarine
trips _ made him a symbol of Russian patriotism and
professionalism.
</P>
<P>
   Although many Russians have soured slightly on the war in
Chechnya as the fighting against rebels there drags on, Putin's
victory in the presidential election in March proved a foregone
conclusion. And in polls last week, 60 percent of respondents said
they viewed him positively.
</P>
<P>
   Kremlin officials had said they wanted an inauguration that
would be muted in character and that would emphasize the continuity
of government. They succeeded in stressing continuity.
</P>
<P>
   But the proceedings Sunday may even have exceeded in splashiness
Yeltsin's own 1996 inauguration, where the crowd was twice as
large.
</P>
<P>
   It was probably impossible to stage anything muted in the Grand
Palace, a massive, 162-year-old edifice whose halls were restored
and thoroughly gilded at a cost of hundreds of millions of dollars
during Yeltsin's tenure. Nor was it clear that anyone tried.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Yeltsin, Putin did not bring the patriarch of the Russian
Orthodox Church onstage to certify his installation, a tradition
that reminded many of the crowning of a new czar. On the other
hand, Yeltsin's inauguration lasted only 15 minutes, and he was too
stricken by heart trouble even to make a speech.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
