<DOCNO> NYT20000507.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8335 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-PUTIN-INAUGURATION-2N     05-07 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUTIN-INAUGURATION-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
MOSCOW: a speech.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Putin's ceremony, broadcast on all major television networks,
was run with military precision and Hollywood style, down to the
aerial camera that tracked his entourage down a deserted riverside
highway and through the Kremlin gates.
</P>
<P>
   A covey of cameras watched as Putin's midnight-blue Mercedes
limousine pulled up at the palace and he emerged, alone. And,
through two or three long minutes, still more cameras followed
Putin through the palace, striding alone down an endless red
carpet, up the 57 steps of the famous Red Staircase and through two
palace rooms packed with applauding guests.
</P>
<P>
   He entered St. Andrew's Hall, where the installation took place,
precisely as the Kremlin clock struck noon. As the ceremony ended,
a choir sang the ``Glory'' aria from an 1836 opera by Mikhail
Glinka, ``Life of the Czar,'' about a peasant who dies to save the
czar from Polish invaders. Outside the Kremlin walls, 30 artillery
pieces fired a booming 30-shot salute.
</P>
<P>
   After the Kremlin ceremony and a blessing from the patriarch,
Aleksei II, Putin reviewed a parade by a regiment of Kremlin guards
and paid tribute to Russia's military by laying a wreath at the
Tomb of the Unknown Soldier just outside the Kremlin walls. He then
spoke at a Kremlin ceremony commemorating the anniversary Tuesday
of the Allies' triumph over Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Putin started work, holding a cabinet meeting and
reappointing Kasyanov.
</P>
<P>
   Kasyanov, like all senior officials in Putin's government,
submitted his resignation after the inauguration as required by
law. Putin said later that he expects to reappoint most of them to
permanent positions.
</P>
<P>
   Although his appointments may offer clues, there is real
uncertainty as to where Putin intends to take Russia next.
</P>
<P>
   He has proclaimed himself a democrat and a capitalist, and some
of his top advisers reflect those views. The head of his strategy
center, German Gref, strongly advocates pro-market reforms. His new
economic adviser, Andrei Illarionov, is viewed by some as a radical
reformer.
</P>
<P>
   Anders Aslund, an expert on Russia at the Carnegie Endowment for
International Peace in Washington, said he believes a ``radical
liberalization'' of the Putin program is occurring. Its first
fruits, he said, may be a plan to replace Russia's graduated income
tax with a flat tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether it will amount to 12 percent or 20
percent,'' he said in an interview. ``Even the Communists are all
in favor of a cap on taxes now. It's an amazing change that has
come about.'' Still, he said, ``there's a substantial worry that he
won't do very much'' beyond tax reform, despite an economic
situation that _ thanks in part to high prices for Russia's oil
exports _ is stronger than many experts might have predicted a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``His situation is good. The economy and political support are
good,'' Aslund said. ``The need for action doesn't seem to be
apparent, and he will have to consolidate his power. And that takes
time.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Aslund's counterpart at Carnegie's Moscow offices, Lilia
Shevtsova, agreed. Putin, she said, is at his core a bureaucrat who
wants to make the system work and not to revolutionize it. Nor does
he have the political clout to carry off a revolution, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can get all the Chicago boys in the world as his
advisers,'' she said, referring to the so-called Chicago school of
free-market economic theory. ``But it means nothing when it comes
to implementing his decisions. Then he has to deal with the
regional governors, these conservative guys who don't want to move,
who will fight him.''
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to the considerable powers that the governors have
developed in their own regions as central authority withered in
Yeltsin's last years, she added: ``If he proceeds with a radical
agenda on the economy, then he's going to put the stick into a
very, very unpleasant ants' nest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
