<HEADER>
A8338 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT &LR;      05-07 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENDERSON SAYS BEWILDERED METS ARE USING A HEADS-OR-TAILS
STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The Mets are so uncertain how to deal with their present
slump, left-fielder Rickey Henderson said Sunday in the glare of
the team's ninth loss in 12 games, that ``they're flipping a coin
and hoping to find an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, replaced in Sunday's lineup by Jon Nunnally, talked
like a man who had just lost the coin flip as he sat steaming in
the locker-room after the Mets were held to one hit in a 3-0 loss
to the Florida Marlins at Pro Player Stadium. The Mets' record has
slipped to 17-16.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to believe in your players,'' Henderson said. ``Once
you don't believe in them, it's tough for us to go out there and
play to win. We're trying to do so many things. How about getting
back to the basics? How about pulling for one another to start?''
</P>
<P>
   Is he saying the Mets have some conflict in their clubhouse?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on a lot of clubs, and I've been on clubs that
win,'' he said. ``If it ain't a family, it's tough to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the 41-year-old intimated, the Mets' brain trust does
not appear to know what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of I-don't-knows, a lot of switching, a lot of
everything,'' Henderson said. ``When you're doing all that, it's
tough to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, who is hitting .205 while having played in 26 of the
Mets' 33 games, said he needed to play more regularly to develop a
rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to play every day, but spot-playing is tough for
anybody, not just Rickey,'' he said. ``I thought I was getting
close to developing a rhythm _but whoever gets out there, let
somebody get in a rhythm. You need a day off, you ask for it. But
the way I see it, if I played two days and needed a rest, I'd hang
it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza, who had the Mets' only hit _ a two-out,
sixth-inning double _ said the team's problems were nothing that
could not be fixed, as the Mets did after a similar slump last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't detect any sign of finger-pointing,'' Piazza said.
``Most of the guys here have been through this before. It's a
matter of riding the storm out and everybody staying focused to
hustle as hard as they can.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine said his team looked tired Sunday after
playing 20 games in the past 20 days. The Mets have a day off
Monday before going to Pittsburgh for a three-game series to
complete a 13-game trip.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday the Mets made Friday's one-run performance look like an
explosion. The Marlins' Ryan Dempster, a 23-year-old right-hander,
walked four in addition to allowing Piazza's hit in a masterly
eight-strikeout complete game.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza broke up the no-hit bid by hitting the first pitch to him
in the sixth, a slider, off the left-field wall. Cliff Floyd jumped
for the line drive, but missed it by several inches.
</P>
<P>
   The closest the Mets came to another hit was Derek Bell's liner
to left in the eighth that Floyd caught with a timely lunge.
Center-fielder Preston Wilson saved Edgardo Alfonzo's try for a hit
in the ninth with a diving catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He mixed a slider and changeup with his fastball and he had
real good location,'' Alfonzo said. ``He deserved to win this
game.''
</P>
<P>
   So did the Mets left-hander Glendon Rusch, under normal
conditions. The Marlins touched him for a run in the first inning
on three straight hits, but he worked out of trouble by getting
Wilson to hit into a double play and prompting Mike Lowell to fly
out. Rusch also allowed two hits in the second with one out, but
retired the next two hitters.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Rusch (1-3) allowed only two base runners before he
departed following the seventh inning. He retired the last seven
batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't let what's happening around him bother him at
all,'' Valentine said. ``He makes good pitch after good pitch. He
looks like a guy who can help us win a lot of games.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite such a well-pitched game, Rusch, who lowered his earned
run average to 3.28, found himself deferring to Dempster's
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to tip your hat to him,'' he said. ``We've got a
great-hitting team and he constantly stayed ahead in the count to
them and made some great pitches. This was one of those days where
he pretty much controlled the game by himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Mets were held to one hit came in 1994 by Andy
Benes, then of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll swing the bats better,'' Valentine said. ``And we'll
pitch as well as we did today. That'll be the sign of a good
team.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
