<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8341 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ELIAN-CIRCUIT0508-COX     05-07 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-CIRCUIT0508-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elian drama moves to Atlanta court this week
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Five simple words will transform a quiet, staid
courthouse in downtown Atlanta on Thursday: Elian Gonzalez v. Janet
Reno.
</P>
<P>
   In a highly charged atmosphere with worldwide media attention,
the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals will hear argument on to
whether the 6-year-old Cuban boy should be able to apply for
political asylum against the wishes of his father.
</P>
<P>
   If the court's past rulings on immigration can serve as a
guidepost, there is cause for concern by the Miami relatives who
want Elian to be granted political asylum.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th Circuit, one step below the U.S. Supreme Court, has
come to be regarded as one of the nation's most predictable when
deciding immigration disputes. It typically sides with federal
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``In immigration, the 11th Circuit is known as one of the more
government-friendly courts,'' said David Martin, a University of
Virginia law school professor who was U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service general counsel from 1995 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Ira Kurzban, a Miami lawyer who has written a book on
immigration law, said it is hard to peg the court as either liberal
or conservative in terms of its immigration rulings.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'd say the court is generally considered to be
deferential, and maybe the most deferential in the county, to the
government on immigration matters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, cases before the court arouse the public's
interest. But nothing compares to the Elian Gonzalez case. An
onslaught of requests from the international news media forced the
court last week to hold a lottery for the 12 seats set aside for
the press.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three judges who will hear the case, two are among the
court's longest-serving members and the third is the court's most
recent addition:
</P>
<P>
   J.L. Edmondson, 52, appointed by President Ronald Reagan in
1986, is perhaps the court's most conservative jurist and one of
its most influential. During oral argument, Edmondson speaks
frankly, rarely allows attorneys to fudge their positions and often
indicates which way he's leaning.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, he wrote the majority ruling that found former
Georgia Attorney General Mike Bowers was within his rights when he
withdrew a job offer to lesbian lawyer Robin Shahar. It was
Edmondson who issued the court's initial ruling in the Elian
Gonzalez case, saying he ``decided to act alone'' in approving a
temporary injunction, ordering that Elian remain in the United
States and that no one assist in his removal.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Dubina, 52, of Montgomery, Ala., also is regarded as one of
the court's conservative, law-and-order judges. He was in private
practice when Reagan appointed him in 1986 to be a U.S. district
court judge. Four years later, President George Bush elevated him
to the federal appeals court to fill the seat left by Judge Robert
Vance, who was killed in a mail-bomb explosion.
</P>
<P>
   In the Gonzalez case, Dubina dissented from the order granting
the motion from Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, to intervene.
The father's motion was ``untimely filed,'' Dubina said, adding
that he believed ``the INS adequately represents (Elian's)
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Wilson, 45, of Tampa, Fla., is the court's most recent
appointee and only African-American. Before being placed on the
court last year by President Clinton, Wilson was the U.S. attorney
for the Middle District of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, while Wilson was serving as a federal magistrate, U.S.
Attorney General Janet Reno asked if he would consider applying to
be Tampa's top federal prosecutor. He did, and Clinton appointed
him. Wilson does not appear to be a liberal jurist. In fact, in an
interview last year, he expressed his admiration for the late U.S.
Supreme Court Justice Lewis Powell, a renowned centrist.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to explain the 11th Circuit's leanings on
immigration, most lawyers and scholars point to the case of Ralph
Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, who ran a commercial cleaning firm and coached his
church soccer team in suburban Atlanta, was detained on Oct. 26,
1997, upon his return from a weekend trip to his native Haiti.
Richardson, a lawful permanent U.S. resident, had to go through
immigration when he returned to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   At Miami International Airport, INS officials discovered
Richardson had a 7-year-old cocaine trafficking conviction.
Authorities decided that this prior offense fell under the
definition of an ``aggravated felony,'' which under immigration law
requires the INS to move for detention and deportation.
</P>
<P>
   Worse for Richardson were sweeping immigration reforms passed by
Congress in 1996. They prohibit anyone in his predicament from
applying for a waiver, which in the past had been allowed if they
could prove they were rehabilitated and living productive lives.
And the reforms also greatly restrict the ability of these
detainees to obtain bail.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of rulings, the 11th Circuit upheld the law,
rejecting Richardson's due process claims. He is still being
detained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were extremely disappointed and felt that the decision was
out of line with the decisions by other circuits across the
country,'' said Kurzban, the Miami lawyer widely known for his
advocacy of immigration rights.
</P>
<P>
   In another immigration decision, the 11th Circuit last year
upheld the INS' deportation of a West African immigrant whose
lawyer had failed to notify him of important immigration hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The court rejected Alexis Anin's claims that he should not be
faulted for the malpractice of his lawyer, who had received notice
of the hearings and had neither told Anin about them nor attended
them on his behalf, prompting a judge's order for Anin's
deportation.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling, the 11th Circuit said the law ``holds Anin
responsible for his lawyer's actions and omissions.'' Anin also
missed the 180-day deadline for filing his appeal, the court said,
noting that no other circuit had allowed such an exception.
</P>
<P>
   But two days after the 11th Circuit issued its July 14, 1999,
ruling, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in San Francisco
granted such an exception. That case was filed by a Mexican
immigrant who missed important immigration hearings and interviews
after his legal representative failed to notify him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-00 1938EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
