<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8343 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-SPAIN-IMMIGRANTS-ART-     05-07 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-IMMIGRANTS-ART-1220(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SPAIN, AN INFLUX OF MOROCCANS LEADS TO TENSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL EJIDO, Spain _ The newly planted orange trees on the quaint
Plaza de la Colonizacion suggest a certain civic pride in this
southern Spanish town, but the rubble and charred remains of
Afrolatino Comunicacion demonstrate how civility has gone up in
smoke.
</P>
<P>
   The 20 telephone cabins in the burned establishment were used by
immigrants, mainly Moroccans, to call home. That was until the
place was set alight on the night of April 20, two days after the
newspaper kiosk of a Moroccan immigrant in nearby Almeria was
burned down.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pure racism _ $12,000 of investment up in smoke
because some Spaniards can't stand Africans,'' said Armon Elia
Mejia, the owner, who is an immigrant from the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   These incidents are the latest spasms in anti-immigrant violence
in this region of southern Spain. After a Spanish woman was killed
in a local market by a Moroccan in early February, there was a
three-day rampage directed against the tens of thousands of North
African laborers here.
</P>
<P>
   The outburst, now known simply as ``la guerra,'' or ``the war,''
was the worst recent case of racial violence in a Europe
increasingly uneasy about immigrants. ``When a people rises up, it
is because they are tired,'' said Alejandro Fernandez, the fiance
of the woman who was killed. ``I tell you, this place is a time
bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   In some senses, that bomb is of purely local manufacture. A lot
happened suddenly to El Ejido, creating a rootless culture in which
sparks flare easily. It became rich through the production of
winter fruits; it became mixed through a massive influx of
Moroccans to pick them; it became angry because its identity was
suddenly unclear.
</P>
<P>
   But in other ways, the quandary of El Ejido is that of all of
Europe. Spain, like many of its partners in the European Union, is
a rich country with a fast-aging population, a low birthrate, a
growing aversion to menial jobs and an uneasy proximity to lands of
poverty. It needs immigrants from poorer places, even as its
national psyche resists them.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Continent, young laborers are being lured from poorer
places, whether in Africa or eastern Europe, only to meet
resistance from wealthy countries afraid that their national
identities will be diluted or their generous welfare systems
overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   In Austria, the party of Joerg Haider rails against
``overforeignerization.'' In Germany, conservatives urge people to
have more children rather than accept immigrants. In France, riots
erupt after an Algerian is shot by police. In Britain, drastic laws
are introduced to curb the growing number of asylum-seekers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe requires immigrants today because of simple
demographics,'' said Kirsty Hughes, a senior European Union
official. ``But try telling that to people. The political
atmosphere is one of fortress Europe, even if immigrants are doing
the jobs nobody else wants to do and are needed to ensure that we
don't end up as a continent of old people.''
</P>
<P>
   Spain is growing older fast. Without an influx of young
immigrants, or a radical change in the birthrate of 1.2 children
per woman, it will have the highest percentage of old people in the
world by 2050, U.N. projections show. People over 65 will account
for 37 percent of the population, compared with 17 percent today.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody will have to support these people under Europe's
taxpayer-financed pension systems, just as somebody on the Costa
del Sol today has to be ready to do the hot, back-breaking work of
picking the cherry tomatoes and basil that the baby boomers of
Hamburg and Helsinki now want on their tables year-round.
</P>
<P>
   But suggest that immigration from Africa or Romania is one
answer, and Western Europe tends to rebel.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the United States, these old nations do not readily see
themselves as ``lands of immigration,'' nor do they readily indulge
the idea that newcomers may be catalysts to innovation rather than
threats to jobs. In Spain, long a poor country that sent emigrants
abroad, the cultural leap required to invert that self-image is
huge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never thought of ourselves as racist _ until the invasion
of the 1990s,'' said Tomas Calvo Buezas, a sociologist. ``Even
today, we deny it publicly, and a successful anti-immigrant
politician like Austria's Haider or France's Le Pen is unthinkable.
But look at our language. We call the rich `Arabs'; we deride poor
North Africans as `Moors.'''
</P>
<P>
   One of the many North Africans eking out an existence in the
vast sea of plastic-covered hothouses that surrounds El Ejido is
Ilhami Elhoussin, 24. In 1998 he paid $500 for an illegal passage
in a small boat from his native Morocco across the narrow strait to
Spain. The other 19 passengers were caught on arrival; he ran and
slipped through.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, his immigrant's dream consists of a hovel
without water or electricity, roofed with sheets of plastic that
are anchored by rocks, set in the middle of an arid field where
garbage skitters in the enervating wind out of Africa. A cousin
shares the tiny shanty; 50 other Moroccan laborers live in abutting
structures on the outskirts of El Ejido.
</P>
<P>
   Some have done slightly better. Eljabiry Salah, 29, has
electricity and running water in his shack. But his bed is a foam
mattress perched on the green plastic crates that serve by day to
collect fruit and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine is a home for animals, not for humans,'' Elhoussin said.
But he would not return to Africa. Here he can earn $25 a day
picking produce. In Morocco, he said, there is no work for young
people, unless a man wants to go into the army for $6 a day.
</P>
<P>
   So most days, carrying his knife and pliers, this young African
in Europe sets out to work ``under the plastic,'' where
temperatures can reach 113 degrees in the spring and summer.
</P>
<P>
   Human ingenuity has not yet conceived a machine to pick
tomatoes. So Elhoussin picks them, filling buckets at a rate of
over 28 pounds an hour. The next day, the plump fruit will be in
Perpignan, France, or Rotterdam, Netherlands, ready to adorn the
Insalata Caprese at lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Such exports, which have risen to over 1.5 million tons
annually, from 100,000 tons in the early 1980s, have turned a
dirt-poor corner of Spain into a boom town. The sun, pouring into
75,000 acres of plastic-covered hothouses, has proved as valuable
as oil.
</P>
<P>
   Construction is ubiquitous in El Ejido, whose population has
almost doubled to 55,000, from 29,000 in 1981. Modern shopping
malls are the rage. But this ``New Spain,'' chic and confident,
remains utterly foreign to Elhoussin and the North Africans whose
labor helped transform the region.
</P>
<P>
   The birthrate in Morocco is two and a half times that of Spain.
Elhoussin is one of eight children _ his youngest sister is 10 _
from a village near Casablanca, and he sends about $350 a month to
his father to help him raise the family. With the remaining $150,
Elhoussin lives simply, seldom going out, especially since ``la
guerra.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the bars don't want us Moroccans at night,'' he said.
``We came here in the same way as Spaniards once went overseas to
work. Young Moroccans today want a house, a car, and the money is
better here. But the majority in El Ejido is racist. They don't
want us to rent their property, they don't want us to look at their
girls, they don't want us to build mosques.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, the violence in February, in which more than 500 North
Africans lost homes, astonished this young Moroccan. As shanties
and cars burned, and a marauding mob wielded clubs, Elhoussin fled
in terror to the snow-capped mountains behind El Ejido, where he
and a group of fellow Moroccans survived for four days without
food.
</P>
<P>
   At last he returned _ but to a changed place where unstated
grievances had become open wounds. The uneasy truce that has
followed is partial, marked by the averted gazes of divided
communities, and punctuated by violence.
</P>
<P>
   In every war there are two realities, seemingly unbridgeable.
People talk past each other, entrenched in their opposing worlds.
</P>
<P>
   To hear Spanish officials and businessmen tell it, the Moroccans
largely brought the cataclysm on themselves. There was the death of
Encarnacion Lopez, the woman who was killed in the market, but also
two other slayings by Moroccans in the 10 days before that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more than 4,000 North Africans here with no fixed
work,'' said Antonio Martin, the official in charge of regional
security. ``If they don't work, they can't eat. So they rob, they
deal drugs, they cause trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The complaints go beyond crime. If the Moroccans live in
shanties, it is because they do not want to pay rent, the Spaniards
say. If they do not want to pay rent, it is because they want to
send all their money home. If ever they do rent, they want to put
20 people in a room, and who in Europe can accept that?
</P>
<P>
   Spaniards, the arguments continue, went to Argentina or Germany
to find work when the country was poor, but were culturally
compatible, unlike these ``Moors'' who expect to be presented with
everything their own government will not give them, even as they
refuse to invest anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is we need their labor, so we are going to have to
learn to live together,'' said Antonio Escobar, the director of an
exporter called Agroponiente. ``Our mental attitude must improve.
But they must also learn to assimilate. Why is it that we have to
adapt to their Ramadan?''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez, 25, the bereaved hotelier who had planned to marry
Lopez, 26, before her slaying set off the violence, still wears a
gold engagement ring, and his blue eyes glisten with tears when he
speaks of her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was humble, she was hard-working, she was loving _ she was
right for me,'' he said, fingering a gold crucifix that nestled on
his chest. ``But a woman is worth nothing to a Moroccan. He'd
exchange her for a goat or a sheep.''
</P>
<P>
   As in all such situations, truth hovers somewhere between the
two sides. The Moors were the eighth-century Arab and Berber
conquerors of Spain who remained until 1492, so history imbues the
tensions with a particular charge. Newspapers in Morocco have been
denouncing Spain's ``new anti-Islamic Crusades.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, after a period of heady expansion, the produce
industry here has entered a period of consolidation. Jobs are
scarcer. The wages of pickers, around $500 a month, do not attract
Spaniards, who expect at least double that, even with unemployment
at over 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of the number of North Africans in the region vary
wildly: 45,000, says Ali Blidan, the leader of an immigrant rights
group; less than half that, according to the police. Most of them
came in the last decade, and the squares of El Ejido are full of
idle young Moroccans.
</P>
<P>
   On the square in the San Agustin district where Afrolatino
Comunicacion was burned down, there are two bars _ one frequented
by Spaniards, the other by Moroccans. The two groups even sit on
separate benches, eyeing each other suspiciously.
</P>
<P>
   In the adjacent police headquarters, Paco Ruiz, the local chief,
offered a different explanation of the recent violence _ which, he
ventured, was caused by rivalry between Moroccans and Algerians
``who cannot stand each other.'' Because they were not allowed to
drink in their own countries, ``they are out of control when they
drink here,'' Ruiz said.
</P>
<P>
   He looked a visitor in the eye and continued: ``The fire may be
out here, but the embers are still burning. This place is going to
explode again.''
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to ensure that it does not, Spanish authorities
have brought in several hundred extra police officers since
February. The government has also introduced legislation allowing
illegal immigrants to regularize their situation if they arrived
before June 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But Elhoussin is not interested. As soon as he can save enough
money, he said, he wants to head north to a ``more civilized place,
like France,'' where he hopes to work in a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The reception there may not be much warmer. The mood of
``fortress Europe'' tends to vary little from country to country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The march from the south to the north is inevitable,'' said
Jean-Claude Chesnais, a French demographer. ``Africa's population
is growing by 20 million a year, while ours declines rapidly. The
problem is we are afraid of the immigration we need.''
</P>
<P>
   The grieving Fernandez sees every reason for such fear. The
stabbing of his fiancee was an aberration, the work of one man. But
emotion is irrational, and Fernandez insists on drawing a general
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who,'' he asked, ``wants to risk living with a neighbor who is
a complete stranger?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
