<SLUG> BC-HKN-PUCK-LEAFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE PLAYING THEIR BEST, MAPLE LEAFS FACE ELIMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The Maple Leafs played their best game of their
Eastern Conference semifinal series with the Devils on Saturday
night. Because it was not good enough, the Leafs are facing playoff
elimination in New Jersey on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the Leafs turn in their best all-around effort, a
4-3 loss that gave the Devils a 3-2 lead in the four-of-seven-game
series, but their top line, led by center Mats Sundin, also
dictated play for the first time in the series.
</P>
<P>
   The result at the Air Canada Center was a familiar one, however.
The Sundin line was held without a point for the fourth time in
five games and the Leafs played the last two periods without
defenseman Aleksandr Karpovtsev, who was hit in the chest with a
stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably played our best game,'' said Sundin, who combined
with Steve Thomas and Jonas Hoglund for seven shots on goal. ``We
created a lot of chances. And still we have nothing to show for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing the line has to show for the series so far is one
Hoglund goal, with assists from Sundin and Thomas, in Game 4. One
goal. Two assists. That's it.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Farkas, the 22-year-old rookie from Boston College, matched
that total with his first goal as a professional on Saturday night.
Farkas, who was inserted into the Toronto lineup for Game 4 to
charge a moribund offense, has done everything Leafs coach Pat
Quinn could have wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Quinn said. ``Here's a guy who was in no man's
land. He certainly has not embarrassed himself at all.''
</P>
<P>
   While his classmates at Boston College have been taking final
exams, and while his roommate and best friend, Mike Mottau, the
Rangers draft choice, plays defense for Team USA at the world
hockey championships in St. Petersburg, Russia, Farkas has been
taking his National Hockey League entrance exams. He has teamed
with left wing Sergei Berezin and center Igor Korolev to give the
Leafs a blazingly quick line.
</P>
<P>
   Farkas' line was the Leafs' most productive one on Saturday
night. He and Berezin each scored a goal. But if the Sundin line
does not produce soon, Farkas soon will be back at Boston College
finishing the work on his degree.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he has played just two professional games, Farkas is
just one goal off the team lead for the series. Darcy Tucker has
two this series to lead the Leafs. And he may have sparked a feud
that will carry into Monday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker had not one, but two, run-ins with Devils goalie Martin
Brodeur on Saturday, including one that sparked a postgame fracas.
Tucker, who is not known for his restraint, promised there would be
more to come in Game 6. The Devils responded by saying they would
welcome all the power plays they can get. That brings up another
sore spot for Toronto: the Maple Leafs are 0 for 18 on the power
play in the series.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils had eight power plays in the last two games compared
to three for Toronto, which is one reason why the officiating crew
was showered with debris after it left the ice on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are asking about our power play,'' said Quinn, after
the Leafs were 0 for 2 on Saturday and the Devils were 2 for 5. But
the power play does not work, he explained, if you never get on it.
</P>
</TEXT>
