<SLUG> BC-BBO-CYBERSPORTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARDING OFF THE `I LOVE NOMAR' VIRUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Security for the online version of voting for
Major League Baseball's All-Star Game begins today with greatly
stepped up measures, the league says, trying to downplay the
incident last year when one fan voted 25,000 times for Boston
shortstop Nomar Garciaparra on the last day to get him in the
starting lineup over New York's Derek Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be dead sure there can't be any fraud in the
voting,'' Tim Brosnan, MLB's executive vice president for business
affairs, told Bloomberg News. ``Without those assurances, the
procedure goes out the window.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost 900,000 of the 12 million votes placed last year came via
the Internet, and MLB expects to triple that this year.
</P>
<P>
   Voting can be found at the sport's official site
(www.majorleaguebaseball.com) as well as a yet-to-launch site
called www.seasonticket.com, an on-demand sports highlight
broadband video service. Balloting ends July 1.
</P>
<P>
   -The first Spanish-language fantasy beisbol game has been
launched at Fox Sports Latin America (www.foxsportsla.com), known
as Grandes Ligas Interactivas 2000 and powered by Stats, Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Manager de Ano'' grand prize is (hold your breath) a trip
for two to L.A. and two tickets to a Dodgers game.
</P>
<P>
   -Those involved in athletic fund-raising should watch how an
online auction conducted by Cal's athletic department comes off,
called the Cal CyBear Auction (www.cybear-auction.org.)
</P>
<P>
   The auction, which started Sunday and runs through May 18,
should generate as much as $200,000 to reduce the department's
debt, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 200 donated items up for bid are access to play on
Haas Pavilion's basketball court for 10 minutes during halftime at
a Bears game, two tickets to agent Leigh Steinberg's annual Super
Bowl party, and a program from the 1982 Cal-Stanford football game
signed by all five Bears players who touched the ball during ``The
Play.''
</P>
<P>
   -Lou Holtz, cyberticket scalper?
</P>
<P>
   At the Web site for the current South Carolina football coach
(!bold!www.coachholtz.com!off!), which primarily is a calling card
for anyone who wants him for personal appearances, a link has been
added to E-Ticketboard.com, which specializes in hooking up people
to buy and sell tickets to thousands of sporting events around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The site claims it is not a ticket broker - just a place for
buyers and sellers to meet. There's a $30 annual membership fee or
$6 single-event cost to use the service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-00 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
