u s BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     05-07 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE RIGHT TIME FOR ALONZO MOURNING  
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ For almost 45 minutes of another classic Knicks-Miami
playoff scrum that the Heat would ultimately survive more than win,
there was no definitive answer to the riddle in the middle. There
were even a few moments when there was the temptation to say that
Patrick Ewing was right, and that Alonzo Mourning was the best
center in the Eastern Conference, next to him.
</P>
<P>
   Three minutes 35 seconds from the finish of Game 1 Sunday, Ewing
lumbered off the bench and back onto the court with the Knicks
leading by 81-79 and looking as if they were ready to stretch out
on the sofa, make themselves at home in Miami's new digs.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing had to this point played Georgetown Junior to a
statistical draw, and, remarkably, on a day when his 37-year-old
body was still recovering from recent back spasms and early on
looked as if he had arrived at American Airlines Arena in need of
assembly and a long extension cord.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me a while to get loose,'' Ewing said after the Heat's
87-83 victory. ``I was just trying to clog the middle and play some
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Knicks, after taking a few figurative punches, had the
Heat in its usual early-series quandary, fighting for a home-court
advantage it worked all season for but not knowing where its next
basket was coming from. The game Tim Hardaway was in no condition
to create a shot for himself. After rising high from his playoff
past, Jamal Mashburn was beginning to fade from fourth-quarter
view. Mourning himself had minutes before ruined one possession by
holding the ball too long on the right side, then blown a dunk and
missed two free throws that helped the Knicks to the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was forcing the issue, instead of being patient,'' Mourning
said, nothing we hadn't heard before from him at this stage of the
season, against this particular opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning would rather be president of the Larry Johnson Fan Club
than admit he's ever been affected by the presence of big brother
Ewing. It's a news media fabrication, ``the one-on-one thing,'' he
said, dismissively.
</P>
<P>
   Tell it to the judge, for in order to compensate for the
injuries that have reduced Hardaway to offensive caretaker, the
Heat can simply no longer afford Mourning battling Ewing to a draw.
The last 3:35 Sunday was an excellent start.
</P>
<P>
   First Mourning worked hard for position, drew Ewing's fourth
foul and tied the score by converting two free throws. After the
Knicks turned the ball over, Mourning isolated Ewing on the right
side, a few feet from the baseline, and his body language shouting
that he had no intention of settling for the jumper.
</P>
<P>
   He has done that too often because Mourning has never been a
comfortable post player, never a center at all, in the classic
back-to-the-basket mold. He doesn't have the true go-to shot, the
reliable hook or turnaround jumper. His signature moves have been
bullish drives, though less crude than they used to be, or the
catch deep in the lane predicated again on brute strength.
</P>
<P>
   On the baseline, though on the left side, was where we had left
Mourning and Ewing in their last close playoff encounter a year
ago. Mourning failed to get around Ewing on a possession that could
have iced the Knicks in the dying moments of Game 5. This time,
Mourning got the step and the benefit of a call. Maybe this was the
law of averages. Maybe it was Ewing's back, or another year off his
reflexes.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning made the two free throws, but then Latrell Sprewell
tied the score from the line with 55.6 seconds left. Once more, you
got the idea that Miami was a single missed shot from coughing up
Game 1. Pat Riley called it the ``need play,'' and as the ball
swung in misdirection, Mourning happened to notice Ewing cheating
in the lane as P.J. Brown rolled through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Patrick playing deeper,'' he said. ``I attacked, turned
and sealed.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Majerle made the precise entry pass, into the left post. All
Mourning had to do was turn and drop the ball in the basket, off
glass. Allan Houston would counter with a sloppy entry pass to
Ewing that Brown slapped away. Jeff Van Gundy would let Miami run
the clock down inside 10 seconds, a gamble he lost when Mourning
faced Ewing up on the right side and nailed his jumper with 5.6
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning had 26 points, the last 8 and the realization that
Ewing and the Knicks would be back to try to undo all his effort
Tuesday night for Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``You keep hearing people say, `Zo, you won the battle today,'''
he said. ``We got a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks missed their last eight shots and still weren't put
away until 5.6 seconds were left. The Heat, for its part, looked
more like a team staggering to the end of Game 7 than one bursting
from Game 1. Hardaway limped off to have his ailing foot retaped in
the second quarter. Mashburn tripped over the foot of the official
Mike Mathis and rolled his ankle. Even Mourning took a
third-quarter blow to the temple from a scrambling Charlie Ward and
dropped briefly to the floor like a rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Heisman Trophy winner had some flashbacks,'' Mourning
said. ``I didn't play much football.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he'd get a few arguments on that one. Mourning will
never be poetry. He will never be pretty. He doesn't have to be
against Ewing. He just needs to play like the man in his prime
against a proud friend whose bones and muscles get crankier by the
month. He needs to substantially win the middle for the Heat to win
the war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-00 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
