<DOCNO> NYT20000507.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8357 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CLINTON-SCHEDULE-NYT &LR;      05-07 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCHEDULE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING ITS FIRST VISIT BY CLINTON, NEBRASKA HAILS THE CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Neb., Ark., S.D., Ind.)  (Eds: Streett in 7th graf cq.) 
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It will be eight stories tall, a huge contraption
of steel and rocks and timber that will span a major highway in
central Nebraska. The ribbon cutting for this unusual monument will
be in July, and organizers are planning a grand affair with hordes
of people, a mock buffalo stampede and, just possibly, but probably
not, a speech by the president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In the seven-plus years of his presidency, President Clinton has
been to Colorado and Wyoming. He has visited South Dakota and Iowa.
Kansas and Missouri together have been hosts to the president a
combined 20 times. But poor Nebraska is the lone state in the union
that Clinton has snubbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The official reaction we've gotten from the White House is
that the president's schedule has not been finalized and they'll
get back to us,'' said Jeff Smith, an advertising executive from
Omaha who is leading the uphill effort to lure Clinton to the
dedication ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've got to be realistic,'' Smith added. ``Nebraska is
not a heavily populated state and it's not known as a Democratic
swing vote in presidential elections. We'll probably have to book
the governor.''
</P>
<P>
   There are less than 6,000 hours left in the Clinton presidency,
a dwindling block of time that many people _ the organizers of the
Great Platte River Road Archway Monument among them _ want to
share. (The monument commemorates a transcontinental route used
after the Louisiana Purchase to open up the West.)
</P>
<P>
   Putting together Clinton's schedule in these final months is a
delicate balancing act that involves squeezing together
fund-raising dinners, presidential speeches and photo opportunities
with golf games, foreign trips and overnight stays in Chappaqua,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   There are also weddings. Stephanie Streett, the woman who
controls Clinton's day as assistant to the president and director
of presidential scheduling, got married on Saturday in
Fayetteville, Ark., and was able to pencil in her wedding onto
Clinton's schedule. It conveniently coincided with a fund-raiser in
Little Rock on Sunday for Hillary Rodham Clinton's campaign in New
York for a Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every minute of the president's day is scripted, from
his first meeting of the morning (usually around 9) until what the
official schedule calls ``good night.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, most of what occurs in the White House revolves
around politics, last week's education tour to Iowa, Ohio,
Minnesota and Kentucky included. In his political role, Clinton has
five Democratic National Committee fund-raisers on his schedule
through June and several benefits for congressional candidates.
Other appearances will be added around those occasions, whether it
is a ``message event'' on a topic, or if the fund-raiser is in
California, a side trip to visit his daughter, Chelsea, in Palo
Alto.
</P>
<P>
   Some days can be a mishmash of disconnected events _ like last
Tuesday's speech to insurance agents, which was followed by a
conference on raising teen-agers and a talk to a roomful of experts
on Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes of every day are set aside to brief Clinton on the
schedule. Time is also reserved daily for briefings by John
Podesta, the chief of staff, and Sandy Berger, the national
security adviser. There is also a bit of wiggle room to respond to
the day's news.
</P>
<P>
   In White House lingo, aides refer to ``toppers'' as brief asides
that the president makes at the top of a speech on an important
news development. But reacting to breaking news can be risky.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 29, when Clinton heard about one 6-year-old shooting
another in Michigan, he mentioned it at a fund-raiser in West Palm
Beach, Fla., but flubbed the facts about how the youngster got the
gun.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are ``departure statements,'' remarks Clinton makes
as he is heading off somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am on my way to North Carolina for another leg of our New
Markets tour to close the digital divide,'' Clinton said at one
event. ``But before I leave I want to say a few words about an
important study that Senator Daschle, Congressman Gephardt and I
have just been briefed on regarding the growing cost of
prescription drugs and the burden these costs are placing on
seniors and on disabled Americans.'' He was referring to Sen. Tom
Daschle, D-S.D., and House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt of
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's influence may be diminishing but his aides say
invitations from childhood friends, political allies and others
continue to flow into the White House at a rate of about 250 a
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I know how busy you are so please try to come,'''
said George Frazier, an insurance agent from Hope, Ark., who made
his pitch on Clinton's private fax line. ``I said, `We've invited
you each year for seven years, and this is your last chance.'''
</P>
<P>
   Frazier, who has known Clinton since the president was a
teen-ager, invited him for a meeting of insurance agents in
Washington last week. But the chances looked grim at first because
Clinton had been scheduled to visit France while the insurance
agents were convening at the Grand Hyatt.
</P>
<P>
   When the trip to Europe fell through, the insurance group
received an advance tip from a White House official, prompting the
association to renew its lobbying effort. Eventually, the trade
group received the good news from a presidential aide, days before
its opening session. ``You got him,'' the aide said. ``You got him
for half an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   But the timing was not ideal. The aide asked if the group could
switch its meeting to the evening because the president dislikes
early morning events. That was impossible, so Clinton showed up
about 8:30 a.m. His scheduled half-hour appearance stretched on
almost two hours.
</P>
<P>
   There are other idiosyncrasies that come with scheduling
Clinton. He likes one day off a week. He routinely runs late. And
he insists upon regular ``OTRs,'' which is off-the-record time
during trips. These visits, which could be a golf game or a stop at
a local restaurant, are not announced ahead of time but are far
from spontaneous. Secret Service agents inspect the fairways, or
the restaurant kitchen, well before his motorcade pulls up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We set up the schedule to match his personality,'' said an
official who has helped set up the president's days. ``He hates
superficial, two-second conversations. He doesn't like late nights
or early mornings. He likes events with real people who are doing
things that are relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in Nebraska consider themselves in that category, and
Clinton has hinted that, along with trips to the Middle East,
Vietnam, Northern Ireland and Africa, he would like to accept
Nebraska's invitation before Jan. 20, 2001, arrives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a standing invitation,'' said Anne Boyle, chairwoman of
the Nebraska Democratic Party. ``It's been delivered by letter,
more than one letter, and by Nebraskans who have visited the White
House.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyle is not upset that Nebraska has yet to appear on Clinton's
schedule. ``Sometimes when a president visits a state it's because
of a natural disaster,'' she said. ``If you look at it that way,
we're lucky.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
