<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MASHBURN A LARGER THREAT TO SPREWELL 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A few months ago, Latrell Sprewell referred to himself
as ``not a morning person.'' He admitted he does not like to get up
early to play basketball, especially those ungodly 12:30 p.m.
Eastern tipoffs mandated by NBC.
</P>
<P>
   That's what, 6:30 in Hawaii?
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't like playing at that time,'' the Knicks forward
said Sunday afternoon. ``But that doesn't make a difference. This
is the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell is right. This is the playoffs. And if he doesn't arise
from his Game 1 slumber and counter Jamal Mashburn over the next
week, the Knicks can sleep in until November.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's a reach for one Heat-Knick scrum. After all,
Sprewell and his teammates are resilient, resourceful, able to find
ways to come back to Madison Square Garden on Friday with
home-court advantage.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, there had to be something disturbing about the way he
was outscored and outplayed by Mashburn, something that said so
much about the perception surrounding this series _ the one about
New York having such a huge advantage over Miami in the mythical
matchup department.
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to work like this: Alonzo Mourning and Tim
Hardaway are locks at center and point guard. P.J. Brown vs. Larry
Johnson is almost a toss-up at power forward. But if Allan Houston
had a clear edge over Dan Majerle at shooting guard going in,
Sprewell was easily the choice over Mashburn.
</P>
<P>
   In a series that can hinge on so many different people and
plays, whoever gets the better of that duel most likely moves his
team forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matchup that can go either way,'' Sprewell said after
he missed 8 of 12 shots and got to the free throw line only four
times in the 87-83 Knick loss. ``He has advantages and I have
advantages. Today, he was able to get off and play a pretty good
game for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mashburn was short of unstoppable. But many of his 21 points
came at crucial moments, with the Knicks a possession or two away
from distancing themselves from the Heat. He made nine of nine free
throws, going hard to the basket through mounds of muscle when he
didn't have an open jump shot.
</P>
<P>
   And he played big. It's a basketball cliche. but with Mashburn
it is apropos. At 6 feet 8 inches and 241 pounds, he is 3 inches
taller and 50 pounds heavier than Sprewell. Physically, he is not a
small forward.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his career, Mashburn has made a habit of nullifying
his size and height advantages by playing smaller, taking fadeaway
jump shots instead of going straight up, settling for short runners
instead of strong layups. He literally shrank himself around the
basket, relying only on his natural finesse.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, he made a clutch 19-footer with 6 minutes left to tie
the game. He scored six straight points at the end of the third
quarter, punctuating the run with an incredibly difficult driving
layup that gave Miami an eight-point lead. He maneuvered his way
through the lane like a bumper car, hitting every Knick before
putting the shot high up on the glass with his body in a jack-knife
position.
</P>
<P>
   He attributes his new-found accuracy and aggressiveness to being
healthy after nursing so many nagging injuries in playoffs past.
But there is a mindset involved, too. He reads those monotonous
matchup graphics, in which one guy is ranked over the other, one
team favored to win the series in so many games.
</P>
<P>
   The three largest South Florida newspapers that cover the Heat
all picked New York in six games or less. In a series of weapons,
Sprewell over Mashburn was a cinch. But when you get beyond the
who-has-the-better-weapon-at-what-position game, Miami is in much
better shape than people realize.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was definitely a lot of hype going on,'' Marcus Camby
said afterward. ``People were saying we were going to sweep 'em or
we're going to handle them well. They forget they came back on us
when we had like a 20-point lead. We're so evenly matched.''
</P>
<P>
   And it may indeed come down to Sprewell-Mashburn, the
after-effects of their matchup reverberating throughout the series.
</P>
<P>
   With Hardaway relatively healthy and directing traffic, Mashburn
doesn't have to bring the ball up the court. He can do less
dribbling and more catching and shooting. And if Sprewell is not in
an offensive rhythm, Houston has to shoulder that much more of the
scoring burden.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how the Heat defended him differently than Toronto in the
first round, Sprewell candidly admitted how Miami double-teamed in
the low post every time he received the ball. ``Toronto didn't do
that until the third game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell reaffirmed how special he can be in the postseason
against Toronto, shutting down Vince Carter and shooting that
picturesque step-back jumper over the Raptor wunderkind to win Game
2 of the series. At the apex of the shot's release, you can see the
incredible focus in his form and on his face. Nothing in the world
meant more to him at that moment than making sure the ball went
through the net.
</P>
<P>
   He went up against a player as determined as himself Sunday, a
player no longer invisible when the game matters _ a small forward
who played larger than himself in Game 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
