u s BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT     05-07 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIOLES' LOOK OF LOSERS TURNS TO RELIEF AGAINST RIVERA  

</HEADLINE>
   By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Derek Jeter knew the game was over. And he knew that
the Orioles knew it was over, too.
</P>
<P>
   He had seen that look on the faces of Yankees' opponents before
when they had to face the supreme closer, Mariano Rivera. The look
of losers.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Rivera reflected later, ``This is a game, and things
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Even to Rivera, who ended last season successfully converting 22
straight save opportunities and had saved a major league-leading 11
games this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the Orioles did the unthinkable at Yankee Stadium Sunday _
they swatted Rivera for three runs in the ninth inning and salvaged
the final game of their three-game series with a 7-6 victory. It
was Rivera's second blown save of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles did not do it easily. Their 4-2 lead had disappeared
in the eighth inning when Scott Brosius tagged a grand slam off
Mike Trombley.
</P>
<P>
   Then Rivera came on for what is usually the opposition's final,
flailing at-bats. He gave up singles to Charles Johnson and Brady
Anderson, yielded a run on another soft single, to Delino
DeShields, to make it 6-5, and had runners on first and second with
one out. Rivera was not mowing them down. But to Jeter, the
Orioles' had that losers' look.
</P>
<P>
   B.J. Surhoff then hit a problematic grounder to Wilson Delgado
at second base. Manager Joe Torre thought Delgado, who is filling
in for the injured Chuck Knoblauch, would throw to second to try to
get the force. Instead, Delgado told him later, he was concerned
that Anderson had passed him, and he wanted to make sure to get at
least the out at first.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with runners on second and third, Albert Belle faced
Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera got two strikes on him and the crowd of 52,559 was
standing for this confrontation, the Orioles' most dangerous big
hitter against baseball's best closer.
</P>
<P>
   Belle drilled a solid single to center that sent home two runs,
produced a 7-6 lead and heralded the end of the Yankees' six-game
winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Albert had big power swings early in the count to go to two
strikes, then he cut down his swing to attack the ball well,''
Baltimore Manager Mike Hargrove said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Belle, who declines to discuss much with the news media,
made two obscene gestures to a reporter who asked him for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera was asked whether he has lost something this season, or
if this was merely a day in the life of a closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm throwing exactly the same,'' he said. ``I know how I'm
doing out there, and I felt just as good as I did all of last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   He will not think about the pitch that Belle hit or the other
three singles he gave up in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't work if you think about it,'' Rivera said. ``It
makes no difference.''
</P>
<P>
   And Torre, whose club has a 13-2 record in games decided by two
runs or less, said, ``I'll take my chances with Mariano coming in
with a one-run lead every night of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Orioles, Sidney Ponson looked good early _ no Yankee
reached base or hit a ball to the outfield the first three innings,
and he allowed only two runs in his six innings. Eventually, Mike
Timlin got the save.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore also heroics at the plate (home run) and in the field
(a diving stop to end an inning with runners in scoring position)
from 39-year-old Cal Ripken Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the guys were thinking about the streak now that
it's over,'' Brosius said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A loss like this,'' he said, ``leaves a bitter taste in your
mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially, he did not have to add, when the Yankees knew they
had it won.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
