<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WHAT A DIFFERENCE A VICTORY MAKES FOR HARGROVE  

</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees were obviously teasing the Orioles. All
nine batters in their lineup went down in their first swings
against Sidney Ponson, the Baltimore starting pitcher, then they
left the bases loaded in the sixth inning and squandered a leadoff
double in the fifth and a leadoff triple in the seventh. When the
Yankees took their turn at bat in the eighth inning, they had the
Orioles where they wanted them. The Orioles were winning, 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   They had been there before. Only two days earlier the Orioles
led the Yankees by 8-5 after six innings, and by 10-8 after eight.
But they lost, 12-10. Bernie Williams hit a game-tying three-run
home run in the seventh inning; Jorge Posada cracked a game-winning
three-run home run in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   So when Scott Brosius unleashed a grand slam in the eighth
inning Sunday, the Orioles knew the feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're almost sick to your stomach,'' said Mike Hargrove, the
Orioles' manager, who had endured similar experiences as manager of
the Cleveland Indians. ``But it's not despair. It's a little bit of
anger that it's happened. You've got to have something to give you
a little bit of an edge, and usually anger will do it for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Yankees have made a habit of winning close games
in the late innings, members of other teams try not to sit around,
when they have a lead, wondering when it will happen this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't think about it until it starts happening to you,''
Hargrove said. ``Then you get a little shellshocked. Somebody claps
their hands and you jump four inches. You understand they've been
doing that. The Indians dropped a couple of fly balls to allow them
to win games, stuff like that. You're certainly aware of it.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's no mistaking it when an opposing player or manager
sees it happening. ``You sure do get the feeling,'' Hargrove said.
``If I'm chewing gum, I just spit it out because I know I'm going
to bite my tongue or the side of my mouth because I'll chew it too
hard.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the Brosius blast against Mike Trombley gave the Yankees a
6-4 lead, the Baltimore outfielders gathered together while the
team was making yet another pitching change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just commented on how amazing it is they come up with such
clutch home runs,'' Brady Anderson said. ``It is amazing. You think
of Bernie's home run the other day, and Posada hit a home run when
we have the wheel play on, thinking he's going to bunt, and he hits
the ball 400 feet. They have an amazing team. They've proven
that.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Orioles talked, too, about how Mariano Rivera makes the
Yankees even more amazing, how after the Yankees snatch the
late-inning lead Rivera comes in and closes out the game, putting
another notch in the win-column belt.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Johnson, the Baltimore catcher, acknowledges that Rivera
has made it unlikely that teams will come back against him. ``He's
tough,'' Johnson said. ``He's probably the best closer in the game.
He showed over the years that once he gets the lead, he pretty much
comes in and shuts the door.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hargrove refused to ascribe supernatural qualities to
Rivera. ``You realize he isn't Superman, that he is vulnerable like
anybody else,'' the manager said. Sure enough, Rivera arrived at
the mound for the ninth inning wearing a pinstriped uniform, not
red-and-blue tights with cape.
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove, however, was also realistic. ``I don't think you ever
think today is the day you're going to get to him,'' he said. ``You
just take it an at-bat at a time and try to build something. Catch
a break along the way.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Johnson laid the foundation with a leadoff single to center
field. Mike Bordick hit a fly ball to deep center, but then came
the break Hargrove talked about. Anderson, as so many batters do
against Rivera, broke his bat _ ``In 12 pieces,'' he said _ but hit
the ball just out of Derek Jeter's reach for a single on which
Johnson scooted to third.
</P>
<P>
   Delino DeShields followed with another single that drove in
Johnson, and after B.J. Surhoff moved the runners to second and
third with a groundout, Albert Belle rapped a single that brought
both home for a 7-6 lead and an eventual improbable victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first time I've seen that happen to Rivera since
Cleveland did it to him in the '97 playoffs,'' said Hargrove, who
managed the Indians to a division series victory over the Yankees
after Sandy Alomar Jr. turned the series around with a home run
against Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles, in the flush of victory, thought they could have
won two games in the series, if not all three. They were happy to
leave Yankee Stadium with one.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a very good club,'' Hargrove said. ``It's always
interesting and fun to play them.'' Everything about it is fun?
``The whole experience,'' he said, ``from the ride from the hotel
to the ride to the airport and everything in between. It's a great
city.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
