<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEGASUS' WIN LEAVES NUMEROUS QUESTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ A day after Fusaichi Pegasus made the Kentucky
Derby look easy, some were left to think of what might have been.
Others can afford to think cautiously of what is yet to come. And
others have just had enough of all this.
</P>
<P>
   D. Wayne Lukas remembered that he might be training Fusaichi
Pegasus right now if his clients would have been willing to bid
past $4 million when the colt sold as a yearling two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at the auction with Coolmore Farm representative Demi
O'Byrne, Lukas said he looked over and saw whom he was bidding
against when the price went past $2 million. It was Japanese
venture capitalist Fusao Sekiguchi, a man for whom Lukas had once
trained some horses.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas' skill in training racehorses may be] exceeded only by his
knowledge of someone's bank account, and he knew Sekiguchi
possessed many yen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved the horse,'' Lukas said. ``But when I saw who we were
bidding against, I nudged Demi and told him `We're in for a
dogfight.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sekiguchi owns him, Neil Drysdale trains him, and it's no slam
dunk that Fusaichi Pegasus will race in the Preakness Stakes _ the
next race in the Triple Crown, on May 20 in Baltimore. Drysdale
would only say it's possible, not probable, that Fusaichi Pegasus
would make the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   But that's only a matter of semantics, because Drysdale said
there's only one consideration that would keep him from sending
Fusaichi Pegasus to Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only if he doesn't bounce right back,'' Drysdale said. ``They
always look good the next couple of days \Rafter a race\S. It's
that third day when they resume training. He resumes training
Tuesday \Rtomorrow at Churchill\S. We have to see how he comes out
of the race. As you know, they're fragile animals.''
</P>
<P>
   If he goes, he won't have 18 other horses to contend with as] he
did in the Derby. A loose count on the Churchill Downs backside
yesterday produced a possible field of no more than 10 horses, if
that many. It could end up being the smallest Preakness field since
Spectacular Bid faced four others in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Aptitude, who finish second by a non-threatening 1 1/2 lengths
in the Derby, is being aimed at the Belmont instead of the
Preakness by trainer Bobby Frankel. Todd Pletcher, who trains
third-place Impeachment, said that colt might try the Peter Pan
Stakes two weeks before the Belmont rather than the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   Horses who might come out of the Derby and go to the Preakness
include fourth-place More Than Ready (if he doesn't go to the Met
Mile instead), eighth-place Captain Steve (provided a slight hoof
injury heals), 15th-place High Yield and 16th-place Hal's Hope
(provided two cuts on his legs heal).
</P>
<P>
   Newcomers could include Gotham Stakes winner Red Bullet (he
finished second, 4 1/2 lengths behind Fusaichi Pegasus in the Wood
Memorial) and Snuck In (trained by Steve Asmussen).
</P>
<P>
   Lukas was upbeat even though the three horses he had in the
Derby (Exchange Rate, High Yield and Commendable) finished 12th,
15th and 17th. That's the worst Lukas has done with a
multiple-horse group in the Derby since he finished 10th, 13th and
``did not finish'' with On the Line, War and Capote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done well in the Preakness with horses that haven't done
well here,'' said Lukas, who won the Preakness with Tank's Prospect
after a seventh-place Derby finish in 1985 and with Tabasco Cat
after a sixth-place Derby finish in '94.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not watering down \RFusaichi Pegasus'\S performance,''
Lukas said. ``I'm just saying off of four races, you don't need to
bronze him yet. There's five grueling weeks left \Rin the Triple
Crown\S. We've all been there and we've seen what can happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's foolish to think the rest of the Triple Crown will be a
walkover. He will be tested again. You just don't run up the white
flag after the Kentucky Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's exactly what Jenine Sahadi is doing. She trains The
Deputy, the 9-2 second choice in the Derby wagering, who finished
23 1/2 lengths back in 14th place.
</P>
<P>
   ``He scoped clean \Rin his breathing passage after the race\S,''
Sahadi said. ``He just didn't run. Chris \RMcCarron, The Deputy's
jockey\S said he never felt comfortable. I'm going to give him a
month to kick back.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most trainers with horses from the Derby, Sahadi would
rather watch than race against Fusaichi Pegasus.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
