<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ENRON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUGH A BEAUTIFUL STADIUM, ENRON FIELD A NIGHTMARE FOR PITCHERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ There is no truth to the rumor that the
Astros pitchers had to be dragged kicking and screaming onto the
team's charter plane from Los Angeles to Houston last night.
</P>
<P>
   Neither, though, did they go skipping and laughing.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, Astros pitchers celebrated the end of a road trip.
That meant they could go back to the Astrodome, a pitcher's
paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Now they work in Enron Field, a pitcher's nightmare that,
because of its tiny dimensions down the foul lines and in the power
alleys, yields home runs in staggering amounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we couldn't wait to get home,'' Astros pitcher Jose
Lima said. ``This year, we don't want to come home. It's just scary
when you see the ball going so fast and so far. I've never seen
anything like that. It's unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being a dream home, the new ballpark has been a house
of horrors. The Astros won just three of their first 12 games at
Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros return home today for a seven-game homestand, trying
to figure out how to turn the haunted house into a home sweet home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got 60-something games left in Enron Field, and we've
got to play a lot better there,'' Astros first baseman Jeff Bagwell
said. ``We've got to start to make that place a home-field
advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been so far, mostly because Astros pitchers have
struggled at home. The staff had a 7.51 earned-run average in the
first 12 games at Enron. Opponents hit .309, and swatted 23 home
runs in 109 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Balls flew out of the park at a rate of 3.83 per game, compared
with 1.44 at the Astrodome last year and even surpassing the 3.74 a
game hit at high-altitude Coors Field in '99.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't making good pitches,'' Astros pitcher Chris Holt
said. ``It didn't matter what field we were playing on, we were
going to get beat. There's little adjustments they can make to the
field, grow the grass a little higher, things that could help us a
little bit. But when you're not making good pitches, which we
weren't doing, you're going to get beat. If you make good pitches,
it doesn't matter what park you're in, you'll be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   They showed what they're capable of on the 10-game road trip
that ended in LA yesterday, holding the opposition to four runs or
less seven times in the first nine games, including two shutouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the good pitching on this road trip means they can go
home with a little more confidence,'' manager Larry Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Confidence could help the pitchers turn things around at Enron.
So could a couple of adjustments, both physical and one mental.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker suggested his staff emulate Cubs pitcher Jon Lieber, who
pitched a complete-game five-hitter and yielded just one earned run
in a 12-3 victory at Houston on April 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he did was throw hard pitches around the knees, sinkers
and sliders, and made us hit the ball on the ground,'' Dierker
said. ``We can do that just like he can. We haven't, but there is
the evidence it can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt said the pitchers need to be more aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing you can't do is get behind,'' he said. ``You've got
to get strike one there. You can't nibble on the corners, because
if they're not called, you're behind. At the Dome, you could lay
that cookie fastball in there and get a popup usually. At Enron,
you can't. Jam shots go out, and balls off the end of the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   The mental adjustment involves the realization that Enron is not
the Astrodome. Pitchers need to forget about shutouts and low ERAs,
and concentrate on minimizing the damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't such an issue with us anymore, because we know the
way the stadium is,'' Lima said. ``It's a beautiful stadium, but
we've got a short porch. We have to say, `Go seven innings and give
up five runs, give your ballclub a chance to win.' ''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
