<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8365 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-GLF-NELSON-TEX     05-07 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NELSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE TREES, LONGER HOLES TO PRESENT CHALLENGE AT NELSON CLASSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ A birdie sanctuary on the front nine has been
eliminated. A forest-in-waiting has been planted on the back nine.
</P>
<P>
   It's little wonder, then, that Loren Roberts feels a bit like a
ruler exiled from his kingdom as he ponders his title defense at
the GTE Byron Nelson Classic. Roberts will tee off in Thursday's
opening round at the Four Seasons Resort facing a TPC-Las Colinas
course that is home to 781 new trees, two enlarged greens, two new
tee boxes and several reconstructed bunkers since he set a
tournament scoring record (18-under-par, 262) there last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll certainly make things interesting. And different,''
Roberts said. ``I'm anxious to see how it affects play.''
</P>
<P>
   So are Nelson officials, who estimate the daily scoring average
for competitors could climb by anywhere from three-tenths of a
stroke to a full stroke per day on the TPC layout. The Cottonwood
Valley course, where golfers play one of their four rounds during
the tournament, has not changed since last year.
</P>
<P>
   The primary changes on the TPC course boil down to alterations
at six holes. Of those, the ones most likely to impact scoring
include new tee boxes that lengthen the sixth and 15th holes, a new
green at No. 12 and a major overhaul of No. 10. In addition,
strategic tree plantings at No. 1 and No. 16 make it imprudent for
some golfers to play from familiar divot locations.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious change is at No. 10, where the tee has been
moved roughly 50 yards to the left, forcing players to hit their
drives over a canal. Four additional fairway bunkers have been
added near the landing area, and the green has been expanded by
1,700 square feet. A pair of greenfront bunkers were also added,
which could make for some well-tucked hole locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can get some pins there that these guys never dreamed of
before,'' said Scott Miller, golf course superintendent at the Four
Seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not one of the holes Miller will be monitoring
closely in anticipation of a shift in scoring average from the 1999
Nelson. The major movement, in Miller's estimation, should occur at
a pair of par-4s that were lengthened by new tee boxes.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth hole has been stretched by 50 yards, to 436. Instead
of pitching wedge approaches, most players now will hit 7-irons or
8-irons. Miller estimated that would translate to an increase of .2
or .3 from last year's scoring average of 3.957.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a much more interesting hole,'' said Paul Pulliam, Nelson
tournament vice chairman. ``It had been a slam dunk for the pros.
It was a birdie hole. But not any more. Now, it's got some
character.''
</P>
<P>
   But the alterations most likely to test a player's character _
and patience _ occurred at No. 15. Lengthened by 30 yards, the hole
is now the second-longest par-4 on the course. It plays at 475
yards, usually into a prevailing south wind. In addition, the 15th
fairway has been raised and 72 trees have been added, eliminating
an option of favoring the left side and allowing drives to roll
back to the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, most of the balls funnel left there, instead of right,''
said Southlake resident and tour pro Brandt Jobe, who practices
regularly at the TPC course. ``I think that'll be the biggest
change for us. You need a bigger drive now, especially on windy
days. And it's got to be straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the impact of the trees in the left rough, Jobe
chuckled.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I'd never noticed the trees there before,'' Jobe
said. ``But now, if you hit it in the trees, you're dead. You've
got no shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The additional trees, combined with the likelihood of approach
shots with 3-irons, prompted Miller to predict the scoring average
would rise by at least a tenth of a stroke per day. That would
allow No. 15, the second-toughest hole in last year's Nelson
(4.216), to eclipse the par-4 14th (4.252) as the toughest hole on
the TPC layout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it definitely will be,'' Pulliam said. ``You'll see
the pros hitting in more long irons instead of 7-, 8- or 9-irons.
That will make a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   In time, the biggest change may be felt at No. 16, where 18
percent of the new trees (137 total) are concentrated. Most,
however, are saplings and will have little impact on play this
year. But there is one large live oak in the right rough,
approximately 310 yards from the tee box. It has no name but could
be dubbed the Tiger Tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's out there for the long hitters. If they lose it right,
they pay a penalty,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   The only new tree that has been named is the ``Peggy Nelson
Tree,'' located in the right rough at No. 1. The live oak is 32
feet high, with a span of 25 feet. It sits 130 yards short of the
green, near the turn of the dogleg at the 385-yard par-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will make them rethink their club selection. Most guys, if
they lose it right, now you're under a tree,'' Miller said. ``Your
choices now are to fly everything and go for the green, like Tiger
Woods, or to lay back with a 3-iron and hit a pitching wedge
\Rapproach\S.''
</P>
<P>
   One other alteration may impact scoring, in Miller's estimation.
The 12th green has been enlarged by 800 square feet, with more
swale added to the putting surface. The combination may result in
some trickier pin placements and more three-putts.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Miller estimated the scoring average on the TPC layout
would increase by .3 to .4] per day because of the changes. Pulliam
offered a higher number.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be surprised if it doesn't go up by a stroke this year,''
Pulliam said. ``As this course matures, it'll go up more than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are not as convinced. Art Barnes, a member of the Nelson
tournament committee, predicted players would make another run at
Roberts' scoring record unless blustery conditions prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the wind's not blowing, they'll tear it up,'' Barnes said.
``The new trees aren't really a factor for this year. They're not
tall enough. This is still a forgiving course. If you spray the
ball, you can't get in that much trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Jobe agreed that the course changes, while aesthetically
pleasing, should not hamper the touring pros with regularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be some problems if you wind up in the wrong
place, but I don't think it will change the scoring much,'' Jobe
said. ``Most of the changes are stuff you can adjust to in a
practice round or two. It's like anything else in golf. The guys
who are playing well will benefit. And it will hurt the guys who
are playing poorly.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
