<HEADER>
A8366 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-JEFFERSON0508-COX     05-07 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON0508-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jefferson, Hemings feud still lacking resolution
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. _ Thomas Jefferson's descendants concluded
their family reunion Sunday without deciding whether to acknowledge
kinship to Sally Hemings, Jefferson's alleged slave mistress.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in a year that two dozen of Hemings' kin
left Charlottesville without an invitation to join the all-white
Monticello Association.
</P>
<P>
   The association's 700 members are entitled to burial in the
Monticello cemetery where Jefferson, the nation's third president,
is buried.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing that we can take back with us that has made a
difference,'' said Hemings descendant Shay Banks-Young of Columbus,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday's meeting in the downtown Charlottesville Omni hotel
lacked the rancor of last year's, the first time Hemings' kin
attended the Jefferson family's reunion.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, several people who've been outspoken on both sides said
Sunday they're confident that the association is trying to resolve
a controversial question that has proved complicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general terms, the issue is, how does the association
determine who is, or is not, a descendant of Thomas Jefferson?''
the association's president, James Truscott, told reporters. ``We
must be able to apply the criteria to anyone, not just Hemings
descendants.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, some Jefferson relatives are skeptical of the
Hemings family's oral histories that link Hemings and Jefferson.
Those Jefferson relatives insist that Hemings' kin provide DNA or
some other substantial proof of their kinship to Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   But if the association adopted DNA as a requirement, some of its
current members couldn't pass the test, Truscott said.
</P>
<P>
   That's because scientists are not able to trace DNA through a
female line. So those Jefferson relatives descended from his
daughters, Martha and Maria, could not prove a relationship by DNA
testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is why we have a complex task,'' said V.R. Shackleford,
chairman of the association's committee studying membership
requirements. ``We are deciding whether we can make a
recommendation that accounts for the unknowns and moves this
process forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's meeting did have some contentious moments revolving
around Jefferson's disputed paternity of Hemings' six children.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of a new organization, the Thomas Jefferson
Foundation, sharply questioned historians from the Thomas Jefferson
Memorial Foundation, which owns Monticello and serves as caretaker
of Jefferson's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   In January, after decades of silence on the questions, the
Memorial Foundation sided with the Hemings' claim of kinship. In
concluding that Jefferson was ``most likely'' the father of
Hemings' six children born at Monticello, the foundation embraced
1998 DNA evidence, written records about Jefferson's life at
Monticello, and the Hemings family's oral histories.
</P>
<P>
   The new organization said the Memorial Foundation overlooked
historical evidence that made a strong case against Jefferson's
paternity. It also noted that the only positive DNA test showed
that Thomas Jefferson could have been one of eight Jefferson males
to have fathered children by Hemings.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides made presentations Sunday. Over the next year, the
association's membership requirements committee hopes to prepare
recommendations for the association's executive committee.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not certain, Truscott said, that the association will
vote next year on the recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Hemings' relatives said they're taking the association at its
word to seek a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people seem to want to be fair, but they've got an angry
and vociferous element,'' said Dorothy Westerinen, 42, of Staten
Island, N.Y. She is descended from Eston Hemings, Sally's youngest
son.
</P>
<P>
   Another Hemings' descendant, Shay Banks-Young, of Columbus,
Ohio, said she is more interested in the right to be buried in the
Monticello cemetery, than to actually be buried there.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is like saying I must sit at the back of the bus,''
Banks-Young said. ''I may like sitting at the back of the bus, but
don't tell me that's what I've got to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to assume if there is a shadow of a possibility
through the DNA and the oral histories that they are a part of our
family,'' said Jefferson descendant Isabella Gardner Coolidge of
Washington. ''And then we must welcome them with open as a
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanita Balthazar-Boettcher, a descendant of Madison Hemings, one
of Sally's sons, said she believes a resolution of the paternity
dispute is at least five years away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of the finger pointing has to stop,'' said
Balthazar-Boettcher, 39, of Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   She said she is convinced by 1998 DNA evidence and her family's
oral history that she is descended from Jefferson and Hemings. She
and her husband, Rusty, named their 15-month-old son, Madison,
after Madison Hemings.
</P>
<P>
   Someday Balthazar-Boettcher hopes to sprinkle the ashes of her
deceased grandmother, in the Monticello cemetery, where Jefferson
is buried.
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, ''I don't think that is as important as it being
known that there was more to Thomas Jefferson that has been
reported over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   Tina Andrews, the screenwriter and co-executive producer of the
recent CBS miniseries, ''Sally Hemings: An American Scandal,'' said
the tension between the Jeffersons and the Hemings is like that of
an interracial marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ''The parents of the white guy tell him it is OK to have her as
a friend, but you cannot bring her into the family,'' said Andrews,
who attended Sunday's meeting, as well as last year's.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
