<HEADER>
A8369 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ELIAN-COURTBOX0508-CO     05-07 0296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-COURTBOX0508-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    11TH U.S. CIRCUIT COURT OF APPEALS
 &HT;    Compiled by Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Jurisdiction: The court, headquartered in Atlanta, considers
thousands of appeals a year from U.S. District Courts in Georgia,
Alabama and Florida. The court's decisions can be appealed to the
U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Cases: A wide variety of cases are considered by the court.
These include appeals of criminal convictions and sentences. And
they include appeals involving civil lawsuits alleging sexual
harassment, job discrimination, antitrust violations, copyright
infringement and voting rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Caseload: The court is the nation's busiest and most efficient
in the numbers of cases considered. Each judge, on average, wrote
267 decisions last year.
</P>
<P>
   Judges: The court has 12 _ five from Florida, four from Georgia
and three from Alabama. The judges have lifetime tenure, and must
be nominated by the president and confirmed by the Senate. The
court has three women judges and one African-American judge. Seven
were nominated by a Republican president, five by a Democratic
president.
</P>
<P>
   Rulings: Panels made up of three judges decide most of the
cases. The full court can be asked to review a panel's ruling and,
in limited circumstances, the 12 judges sit as a whole to hear the
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   History: Until 1981, the court was known as the 5th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals and had jurisdiction from Texas to Georgia. But a
mounting caseload led Congress to split up that court and create
the 11th Circuit in Atlanta. Before the court was broken up, the
5th Circuit was noted for its landmark rulings in desegregation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-00 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
