<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' OUTFIELDERS GAINING EXPERIENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE SANCHEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ If the names of outfielders Chad Curtis and
Jason McDonald sound foreign in the Rangers' starting lineup, there
is one solution: Get used to it.
</P>
<P>
   At least for now.
</P>
<P>
   With starting left fielder Rusty Greer (left hamstring) and
starting right fielder Gabe Kapler (partially torn hip flexor) both
on the 15-day disabled list, Curtis starts in left field and
McDonald in right for the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great to get the opportunity to help out the
team,'' McDonald said. ``I've been give the chance to do something;
hopefully, I'll make the best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald started his fourth consecutive game yesterday in a 7-6
loss to Oakland and hit his second home run of the season. He did,
however, hit into an inning-ending double play in the fourth inning
with the bases loaded and the Rangers trailing 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth inning, with Oakland leading 7-6, he struck out
with Curtis on third base and Mike Lamb on first to end the inning.
He finished the day 1-for-4 with two strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't come through when they needed me,'' McDonald said.
``\ROakland reliever Doug Jones\S made some good pitches and got
me, but overall, I think I'm doing OK.''
</P>
<P>
   In Curtis' 14th consecutive start yesterday, he went 2-for-3
with a single, a double, and a walk. He is 25-for-83 in the past 21
games since taking over for Greer with 10 of his past 17 hits going
for extra bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot easier when you get in there every day,'' Curtis
said. ``It's nice to show what I am capable of doing, and
hopefully, the fans will get some confidence in me when I get in
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I am good enough to play every day, and when Rusty
comes back that will be a big boost to our team. But I am a pretty
good player myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have been looking for another outfielder, and last
week, Rangers general manager Doug Melvin asked about acquiring
Philadelphia Phillies outfielder Ron Gant and Los Angeles
outfielder Todd Hollingsworth. Neither deal materialized.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can do is play the best I can,'' McDonald said. ``I
can't worry about if they get another outfielder or not. If they do
get another, I can't think about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said he's no longer seeking another outfielder and is
confident of the play of Curtis and McDonald.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting to believe these guys can do just as good of job
as anybody who is out there,'' Melvin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
