<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8378 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FAIRBANKS-OBIT0508-CO     05-07 1644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAIRBANKS-OBIT0508-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Douglas Fairbanks Jr., a man of many talents
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Douglas Fairbanks Jr., a star of stage,
screen and television, a friend to royalty, a real-life war hero
who spent many years in Palm Beach, died Sunday. He was 90.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Fairbanks died from natural causes at Mount Sinai Medical
Center in New York. He had suffered from Parkinson's disease for
years, said his former personal assistant, Kay Hutchins of West
Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Fairbanks was a relative, friend or lover to some of the biggest
names in entertainment _ his father was the swashbuckling star of
silent film, Douglas Fairbanks Sr.; Joan Crawford at one time was
his wife; and Sir Laurence Olivier was a close friend. But Mr.
Fairbanks was a man of his own making.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared in some 75 movies, served as consultant to
presidents, and earned a chestful of war decorations, including the
U.S. Silver Star for his service as a Naval commander in World War
II. And King George VI gave him an honorary knighthood in 1949.
``Always, always thoughtful and appreciative,'' said Hutchins, 81,
who worked with Fairbanks for 15 years through the '80s and early
'90s. ``Women and men liked him. Women, of course, threw themselves
at him.'' Longtime resident Herbert Swope, one of Fairbanks'
closest friends locally, said the actor's congeniality and charm
would captivate guests at the parties they frequently attended in
Palm Beach. Fairbanks did everything gracefully, whether it was
writing about his many romances with leading ladies like Marlene
Dietrich or answering a question he'd been asked a thousand times,
Swope said. Fairbanks was a frequent visitor to Palm Beach since
the 1930s and finally purchased his historic home, the Vicarage, in
1971. There he led a quiet life and maintained a low profile
devoting much time to charities. Fairbanks sold the pink lakefront
mansion in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The only child of socialite Anna Beth Sully Fairbanks, daughter
of a cotton financier, and silent screen star Douglas Fairbanks
Sr., he was born Dec. 9, 1909. He attended schools in London, Paris
and the United States including Harvard Military School in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Of the many movies Mr. Fairbanks made, he once told a reporter
he only liked a few.
</P>
<P>
   One time he said his most fulfilling roles were in such films as
``State Secret,'' ``The Exile,'' ``The Corsican Brothers,'' ``Gunga
Din,'' ``The Prisoner of Zenda,'' ``The Amateur Gentlemen,''
``Catherine The Great'' and ``The Dawn Patrol.''
</P>
<P>
   He performed on stage in such productions as ``My Fair Lady,''
``Saturday's Children,'' ``The Pleasure of His Company,'' ``Romeo
and Juliet,'' ``The Secretary Bird'' and ``Present Laughter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like acting that much,'' he said in 1976. ``Actually,
in my lifetime, I've done only about a dozen things I've really
enjoyed and it was always in the area of writing or producing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't take all this celebrity stuff too seriously ... I'm
easily embarrassed,'' he said during a 1978 interview. ``I'm shy
about being the center of attention so I've developed an armor
against it _ a protective aura.''
</P>
<P>
   He grew up surrounded by stardom in ``Pickfair,'' the Hollywood
mansion named in honor of his father and his stepmother, Mary
Pickford, the golden-haired silent film star.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy trying to succeed in an industry his father had
conquered in the days of silent films.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was one of those lucky people who began to be
successful the day he was born,'' Mr. Fairbanks said during a 1984
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Fairbanks Jr. was a better actor than Fairbanks Sr., but not as
physically graceful. Blithe and debonair, he always seemed vaguely
English, even though he was American by birth and training. His
first real success came in the early years of sound, in the
back-to-back hits ``The Dawn Patrol'' and ``Little Caesar.''
</P>
<P>
   After an early estrangement from his father _ the elder
Fairbanks felt his son to be unfairly capitalizing on his name _
the two men reconciled and became quite close long before Fairbanks
Sr.'s death in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   The younger actor sought career advice from his father, which
led him to one of his greatest successes, Rupert of Hentzau in the
1937 version of ``The Prisoner of Zenda.'' Fairbanks Jr. was
doubtful about playing the part because of its comparatively small
size.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take it,'' his father advised. ``It's the best part in the
script. Rin-Tin-Tin could play and make a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The years on either side of World War II were the peak of Mr.
Fairbanks' film career, with ``Gunga Din'' just before the war, and
``Sinbad the Sailor'' afterwards. He then started his own
production company, which resulted in very good pictures such as
``The Exile'' (for which Mr. Fairbanks wrote the screenplay) and
``The Fighting O'Flynn.''
</P>
<P>
   His last major movie was ``Mr. Drake's Duck'' in 1951 although
he was killed off in the first 20 minutes of ``Ghost Story,''
released in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Born in New York City, Mr. Fairbanks lived many years in
England. In April 1939 he married Mary Lee Epling Hartford, former
wife of an heir to the A&AMP;P grocery chain fortune, whom he met at a
party at Swope's house.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Fairbanks' first marriage, at age 19, to the late Joan
Crawford, ended in divorce after four years in 1933. When he was
just 20 years old, he appeared opposite Greta Garbo in ``A Woman of
Affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   He was commissioned lieutenant (j.g.) in the Naval Reserve in
1941 and proceeded through the ranks to full commander in the Navy
during World War II. He trained and led commando units, served on a
destroyer providing convoy escort in the North Atlantic, served on
minesweeper patrol and eventually was assigned to Admiral Lord
Louis Mountbatten's Combined Operations headquarters, at first in
planning, then in special weapons and camouflage sections.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Fairbanks earned the British Distinguished Service Cross,
Crois de Guerre with Palm from France, the War Cross for Military
Valor (Italy), and an American Silver Star. The French commendation
said in part:
</P>
<P>
   ``With electric power gone, radio shot away, with German shells
continually straddling or near-missing his ships, he successfully
deployed the (naval) unit behind a smoke screen and emerged in a
new and tactfully superior position. Then he closed with the enemy
and, after an intense exchange of fire, both German ships were
sunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Fairbanks devised a plan to end the war with Japan that so
impressed President Franklin D. Roosevelt that he made an
appointment to talk it over. But Roosevelt died the day before the
scheduled conference and some of Mr. Fairbanks' superiors scotched
the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly the plan was to try, through secret neutral channels, to
influence the dowager Empress of Japan to intercede with Emperor
Hirohito to bring about a coup d'etat that would lead to an end of
the fighting. His father had had a close relationship with the
Japanese royal family.
</P>
<P>
   Fairbanks was the first U.S. naval officer ever assigned to lead
a crack British commando unit across the English Channel. King
George gave him an honorary knighthood for his work in connection
with Anglo-American affairs and also in recognition of his
chairmanship for a fund-raising committee that sent more than $150
million worth of food parcels and other goods to European countries
after the war.
</P>
<P>
   Had Mr. Fairbanks been a British citizen, the honor would have
entitled him to be called ``Sir Douglas.'' He was well liked by
British royalty and for many years maintained a home in London.
</P>
<P>
   In 1951 he was appointed chairman of American Relief for Korea
by the State Department, serving in that position until 1955.
Between 1948 and 1963 he was national vice president for the
American Association for the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Fairbanks also wrote two volumes of autobiography: ``Salad
Days'' and ``A Hell of a War.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his fame, he didn't take himself or his movie career too
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   He had an impressive list of public service appointments and
associations including membership on the U.S. Military Delegation
to the SEATO Conference _ representing the Navy _ in London in
1971, a member of the Council on Foreign Relations Inc., and a
trustee of the Pacific War Memorial. He served as President
Roosevelt's envoy to Brazil, Argentina, Uruguay, Chile, Peru and
Panama in 1940-41 and was a part-time consultant to President Harry
Truman on foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Douglas Fairbanks Presents,'' which played two years each on
NBC and ABC, produced 160 half-hour television plays in the 1950s.
He acted in 50 of them. He also enjoyed collecting rare books,
letters and documents. His hobbies were photography and travel.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Fairbanks, who was a member of the Academy of Motion Picture
Arts and Sciences, never was nominated for an Oscar. But it didn't
bother him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father never got one, John Barrymore never got one, (Greta)
Garbo never got one and Charlie Chaplin didn't get one until two
years before he died,'' he said in March 1987 after mailing his
Academy Awards selections. ``So those of us who never have are in
very good company.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife of almost 50 years, Mary Lee Fairbanks, died in 1988.
Three years later, Fairbanks married his third wife, Vera Shelton
Fairbanks, a merchandiser for the Home Shopping Network. He is
survived by her and three daughters, Daphne, Victoria and Melissa,
as well as eight grandchildren and six great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Vera Shelton Fairbanks said Sunday that Mr. Fairbanks will be
buried next to his father in a Los Angeles cemetery. Memorial
service plans had not been finalized Sunday afternoon, but she said
the family would likely hold services in both New York and London.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
