<HEADER>
A8380 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MENSA0508-COX     05-07 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENSA0508-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For testers, it's how you play the game
 &HT;    By Jen Sansbury
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It doesn't take a genius to know when a game's not
worth playing, but if even geniuses can't make heads or tails of
it, it may be time to go back to the drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 brainy types, members of American Mensa, spent most of
this weekend in Atlanta evaluating 40 new games.
</P>
<P>
   But this was no solemn chess match for the high IQ'ed. The
Mensans played games on boards, cards and computer chips. They
tried their hands at games with pegs, of plastic and puzzles.
</P>
<P>
   Mensa in Georgia, one of the largest regional groups in the
country, hosted Mind Games 2000. About half the testers came from
out of state to play games submitted by mid-sized and mom-and-pop
game companies competing for only five Mensa Select seals of
approval.
</P>
<P>
   The judges say they attended because they love games and yearn
for a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   I don't have people to play,'' said Robyn Dixon, who drove five
hours from Tallahassee, Fla. ``They won't play with me because I
win.''
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for the competition, the games had to have been
released on the market or significantly changed since March 1999.
The judges ranked each game on appearance, clarity of the
instructions, interest, originality and how much fun it was to
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them are stupid _ you can tell from the beginning _ or
too complex,'' said Joy Glucksman, an Atlanta attorney. ``It's not
going to be a 'game' if there's 20 pages of rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The hotel meeting room-turned-gameroom stayed open around the
clock for diehards like Amy Whinston of Portland, Ore., who played
until 6 a.m. one morning.
</P>
<P>
   The Mensans said most of the other games also were good, but
could use better packaging, pieces or directions. Their comments
will be forwarded to the manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them don't necessarily care if they win. They look at
it as a way to get feedback on their game,'' said Mark Witter,
marketing director for American Mensa, based in Arlington, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Trivial Pursuit received one of the first Mensa Select seals in
1990. Though all the winners may not have become household words
over the years, Witter said, some have met with solid success,
including Magic _ The Gathering, a fantasy card game, and Set, an
educational game.
</P>
<P>
   This year's top five picks were 3 Stones by Enginuity Games,
Finish Lines by Games for All Reasons, iMAgiNiff by Buffalo Games,
Time's Up by R&AMP;R Games and Zertz by Schmidt International.
</P>
<P>
   Like every year, there were a few duds. Dixon dismissed one game
that required players to use all five senses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We refused to play when it said 'smell someone else's dirty
laundry,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
