<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8385 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-IRWIN0508-COX     05-07 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-IRWIN0508-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Irwin shoots for another turnaround
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He has won three U.S. Opens and they comprise the
highlight reel of his professional life. Vast as his post-50
riches, nothing accomplished on the Senior Tour will ever compare.
</P>
<P>
   But say this about Hale Irwin's victory in the Nationwide
Championship last year at The Golf Club of Georgia. What the story
lacked in career impact, it made up for in closing drama. The
thrilling, 74-yard sand wedge shot at the par-5, 18th hole landed
on the front of the green, bounced twice and trickled into the cup
for an eagle, instantaneously winning the tournament for Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   Observing it all after finishing at 8-under, Bob Murphy felt
like a man who had turned a corner and walked into a car door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never done anything like that before,'' Irwin said. ``I
knocked in a long putt to get into a playoff in the (1990) U.S.
Open, but I've never holed a shot like that and then been handed a
trophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody ever claimed it wasn't a strange or unpredictable game.
Odds on Irwin completing the tournament with such an exacting shot
a few days before bordered on laughable. The same Hale Irwin _
three-time U.S. Open champion and long-time Senior Tour dominator _
fiddled in the locker room with a new putter, searching for lost
magic. Positioned an unfamiliar 25th on the money list, Irwin
decided that after 16 victories in two years, it was simply a case
of, ``paying my dues a little bit now.'' Clearly, he was prepared
for a rough summer ride of watching newcomers Allen Doyle and Bruce
Fleisher dice him on the leaderboard.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Bob Duval made the most foretelling comment
early in Nationwide week. ``Don't say anything,'' Duval warned when
asked the Irwin slump. ``You know what they say about sleeping
bears. Just let him alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, the wedge at 18 would provide a scary catalyst
for Irwin; he won four more times in the next seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that was the type shot I was struggling with,'' Irwin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's the minute things that separate playing in the
middle of the pack from accepting a winner's check. Irwin decided
on a return to the original Titleist Professional, 90-compression
ball he had used during his 1997-98 tear prior to last year's
Nationwide. He said the old ball gave him a slightly different ball
flight. On Sunday afternoon, the trajectory became, well, two
bounces and into the cup on the 54th hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``That little bit of a change was all I needed to make,'' said
Irwin, long regarded as one of golf's finest iron players. ``The
new ball seemed like it came off the club a little quicker and
produced a little different flight. The old one seemed like it
stayed on the club a little longer and I could get my old
trajectory. ... I've been playing it ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   By season's end, Irwin was bothered by shoulder problems and
failed in a late run to catch Fleisher. But Irwin set a Senior Tour
record with at least $2 million in winnings and five victories for
a third straight year.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin returns to Atlanta this year hoping to find a similar
switch. Although fifth on the money list ($539,768) he has three
seconds and no victories. Each runner-up week has included at least
one penalty stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just been making one or two mistakes along the way that I
shouldn't,'' Irwin said. ``Ultimately, most of the mistakes you
make are mental. If you hit a ball in the water, generally you
shouldn't have been aiming so close in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   The Golf Club of Georgia, with its undulating greens, can get a
player doing exactly that in an attempt to find the more puttable
areas. Irwin had done everything but win in the Nationwide,
finishing second in 1995,'97 and '98. A notable near-miss in 1995
ended with Irwin trying to launch a 3-wood to the 18th hole off a
slightly downhill lie and finding the pond.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a position golf course,'' Irwin said. ``The long hitter
has a distinct advantage, but you can't just step up and whale it.
The greens are not extraordinarily difficult to hit, but it's a
course fraught with potential disasters. You can play aggressive,
but you need to be prepared for a wild ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin has been very active in his course design work and is
building a house in Phoenix. ``I feel fairly good, but I'm not on
top of my game, simply because I have so many other things swirling
around,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He will play in the U.S. Open at Pebble Beach next month two
weeks after turning 55, joining Jack Nicklaus as the only Senior
players in the competition. But he will attempt to prevent the
burnout that occurred late in 1998 and carried into the beginning
of 1999. In August, Irwin will prepare for the Senior Tour finish
with a fishing trip to Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I've never done before, but it's something I
need to do,'' he said. ``The machine still works, but the battery
runs down.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
