<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8386 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-NYT &LR;      05-07 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON AND KNICKS MALFUNCTION IN FINAL 5 MINUTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 6,7,8,9,10 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Deep in the pit of a prized new venue that is decorated
in the happy color scheme of a Life Savers pack, a fretful Pat
Riley was as helpless a sight Sunday afternoon as he was a year ago
in the dank and gloomy air of the old Miami Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, an anxious Riley was planted on the sideline,
waiting to see if Allan Houston would begin to summon the kind of
mental focus that can bend spoons, move pencils and throw his Heat
into a trance. So, Riley, his team and the screaming masses inside
American Airlines Arena seemed to be bracing themselves for the
moment when the serene shooter would make another playoff game go
``poof.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was an apparent malfunction in Houston's spell. A
missing ingredient in his potion. Instead of undoing the Heat,
Houston fell apart in the final five minutes of Game 1 Sunday.
Instead of calm, Houston exhibited uncharacteristic jitters as he
botched an open 3-pointer and turned the ball over three times in
the Knicks' 87-83 loss. Instead of deflating the Heat's hope of
growing from their past pains, he opened the way for them to take a
1-0 lead in this four-of-seven-game, second-round playoff series,
87-83.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's final misstep came when Dan Majerle _ the old guard
who was patrolling him the day he eliminated the Heat last year
with his destined runner _ stuck his jalopy-shaped body on Houston
at the top of the arc with five seconds left in the game. As
Houston moved to shoot, Majerle stripped the ball in mid-dribble
with 1.7 left on the clock. Any chance for a miracle was officially
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm going to be the guy with the ball in his hands at the
end of the game, I've got to get a shot up or make something
happen,'' said Houston, who finished with a team-high 21 points but
was eight for 18 from the field. ``In the past, I've usually done
that. I didn't do either today, and that's what's so disappointing.
We didn't do what we had to at the end to get this win.''
</P>
<P>
   Alonzo Mourning did exactly what his team needed. He did not
take pity on his mentor, Patrick Ewing. He did not think twice
about how Ewing spent his idle moments on the bench Sunday wrapped
in a heating pad for his tight back. He did not freeze at the
moment he had a late-game encounter with his boyhood hero.
</P>
<P>
   Calmly, Mourning slipped to a spot outside the paint. And with
Ewing laboring to reach him 17-feet from the basket, Mourning rose
off the floor and sent up a soft jumper that was nestled by the net
with 5.6 seconds on the clock. As it turned out, it was the
game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to admire Patrick's attitude and his determination,''
said Mourning, who led the Heat with 26 points and helped hold the
ailing but able Ewing to 17. ``That's one of the things I've
admired about him over the years, from watching him play at the age
of 12. A lot of him has rubbed off on me. He's the reason I
approach the game the way I do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heat approached this game with desperation. The Knicks
arrived with an air of arrogance that didn't wear well. It's as if
they thought the game would just come to them in the end _ because
it has so often. When it didn't, they grew impatient.
</P>
<P>
   During a fourth quarter filled with too many jump shots and not
enough drives, the entire team failed to keep their composure. In
the final five minutes of the game, the Knicks were 0 for 5 and
committed four turnovers. And not one of the Knicks who had haunted
the Heat in the past could avoid a trap door.
</P>
<P>
   A harried Chris Childs failed to crush the Heat by missing two
3-pointers in the final four minutes; and a wide-open Larry Johnson
wavered just enough when he unleashed a 3-pointer with 1 minutes 11
seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him out there by himself,'' said Tim Hardaway, who
limped on his injured foot, left the game briefly to get retaped,
and finished with six points and seven assists. ``If he had hit
that one, we would have seen him doing his `L.J.' thing up and down
our court.''
</P>
<P>
   But with his team down by two points, Johnson missed the
go-ahead shot. But in some ways, the Heat created Johnson's miss by
playing aggressive defense most of the game. It was the kind of
hovering effort that left the Knicks to shoot just 42.3 percent
from the field, the kind that left Johnson shocked at how alone he
was at that point in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``All day long, they were rotating to me,'' Johnson said. ``So,
I was a little surprised to see myself that wide open. Once I saw
that, I thought I rushed it. Got too excited. I've got to hit that.
I really do.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Knicks managed to tie the game with 55.6 seconds left
when Jamal Mashburn mindlessly fouled Latrell Sprewell. Finally,
Sprewell had a chance to make an impact. For most of the day, he
had been banged and bumped off his game by the bulky Mashburn. This
was not the more-compact, less-experienced Vince Carter. This was
harder. Without double teams to help him, Sprewell gave up 21
points to a steady Mashburn. Without a way to score around his
size, Sprewell ended up with 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   But his last two were critical. Sprewell made his free throws,
tied the game at 83-83, but watched Houston commit 2 turnovers in
the span of 30 seconds. With his logic on the blink, Houston tried
to zip a pass to Ewing in the post, right beneath the chin of P.J.
Brown, who grabbed the steal with 28.3 seconds on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just one of those passes where I would have really had
to thread a needle,'' Houston said. ``That's probably the single
play I wish I could have back. I don't care if Patrick was Jerry
Rice, that would have been a tough one to catch. As soon as threw
it, I wish I had it back.''
</P>
<P>
   There were a lot of those moments during the game. The Knicks
wished the first quarter hadn't happened, when they failed to match
the Heat's intensity, and went on a 0-for-12 stretch over a
seven-minute period. They wished they hadn't fallen behind by eight
points twice in a third quarter that was only revived on the solo
intensity Charlie Ward showed as he drove to the hoop and dove on
the floor. On one move, he left Hardaway in pain as he planted his
bad foot to stop Ward's drive. On another, Ward crashed into
Mourning's right temple in a scramble for a loose ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Heisman Trophy winner had a flashback,'' Mourning said.
``He went head-first into me. That's the way both coaches teach.
The football player he is, he shook it off. I had to gather myself
and get back into it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heat did that all day. If the Knicks made a run, the Heat
regrouped. If the Knicks came up with a big play, the Heat returned
it with two. While the Knicks melted down in the fourth quarter
with five turnovers, the Heat didn't turn it over once.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept their composure,'' Houston said. ``That's something
we usually pride ourselves on doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, they do it right here, right in the pit of Riley's
turf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
