<DOCNO> NYT20000507.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8389 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-LIBERALS-2TAKES     05-07 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-LIBERALS-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA CRACKS DOWN ON VOCAL LIBERAL INTELLECTUALS
</HEADLINE>
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China's leaders are trying to rein in a growing and
increasingly assertive liberal intellectual movement, criticizing
prominent academics and authors in speeches, forbidding newspapers
from running their articles and punishing or shutting down
publishers who have brought out their work.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, unofficial and quasi-official outlets for
liberal political ideas have multiplied rapidly in China _ on the
Internet, in informal discussion groups, in magazines and books
that result from collaborations between independent editors and
state publishers. At a time of rapid economic and social change,
China's leaders clearly view this trend as a threat to their
political power.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his Western-leaning economics, President Jiang Zemin has
in the last year constantly reiterated the importance of standing
fast by Communist ideology in a China overrun with dot-com
start-ups. In the last few months, those admonitions have led to a
series of punitive actions against writers perceived as straying
too far in a liberal or reformist direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very tense time,'' said a prominent professor, who like
others would speak only if not identified. ``President Jiang is
very unhappy with some things that friends have written. He wants
to undertake some ideological cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   In a country where economic reforms have spawned greater
pluralism in ideas and the means to express them, it is impossible
to mount a concerted old-style Communist Party campaign, academics
here say. But the scattershot attacks have been many and varied,
and do have short-term consequences, at least.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In a speech in Guangdong province, Jiang himself directly
criticized a much-revered retired official of the Chinese Academy
of Social Sciences, Li Shenzhi, for an Internet essay.
</P>
<P>
   The editorial offices of the Reform Publishing House in Beijing
have been shut down for bringing out ``The Secret Scriptures of
Officialdom,'' a book that obliquely describes the back-stabbing
and bribery required to attain public office.
</P>
<P>
   High-level officials have canceled the scheduled publication of
the second volume of the official ``History of the Chinese
Communist Party,'' covering 1949-82, saying the final draft was too
critical of the party's past errors. As a result, in part, Gong
Yuzhi, one of the book's chief editors, has retired as head of the
Central Party School.
</P>
<P>
   Editors at two lively, independent newspapers, Southern Weekend
and Shopping Guide, have been replaced. And editors at a popular
newspaper have been criticized for reporting that several employees
of the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency were disciplined for the
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade a year ago _ a fact not
reported in the state-controlled media.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For example, Liu Juning, a political scientist who has written
about the need for political reform, was fired from his job at the
Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, and editors at the state-owned
Commercial Publishers had to write self-criticisms for publishing
his book.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is evident that Jiang Zemin feels that the intellectual
community has become too brazen,'' said a newspaper commentator,
who also would not be identified. ``Everyone is aware of the spirit
of Jiang Zemin's speeches. And even if they don't agree, they know
if they don't act, they're putting themselves in danger.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese liberals say the timing of the intense criticisms, after
years of stuttering but slowly expanding intellectual freedom, is
probably related to Communist Party politics.
</P>
<P>
   They say China's leaders are nervous about the liberalizing
forces that could be unleashed by China's expected entry into the
World Trade Organization, as early as this year. They add that
Zemin's tenure as president and party leader will probably end in
the next few years and that he is trying to burnish his image to
maintain some role for himself in the future. That means turning
down the volume of critics.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the campaign has had a clear dampening effect: China's
growing stable of liberal intellectuals _ in universities,
government research institutes, the media and publishing _ are
lying low. For instance, more than half a dozen people who last
year would have been happy to be quoted by name, refused to be
identified in this article.
</P>
<P>
   But most remain confident that the current tightening on
intellectual life will pass. And in the China of today, threats
from the central authorities have diminished influence. Bookstores
are still filled with provocative books. And people fired from
government institutes can now often find alternative employment in
the expanding private sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can continue to do my work, but it will be more difficult,''
said Liu, the political scientist who was fired. ``Now, for
example, I think it will be very difficult to publish articles or
books in the major media. And, perhaps, students will not be able
to invite me to lecture at universities.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The government's surprising face-off with Li _ by far the most
talked-about event in the crackdown _ shows both the government's
determination to curb liberal voices, and also how far some
essayists have gone.
</P>
<P>
   A one-time aide to Zhou Enlai, the late prime minister, Li had
been considered nearly untouchable, until he was berated by Jiang
in a speech this year to Communist Party cadres. The criticisms
were deleted from published versions of the lecture, Chinese
journalists said.
</P>
<P>
   Li, who is in his late '70s and will probably suffer no
immediate effects from Jiang's speech, has long issued muted
criticisms of the government, generally concerning the 1988
military suppression of pro-democracy protesters in Tiananmen
Square. But his recent essay was considerably more explicit,
mocking last year's lavish celebration of 50 years of Communist
rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitler is dead, Stalin is dead; there can't be that many
countries left that strive for this vision of grandeur,'' he wrote.
``My own guess is perhaps only Kim Jong Il's Korea would embrace
it.''
</P>
<P>
   His essay was widely circulated in intellectual circles _ on
paper and by e-mail. It was ultimately posted on the Internet,
though not by Li himself, his friends say. That is when it came to
the attention of government officials.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Although liberal academics say senior officials have also
directly criticized a few other longtime reformers, including the
economist Mao Yushi, the tightened policy has generally trickled
down by more circuitous routes.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, Jiang has insisted that all officials
rededicate themselves to Communist ideology through his ``Three
Stresses'' campaign (``Politics, Study, Probity''), and some have
clearly heeded the call.
</P>
<P>
   In early March, the central government's News and Publications
bureau called publishers to a conference just outside Beijing to
deliver Jiang's admonitions, specifically criticizing two
publishing houses.
</P>
<P>
   Although all publishing in China is theoretically owned and
controlled by the state, most publishers these days collaborate
with independent, for-profit book editors, generally by selling
them a government license to print a particular book. This
widespread practice, which started as a way to raise money for
cash-strapped state publishers, has opened up the industry to a
broad spectrum of politically sensitive topics, since the actual
editing is no longer done by government employees.
</P>
<P>
   At the conference, state publishers were told that Jiang wanted
to curb the practice and were instructed to review all books they
had brought out since 1997 to see if they contained attacks on the
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, all of the publishers totally withdrew, without
exception,'' said an independent editor. ``Now they've started
coming back, but very slowly, and the book has to be totally secure
and unprovocative.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The tightening has surprised many Chinese who had hoped that the
government would open publishing and generally relax security, once
the 50th anniversary celebrations were over last fall. And in a
throwback to old-style Communist campaigns, trouble for individuals
has often been heralded by an article in an obscure journal or a
letter to the editor.
</P>
<P>
   Liu's firing from the Academy of Social Sciences grew out of an
indignant letter from a graduate student at Beijing University who
had heard him speak. The letter, printed in Guangming Daily, a
party newspaper aimed at intellectuals, was addressed to the
academy and also to the president.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even as Chinese intellectuals bemoan the current climate,
they feel more inconvenienced than terrified by the government's
wrath.
</P>
<P>
   ``The methods are pretty much the same as in Deng Xiaoping's and
even Mao's time,'' the professor said. ``What's different is that
nobody pays attention anymore. The effect is very limited.
Intellectuals don't feel that much pressure. And ordinary people
don't pay much attention or sympathize with the authors.''
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that the current effort would peter out within a
year because ``no one approves of this kind of criticism anymore.''
And the graduate student who caused the dismissal of Liu would
probably have trouble getting a university job in the future, he
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And even as some authors complained that publishers had put
their books on hold, strong liberal voices were cropping up here
and there _ in some very unlikely places.
</P>
<P>
   The current edition of ``Reading Room,'' a monthly journal
published under the auspices of the Hunan Province News and
Publication Bureau _ the provincial censorship organ _ features two
long, somewhat daring essays. One advocates more aggressive
economic reform. The second explores the often prickly relationship
between writers and politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``In China, winning and consolidating state power was the main
objective of all revolutionary work, and publishing, as a part of
it, was no exception,'' Li Xianzhi wrote in this second essay.
``The longstanding precepts of `class struggle' and `ideological
dictatorship' destroyed people's ideas of rule of law, that is,
their ideas of freedom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
