<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8391 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-PHILS0508-     05-07 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PHILS0508-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Phils knock wind out of Braves
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Braves should thank their record 15-game winning
streak. Without it, the injury-plagued team would be three games
under .500 and certainly no one would be talking about this being
Atlanta's best team ever.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves lost 7-4 Sunday to the Philadelphia Phillies and got
a scare in the process as two more players were forced out of
action.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Terry Mulholland experienced trouble with his
breathing in the fourth inning and was removed after being rocked
for eight hits and five runs. He was taken to Piedmont Hospital as
a precautionary measure but is expected to rejoin the team today in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Quilvio Veras landed hard on his right wrist when
Doug Glanville upended him trying to break up a third-inning double
play. Veras struck out in the bottom of the inning, then was
replaced by Keith Lockhart. X-rays were negative and Veras hopes to
play against the Marlins tonight.
</P>
<P>
   After putting two players on the disabled list Friday and one
more Saturday, at least the Braves got some good injury news for a
change.
</P>
<P>
   The magic of the Braves' streak is definitely missing, however.
After leaving 10 men on base Saturday in a 6-0 loss to Curt
Schilling and the Phillies, Atlanta stranded 11 on Sunday. The
Braves were 2-for-20 with runners in scoring position during the
two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple of days, we just haven been able to get a hit
when we needed it,'' manager Bobby Cox. ``Things even up in this
game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what we did the last couple of weeks wasn't going to
last all season,'' Chipper Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had a chance to make a dramatic rally in the ninth
inning, loading the bases with nobody out. But Atlanta could score
only one run, on a sacrifice fly by Jones to deep left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a good pitch to hit, but just missed it,'' Jones said.
``I was looking for a fastball and I didn't adjust quite enough on
the slider.''
</P>
<P>
   The series loss was the Braves' first at home this season and
only the second in 19 series going back to last year.
</P>
<P>
   But discounting the 15-game winning streak, the Braves are only
6-9. They started the season 5-6 and are 1-3 since winning No. 15
last Tuesday in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies, who have the worst record in the National League,
came close to sweeping the Braves. Atlanta blew a four-run lead in
the ninth inning Friday, but Andruw Jones won the game with a
walk-off homer in the bottom of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Jones hit his eighth homer Sunday off Andy Ashby, but it came
with the bases empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was big to get this series against the best team in the
National League,'' said Phillies catcher Mike Lieberthal, who tied
his career high with four hits, including a homer.
</P>
<P>
   The back-to-back losses were the first for the Braves since they
were swept by the Cubs in a three-game series at Chicago that ended
April 14.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are 14-4 at Turner Field, but just 7-5 on the road
going into their seven-game trip to Florida and Philadelphia, where
they will have to face Schilling again Friday..
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux (4-1) will pitch for the Braves tonight. He is
trying to bounce back from a 6-4 loss at Los Angeles on Wednesday
that snapped the winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these injuries are freaky,'' Chipper Jones. ``But we can't
get down about them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can still put a good team out on the field,'' Cox said.
``I'm not alarmed about our team at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
