<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8396 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-UTAH-REPUBS-NYT &LR;      05-07 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTAH-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BESIEGED GOP CONGRESSMAN IN UTAH FACES RUNOFF IN RE-ELECTION BID 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ After all the chaos of the last two years, Rep.
Merrill Cook of Utah left the Republican state party convention
Saturday still unsure how the turbulent past might affect his quest
this year to win a third term in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   A series of unpleasant incidents, including public temper
tantrums, staff disputes and a trial in which a jury determined he
owed a former campaign consultant almost $200,000, has made him one
of the country's most vulnerable House Republicans, in the view of
Democrats, who need a net gain of six seats to regain the majority
they lost six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And he might still be.
</P>
<P>
   Through two rounds of balloting that eliminated only one of two
challengers, he failed to win the 60 percent of delegate votes he
needed to secure the party nomination without a primary as he had
two years ago. Instead, he faces a June 27 runoff against Derek
Smith, an energetic political novice whose strong showing was
bolstered by support from a surprising source, another Utah
congressman, Rep. Christopher B. Cannon. It is widely known in Utah
that Cannon and Cook are not especially fond of each other. Cannon,
who lent the challenger some of his staff for the campaign,
nominated Smith at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   After a first round in which Cook won 45 percent of the vote to
31 percent for Smith, a business owner, and 23 percent for Jeff
Wright, a venture capitalist, Cook's margin narrowed in the second
round, with 53 percent to 46 percent for Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Cannon and Utah's other representative, James V. Hansen,
advanced straight to the general election. Cannon, who represents
eastern Utah, won 78 percent of the vote in a bid for a third term.
Hansen, who represents the western side, was unopposed in seeking
an 11th term.
</P>
<P>
   Cook pronounced himself satisfied with the outcome, insisting
that advancement to a primary, as opposed to elimination,
vindicated him and showed that delegates from his district, the
greater Salt Lake City area, appreciated his work in Washington, if
not his well-publicized troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was not the unequivocal coronation he sought from
delegates who let no opportunity pass without reminding most
incumbents they should take nothing for granted, especially if they
have shown any moderate tendencies. Even though Sen. Orrin G. Hatch
surpassed the 60 percent to avoid a primary in his race for a fifth
term, he was greeted with a healthy mix of boos and jeers upon
introduction.
</P>
<P>
   So was Gov. Michael O. Leavitt, who is running for a third term
against three challengers and failed to reach 60 percent in any of
three ballots, putting him in a primary for the first time since
1992. He will face another political newcomer, Glen Davis, a
businessman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unconscionable, for all they have given to the party,''
Dan Jones, a Republican pollster and consultant, said of the
booing. ``I'm surprised. But it shows there is a real schism in the
Republican Party. The far right is alive and well. Moderates are
frustrated how to respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Utah is one of the most Republican states in the country. Every
major office but one, state attorney general, is held by a
Republican, and that could change because Jan Graham, a Democrat,
is not seeking re-election.
</P>
<P>
   But in Utah, there are Republicans and there are Republicans.
And when one makes an exception to unfettered gun ownership rights,
for example, as Leavitt did in pushing a measure that would have
prevented people from carrying concealed weapons into a church or
school _ it failed in the Legislature _ he loses support. For that,
many delegates opposed to Leavitt branded him ``a liberal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These conventions are the political version of hazing,''
Leavitt said. ``You have to expect it as a two-term incumbent.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Hatch, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee,
were no less charitable. They passed out literature accusing him of
being soft on gun rights by favoring a three-day waiting period for
background checks at weekend gun shows as part of last year's
juvenile justice legislation even though the National Rifle
Association, which opposes checks that take so long, has endorsed
him.
</P>
<P>
   In Cook's case, the concerns reflected not so much his record as
his controversies, which left him nervous and confused before the
voting. At a candidates' forum on Friday night, he conceded he
could win ``anywhere from 15 percent of the vote to 75 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Calmer after the balloting, he promised he was not disappointed
at all, even with the prospect of a contentious primary and charges
by Smith supporters that he was no longer electable. ``I always
felt this was the toughest part, the convention phase,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he wins the primary, Cook will have his hands full with
his Democratic opponent, Jim Matheson, the son of a popular former
Utah governor, Scott M. Matheson, who was nominated Saturday at the
more serene Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats also nominated Bill Orton, a former congressman,
to run for governor; Scott Howell, the state Senate minority
leader, to oppose Hatch; Kathleen McConkie Collinwood to oppose
Hansen; and Donald Dunn, a former White House staffer, to face
Cannon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
