<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8397 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-SIERRA-LEONE-ART-785(     05-07 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-ART-785(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTING RESUMES NEAR CAPITAL OF SIERRA LEONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone _ Sierra Leone edged back toward war on
Sunday as government and rebel forces fought each other in a town
not far from the capital, Freetown, and the U.N. force that was
supposed to keep peace between them sank deeper into disarray.
</P>
<P>
   Panic spread through Freetown early Sunday after the U.N. force
mistakenly announced that rebels of the Revolutionary United Front
were advancing to the capital by using human shields and were less
than 15 miles from this seaside capital. Even after the United
Nations retracted its announcement in the predawn hours, the
streets of Freetown remained tense through the day.
</P>
<P>
   Rifle-toting former soldiers who had fought against the
government and who should long have been disarmed, under the terms
of a peace accord that was reached nine months ago, roamed the
streets. Hundreds of them assembled at the national stadium after
their leader, Lt. Col. Johnny Paul Koroma, the chief of a junta
that briefly controlled Sierra Leone in 1997, said on national
radio that no one had a monopoly on violence.
</P>
<P>
   A government helicopter gunship attacked the junction town of
Rogberri, about 25 miles east of here, as rebels were said to be
advancing from that direction, said Oluyemi Adeniji, the U.N.
special envoy to Sierra Leone, adding that his mission had learned
of the assault only after it had taken place.
</P>
<P>
   The international force took reporters to the area Sunday to
show that it was not under rebel control, although many refugees
could be seen fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been some violations on both sides,'' Adeniji said
at a news conference. ``So we are now picking up the pieces and
trying to put things back to the status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   The fighting largely eclipsed diplomatic efforts to secure more
than 500 U.N. peacekeepers and civilians who were still being held
hostage by the rebels. Foday Sankoh, the leader of the rebellion,
still denied that his men were holding hostages, although Adeniji
said Sankoh had pledged to help the United Nations locate its
missing personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Britain, the former colonial power in Sierra Leone, announced
Sunday that it was sending warships and 700 to 800 troops to West
Africa to help citizens who might need to flee Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the Clinton administration is still pondering a
request to provide air transport for Bangladeshi soldiers slated to
join the U.N. mission in Sierra Leone and indicated that it expects
the British to take the lead in any international response to the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to help,'' said a senior administration official.
``The directive we have is to be helpful and to respond
positively.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite this small West African country's relative lack of
political significance, the success or failure of the United
Nations here will be closely watched in Africa. Perhaps more than
any other African country, Sierra Leone _ whose nine-year civil war
produced searing images of mutilated men, women and children _ came
to symbolize the West's post-Cold War indifference to Africa and
its conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   So if Sierra Leone was regarded as a recommitment of the
international community to peacekeeping in Africa, the mission so
far has proved to be an embarrassment for the Western governments,
including the Clinton administration, which supported it.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the falling credibility of the international
peacekeeping effort, Adeniji said that ``people tend to exaggerate
mistakes and to minimize credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Miyet, the chief of peacekeeping for the United Nations,
left Sunday for Freetown to help broker the release of the hostages
and bolster the morale of the other peacekeepers, the U.N.
spokesman, Fred Eckhard, said in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations' latest humiliating setback took place with
the false announcement of an imminent invasion by the rebels, who
had frequently accused the peacekeeping mission of creating panic
by spreading false information.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. personnel and vehicles moved across town in the middle of
the night to western Freetown, as Philip Winslow, the spokesman for
the U.N. operations here, spoke live on CNN about the impending
invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Adeniji, who is the United Nations' special envoy to Sierra
Leone, said that the mistake happened after ``taking reports
without proper verification.''
</P>
<P>
   The mistake, however, seemed to increase the population's
skepticism about the peacekeeping mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they could not give us adequate information about what is
going on in the country, about security positions, then it is clear
to us that they are not competent to protect us,'' said Sahr
Kellie, 26, a university student who had come to the stadium. ``I
don't trust them anymore.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The departure of many foreigners also appeared to deepen many
Sierra Leoneans' anger at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department ordered the departure Sunday of
nonemergency staff from the U.S. embassy here, and evacuated
Americans aboard helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Many nonessential U.N. personnel and workers for nongovernmental
organizations were evacuated over the weekend, and the departure of
many foreigners appeared to deepen many Sierra Leoneans' anger at
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   James Roy, 42, said he had come to the stadium to show support
for the former soldiers, because he had lost faith in the United
Nations and feared that its mission here might fail, as other
missions by the international organization had failed elsewhere in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a Sierra Leonean who has been suffering for nine years,''
he said. ``And your United Nations is not coming to do anything.
How could 300 men with all their ammunition, and all their
reputation, allow themselves to be disarmed like that?
</P>
<P>
   ``The same thing happened in Angola. The same thing happened in
Somalia. I don't want a repeat of that here.''
</P>
<P>
   The former soldiers at the stadium, one-time allies of the
Revolutionary United Front, fought against the government of
President Ahmad Tejan Kabbah. In a brutal assault on Freetown in
January 1999, the rebels and soldiers killed thousands of civilians
and chopped off the hands, arms and legs of hundreds. A
Nigerian-led West African peacekeeping force prevented the fall of
Freetown at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from abroad, Kabbah signed a peace treaty with
the rebels last July. The treaty lifted a death penalty that had
been imposed on Sankoh and made the rebel leader a member of a
power-sharing government. Under the accord, the 45,000 estimated
combatants were supposed to have finished voluntarily disarming
last year. But the combatants, especially those belonging to
Sankoh's group, delayed doing so.
</P>
<P>
   According to official figures, half of the total are said to
have disarmed. But the real figure is probably lower. It is
impossible to know precisely how many fighters answer Sankoh's
orders, but it could be more than 10,000. The United Nations, whose
force was expected to reach a full strength of 11,000 by July, now
has 8,700 troops in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh blames the United Nations for the current crisis, saying
that its peacekeepers tried to force some of his men to disarm. But
officials with the peacekeeping force and U.S. officials say the
clashes appeared to have been well coordinated by Sankoh's group.
</P>
<P>
   The hostage-taking and killing of Kenyan peacekeepers occurred
at three different locations last week just as the Nigerian-led
West African force pulled out of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   It became increasingly clear that Sankoh, a man who would be
considered a war criminal in most countries, was not interested in
peace.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, as his men delayed giving up their arms and
frantically mined diamonds in the Kono district, which they kept
off-limits to the United Nations, it was thought that Sankoh had
amassed a war chest for a future election or war.
</P>
<P>
   Liberia's president, Charles Taylor, a former guerrilla and
longtime supporter of Sankoh, became president of his country by
refusing to disarm and thus frightening Liberians into voting for
him. Many believe that Sankoh is following that example.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. force made slow progress as it saw its movements and
deployment blocked often by the rebels. Peacekeepers were disarmed
and robbed of their equipment by rebels in several instances.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last week, the rebels seemed to gain control over the
peacekeepers with surprising ease. Clearly embarrassed by the
situation, U.N. officials have been extremely reluctant to provide
full details of the incidents. At first they said they could not
explain the whereabouts of certain troops, simply saying that they
were no longer in contact with U.N. headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   It is still unclear how many hostages there are and how many
peacekeepers have been killed. Until Sunday evening, U.N. officials
had been saying that 300 were being held hostage and that they had
lost contact with 200 Zambians.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Sunday night, Adeniji, the special envoy,
was asked whether the 200 were now considered hostages. ``As long
as they've not been found, they've not returned, that's our
assumption,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-00 2106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
