<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8399 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-PATIENTS-RIGHTS-725&AMP;A     05-07 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATIENTS-RIGHTS-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SETS MEETING ON PATIENTS' RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ White House officials and Democrats in Congress say
they have become concerned that negotiations on a bill to define
patients' rights have stalled.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has summoned 10 members of Congress to the
White House in an effort to galvanize talks on the issue, one of
his party's top legislative priorities this year.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats do not accuse the Republicans of bad faith, but say
the negotiations have become enmeshed in a slow, frustrating
process that seems to be leading nowhere. Each party says the other
is responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Senate and the House passed very different
versions of the legislation, which would for the first time
establish comprehensive federal standards for private health
insurance, especially health maintenance organizations and other
forms of managed care. For decades, insurance has been regulated
mainly by the states.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations are widely viewed here as a major test of the
leadership abilities of Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., chairman of the
House-Senate conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   As assistant majority leader of the Senate, Nickles has
repeatedly shown his ability to round up Republican votes. But
never before has he faced such a public test of his ability to
forge compromises with Democrats on complex issues with immense
political overtones.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointed at the pace of negotiations, Clinton invited
leading conferees from both parties to the meeting, tentatively set
for Thursday. Chris Jennings, the president's health policy
coordinator, said, ``We are very troubled by the delays.'' He said
Clinton would urge the conferees to ``roll up their sleeves and get
down to work.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Nickles said: ``I don't think the talks have
stalled or bogged down, but they've moved back a little bit. We
keep trying to move forward, but there's been two steps back by the
Democrats. We closed some issues that the Democrats now say are
still open. I hope to accelerate the pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Those expected to attend the meeting include Nickles, Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., and Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   John Podesta, the White House chief of staff, and Donna Shalala,
the secretary of health, met last Wednesday with consumer
advocates, doctors, nurses and others who support the
administration's position. After the meeting, the consumer
advocates and health-care professionals complained that Republicans
were delaying the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Nickles said he did not appreciate the administration's efforts
to pressure the conferees by mobilizing its allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been successful in keeping politics out of this for the
last three or four months,'' Nickles said. ``But the Podesta
meeting suggests that the administration is trying to politicize
the process. That's not helpful. This process would be very easy to
blow up.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 14, just before the spring recess, House and Senate
negotiators said they had reached a tentative agreement on an
appeals procedure that would allow patients to obtain an
independent medical review of decisions by an HMO to deny care or
coverage. But lawmakers have been unable to translate that
conceptual agreement into legislative language.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Kennedy said, the negotiators have not even begun to
discuss the two biggest issues: Should patients have a new federal
right to sue HMOs for injuries caused by substandard care? Should
the protections of federal law apply to all Americans with private
health insurance _ more than 160 million people _ or just to those
in certain types of health plans that are now exempt from state
regulation?
</P>
<P>
   Clinton strongly prefers the House bill because it would cover
more people and make it easier to sue.
</P>
<P>
   Republican and Democratic congressional aides have been meeting
several times a week to discuss compromises on other issues, like
access to emergency care and to medical specialists. But Democrats
said the negotiations had been hampered because they were not
allowed to keep copies of the legislative language proposed by the
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Distrust between the parties appears to be growing. Democrats
said the Republicans were making a political calculation, trying to
decide whether public concern about HMOs was deep enough to require
congressional action this year. For their part, Republicans resent
the pressure from the White House.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Joanne L. Hustead, director of public policy at the National
Partnership for Women and Families, an advocacy group supporting
the House bill, said Republicans were ``dragging their feet.'' And
she added, ``I believe that the Senate leadership is not committed
to getting a bill enacted into law.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about this view, Nickles said: ``That person doesn't know
what they're talking about. We've been pushing very hard to get a
bill that gives patients protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has often demanded that Congress pass ``a patients' bill
of rights,'' but lawmakers say he may inadvertently have shifted
public attention from that issue by giving more emphasis to another
goal: expanding Medicare to cover prescription drugs for the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   John B. Crosby, executive director of the American Osteopathic
Association, said doctors strongly supported the legislation to
define patients' rights and make HMOs more accountable. But Crosby
said, ``Medicare drug benefits have taken away a lot of attention
from the patients' bill of rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Nickles has opposed any expansion of patients' right to sue,
saying the prospect of such lawsuits would lead to an increase in
premiums and could cause employers to drop coverage for their
workers.
</P>
<P>
   But his home state, Oklahoma, has just adopted a law making it
easier for patients to sue HMOs and other insurers for the
unreasonable denial of medical care. Under the law, a health plan
can be required to pay damages if it fails to exercise ``ordinary
care'' in treating patients.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, the chief sponsor of the Oklahoma bill, state
Sen. Brad Henry, a Democrat, said: ``Senator Nickles is definitely
out of step with the public here in Oklahoma. Polling information
shows that 72 percent of Oklahomans support giving a patient the
right to sue.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oklahoma measure, approved 94-5 in the state House of
Representatives and 44-2 in the state Senate, was signed by Gov.
Frank Keating on April 28.
</P>
<P>
   Karen M. Ignagni, president of the American Association of
Health Plans, which represents HMOs, said: ``Just prior to the
congressional recess, members of the conference committee seemed to
be making significant progress. But things are slowing down. I'm
baffled how things could have changed so much in three short
weeks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
