<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL MEMO: NUMBERS SUGGEST A BREAK IN THE PATTERN 
</HEADLINE>
  By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The latest numbers offered a stunning
contradiction: a 3.9 percent unemployment rate, the lowest in 30
years, and two major national polls showing Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas leading Vice President Al Gore by 5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   To put that contrast in perspective, the last time a president's
party lost the White House in good times was 1920. And even then,
the country was recovering from the double-digit inflation of World
War I.
</P>
<P>
   So why isn't the booming economy blowing Bush away? Have the
rules changed?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   First, the economy has stayed strong so long that most people
are not worrying about it. Peter D. Hart, a Democratic pollster,
said, ``It doesn't sit there as a major worry that people talk
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Teeter, a Republican pollster who collaborates with Hart
on the NBC News/Wall Street Journal poll, said one reason for Bush
support among older people was that ``only about 6 percent of the
old people have economic worries.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, Gore does not get credit for the way things are. Polls
show the public gives it to President Clinton and Alan Greenspan,
chairman of the Federal Reserve Board.
</P>
<P>
   That may be reasonable enough, but Gore's own weakness as a
candidate compounds that problem. After all, Gore is campaigning on
a promise to keep the same economic policies Clinton has followed,
while Bush's central campaign message is that he wants a very big
tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   But the NBC/Journal poll showed that only 27 percent of voters
thought Gore was very likely or fairly likely to pursue policies
that would keep the economy strong, compared to 32 percent who said
that of Bush. (Both of them enjoyed less credence than they did in
December, when 36 percent had confidence in Gore and 43 percent in
Bush.)
</P>
<P>
   The NBC/Journal poll had Bush ahead, 46 percent to 41 percent. A
Gallup Poll for CNN and USA Today had the Bush lead at 49 to 44.
Both polls were taken the last weekend of April, and the margin of
sampling error for NBC/Journal survey was plus or minus 3
percentage points, one less than for the Gallup Poll.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has simply not capitalized on winning his party's
nomination more easily than Bush won his or achieving quickly the
party unity and support from Bill Bradley that Bush is still
seeking from Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Teeter said the data in the NBC/Journal poll explained it.
``Gore is not a very good candidate,'' he said. ``He is not a very
likable candidate.'' Teeter argued that Gore's frequent attacks on
Bush ran the risk ``of looking like the guy who is out of his
time,'' out of step with an optimistic country.
</P>
<P>
   Though Teeter agreed that a strong economy was a major factor in
retaining a president or his party, he said the most ``likable''
candidate had won most postwar elections. The clearest exception
was 1968, when a losing war, civic turmoil and rising inflation
helped Richard M. Nixon edge out Hubert H. Humphrey. In 1976,
Teeter said, both Jimmy Carter and President Gerald Ford seemed
likable.
</P>
<P>
   Still, these are early days. When the nomination contests ended
in March, public interest in the campaign plummeted, and surveys by
the Vanishing Voter project of the Joan Shorenstein Center on the
Press, Politics and Public Policy at Harvard University show that
knowledge about the candidates has also declined.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that the Gore message in the summer and
fall will emphasize continuity and accuse Bush of risking
prosperity for a needless tax cut. Comparisons with the last
Republican administration are inevitable, but will have special
bite because the phrase ``Bush recession'' will surely be used.
</P>
<P>
   Hart, while conceding Gore's weak standing, cited a focus group
he conducted last Tuesday in a Philadelphia suburb as offering hope
for Gore. Everyone in the group of 12, whether he or she favored
Bush or Gore, ``wanted the same policies,'' he said. ``They didn't
want to tinker with the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is sitting on a gusher,'' Hart said, if he can find a
way to identify himself with the voters' desire for continuity.
</P>
<P>
   The best evidence that it is not too late for Gore comes from a
New York Times/CBS News Poll taken in May 1988. That was the last
time a vice president ran to succeed a popular president in an
economic boom. Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts led Vice
President George Bush, 49 percent to 39 percent. It didn't last.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
