<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRYSDALE SAYS PREAKNESS   ONLY `POSSIBLE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. - Immediately after Saturday's Kentucky Derby,
in which Fusaichi Pegasus waltzed to the first victory by a betting
favorite in 21 years, it was hard to imagine anything keeping the
brilliantly athletic colt from the first Triple Crown sweep in 22
years.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday morning a spoiler emerged. It's Neil Drysdale,
Fusaichi Pegasus' trainer, who suggested the Japanese-owned horse
is only a ``possible'' entrant in the May 20 Preakness Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this was just Drysdale playing semantic games with the
press as he did throughout Derby week. Or maybe it must be taken
seriously - the English-born Hall of Famer is legendary for
refusing to race any horse who's less than 100 percent healthy and
in form.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to just see how he is the next few days,'' Drysdale
said at the Churchill Downs barn where Fusaichi Pegasus awoke,
alert and apparently healthy, as the most respected Derby winner in
at least a decade. ``He's fine at this very minute in time, but all
he's done is go for a walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always look good the first couple of days (after a race).
It's the third or fourth days you've got to be careful of, when you
start training them again. It was hot (Saturday), and we'll have to
see what that took out of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale said his tentative plans call for Fusaichi Pegasus to
remain at Churchill Downs before flying to Baltimore the Wednesday
before the Preakness. The trainer intends to go first to inspect
the track surface.
</P>
<P>
   The trainers of most of the 18 horses Fusaichi Pegasus and
jockey Kent Desormeaux defeated in the 1-mile Derby were proceeding
on the assumption he will go on to the 1 3/16-mile Preakness. It
appeared as few as three would challenge him at Pimlico Race
Course.
</P>
<P>
   The three are Captain Steve (eighth), High Yield (15th) and
Hal's Hope (16th). Throw in non-Derby horses Red Bullet (second to
Fusaichi Pegasus in the Wood Memorial) and Snuck In (second in the
Arkansas Derby), and you have a Preakness field of six. That would
be the smallest since 1979, the year Spectacular Bid, the last
winning Derby favorite, beat four in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Some other Derby horses' trainers said they would consider the
Preakness. Ruled out were Aptitude (second in the Derby, waiting
for the June 10 Belmont Stakes, the third leg of the Triple Crown),
The Deputy (14th, heading back to California for a rest) and Anees
(13th).
</P>
<P>
   ``Neil did a great job with this horse,'' said John Kimmel,
trainer of fifth-place Wheelaway, who's likely to wait for the
Belmont. ``He really didn't train him that hard. It just shows how
much talent (Fusaichi Pegasus) has. (Now) he comes out of it as a
pretty fresh horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenine Sahadi, trainer of The Deputy, rated Fusaichi Pegasus a
stronger Triple Crown candidate than Silver Charm, Real Quiet and
Charismatic, the past three Kentucky Derby winners, each of whom
came within a Belmont victory of being the first to sweep the
classics since Affirmed in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's raw talent and he just keeps getting better,''
Sahadi said of the one-time $4 million yearling.
</P>
<P>
   Rallying from 15th to win by 1 lengths with seeming ease, the
Japanese-owned, Hollywood Park-based son of Mr. Prospector recorded
his fifth consecutive victory, rewarded his backers in the crowd of
153,204 with a 2-1 payoff, and changed almost everybody else's
minds.
</P>
<P>
   He was cooler and better behaved than expected, bucking once
during the walk from the barns; Drysdale said Fusaichi Pegasus was
bothered by flies and then by his fly net. He proved more nimble
than a big horse should be as he picked his way through traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like Shaquille O'Neal, able to make the spin move,
despite being 1,200 pounds,'' Desormeaux said.
</P>
<P>
   He impressed even High Yield trainer D. Wayne Lukas, the
four-time Derby winner who had sounded skeptical, comparing
Fusaichi Pegasus to 1992 Derby flop Arazi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not watering down the performance. It was brilliant, it
was best on the day, it was everything everybody hyped it to be,''
Lukas said Sunday. ``I'm just saying you can't run up the white
flag. He's going to be tested. ... We've got to just keep going
over there (and challenging him).''
</P>
<P>
   But will he be there when they do?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
