<DOCNO> NYT20000507.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8407 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SHALIKASHVILI-PROFILE     05-07 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHALIKASHVILI-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MILITARY MAN'S SOFT-SELL APPROACH ON ARMS CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wash., Ill.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT21 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For Gen. John M. Shalikashvili, a man with an
intimate knowledge of war, there is a clear logic to his new
assignment to persuade the Senate to reconsider a treaty ending
underground nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
   As a Polish child fleeing the Red Army in Warsaw in 1944, a
teen-age refugee in Berlin, a young Army major in Vietnam, the
supreme commander of NATO forces in the early years of the Bosnian
war and then chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, the retired
Army general has seen war from nearly every possible vantage point.
</P>
<P>
   ``War has never been something theoretical for me or my
family,'' said Shalikashvili, who commutes here from his retirement
home on Puget Sound to act as the president's special adviser on
the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, which the Senate rejected last
year.
</P>
<P>
   He even survived the stomach-dropping experience of discovering
that his family's war experience was darker than he had realized.
In 1993, while he awaited Senate confirmation for the top military
job, historical documents were uncovered showing that his deceased
father, Dmitri Shalikashvili, had served in a German army unit
commanded by the Waffen SS.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, he was a kind and gentle man, and I loved him very
much,'' the general told the Senate panel on the day of his
confirmation hearing. ``I'm deeply saddened that my father had this
tragic association.''
</P>
<P>
   A military man to the core, the general does not speak easily of
things personal. When he retired as chairman in 1997, he and his
wife moved to Steilacoom, Wash., south of Seattle, to a home with a
clear view of the Olympic Mountains, and most important, close to
their grown son, Brant, their only child.
</P>
<P>
   In his spartan office on the fifth floor of the State
Department, he talks, instead, of the American soldiers he wants
protected not only by state-of-the-art weapons and fighter jets,
but by arms control as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a combination of making sure we have the means of
protecting ourselves with weapons and by diminishing the number of
weapons out there that our soldiers have to confront,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how his childhood, his Central European roots as well
as his move to Peoria, Ill., at age 16, affect his support for arms
control, he ducks the question with the gentle command: ``Don't
make me sound schmaltzy.''
</P>
<P>
   What matters, he said, are his years as an officer and commander
who actually had to prepare defenses against weapons of mass
destruction and how he became convinced ``that we will be much
better off with the test ban treaty than without it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the chairman through most of the negotiations,'' he
explained. ``I undertook a separate, independent investigation,
including careful discussions with laboratory directors. And I
recommended to the president in 1996 that he should sign the
treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, the general noted, the military has supported the
treaty banning underground nuclear testing.
</P>
<P>
   That seal of approval, though, was not enough to sway the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, by a vote of 51-48, the Senate rejected the treaty
that had taken decades to negotiate with over 100 nations and was
viewed as the single most important measure for halting the
proliferation of nuclear weapons. If renegade countries like North
Korea and Iran continued testing, the senators reasoned, then the
United States also had to be able to test its weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The United States was denounced from Berlin to Singapore for its
``arrogant'' defeat of that treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Now several conservative senators are going one better and
trying to pull out of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying not to get entangled in that debate,'' the general
said, ``but you can't talk in a vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   So in the middle of the most heated arms control debate in
recent memory, one tied to whether the United States will build a
national missile defense system, the general is taking a soft-sell
approach.
</P>
<P>
   He meets with senators in private, away from the limelight, to
fulfill his mandate to persuade the Senate to approve the treaty
sometime in the next administration, not in President Clinton's
final months.
</P>
<P>
   ``This way people don't feel the same pressures of time or
politics,'' he said. ``I tell them this is too important a treaty
to be left languishing on the shelf.''
</P>
<P>
   Barely a month into his job, the general has talked to a dozen
senators. While he will not discuss these private conversations, he
said he had figured out the nature of the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are senators who don't feel comfortable with any arms
control treaties and there are others who don't like this
particular treaty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Facing this new battlefield seems oddly familiar to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't feel much different from when I was chairman of the
Joint Chiefs,'' he said. ``I had to go to the Senate for the
budget, and for Rwanda, Bosnia, Haiti, Iraq and the Chemical
Weapons Treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   The subject matter _ the hard-nosed details of verification of
nuclear stockpiles as well as the nuanced diplomatic consequences
of trying to renegotiate the treaty _ is exactly what he had to
juggle as NATO supreme commander, the first time he felt like a
soldier-statesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly with my background, knowing war in Europe, knowing
the totality of Europe, I could easily understand Europeans and
convince them why America wants certain things,'' said the general,
relaxing his rule on personal reflection for a moment. ``And I felt
European and American, the commonality of my experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those European diplomats who became friends are now
calling him to register their complaints about the Senate and its
aversion to arms control treaties.
</P>
<P>
   He tells them what he tells the senators. ``As a military man I
can't accept the notion that arms control agreements don't have a
place in our national security anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
