<HEADLINE>
STEVENS'S HARD-HITTING PLAY PUTS DEVILS IN COMMAND 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Devils have a grand opportunity to
advance to the third round of the Stanley Cup playoffs for the
first time since capturing the trophy in 1995. They are a victory
from reaching the conference finals for two reasons: they have
raised their intensity level and their best players have been more
effective than the opposition's.
</P>
<P>
   It happened against the Florida Panthers in the opening round,
and it is happening again against the Toronto Maple Leafs in the
second round.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils defeated the Leafs, 4-3, Saturday night in Toronto,
giving them a 3-2 lead in their four-of-seven-game Eastern
Conference semifinal series. Game 5 was probably the best in the
series for Toronto, but the Devils still prevailed primarily
because of an inspiring performance by Scott Stevens and a number
of brilliant plays by Patrik Elias, Scott Gomez and John Madden.
</P>
<P>
   With goalie Martin Brodeur doing his part and the team making
few mistakes in their zone, the Devils showed their resilience by
coming back from two one-goal deficits.
</P>
<P>
   After a strategy meeting here Sunday, Stevens said the Devils
were aware of what they had to do to wrap up the series Monday
night in front of their home crowd at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to play hard and not give them any life,'' Stevens
said. ``We've got speed like they do, but we've got to put it to
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to his head coach, Larry Robinson, Stevens added,
``Larry is getting us to do the right things.,''
</P>
<P>
   Said Ken Daneyko, who has teamed up with Stevens to help kill
all 28 Toronto manpower advantages: ``You can use all the cliches
and check out the past. The bottom line is we stay focused on what
we have to do, which is play with discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   And along with playing a huge part in neutralizing Toronto's top
line of Mats Sundin, Jonas Hoglund and Steve Thomas, Stevens
delivered two crunching hits on Tomas Kaberle and Kevyn Adams that
were reminiscent of the thunderous hit he delivered on Detroit's
Slava Kozlov in the 1995 Stanley Cup finals, which the Devils
swept.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be physical,'' Stevens said. ``I always try to be
physical. I got the hits and we got some goals. It was nice to
catch two people in the middle of the ice. I think others will be
thinking about it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stevens was not the central figure in the melee that broke
out at the conclusion of the game. The trouble started with
Toronto's Darcy Tucker tangling with Brodeur and Steve Thomas with
Scott Niedermayer.
</P>
<P>
   Fans pelted the Devils with soft drinks and other debris as
players barked at each other in front of their benches before being
escorted to the dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens did not think there would be any carryover in Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's closed,'' he said. ``It's too important to stay
disciplined.''
</P>
<P>
   Niedermayer and Brodeur were the only players who were assessed
penalties from the fight. Niedermayer drew 40 minutes for roughing
and cross-checking and Brodeur got 20 for roughing.
</P>
<P>
   John Madden, whose only goal in the playoffs turned out to be
the winner on Saturday, said, ``It's not going to help your team if
you carry over.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Holik, who has been dominant winning face-offs, was
another player who did think there would be lingering trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is we know what we can do to be successful, and
fighting is not one of them,'' Holik said. ``What we've got to do
is bring into the game the attitude like last night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
