<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S SPORTS FOUNDATION LOOKS BEYOND OPENING DOORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LENA WILLIAMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Female athletes, coaches, administrators,
educators and entrepreneurs gathered here this weekend to celebrate
their accomplishments and to prepare for the challenges ahead.
</P>
<P>
   In assessing the state of women in sports, those attending the
14th annual conference of the Women's Sports Foundation agreed that
there were more opportunities for women since Title IX of the 1972
Educational Amendments banned sex discrimination in
federally-funded school programs. Now, in a stance that reflects
the influence of the foundation and its constituency, the group
wants to focus less on getting in and more on moving up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially the primary function was opening doors of
opportunity,'' said Donna Lopiano, the executive director of the
foundation. ``Now, it's exploiting the participation of women in
sports in an economic sense, gaining access to assets, program
expansion and addressing the continuing problem of girls being
discouraged from sports.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was echoed in the theme of the conference: Brave
New World of Women's Sports. For the 350 who registered for the
three-day event at the Long Island Marriott, it was a chance to
exchange information and ideas, network and develop strategy to
fulfill the potential that women have in athletics.
</P>
<P>
   It provided a setting for the kind of informal debate many women
had not engaged in since their college days, on topics as disparate
as the feasibility of a 24-hour women's sports channel and the
notion that news media images have increasingly portrayed female
athletes as sex objects.
</P>
<P>
   During a panel discussion on women of color in sport, Krista
Ford, the only African-American woman on the United States
bobsledding team, talked about the trials and tribulations that
come with being ``a first and only.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no diversity in winter sports,'' said Ford, who also
competes in bodybuilding. ``In bobsledding, there are no women on
member boards. It's all good old boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford said she had grown weary from the constant battles, but
vowed to continue the fight ``so other kids won't have to go
through the hell we've had to endure as pioneers.''
</P>
<P>
   Established in 1974 by Billie Jean King, the foundation has
emerged as a leader and advocate for women's sports. From May 1974
to May 1999, the foundation awarded more than $5 million in grants
and scholarships to girls' sports programs, elite athletes in
training and other leaders in women's sports. It annually responds
to more than 100,000 requests for information on issues ranging
from pregnancy and exercise to coed sports, and assists more than
700 students, parents and coaches a year on gender equity issues.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure its place in the future, the foundation has begun to
change the way it reaches its audience. Last year it created a Web
site &QL; 
www.womenssportsfoundation.org.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women's sports has been somewhat prevented from educating the
next generation,'' Lopiano said, noting that because men are still
largely in decision-making roles in athletics, women do not have
equal access to young athletes. ``We had to find a way to leap over
the more traditional communication systems of getting to kids
through teachers in the schools and go directly to the teens by
using teen media vehicles: television and the Web. The Web is the
most cost effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Another measure of the foundation's clout was found in the mix
of corporate sponsorships for this year's convention. Although
there were female-oriented sponsors like Tampax and Sports
Illustrated for Women, big donors also came from the finance,
apparel and telecommunications industries. Among them: Merrill
Lynch, Mervyn's of California and America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Karin Lofstrom traveled here from Ottawa, where she runs an
on-line company for women's sports products.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have an organization like the Women's Sports
Foundation in Canada,'' she said. ``It's so exciting to be here
with these women, who are helping to change the role women play in
sports not only in America but throughout the world.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
