<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROYAL KPN REOPENS TALKS ON MOBILE PHONE VENTURE
</P>
<P>
   Royal KPN returned to the bargaining table with another
potential partner, NTT DoCoMo of Japan, just days after KPN called
off merger talks with Telefonica of Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Royal KPN, the largest telephone operator in the Netherlands,
and DoCoMo, the mobile operations of Nippon Telephone &AMP; Telegraph,
have been negotiating in fits and starts for over a month now. They
are hoping to reach an agreement that could include an alliance
between the two companies' mobile telephone operations.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAELI CABINET PASSES TAX MEASURE
</P>
<P>
   Israel's Cabinet voted to overhaul the country's tax system for
the first time in a quarter-century, backing a finance ministry
proposal for lower income-tax rates balanced by new levies on
inheritances, foreign earnings and capital gains.
</P>
<P>
   HYUNDAI ANNOUNCES `WORLD CAR' DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai Motor said it had agreed to take part in an alliance
with Mitsubishi Motors and DaimlerChrysler to build a 1-liter
``world car'' with commercial production set for 2002. But
DaimlerChrysler denied that it had agreed to take part in the
venture.
</P>
<P>
   TIME WARNER'S PUBLIC RELATIONS GAFFE
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's decision to block the ABC television network in
3.5 million homes last Monday will surely be a prominent chapter in
public relations history. In just 39 hours _ the time it took for
it to restore the ABC signal _ Time Warner managed to anger many of
its customers, rile local and national politicians, draw the ire of
the Federal Communications Commission, and upset what had looked
like smooth sailing on the way to approval of its merger with
America Online.
</P>
<P>
   CISCO REMAINS ON TOP, FOR NOW
</P>
<P>
   Cisco is the undisputed leader in Internet communications
equipment and the No. 1 company in market value. But in the new
economy, few titans remain astride their industry for long, and
several newer communications-equipment companies have Cisco in
their sights.
</P>
<P>
   `MILLIONAIRE' ENTERS `E.R.' ZONE
</P>
<P>
   With a week of celebrity contestants, ABC had already found a
new way to use ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' to hammer its
competitors in a sweep month. But last Thursday the network managed
to pile on some additional torment for NBC: ABC quietly let the
Thursday edition of ``Millionaire'' run eight minutes long, just
enough to blunt the start of NBC's strongest series, ``E.R.'' ABC
beat ``E.R.'' in its first half-hour, something no regularly
scheduled ABC show had done in the seven-year run of the hit
medical drama.
</P>
<P>
   A TOP INSPIRED BY BUCKMINSTER FULLER
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Przybilla's childhood jungle gym inspired a lifelong
fascination with Buckminster Fuller, the architect and futuristic
thinker who invented the geodesic dome, and that led to Przybilla's
newly patented invention, which he describes as an omnidirectional
top. He says that his tops can help children develop an intuitive
understanding of physics or chemistry in much the same way that an
understanding of geometry can grow out of playing with square,
triangular and rectangular blocks.
</P>
<P>
   UNILEVER'S $40 SHAMPOO CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   Unilever _ a company known for its household and personal-care
products _ is planning a multimillion-dollar advertising
extravaganza for a shampoo line. The British-Dutch conglomerate is
staking millions in production costs and over $40 million in media
buys to promote the 2-year-old ThermaSilk shampoo, conditioner and
hair-care line. The campaign goes on the air on network television
Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
