<HEADER>
A8416 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LUKAS-NONFICTION-NYT &LR;      05-07 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUKAS-NONFICTION-NYT </SLUG>
  
 When Truth Challenges Fiction and Becomes Art  
 By SARAH BOXER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ It has a clunky name: ``nonfiction
narrative'' or ``narrative nonfiction.'' It is factual writing that
reads like a good novel. It happens in books, in magazines and
occasionally in newspapers, or at least it used to. ``Dispatches,''
``A Bright and Shining Lie,'' ``The Soul of a New Machine,'' ``In
Cold Blood,'' ``Into Thin Air'' and ``The Professor and the
Madman'' are examples.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday there was a daylong conference here devoted to the
state of narrative nonfiction. First, the Columbia University
Graduate School of Journalism and the Neiman Foundation for
Journalism at Harvard University gave out three awards in the
genre: two in memory of J. Anthony Lukas, the author of ``Common
Ground,'' who died in 1997, and one in memory of Mark Lynton, a
senior executive at Hunter Douglas in the Netherlands, who died the
same year and whose family has financed the prizes.
</P>
<P>
   The J. Anthony Lukas Book Prize ($10,000) went to Witold
Rybczynski, an architect and professor of urbanism at the
University of Pennsylvania, for his book ``A Clearing in the
Distance: Frederick Law Olmsted and America in the 19th Century.''
The Mark Lynton History Prize ($10,000) went to John W. Dower, a
professor of Japanese history at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, for his book ``Embracing Defeat: Japan in the Wake of
World War II.'' The J. Anthony Lukas Work-in-Progress Award
($45,000), for authors who have run out of money before finishing
their books, went to James Tobin, who is working on a biography of
the Wright brothers.
</P>
<P>
   The morning panel, moderated by Alan Brinkley, a professor of
history at Columbia University, was given over to the prizewinners
talking about the future of their art. The three men were pretty
sanguine. The one thing that seemed to weigh on their minds was the
boundary between fiction and nonfiction. Should it be there? Is it
arbitrary?
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said great fiction is generally a notch above great
nonfiction. But occasionally a nonfiction book like ``Common
Ground'' or ``Rising Tide'' rises to the level of fiction. The best
nonfiction books are not just about school busing in Boston or a
flood in the Mississippi Delta, Tobin said. They are about ``what
it means to be human in these circumstances,'' just like good
fiction. But despite the similarities, Tobin said, the fence
between fiction and nonfiction should remain. When he learned that
the end of Truman Capote's ``In Cold Blood'' was made up, he said,
``I felt let down.'' Why? ``There is something about knowing that
these events took place.''
</P>
<P>
   Rybczynski is no champion of the boundary. He agreed that people
can feel deceived by nonfiction. But, he said, they can also feel
deceived by fiction in which real people masquerade as characters.
He thinks the term nonfiction, which he guessed dates to the 19th
century, may be itself fictitious. The idea that nonfiction is
different because it is true, he said, is absurd: If nonfiction
were true, there would be one biography for one life, and it would
be updated as new facts came to light.
</P>
<P>
   There is no one truth, Dower said, any more than there is a
single Japan. A writer of history relies on sources who may or may
not remember things accurately. And in the end, he said, the way
that people actually remember an event, whether they are right or
not, can be as important as the facts themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The panel of journalists in the afternoon, moderated by Robert
Vare, who teaches at the Neiman Foundation at Harvard, was
considerably less sanguine. The participants suggested that while
this may be the golden age of narrative nonfiction for books, it is
not the case with magazines and newspapers. The general-interest
magazines that once published long nonfiction articles are now
looking more like newsweeklies, and the newsweeklies are looking
more like newspapers. Everyone wants stories faster, cheaper,
shorter and timelier.
</P>
<P>
   Alma Guillermoprieto, who writes for The New Yorker and is the
author of ``The Heart That Bleeds'' and ``Samba,'' said she
despaired of poorer countries like Mexico and Brazil ever having
the money to support journalists who want to write articles that
require weeks or months of research. Out of some 18 million people
in Mexico City, she said, there are fewer than 200,000 newspaper
readers. The United States is lucky. It has readers who have money
to buy papers and editors who have money to spend on reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Hart, the editor of The Oregonian, which just won a
Pulitzer Prize for a report about the journey of 20 pounds of
potatoes from the farm to a box of McDonald's french fries in
Singapore, talked about American newsrooms, past and present. He
talked about Damon Runyon, Ernie Pyle, Ernest Hemingway, Walt
Whitman and Mark Twain: reporters who were writers. The
19th-century newspaper was full of voices and stories. So why do
editors give you a blank look if you talk about denouement? Why do
they demand that everything be told in the first paragraph?
</P>
<P>
   The other journalists offered him some answers. Michael Kelly,
the editor of The Atlantic Monthly and the author of ``Martyr's
Day,'' a book on Saddam Hussein, blames the camera. In the 19th
century, correspondents had to describe what a battle or a volcanic
eruption looked like, he said. Now most editors find dispatches
from the front pointless or anachronistic. They've got the picture,
they figure; why do they need a description? When A.J. Liebling
described Gov. Earl Long of Louisiana cooling his face with a
handkerchief dipped in Coca Cola, young reporters were hanging on
his every word, hoping to write like him one day, Kelly said. Now
our literary farm system is destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Kirn, a book critic and the author of ``Thumbsucker'' and
``She Needed Me,'' said the appetite for narrative nonfiction was
there, but was being satisfied ``synthetically.'' He thinks he
knows what this nonfiction junk food is, he said: it is the
``spurious supernarrative,'' about people like O.J. Simpson or
Monica Lewinsky or Elian Gonzalez, with characters and plots that
everyone knows but no individual authors. The supernarratives are
covered by packs of journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Editors are now seeing the folly of their ways and learning that
there are some things that reporters do better that anyone else,
Kirn said, which is to tell a true story that no one knows. If you
want to call it narrative nonfiction, go ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-00 2133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
