<DOCNO> NYT20000507.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8417 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HOUK-CHARITIES-ART-2T     05-07 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUK-CHARITIES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPETITORS CHALLENGE A PHILANTHROPIST'S MOTIVATIONAL METHODS 
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Va., Fla., Ohio, Calif., Wash.) (ART ADV: Photo NYT23 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   J.T. Houk, the impresario behind one of the nation's largest
charities, is no stranger to controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The Internal Revenue Service once tried to revoke his
organization's tax-exempt status. Last year, Congress and the IRS
put a stop to a charitable giving strategy promoted aggressively by
Houk that critics said benefited donors more than recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Now Houk is facing a challenge to what he claims is the
cornerstone of his brand of philanthropy: finding ways to have
donors and volunteers pay themselves for their charitable deeds.
</P>
<P>
   Rejecting the notion that anyone ought to perform a charitable
service for free, Houk derides what he calls the ``charity poverty
syndrome.'' He acknowledges that some people make exceptional
volunteers, but says, ``Volunteers give you dregs, not dynamite,''
especially as fund raisers. ``You get what you pay for.''
</P>
<P>
   Donors who entrust money instead to his Falls Church, Va.,
charity, known as the National Heritage Foundation, set up
individual accounts that mimic foundations at a fraction of the
cost. In turn, they are eligible for immediate tax deductions for
their gifts and are encouraged to use the money in their accounts
to pay salaries and expenses for themselves and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Donors need not worry about the low pay charities offer, says
the pitch on the foundation's Web site, ``We would strive to bring
your salary up to private industry standards.''
</P>
<P>
   But many in the charitable world bridle at the notion that
people have any business paying themselves to carry out their
charitable impulses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like paying the Girl Scouts to sell cookies,'' said Jack
Shakely, president of the California Community Foundation, which is
one of many competing charities that also offer ``donor advised''
funds, which allow donors to set up individualized accounts with
funds earmarked for charity.
</P>
<P>
   The California Community Foundation bars donors from paying
themselves or family members. ``It's not illegal, but it just
doesn't pass the 60-second smell test,'' Shakely said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Heritage Foundation, however, is far less
restrictive, one reason why at last count tens of millions of
dollars from some 4,000 foundations had been set aside for charity
under its auspices. How much of that money will ever go to
worthwhile causes is far from clear.
</P>
<P>
   Administrative and marketing fees payable to National Heritage,
some of which are split with financial advisers who bring in the
funds, come right off the top. Then there are also the many
families who dip into their National Heritage accounts to pay
themselves salaries or defray expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. W. John Martin of Rosemead, Calif., set up his charity to
fund research on viruses that no university or government agency
would underwrite.
</P>
<P>
   Robert and Cynthia Fleming of Poulsbo, Wash., used some of the
money they gave to National Heritage to send their son to Mexico
for three years, calling it missionary work. While the Flemings
could have tried to create their own foundation, it would have been
``very time consuming and expensive,'' said Ms. Fleming, who heard
Houk's spiel on radio and was persuaded.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome T. Barrett of Falls Church, Va., heard about National
Heritage from a colleague. What he finds most appealing was
foundation officials' willingness to look after many of the details
of running a charity. ``They take care of the money, and they will
defend you in court'' if a donor runs afoul of IRS rules, Barrett
said.
</P>
<P>
   He uses his charity, Friends of FMCS History Foundation, to
sponsor research on a book he is writing on the federal Mediation
and Conciliation Service, where he once worked. His foundation no
longer has enough assets to allow him to dole himself a salary, but
it covers the rent on his office.
</P>
<P>
   While Houk says the National Heritage Foundation ultimately
controls where every dollar under its management goes, many of his
competitors want Congress to outlaw use of such accounts to siphon
money to donors and their families. The effort to curb this
practice was reported last Friday in The Wall Street Journal. The
Clinton administration has proposed going further: restricting the
gifts these funds can make to charities registered with the
Internal Revenue Service. That would preclude donors from giving to
foreign charities and needy individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Houk makes no bones about favoring old-fashioned
entrepreneurship as a way to invigorate the nation's charities.
Accustomed to being the focus of regulatory ire, Houk, a former
Fulbright scholar who boasts a law degree, an M.B.A. and a Ph.D.,
refuses to back down even at the risk of further scrutiny by the
IRS and sharp public criticism. ``The envelope needs pushing,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   If that makes him something of a maverick, so be it. ``All
progress is created, in my opinion, by skewed personalities,'' he
said. ``The champion is not an average guy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Quick to rely on biblical sources to support his views about
paying volunteers, he claims the National Heritage Foundation has
the potential to revolutionize churches, schools and other
charities. But he is convinced that competing charities, the
government and the media are conspiring to put an end to his
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Dayton, Ohio, Houk, who is known as Dock, describes
himself as coming from a wealthy background. He said his family was
connected with the Mead Corp., the giant paper company. He claims
to have given nearly all of his inheritance to charities except for
some property he kept for his wife and some small mutual fund
accounts for his grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Brown University, he spent a year in
Finland on a Fulbright scholarship, where he earned an M.B.A.
Later, he added two other advanced degrees before working for the
government researching the impact of international aid.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, dismayed by the government's actions to crack down on
private charities, Houk created the National Heritage Foundation in
anticipation of the 1969 Tax Reform Act, which took aim at
perceived abuses by corporations and individuals whose charitable
activities were said to be more for their benefit than that of
others. ``I didn't like the 1969 tax act,'' Houk said. ``I thought
it might cauterize charitable giving.''
</P>
<P>
   Houk was also busy on other fronts: creating what he claims was
the first socially conscious mutual fund and teaching in the
economic and business department of Liberty University, the college
founded by the Rev. Jerry Falwell.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1980s, the National Heritage Foundation was coming
under increased scrutiny by the IRS, which can revoke a charity's
tax-exempt status for some offenses. The service brought a case in
1982, alleging that the charity was really a group of private
foundations, which would be subject to different requirements, and
that it offered significant private benefits to financial planners
who promoted it.
</P>
<P>
   Houk's organization, which by then had ousted him at the
insistence of a big donor and had changed its name to National
Foundation Inc., won the case in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   He got going again in 1994, forming a new group that he again
called the National Heritage Foundation. It invoked many of the
same principles about the evils of big government, attracting many
powerful supporters. For instance, Bruce R. Hopkins, a prominent
Kansas City charity lawyer, wrote the forward to Houk's book, ``The
Coming Charitable Revolution,'' in which he lauded Houk's vision of
a grass-roots brand of philanthropy. That said, Hopkins said in an
interview he never meant to provide Houk's organization with a
blanket endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   There also remains significant enthusiasm for Houk's creativity
at motivating people to give among people who work with donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big issue is charitable entrepreneurship, and how far you
can push that,'' said C. Dennis Brislawn, a trusts and estate
lawyer in Kirkland, Wash., who has set up foundations for clients
at National Heritage. ``Dock Houk is one of the champions to push
the limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides getting a cut of the fees levied on donors' accounts,
financial planners who generate a lot of business for National
Heritage have also been rewarded occasionally by having foundations
set up in their own names at National Heritage's expense. Planners
may also use foundations to pay themselves for raising funds for
charity.
</P>
<P>
   What Houk and his organization get out of all this is open for
debate.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, when people were enthusiastic about a plan to buy
so-called split-dollar life insurance policies at his urging,
National Heritage took in $128 million in revenue, its tax returns
show. The split-dollar life insurance scheme, in which donors'
gifts to a charity were used to buy life insurance policies naming
both the charity and donors' heirs as beneficiaries, was outlawed
last year, and Houk says National Heritage's revenues fell to about
$61 million in 1999, information that is not yet available on the
tax returns. Some donors who took his advice and bought
split-dollar life insurance policies that have backfired are
mulling lawsuits, although it is not clear that Houk would be the
target of such actions.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a banner year like 1998, only $3 million was disbursed
to outside charities, the tax returns show. Another $3 million
covered other program expenses like honorariums and publicity, and
nearly $60 million was used to buy insurance policies and other
investment products used to build endowments. And information on
how much donors are paying themselves cannot be gleaned from the
tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   The charity's 1998 tax return makes no mention at all of Houk's
own pay package and does not list Houk as one of its top officers,
omissions that Houk acknowledged were an error, especially when the
organization's letterhead refers to him as its executive director
and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Houk says he makes about $6 an hour, roughly $12,000 a year or
so, in keeping with his sense that he does not need the money. He
does, however, allow the organization to pick up some of his
expenses, like frequent travel to the West Palm Beach, Fla., area,
where he maintains a modest office.
</P>
<P>
   Having installed his wife, son and daughter-in-law in top
positions at National Heritage, he allowed them as a group to make
about $166,000 in 1998 salaries, according to the tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   At an airport lounge in West Palm Beach last Friday, Houk said
he did not understand why he was such a target for regulators, who
he said were paying undue attention to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're probably more socially responsible than the average
bear,'' Houk said defiantly. He says he could easily spend his days
playing tennis and enjoying life, but there is little sign of
surrender. ``We're not going to quit fighting,'' Houk said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
