u s BC-OLY-FOXHALL0508-COX     05-07 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-FOXHALL0508-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Victorious Loudon hopes to make leap to Olympics
 &HT;    By Carrie Teegardin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tiffani Loudon's lead in the inaugural Foxhall Cup
appeared to be in jeopardy Sunday morning, when her 14-year-old
horse Makabi woke up sore and tired from Saturday's grueling
cross-county round.
</P>
<P>
   The veterinarians had to think twice before allowing Makabi to
compete in Sunday's stadium jumping, the final phase of the equine
triathlon. And Loudon knew she had absolutely no room for error,
with Australian Olympic gold medalist Phillip Dutton standing in
second place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to calm myself,'' Loudon said.
</P>
<P>
   And that she did. Before a hushed stadium of 4,000 spectators,
the 5-foot Loudon guided the veteran bay horse to a picture-perfect
round on the jumping course. Not a single rail dropped and Loudon
and her mount picked up a national title, three silver trophies and
a $55,000 check.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this horse, for one,'' Loudon, 24, told the spectators
after being asked how she felt about winning.
</P>
<P>
   If the horse wasn't feeling his best Sunday, he didn't show it.
Only five other riders were able to produce a clean round over the
jumping course.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran well all weekend,'' said Loudon, of Blythewood, South
Carolina. ``He couldn't have done anything better, I don't think.
Yesterday, he didn't miss a beat, he didn't put a foot wrong and
today he was great.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear whether Makabi's efforts will be enough to earn
Loudon a spot on the U.S. Olympic equestrian team. The Foxhall Cup
was an Olympic trial. But Loudon missed a key trial last weekend in
Kentucky because Makabi was not sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's every rider's dream,'' Loudon said of the Olympics.
``We'll just have to take each day and see what happens. I would
love to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Foxhall Cup is a competition in ``eventing,'' one of three
Olympic equestrian sports. It's a triathlon in which horses and
riders face off in dressage, cross-country and stadium jumping. The
Foxhall Cup is the most high-profile equestrian competition ever to
be staged in Atlanta, other than Olympic competition.
</P>
<P>
   Held in Douglas County, the event is hosted by Atlanta
businessman Jim Richards and his wife, Janet, at their 1,200-acre
farm along the banks of the Chattahoochee River. While the event
drew just 3,500 spectators for Saturday's cross country competition
and 4,000 for stadium jumping, Richards said he and his staff were
thrilled with the outcome. He's hoping Foxhall will draw up to
100,000 within five years. Richards has a 25-year contract to host
the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited about where we're headed,'' Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
