<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALMON HAS BIG ROAD TRIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE -- When the Angels began their six-game trip to
Baltimore and Seattle, nobody on the club had a lower batting
average than Tim Salmon's .217. But that was about to change.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon had hit a game-winning homer in the 13th inning on April
29, the second-to-last day of the homestand, and he said at the
time that maybe that was what he needed to get going. It turned out
he was right.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon hit .474 (9 for 19) on the trip with three homers and six
RBIs, raising his overall average to .261.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like it,'' Salmon said when asked of the game-winning
homer was the catalyst he needed. ``Up to that point I felt I was
swinging pretty good, I just wasn't getting hits. Sometimes it
takes something to get you over the hump. You're looking for that
bloop single in a crucial situation. For me, it was that homer.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon said he was never worried about getting his swing to
where he needed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a track record, I have that to go on,'' he said.
``I've had bad starts in the past and went on to have good seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not isolated. There are always guys out there off to a
slow starts and they rally to have a great year. You don't expect
(Ken) Griffey to hit .200 all season, do you? It's not fun to have
a slow start by any means, but it helps when other guys are having
a good start. Then when they cool off, I'm hot, it's my turn. It
seems a little bit unrealistic for all nine guys to be hot all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   As hot as Darin Erstad was in April, he's been cold in May.
After Sunday's 0-for-5 performance, Erstad is hitting .115 (3 for
26) this month. But Erstad will not overanalyze his swing and try
to make too many changes, like he did last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The approach is the same,'' said Erstad, who is hitting .383.
``You still to to hit the ball in the same spots, stay inside the
ball. You make a little adjustments but nothing drastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad said his current slump doesn't make him feel any added
pressure, but ``It drives me to be better. If I'm just going
through the motions, I'm going to quit.''
</P>
<P>
   The past year has been quite a whirlwind for Mariners pitcher
Brett Tomko. Tomko, who grew up in Placentia and played two seasons
for Mt. San Antonio College, began last season in Cincinnati at the
Reds' ace, but struggled to a 5-7 season. Amid a winter of trade
rumors, he finally was traded to Seattle, heard more rumors he was
going to be traded to the Angels, then started the season at
Triple-A Tacoma after the Mariners sent him down.
</P>
<P>
   He was called up April 22 to replace the injured Jamie Moyer,
and is 1-1 with a 5.30 ERA in three starts going into today's start
vs. Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Back in February, Tomko said ``It would be nice someday'' to
play in his hometown. ``(Seattle's) not my backyard, but it's still
close.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomko will forever be noted in baseball history as one of the
players traded for Ken Griffey Jr. But he didn't necessarily think
of it as a good thing initially.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had apprehensions coming over here,'' he said. ``Cincinnati
Reds was all I knew my first five years. At first I was a little
nervous. But I've made a lot of friends and I'd like to stay and
compete for an AL West title.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Gary DiSarcina, out since May 2 with a sore shoulder,
is expected to start tonight vs. Oakland. DiSarcina has played in
only 11 of the team's 32 games this season.
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS VS. OAKLAND
</P>
<P>
   Time: 7:05 at Edison Field
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: FSN; KLAC-570, XPRS-1090
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: Ramon Ortiz (2-2, 5.47 ERA) will start for Anaheim
against Oakland's Ariel Prieto (first appearance). The Angels
finished their trip to Baltimore and Seattle at 3-3, but lost the
final two games to the Mariners after holding a share of first
place with them. The Angels, currently 16-16, have not been more
than two games above or below .500 all season.
</P>
<P>
   -- Joe Haakenson
</P>
</TEXT>
