<SLUG> BC-NYC-COL-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: MAN WITHOUT EMPATHY NOW ASKS IT OF VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOYCE PURNICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treat him is if he were Everyman, says Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani. Public officials have problems, too.
</P>
<P>
   Will the public accommodate him, as one recent poll suggested?
That would mean a married candidate _ if Giuliani remains a Senate
candidate _ can acknowledge a relationship with ``a very good
friend,'' pronounce his behavior to be nobody's business, and
suffer no ill political consequences.
</P>
<P>
   All this from a Catholic school alumnus who has labored to rid
his city of sleaze, tried to punish a museum that exhibited art he
considered immoral and wants the Ten Commandments posted in public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about your Nixon-to-China syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   We don't know if the mayor will pursue his Senate campaign,
given his bout with cancer. We do know that he is asking a lot of
tolerance from New Yorkers _ and from his wife, Donna Hanover, who
now refers obliquely to the need for ``decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very unusual thing,'' said Michael Beschloss, a
historian of the presidency. ``You can rack your brain and not find
a precedent in recent history that foreshadows this.'' Not,
Beschloss noted, that it comes out of nowhere. A half-century ago,
a divorce spelled the death knell of presidential aspirations; by
1980, Ronald Reagan, a divorced man, was elected. Bill Clinton won
the presidency in 1992 despite Gennifer Flowers and survived Monica
Lewinsky, and impeachment, with his popularity intact.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Hart's presidential candidacy collapsed primarily because
of revelations of an affair, but only after he boasted of a solid
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and Hanover long ago acknowledged leading separate
lives, so the mayor's problem is not hypocrisy. But can a man not
known for his empathies ask the public to understand that public
officials also live the lives ``that other human beings do''?
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has worked a lifetime creating the impression that he
is unlike the rest of us: the tough, unyielding prosecutor; the
high-minded, uncompromising mayor. He routinely berates those who
ask him questions he doesn't like and roughly faces down all
critics.
</P>
<P>
   Public matters, not private, Giuliani would say. But
distinctions blur. In the long run, what is likely to matter most
is what people think of the Giuliani they know, not of his new
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the rule in politics is if you have a general
reservoir of good will among your constituents, you can get away
with it,'' suggested Robert Ellis Smith, publisher of the
newsletter Privacy Journal. ``People have come to know Giuliani
over several years. Everyone pretty much has made up his mind about
him as a public figure. Associating with someone not his wife isn't
going to change people's minds.''
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers do, indeed, know Giuliani; few are undecided between
him and Hillary Rodham Clinton. Even his conduct in addressing this
friendship was in character. The mayor, who loves to manipulate the
media, all but announced the relationship himself.
</P>
<P>
   The story broke last week in the tabloids after the mayor
brought Judith Nathan to several public events, including (tweak,
tweak) the Inner Circle, a reporters' dinner and show held March
11. Rumors flew, and finally the couple were seen together so
frequently that the story broke, first in The Daily News, then The
New York Post. They said she was a divorced nurse, a mother of a
15-year-old girl, who works for a pharmaceutical company and has
been seeing the mayor for months.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor confirmed his friendship, perhaps, because the timing
was good: he was drawing sympathy for his diagnosis of prostate
cancer. Besides, he knew that two books about him were in the works
and that Gail Sheehy had written an article about the Senate race
in the new Vanity Fair. Getting potentially damaging news out
yourself is good politics.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers may not care much about inside baseball. What they
know is that the mayor has a failing marriage, that Giuliani is
open about pursuing midlife happiness, that Hanover is upset, that
two children are caught in the middle. There are consequences, as
there are for millions of people in troubled marriages.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor will not lie about it, to his credit, but asks the
public to allow him a degree of latitude that he has rarely granted
others. It seems logical that the voters' willingness to separate
his personal and political identities will depend not on any
theories about what is private in public lives, but on the
reputation Giuliani long ago created for himself _ and on Hanover's
``decisions.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
