<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-CUBANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT CUBAN DAY PARADE, MAYOR HAILED AS HERO  

</HEADLINE>
  By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thousands chanted his name. Hundreds waved his blue
``Rudy'' campaign signs. And after a dozen days that few could
doubt Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani would rather forget, there was
little hesitation by the mayor about how to respond: an
enthusiastic thumbs up and a broad, relaxed smile.
</P>
<P>
   The scene took place Sunday afternoon on the Avenue of the
Americas as Giuliani marched in the annual Cuban Day Parade.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has long been popular with the city's small but vocal
Cuban-American population, having snubbed Fidel Castro during his
1995 visit to the city and named a corner outside the Cuban Mission
to the United Nations in honor of an exile group that lobbies for
the overthrow of the Castro government.
</P>
<P>
   But after several months of persistent criticism of the Clinton
administration's handling of the Elian Gonzalez affair, Giuliani
appeared Sunday to have achieved hero status.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viva Rudy,'' they chanted, as he stepped out of his city car.
``We love you,'' ``Go Rudy, go,'' ``You are our hero,'' others
yelled. Some even made reference to his announcement 11 days ago
that he had been told he had prostate cancer and to his more recent
acknowledgment of a close friendship with an Upper East Side woman,
saying, ``I pray for you,'' and ``Everything will be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor is a strong person,'' said Ermina Rivero, 74, a
retired teacher, who wore a ``Women for Rudy'' button and a T-shirt
featuring a photograph of Elian and the words ``Federal Child
Abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He fights for the people,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor was unabashed about his admiration for the
Cuban-American community, saying he felt a ``very close kinship''
to immigrants who, like his Italian-American relatives, quickly
became self-sufficient after arriving in the United States. He also
said he appreciated the struggle by Cuban-Americans against what he
called the oppression of the Castro government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have tremendous respect for the Cuban-American community
because they embody the very best values of America,'' Giuliani
said, as supporters chanted his name. ``And I know at this time
they are suffering even more than usual because of the events of
the last couple of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, a candidate for United States Senate, again condemned
President Clinton and Attorney General Janet Reno Sunday for the
seizure of Elian from his Miami relatives last month before
reuniting him with his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used those agents as storm troopers,'' Giuliani said
Sunday, repeating a description he has used, which some have called
inappropriate. The federal agents, he said, ``dressed up as if they
were involved in a major war confrontation and they went in with a
machine gun pointed at a child.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
