<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8444 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-EAST-COAST-HEAT-NYT &LR;      05-07 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAST-COAST-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCORCHER ENWRAPS MID-ATLANTIC STATES, SETTING HEAT RECORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 11,12 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The molten sun beat down mercilessly. The hot, slow
afternoon was a furnace. The parks lay green and motionless.
Pavements shimmered like burning lakes. It might have been one of
those torrid days in August when the heavy iridescent air presses
down on the spirit and all seems hopeless.
</P>
<P>
   But the heat wave that smothered the metropolitan area and the
mid-Atlantic states Sunday was no illusion. Normally in the high
60s in early May, the temperature hit 93 degrees in Central Park
just after 3 p.m., breaking a record of 92 set in 1939, when the
World's Fair opened in New York and war in Europe began.
</P>
<P>
   Other records from New England to Virginia were also shattered.
It was 94 degrees in Newark and Concord, N.H.; 93 in Salisbury,
Md.; 92 in Atlantic City; 89 in Burlington, Vt.; and 87 in
Bridgeport, Conn. _ all records. And it was 90 in Boston,
Philadelphia and Washington, although those were not record highs.
Meteorologists said the region's heat-humidity index was in the
mid-90s.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual spring heat _ a huge, humid air mass from the
Midwest that was expected to linger until Wednesday _ felled about
40 people with dehydration and exhaustion on a five-borough bicycle
tour of New York, while 40,000 other cyclists survived the 42-mile
ordeal by pausing along the way to gulp gallons of water and get
doused by kindly strangers with garden hoses.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency medical service workers treated those stricken by the
heat and said no one was hospitalized. No deaths or serious
injuries were reported in the region, but the heat depleted many of
the well-conditioned runners in the Olympic marathon trials in
Pittsburgh, with only two Americans, one man and one woman,
qualifying for the Summer Games in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the Saharan heat, it was a lovely day in New York.
Castles of clouds drifted in a liquid blue sky that seemed to go
with tinkling chimes on a country porch. On Broadway, greengrocers
set out pyramids of limes, oranges and apples. Down at the Battery,
sea gulls dipped and soared, pencil lines in a musical composition,
and the harbor rippled like blue-gray silk.
</P>
<P>
   While millions kept to the air-conditioned comfort of homes or
sought relief in refrigerated theaters, shady parks, beaches or
country retreats, there were many who challenged the day in shorts,
tank tops and sunglasses, getting out to roller-blade, jog, stroll
or just sit in the sun with the Sunday papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm used to this, but it's too darned hot,'' Bruce Anderson,
41, a native of Mobile, Ala., said as he and his newspaper wilted
on a bench on West Street by the Hudson. ``This weather makes you
not want to do anything,'' he added. ``I'm going home and take a
nap.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White Horse Tavern on nearby West 11th Street, Anna
Meyer, who had come from upstate New York for the Bike New York
Tour, breezed in with a sweaty exhilaration and joined the crowd.
``It was a great day, perfect weather for riding,'' she said. ``Now
I deserve a couple of beers and a burger.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Brooklynites flocked to Prospect Park, and despite
the heat some danced lavishly to the beat of 20 musicians on congas
and steel drums. Yaffa Chapman, 33, of East New York, shook her
hips in a colorful African lapa skirt and beamed. ``Me not dancing
in the summer is like man keeping nature from blossoming,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Her friend, Guy Isa Love-Zion Proud Nubian Messiah, also known
as Guy Perry Hargett, whispered encouragement and rejoiced over the
steamy summerlike day. ``Occasionally, the heat makes you think of
ancient times,'' he said. ``It leads you to put your foot down anew
with a little ancient African boogie.''
</P>
<P>
   For Juce St. Victor, 28, it was a day to go fishing. He combed
the shore of Prospect Park Lake with his sons, Jamel, 9, and
Jiovanni, 3, and a red cart carrying fishing rods and a boom box to
play Bob Marley. ``The heat doesn't bother us,'' he said. ``We get
fresh air in the park.''
</P>
<P>
   While most of the region sweltered, there were cool breezes off
the ocean on the south shore of Long Island. Elana Sessler, of
Atlantic Beach, ran errands, played tennis and was still going at
midafternoon. ``I went for a bicycle ride on the boardwalk,'' she
said. ``That was glorious.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Petrosino, 7, of Island Park, cooled off with a
hockey lesson at Long Beach Arena while his parents watched.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much better in there,'' his father, Ralph, said as they
came out blinking in the sunlight. ``It's got to be 35 to 40
degrees. There's a nice humidity haze. It works for me, if I can
get two hours in air-conditioning.''
</P>
<P>
   Artificial cool was also on the mind of Lyle Tick, 24, an
account executive for a Manhattan advertising agency, who spent the
morning buying and installing a new air-conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suffered last summer with no air-conditioning,'' he said,
``so at the first sign of heat I went out and got one.''
</P>
<P>
   Why was it so hot in early May?
</P>
<P>
   Paul Knight, a meteorologist at Pennsylvania State University,
said dry, mild weather last summer and winter in the Rockies and
the northern Plains states left the ground from Montana through the
Dakotas, Minnesota and the Great Lakes states very dry. That is the
region where most of the weather reaching New York and the East
comes from.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring, the sun's radiant energy warms the ground and
evaporates the moisture in it, he noted. The sun does not heat the
air directly, but first heats the ground, which transmits the
warmth into the air. But when the ground is already dry, as it was
this spring, the efficiency of the heat transfer from sun to ground
to air is extremely high.
</P>
<P>
   So the air over the Great Plains has been getting increasingly
hot this spring. A week ago, meteorologists knew a big heat wave
was on the way, heading east and setting records. In recent days,
records in the high 80s and low 90s were set in the Dakotas,
Minnesota, Wisconsin and Michigan, Knight said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And voila, it comes to New York and the East Coast,'' Knight
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
