<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTON-FUNDRAISER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT EXTOLS MRS. CLINTON'S CANDIDACY TO FRIENDLY CROWD IN
ARKANSAS
</HEADLINE>
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ It was an afternoon filled with nostalgia
and sentiment as President Clinton returned here Sunday both to
revisit memories of his political life in Arkansas and to preside
over a fund-raising reception for his wife's effort to be elected a
U.S. senator from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Before an audience of more then 300 Arkansans, the president
introduced Hillary Rodham Clinton as someone who would do ``a
superb job'' as senator.
</P>
<P>
   To a crowd made up of her old friends, political associates,
former fellow law school professors and child-advocate colleagues,
Mrs. Clinton called the trip ``a very pleasant journey in time.''
</P>
<P>
   While Mrs. Clinton has campaigned throughout the state of New
York as a Senate candidate, Sunday's reception at the New State
House Convention Center was one of the rare occasions when the
president attended an event with his wife's political campaign as
its centerpiece. He appeared with her when she made a formal
announcement of her candidacy in February, but did not speak at
that event.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the president spoke effusively Sunday about his
wife, portraying hers as one of the most important races of the
2000 campaign year. ``I have spent the last almost 30 years having
conversations with my wife about every conceivable issue,'' Clinton
said. ``In my whole life, I've never known anyone who had a better
grasp of the issues. I think the Senate would be a much better
place if she were there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's reception, which raised about $100,000 for Mrs.
Clinton's Senate campaign, seemed to be a personal pilgrimage as
well as a political event for both Clintons. Before the president
and Mrs. Clinton spoke to a decidedly partisan audience, the
audience heard the two extolled by two of their closest political
allies in this state: the former Sens. Dale Bumpers and David
Pryor.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton repeated many of the themes that are fixtures of
her speeches in New York. She talked about her opposition to school
vouchers and the need to make health care more widely available.
But she, like the president, also reminisced about her days in
Arkansas, her once-adopted state.
</P>
<P>
   In Little Rock, where the president's change of voter
registration from Arkansas to New York made front-page headlines,
Mrs. Clinton's decision to seek office in another state has been a
matter of some local controversy.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday's reception offered nothing but warm enthusiasm for
the Clintons, who a day earlier attended the wedding of a staff
member near Paris, Ark. And the president made clear his strong
feelings about his native state, referring to Arkansas in his
remarks as ``home'' and telling the audience of his plans to make
frequent stays in an apartment to be included in the presidential
library that will bear his name, which will be built near the
convention center.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton took pains to explain to the audience that his wife's
decision to run for the seat being vacated by Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y., was one that came to her at the urging of others.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton did not mention Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, her
Republican rival. But she bitterly chastised the Republican Party
for advocating the use of a budget surplus to finance a large-scale
tax reduction.
</P>
<P>
   Both Mrs. Clinton and the president talked about the role
reversal they had undergone after she became a candidate. She spoke
of the critique the president had offered her during her rehearsal
of the speech in which she officially announced her candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had and probably still have a lot to learn about being a
candidate,'' Mrs. Clinton said. ``And I'm trying to do the very
best job I can. But I want to take back every time I said to Bill,
`You know, you could have said it like this.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
