<HEADER>
A8446 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IRELAND-PEACE-BOS &LR;      05-07 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-PEACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTH SIDES CHALLENGED TO IMPLEMENT PEACE PLAN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NewsAnalysis
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ After 30 years of being at war with each other, the
IRA's ruling Army Council and the leaders of the Ulster Unionists
now find themselves in the same boat, trying to sell to their
grass-roots the idea that the IRA's offer to allow international
inspectors to check its hidden arms dumps is the only way to keep
the Northern Ireland peace process alive.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides face challenges in succeeding and risks if they fail.
</P>
<P>
   David Trimble, the prickly but pragmatic Ulster Unionist leader,
has to convince his party that by accepting the IRA's pledge, they
have a chance to defang the IRA, even if the guns never get
formally turned in and simply remain in the hidden dumps.
</P>
<P>
   Such a formal handover of weapons is seen by the IRA as a
surrender it did not agree to when it called a cease-fire to allow
politics to take over.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble's strongest argument is that if unionists really want to
disarm the IRA, this is the most realistic chance. Saying no to the
IRA offer to put arms ``beyond use'' will ensure unionists never
get what they say they want.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the unionists are entitled to say no. It is, after
all, despite republican protests to the contrary, a free country.
But the unionists would reject the deal at their own political
peril.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with senior officials from both the British and Irish
governments suggest that British Prime Minister Tony Blair and his
Irish counterpart, Bertie Ahern, would be furious and embarrassed
if the unionists thumb their nose at the deal that the two leaders
so patiently stitched together.
</P>
<P>
   If rebuffed, London and Dublin would likely draw up an
alternative plan that would not be as advantageous to unionists as
the current one.
</P>
<P>
   Internationally, meanwhile, the unionists would be seen as the
obstructionists to progress. The same would go for the IRA if,
faced with grass-roots opposition, the IRA leadership reneges on
its offer to let former Finnish president Martti Ahtisaari and
former African National Congress chief negotiator Cyril Ramaphosa
inspect their arms dumps.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA has a lot to gain by keeping the peace process alive.
The IRA leadership can point to the promised reform of the Royal
Ulster Constabulary, the 90 percent Protestant police force. In
return for the IRA pledge, the British government has promised to
reduce British troop levels, which at 15,000  &UR; today &LR;  are already
the lowest in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   It took the IRA nearly 30 years to kill 300 police officers and
700 British soldiers. By embracing democracy, the IRA could send
the British army packing in a few years, and could in 10 years cut
the 13,000 police force in half, and make its composition closer to
that of Northern Ireland, which is 40 percent Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' an IRA man said in a recent conversation, ``is real
power.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most significantly, IRA leaders can point to the early
parole of some 400 of its prisoners, the last of whom are scheduled
to be released by July 28. For 30 years, republicans sent thousands
of their own young to warm cells and nearly 400 to cold graves.
Anyone who wants to go back to war has to assume responsibility for
consigning the next generation to death and prison.
</P>
<P>
   Showing the flexibility and resiliency that has marked their
partnership, Blair and Ahern have pushed next Monday's deadline for
disarming back to next May. That is already being seized on by some
unionists as one concession too many. But there is nothing the IRA
could do, short of ordering its members to commit mass suicide,
that would satsify hard-line unionists like the Rev. Ian Paisley,
leader of the fundamentalist Democratic Unionists.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for comment on the IRA's pledge, Paisley said, ``I don't
trust the IRA.''
</P>
<P>
   But most unionists, whether they like it or not, have to trust
that what the IRA said on Saturday was a genuine and sincere
attempt to show that the war is over at a time when the IRA is
unable or unwilling to say explicitly that the war is over.
</P>
<P>
   Those in the IRA who do not like the idea of letting outsiders
peruse their arms dumps have two options. They can sulk and lament
the end of their ``armed struggle,'' or they can join dissident
groups and mount a new campaign of violence. If they choose the
latter, they will find few republicans willing to offer them
support, much less their homes as havens and their children as
recruits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-00 2226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000507.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8447 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OCONNOR-FUNERAL-ART-N     05-07 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCONNOR-FUNERAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CARDINAL'S FUNERAL, ANCIENT RITUAL AND VIVID SPECTACLE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT24 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JUAN FORERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cardinal John O'Connor is to be honored Monday in a majestic and
intricately planned Roman Catholic funeral Mass that, though rooted
in ancient traditions that viewed death as a bleak event, will
celebrate his anticipated ascension into heaven and eternal life
with God.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 3,500 people _ including President Clinton, city
and state leaders and cardinals and archbishops in colorful
vestments _ are to gather under the soaring spires of St. Patrick's
Cathedral at the Mass for the cardinal, the eighth man to lead the
Roman Catholic Archdiocese of New York.
</P>
<P>
   From the opening prayers to the singing of hymns to the taking
of communion, the ceremony is at its core the same carefully
structured Mass of Christian Burial held the world over for any
Catholic, said the Rev. Thomas Lynch, who teaches church history at
St. Joseph's Seminary in Yonkers. But the people packing the pews
of the church _ and presumably millions more who will watch on
television _ will see an elaborate, two-hour event filled with
pageantry and spectacle honoring O'Connor, who died Wednesday at
80.
</P>
<P>
   With the cardinal's closed coffin resting in the center aisle
near the altar, the light streaming through the church's stained
glass, the ceremony will begin with a procession estimated to take
45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Following a cross bearer, hundreds of priests, nuns,
seminarians, deacons, representatives of lay orders and leaders of
other religions will file through the bronze portals of St.
Patrick's.
</P>
<P>
   Archbishops will follow. Those coming last will be among some of
the highest-ranking officials in the Catholic Church, 15 cardinals
from the United States and five other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Among them will be Cardinal William Wakefield Baum, a Vatican
official and the senior American cardinal, who will speak to the
congregation. Cardinal Bernard Law, archbishop of Boston, will
deliver the homily, and Cardinal Angelo Sodano, the Vatican's
secretary of state and Pope John Paul II's No. 2 man, will preside
over the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Awn, a former Jesuit priest and a professor of
religion at Columbia University, said the rich, elaborate nature of
a cardinal's funeral harks back to an ancient church in which
cardinals were actually princes and popes were monarchs.
</P>
<P>
   ``On occasions like this, religious institutions like the Roman
Catholic Church fall back on the classical traditions,'' he said.
``So all of the rituals surrounding the funeral of a cardinal are
very reminiscent of these ancient, older allusions.''
</P>
<P>
   The ancient Christian ceremonies were gloomy and foreboding. And
through the centuries, Catholic funeral ceremonies with their
medieval chants, candles surrounding coffins and apocalyptic hymns
like ``Dies Irae'' (Day of Wrath) _ continued to emphasize concern
about judgment day.
</P>
<P>
   Things started to change with the Second Vatican Council in
1965. The Catholic Church, in its drive to broaden participation,
ceased to compel the use of Latin in Mass, did away with black
garments and simplified its ceremonies. Other revisions came in the
following years, affecting the rites of burial. Monday, say church
officials and experts on the liturgy, the focus is on celebrating
the deceased's new life.
</P>
<P>
   For mourners, the effect has been one of affirmation and faith,
stressing the hope and renewal that come with the afterlife.
</P>
<P>
   That emphasis starts from the very beginning of Mass, with the
cardinal's wooden coffin covered with a white pall and blessed with
holy water, reminiscent of the joy of baptism. A Gospel book is
placed on the coffin, a sign that those who remain must carry on
the Gospel of Christ to the world. A crucifix will rest on the
coffin.
</P>
<P>
   The concelebrants _ those who come in union to celebrate the
Mass _ will enter the sanctuary area, Cardinal Sodano in the center
and the other cardinals close by.
</P>
<P>
   After an opening prayer, Mother Agnes Donovan, the superior of
the Sisters of Life, an order founded by the cardinal, will do the
first reading from the Old Testament. The reading, from the Book of
Wisdom, says that the ``souls of the just are in the hand of God,
and no torment shall touch them.''
</P>
<P>
   The second reading, from the New Testament, is from the letter
of Paul to the Colossians. Read by Therese Snyder of the Catholic
Guild for the Blind, Paul explains that he has found ``my joy in
the suffering I endure for you,'' and says that he became a
minister through God's will.
</P>
<P>
   The third and last reading, from the Gospel of Mark, recounts
the Passover Supper. In one of the most important biblical
passages, Jesus tells his followers, ``Take this, this is my
body.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Ann Rehrauer, associate director of the Liturgical
Secretariat for the U.S. Catholic Conference of Bishops in
Washington, said the themes in the readings would carry a strong
sense of hope.
</P>
<P>
   Law will then speak in the one portion of the Mass that is not
scripted. But the homily is expected to be far different from a
free-wheeling eulogy one might hear in other Christian churches,
with the emphasis on the deceased's accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   While O'Connor will certainly be lauded, the homilist's primary
goal is not to praise him, Rehrauer said. Rather, it is to give
thanks to God. ``Anything the cardinal was able to do, he did for
the grace of God,'' she added, ``which is different from a eulogy,
which says isn't this a terrific person.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Prayer of the Faithful, members of the cardinal's
family will bring the gifts of bread and wine to the altar and
prayers are then offered.
</P>
<P>
   The steps that follow are among the most significant and
emotional in Catholicism, starting with a recollection of Christ's
words and deeds at the Last Supper. Catholics believe that by
taking bread, giving thanks, breaking bread and giving it to the
disciples, Christ gave of himself. The next day he was crucified.
And by now accepting the body and blood of Christ, the believer is,
in turn, accepting him and his teachings.
</P>
<P>
   After communion, the last prayers are read over the body of the
cardinal. The coffin is blessed with holy water, again recalling
baptism. The choir will sing ``may the angels take you into a
paradise.''
</P>
<P>
   The coffin will then be carried up the altar, around the rear
and down a narrow stairwell to a crypt that holds the bodies of
five cardinals, four archbishops and other church leaders.
Accompanying the coffin, will be the cardinal's family and a few
clergy members.
</P>
<P>
   In the crypt, a final prayer is said, holy water is sprinkled
and the choir sings the traditional hymn to Mary, ``Salve Regina.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-00 2226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
