<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8449 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-DNA-REVIEW-425&AMP;ADD     05-07 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DNA-REVIEW-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI PROPOSES DNA BOARD TO REVIEW OVERTURNED CONVICTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki on Sunday proposed the creation of a state
DNA Review Committee that would examine all convictions in New York
overturned because of new genetic evidence. The panel would also
propose regulations to improve the use of the precise forensic
science of DNA profiling by the state's criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, as the reliability of genetic evidence has
improved, DNA testing has been used to set aside 64 criminal
convictions in the United States, according to statistics
maintained by the Innocence Project at the Benjamin N. Cardozo
School of Law at Yeshiva University. Seven of the overturned
convictions have been in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In the most prominent New York case, Victor H. Jenkins was
convicted of raping a Buffalo woman in 1982, a time when current
DNA profiling methods did not exist. Jenkins served 17 years in
prison before DNA evidence exonerated him last year. Pataki said
Sunday that the committee would work to find the causes of this
mistaken conviction and of others in New York, and would make
proposals to more thoroughly implement the use of forensic DNA in
future investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is not to convict someone of a crime,'' Pataki said.
``The point is to convict the right person of a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Pataki's plan, the review committee, which would require
legislative approval to be created, would serve as a subcommittee
of the 14-member State Forensic Science Commission, a board that is
responsible for certifying crime labs in New York. It would include
defense lawyers, prosecutors, judges, forensic scientists and
senior police officials.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Scheck, a law professor and a member of the commission,
said the committee would examine each conviction in New York that
was set aside by exculpatory DNA evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that is amazing about DNA exonerations is
that no opinion is ever written about them,'' Scheck said Sunday.
``What happens is the judge just issues an order and the person
walks out of prison. The idea is to have a blue-ribbon commission
that basically would issue a report about what went wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheck is a co-author of ``Actual Innocence: Five Days to
Execution and Other Dispatches from the Wrongfully Convicted'' and
is a co-founder of the Innocence Project, a student-professor
program in Manhattan that has helped exonerate dozens of inmates
through post-conviction DNA testing.
</P>
<P>
   The governor plans to announce his proposal formally Monday
morning in Manhattan at the Fifth Annual Conference on the Future
of DNA.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He said the project's review of DNA exonerations had found that
among the most common causes were incompetent defense counsel,
shoddy or fraudulent crime labs, inaccurate identification by
witnesses, false confessions, misconduct by the police and
prosecutors, and reliance on incriminating testimony from inmates
who negotiate with the authorities, a class of witness often
referred to by defense lawyers as ``jailhouse snitches.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Jenkins, when the 23-year-old victim saw him at a
Buffalo police garage, she did not identify him as the attacker.
But later, after the police showed her a variety of pictures of
Jenkins, and under what one of his defense lawyers described as
suggestive pressure, she said he was the one who raped her. That
identification led to the conviction; nearly two decades later, DNA
evidence showed it was almost certainly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said he had a personal brush with erroneous convictions
in the 1980's, when Nathaniel Carter, with whom the governor played
basketball as a teen-ager in Peekskill, N.Y., was convicted of
murdering his former wife's foster mother. Carter spent 28 months
in jail. He was freed when his former wife admitted to the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me aware that we truly have to seek to have a fair
system of justice,'' Pataki said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is the latest in a series of Pataki's DNA
initiatives. Last year, he successfully pushed for the expansion of
DNA testing, which now requires roughly 65 percent of convicted
felons to submit DNA samples for a state offender database. This
year he has proposed legislation to expand testing further, so that
it includes any citizen convicted of any crime.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has also proposed eliminating statutes of limitations for
16 felonies, including rape and second-degree sexual assault, in
which DNA evidence is often collected.
</P>
<P>
   His latest proposal has many elements, he said. In addition to
investigating the facts behind DNA exonerations, Pataki said, the
review committee would be charged with creating state policies for
the collection, handling and storage of DNA evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Two recent cases illustrated the need for these policies, the
governor said.
</P>
<P>
   In the first case, the Westchester County district attorney's
office was able to secure an indictment this year for a 1979 murder
because the police had saved a sheet with the attacker's
bloodstains on it. DNA testing matched the blood to that of Walter
Gill, an inmate at the Sing Sing Correctional Facility in Ossining,
N.Y. who recently submitted DNA to the state offender database.
</P>
<P>
   In the other case, Coney Island Hospital performed a rape
examination last year but failed to properly collect and submit DNA
from the victim, weakening the state's case against Anthony Jones,
a serial sex offender who attacked the woman on the morning after
he was released from prison. Jones was convicted this spring of
second-degree assault. With no DNA evidence to support them,
multiple sex-crime charges against him were dropped.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said that many police officers and hospital
employees did not yet have experience collecting DNA from victims
and from crime scenes, and that even when it was properly
collected, there was not a formal set of rules to govern its
storage and retention. The committee would be asked to create them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
