<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8450 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-PATAKI-PACS-NYT &LR;      05-07 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-PACS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT-OF-STATE PACS CONTINUE TO AID PATAKI  

</HEADLINE>
   By WINNIE HU    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki, hoping to keep his political
choices open, has continued to raise money through two political
action committees that he set up outside New York to enhance his
national profile.
</P>
<P>
   The stated purpose of those committees, which bear the name
``21st Century Freedom,'' is to help Republican candidates around
the country who share his views. But campaign records show that
most of the total of $892,573 raised so far has been used to
benefit Pataki by building new political alliances and subsidizing
an increasingly expensive political apparatus that helped him win
two terms as governor.
</P>
<P>
   The out-of-state PACs _ one was formed under federal law, and
the other in Virginia, where there are no limits on contribution
amounts _ have channeled $67,433 to state and federal races outside
New York. Yet they have paid at least $126,944 to Pataki's longtime
pollster, Arthur Finkelstein; $118,046 to his political
consultants, Kieran Mahoney and Adam Stoll; and $190,653 to a
half-dozen campaign aides who are or have been on his payroll for
years.
</P>
<P>
   Other money has been used to hire prominent Republican
consultants who could help Pataki in a future run for national
office. For instance, Benjamin L. Ginsberg, an elections specialist
at the Washington law firm of Patton Boggs, whose clients include
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, billed $7,264 in legal fees as
recently as March. Stephen Moore, an economist with the Cato
Institute in Washington, received $27,500 for fine-tuning Pataki's
fiscal proposals, while Peggy Noonan, a speechwriter for Presidents
George Bush and Ronald Reagan, was paid $10,000 to polish his
words.
</P>
<P>
   The money figures are the latest the committees had available.
In the case of the Virginia PAC, they cover all of calendar 1999;
the federal PACs figures cover the period from January 1999 to
March 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pataki has not revealed his political plans, it is
clear that he commands substantial resources that could be
mobilized on short notice. In the last week, politicians and
lobbyists have speculated that Pataki may do just that to run for
the Senate against Hillary Rodham Clinton if the probable
Republican candidate, Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani, is forced to drop
out because of his prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, the most successful political fund-raiser in the state's
history, has brought in a total of more than $3.2 million in
contributions since January 1999, including $2.4 million through
his main campaign fund, Friends of Pataki, which is based in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   He has already spent more than two-thirds of that money _ mainly
on political consultants, salaries for his full-time campaign staff
members, travel and fund-raising expenses _ even though he does not
face re-election until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a complete change in culture,'' said Assemblyman Richard
L. Brodsky, a Democrat from Westchester County who has criticized
Pataki and Republican leaders for their aggressive fund-raising
practices. ``There is no election cycle anymore; it's flat-out
fund-raising from the inauguration to the next election.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenia Mucha, chief political adviser to Pataki, said money from
all three committees had enabled the governor to travel around the
country and build support for the party. ``The governor feels very
strongly about promoting the Republican agenda of smaller, more
effective and efficient government, lower taxes, individual freedom
and other issues that are part of it,'' she said. ``We have and
will continue to use these PAC's to disseminate and promote that
message.''
</P>
<P>
   Many lobbyists and other regular contributors complain that they
are paying heavily for Pataki's growing political activities. They
say privately that Pataki's campaign aides have aggressively
encouraged them to send donations to the Virginia or federal PAC's
as a way to skirt New York's contribution limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they call and ask us to make out two or three checks
instead of one,'' said a lobbyist who had given several thousand
dollars to Pataki's committees but spoke on condition of anonymity
because the issue had become so sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   Under New York election law, a corporation's contributions to
all candidates and committees is limited to $5,000 a year. The law
also limits an individual's donation to a state official's
statewide general election campaign to $30,700 over the four years
of the official's term. But several corporations and individual
donors would have exceeded those limits if their donations to all
the committees were tallied up.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic, one of the state's largest employers, contributed
$50,000 to the Virginia committee _ 10 times the corporate limit in
New York _ in addition to $50,500 in largely unregulated soft money
to the Republican Party's housekeeping committee. Although Pataki's
PAC is separate from the Republican committees, they often transfer
money back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   A real estate developer, Peter S. Kalikow, contributed $25,000
to the Virginia PAC and $12,500 to Friends of Pataki, a total of
$37,500, which is more than the state's limit for individual
donors. He also directed $12,500 to the Republican state committee,
and his company, H.J. Kalikow, gave $5,000 to the state committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia PAC collected $291,400, or more than half its total
contributions, from New York businesses, residents and other
political committees. The federal PAC, which is barred from
accepting corporate donations and limits individuals to $5,000,
still raised $356,073 including $138,375 from New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   Blair Horner, legislative director for the New York Public
Interest Research Group, said Pataki's multiple committees had made
a sham of the state's campaign finance laws. ``It essentially means
there are no campaign contribution limits for governor,'' he said.
``Those who are seeking to curry favor can give as much as they
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Mucha rejected such criticism. ``This gives us the ability under
the law _ which, the last time I looked, both parties were doing _
to go out to other states and other arenas and talk about the
governor's successful record in New York and the principles of the
Republican Party,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, Pataki's out-of-state committees have helped
finance Republican aspirations in other parts of the country. The
Virginia PAC contributed $28,000 to 12 Republican candidates
running for the State Legislature in New Jersey, and $28,100 to 8
Republican candidates in Virginia. The federal PAC contributed
$11,333 to 11 Republicans from Vermont to Arizona who are running
for the federal office.
</P>
<P>
   But campaign records show that most of the money has been used
to further Pataki's own political interests. There was little real
difference in how the money was spent from the three committees _
indeed, the same political consultants drew regular payments from
each one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
