<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ENID NEMY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   After visiting her mother, Grace Burney got into an elevator
with her husband and children and realized that the man facing her
looked familiar. He was dressed in a T-shirt and shorts, carried a
bicycle helmet and was standing between an older couple _ his
parents, she figured. Finally, her staring became obvious. The
father smiled at her and pointed at his son. ``You recognize him?''
he asked. But Burney still could not place the face.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to high school together,'' the younger man joked. Not
possible, she thought, too big an age difference. The man kept
bantering. ``Where do you live?'' he asked. Burney told him, and
asked where he lived. His reply did nothing to help her. She still
could not place him. As they were leaving the elevator, he finally
assuaged her curiosity. ``I'm your senator,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Charles Schumer, who had bicycled from Brooklyn to Queens
and had also been visiting his parents. They were seeing him off.
</P>
<P>
   Shelley Miller and Janet Capron were at the Quad Cinema in
Manhattan. As the two remaining films were about to begin, the
usher in charge announced the order of admission: ```Beautiful
People,' line for `Beautiful People' only.'' The crowd laughed and
the usher lifted the velvet rope.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement that followed delighted the remaining
moviegoers. ``Next _ `Trash,''' the usher declared.
</P>
<P>
   The two women bowed proudly before entering the appropriate
theater.
</P>
<P>
   During a visit with his sister and her family, Ashton Spann
offered a $10 bill to one of his grandnieces who was in her early
teens. She was reluctant to accept it and protested, albeit
somewhat mildly, ``Oh, you don't have to do that, Uncle Ashton.''
</P>
<P>
   Spann insisted. He put the bill in her hand. ``Now, now, that's
what uncles are for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   She gave him a hug and whispered in his ear, ``Gee, Uncle
Ashton, you certainly know your job description.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because I have written two books on Eleanor Roosevelt, a
friend gave me a book called ``The Eleanor Roosevelt Girls'' by
Bonnie Bluh, as a birthday gift. It made me eager to read Bluh's
other works, and one weekend a friend and I went into a bookstore
in Greenwich Village. The saleswoman said that they had no other
books by that author and that a search of Books in Print found
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``How odd,'' I said. ``Several other titles are listed in the
author's new book as well as three plays. I'd love to meet Bonnie
Bluh _ we both seem to love Mrs. Roosevelt.'' Then I asked if by
chance, she knew Bluh. ``I'm afraid not,'' the saleswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   A tall young man nearby spoke up. ``I know Bonnie Bluh,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really?'' I exclaimed. ``That's great. Do you know her well?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, yes, I guess so,'' he replied. ``I am her son.''
</P>
<P>
   We all broke out laughing. I handed him my card and said I would
love to hear from his mother. A few weeks later, my phone rang. It
was Bonnie Bluh and we arranged to meet.
</P>
<P>
   _ STELLA K. HERSHAN
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   Buttons! Buttons! Our lives are full of buttons. We push them
from our first waking moment until day's end. Pushing buttons to
start the day _ to illuminate the dark, start coffee, ignite a
stove, use a hair dryer, curling iron, radio, CD player, washer,
dryer, cross a street, use a computer, calculator, cell phone,
telephone, elevator, snack machine.
</P>
<P>
   WHOOSH! Think of a life button-free. There would be no life at
all, because I'm sure it's buttons that light up the sun and click
on the moon and stars. Thoughts bring out dimples and smiles or
tears and sobs from built-in buttons that are triggered by
happiness or sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   And then at night we push a button to close out the world and
activate the button of dreams. There are a million buttons in our
lives. We live in a button box.
</P>
<P>
   _ ELEANOR NYSTROM
</P>
<P>
   The company they worked for was bought out, and during a
farewell lunch Philip L. Rolston and his colleagues were recalling
memorable moments in their years with the firm. They pinpointed one
of the highlights as a speech to the staff given by their
president, who had just been hired from France.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand you have heard many rumors in the vineyard,'' the
president began. The staff was at a loss: How did vineyards get
into the act? Sensing their bewilderment, the president turned to
an aide. ``How does that expression go?'' he asked. The aide put
him right _ a matter of one word. ``The grapevine,'' the aide said.
``The phrase should go, `I understand you've heard many rumors on
the grapevine.'''
</P>
<P>
   I'LL TAKE MANHATTAN
</P>
<P>
   I dreamed about retiring
</P>
<P>
   and venturing out west;
</P>
<P>
   I'd trade the city's frantic pace
</P>
<P>
   for open space and rest.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually it dawned on me _
</P>
<P>
   to move would prove sheer folly,
</P>
<P>
   For life's not worth a whit without
</P>
<P>
   A shmeer on my bialy.
</P>
<P>
   _ JANE FEIRMAN
</P>
<P>
   HEADLINES
</P>
<P>
   I've developed a topsy-turvy frown!
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because every goshdarned clown
</P>
<P>
   who has a newsstand in our town
</P>
<P>
   places the headlines upside down!
</P>
<P>
   _ VINNI MARIE D'AMBROSIO
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   My grandchildren visited me recently and as a treat, I took them
to FAO Schwarz, the ultimate toy store. I told them they could
wander through the store and play with the samples and then each of
them could make a choice of one toy. We were followed into the
store by another grandmother and her grandson. I realized she was
more creative than I when I overheard her tell the boy that this
store was like a museum _ you were allowed to touch but there was
nothing to buy.
</P>
<P>
   _ SHIRLEY JANOWITZ
</P>
</TEXT>
