<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-O'CONNOR-EGAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGAN, A BISHOP IN CONNECTICUT, SEEN AS O'CONNOR SUCCESSOR
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. _ Monsignor Stanley B. Rousseau knew something
was up when he looked through the confessional and saw a news
photographer sitting on the other side, waiting to ask permission
to take pictures from his church roof.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, all eyes are on St. Patrick's Cathedral, where
Cardinal John J. O'Connor will be buried Monday after 16 years as
the outspoken shepherd of the country's most visible Roman Catholic
flock.
</P>
<P>
   But here in southern Connecticut, attention is focused on Bishop
Edward M. Egan, who is widely expected to be tapped by Pope John
Paul II to succeed O'Connor as archbishop of New York.
</P>
<P>
   As always with the secretive church, those who really know
aren't talking, and the Vatican isn't expected to announce its
choice for the new archbishop of New York until Tuesday at the
earliest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The announcement is the prerogative of the Holy Father, and as
far as I know he has not made any announcement,'' Boston's Cardinal
Bernard F. Law said before heading to New York to attend a memorial
Mass Sunday &UR;  &LR; night and to deliver the homily at O'Connor's funeral.
``I think during these days, the focus very appropriately is on
Cardinal O'Connor and his legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   But the consensus among American church officials is that Egan
is the man; several other bishops have said they have received
notice that they will not be going to New York, and some news
reports have had Egan asking his top aides in Connecticut to submit
their resignations to make room for his successor's aides.
</P>
<P>
   Egan, a 68-year-old native of Chicago, seems to have the perfect
resume for the New York post. As a canon lawyer, he spent two
decades at the Vatican advising popes Paul VI and John Paul II, and
he spent two years as an auxiliary bishop overseeing Catholic
schools in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Like O'Connor, who came to New York from Scranton, Penn., and
the bulk of Egan's experience is in a relatively small and obscure
see, here in southern Connecticut. And, also like O'Connor, Egan
shares the doctrinaire ideology of John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   ``He takes the pope's line and is very much into the church's
teaching,'' said Gene Doris, the athletics director at Fairfield
University, a Jesuit school in the Bridgeport diocese. ``He is not
one of those American bishops who is more understanding of the
other side.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Doris said, Egan was a strong supporter of a
measure adopted last year by US bishops to require Catholic
theologians to obtain approval from their local bishop to teach at
a Catholic school. And, Doris said, Egan has opposed a variety of
speakers at Catholic colleges who have held views contrary to
church teachings on social issues such as abortion and
homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   The diocese of Bridgeport, which includes 360,000 Catholics in
Fairfield County, is extraordinarily economically diverse. It
includes a city that has been one of the most troubled, Bridgeport,
as well as a string of wealthy New York suburbs, including
Greenwich, that are referred to as the Gold Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Egan arrived in 1988 to take over a diocese in debt, and turned
around church finances with a fund-raising zeal that has continued
unabated. He has exhorted the diocese's many rich Catholics to
donate more money, and has raised millions to refurbish church
facilities and to aid the poor and the diocese's many immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   But Egan is best known for his successful efforts to save the
diocese's school system, which was suffering from declining
enrollment and weak finances when he arrived. In a move that
overturned one of the fundamental organizing principles of the
Roman Catholic Church, Egan abolished parish schools, creating
instead a Catholic school system organized into regions in which
the regional schools were financially supported by all parishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``His proposal was not well-received, but, in hindsight, it
saved Catholic education in our diocese,'' said the Rev. Lawrence
J. Carroll of St. Joseph's Church in Brookfield. ``We're now
thriving and putting on additions to schools due to his
foresight.''
</P>
<P>
   Egan also started a seminary program here (the only one in the
diocese had closed years earlier). It is so well-regarded that the
admissions dean at Stanford University chose that school when he
decided to become a priest.
</P>
<P>
   ``His area of priority definitely has been Catholic education,''
said James D. Fitzpatrick, assistant vice president of Fairfield
University. ``He realized there was a challenge, he took a lot of
heat, and it's strengthened the schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other Catholic bishops, Egan has had to deal with the
repercussions of sexual abuse by Catholic clergy, and he has been
faulted by one lawyer, Cindy Robinson of Bridgeport, for showing
little sympathy to victims. Robinson represents 21 people who say
they were abused by priests of the Bridgeport diocese.
</P>
<P>
   But he has maintained good relations with priests and
parishoners here, judging from interviews Sunday around the
diocese. Despite the stereotype of canon lawyers as being academic
and aloof, Egan is said to have a warm personality, and his
presence at the pulpit, with his large frame and strong voice,
commmands attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very sad to see him go,'' said Martina E. Hall, 40, of
Bridgeport, who said she was disappointed, but not surprised, that
Egan seemed to be headed to New York, because Egan's close ties to
the pope were well known. ``He is a really friendly, personable
person, and whenever you meet him, he gives you one-on-one
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall was one of several Nigerian immigrants praying Sunday at
St. Augustine's Cathedral in Bridgeport, the seat of the diocese,
which boasts immigrants from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``His preaching has given me my life,'' said Helen Eneh, 38, of
Bridgeport, a student at Sacred Heart University, one of three
Catholic colleges in the diocese. ``I really love him as a bishop,
and wish he could stay.''
</P>
<P>
   The priest at the cathedral, Rousseau, said Egan is not as
colorful as O'Connor _ Egan has a less playful, more restrained
demeanor _ but that he should do well as pastor of New York's 2.4
million Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very outgoing and affable _ he's an extrovert,'' Rousseau
said. ``O'Connor was a character. Bishop Egan will establish his
own style.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, 80, died Wednesday of brain cancer. According to the
Associated Press, dignitaries expected to attend the funeral
include President Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton;
Vice President Al Gore; former President George Bush and his son,
Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush; UN Secretary
General Kofi Annan; Secretary of State Madeleine Albright; and more
than 100 bishops, archbishops, and cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Governor George Pataki and Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani, along with
two of O'Connor's closest associates, former Mayor Edward I. Koch
and Wall Street investment banker Ted Forstmann, are also expected.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor will be interred in the crypt beneath the cathedral's
altar, where all the previous archbishops of New York are buried.
</P>
<P>
   Globe correspondent Thomas Grillo contributed to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
