r a BC-QUEPASA-AZR &LR;      05-07 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUEPASA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUEPASA.COM REACHING OUT
 FOR MORE LATINOS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 BY DANIEL GONZALEZ 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - Arturo Jimenez is one of a growing number of
Hispanics defying the notion that they don't go online.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use it frequently for news, enter tainment; for what's ever
going on in the Latin world,'' said Jimenez, 31, an account
executive at Radio Unica, a Spanish-language talk-radio station in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 U.S. Department of Com merce study found that less than
13 percent of Latino households had Internet access, compared with
30 percent for Anglos.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past two years, the gap has narrowed as increasing
numbers of Latinos rush to get online, accord ing to Ekaterina
Walsh, an analyst at Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said 28 percent of the nation's 32 million Latinos are
online at home. The number jumps to 47 percent when access at work,
school or library is included, compared with 43 percent for Anglos,
Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hispanics are actually at the fore front right along with
Asians,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That effort is being aided by Quepa sa.com, a Phoenix online
firm that is distributing 2 million computer disks to attract more
Latinos, especially young, upwardly mobile ones like Jimenez, to
its bilingual Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The site, a sort of Latino version of America Online, offers an
array of news and information in English and Spanish as well as
chat rooms, links and a search engine to help guide viewers around
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Like a lot of start-up companies, especially those on the
Internet, Quepasa.com lost money in its first year of operation:
$28 million last year. Still, the firm raised $48 million in its
initial public stock offering, and the number of registered Quepa
sa.com users increased 108 percent in the last quarter of 1999 to
more than 210,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Trujillo, Quepasa .com's chief operating officer, said that
while the decision to offer free Internet access is primarily
market driven _ more viewers means more advertisers _ the company
also wants to help close the information-technology gap between
Latinos and Anglos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is the only venue that establishes the
opportunity for an equilibrium for our community to be competitive,
productive citizens,'' Trujillo said.
</P>
<P>
   You do not have to be Hispanic to take advantage of
Quepasa.com's free Internet access. It's available to anyone and
can be downloaded from the company Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the giveaway is primarily tar geted at Latinos. Most of
the 2 mil lion computer disks distributed by Quepasa.com were
mailed to Latino households with a high probability of owning a
computer, Trujillo said.
</P>
<P>
   Other disks are distributed at com munity events such as last
month's Hispanic Business Expo at the Phoe nix Civic Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Simply offering free Net access won't solve the underlying
issues between the information technology have and have nots, said
Andy Carvin of the Benton Foundation in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if everyone has Internet ac cess tomorrow,'' Carvin said,
``it really won't make that much of a difference if they lack the
literacy skills to take advantage of the technology and the
information, and if they don't have access to content that is
relevant to their own lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Web sites like Quepasa.com that cater specifically to the Latino
com munity also face the challenge of providing content that is
relevant to a broad range of interests and backgrounds, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a great deal of difference between a third-generation
Cuban-American family in Miami and a migrant worker family from
Guate mala in the Pacific Northwest,'' Carvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Cavanagh, who studied In ternet access for a New York
busi ness research group, The Conference Board, said Quepasa's
offer of free Internet access may be viewed as a ``welcoming
gesture'' by Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latinos are coming online in large numbers,'' Cavanagh said.
``If Que pasa can convince the Latino com munity that they care
about the community, they could do very well with that market. They
could have a chance to corner that market before anyone else can. I
think its a very shrewd marketing move.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
