r l BC-TV-GOODY-LOV-AZR &LR;      05-07 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-LOV-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD TIME TO HUG YOUR TV _ REALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You hear it so often when you're a television critic that it's
all you can do to keep from strangling somebody:
</P>
<P>
   `TV? Oh, there's nothing good on TV anymore.`
</P>
<P>
   People spout this knee-jerk nonsense with the smug confidence
that the good old days of ``Hello Larry'' were some sort of
cultural high-water mark. Which is fine - we always remember the
past as being better than it really was (watch any ``Gilligan's
Island'' rerun for proof).
</P>
<P>
   No, the thing that irritates me to the point of implosion is,
simply, this:
</P>
<P>
   They're wrong.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of things to love about television, right now,
right in the middle of this supposed TV draught. Five of them
follow:
</P>
<P>
   _ DYSFUNCTIONAL FAMILIES. At first blush, it seems as if one of
the reasons a great show like ``The Sopranos'' or ``The Simpsons''
captivates us is that it allows us to feel a little superior -
normal, if you will, happy that we don't have to balance a midlife
crisis with a career in the Mafia, or a job as an inspector at a
nuclear plant with an insatiable thirst for Duff beer.
</P>
<P>
   On closer inspection, that turns out not to be entirely true.
Certainly the extremes don't apply to most families, most families
never having had to deal with a dad who gunned someone down or
invented his own religion (approved by God, no less). But at their
hearts, parents in shows like ``The Sopranos'' and ``The Simpsons''
(let's toss in ``Malcolm in the Middle,'' as well) struggle to keep
their families together, no matter how unorthodox their methods.
That struggle is what really makes them worth watching - and, one
hopes, identifiable.
</P>
<P>
   _ AARON SORKIN. This time last year I might have said David
Kelley. Or maybe Tom Fontana. The point is, there are some great
writers working in TV right now, and television is, if anything, a
writer's medium.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley has gotten too cutesy, if not downright dumb, with ``Ally
McBeal,'' but ``The Practice'' is still riveting at times.
Fontana's middle name could be ``Gritty'' for ``Oz'' alone; toss in
the canceled ``The Beat'' (and let's not forget the late, great
``Homicide: Life In the Street'') and you've got a guy in touch
with the seamier side of life. In, you know, a good way. But ``The
West Wing's'' glistening gab and ``Sports Night's'' rapid-fire rap
lands Sorkin at the top of the writing heap. You could enjoy these
two shows almost as much without a picture. And that's just not
supposed to happen.
</P>
<P>
   HBO. Yes, it's cable, but there's no better network going. Great
as ``The Sopranos'' is, it's not the only think HBO has going for
it. We've mentioned ``Oz.'' Then there's ``The Corner,'' an
excellent look at the ugly life of a drug-infested Baltimore
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   But don't get the idea rugged, violent drama is all you'll see
here. In the past year HBO has also shown a great biography of
Howard Cosell; ``American Hollow,'' a documentary about a
poor-but-proud family in Appalachia - even a fantastic kids' show,
an animated version of the classic book ``Goodnight Moon.''But
perhaps HBO's neatest trick is what it manages with ``Real Sports
With Bryant Gumbel'' - make Bryant seem likeable. (CBS' ``The Early
Show'' hasn't figured out how.)
</P>
<P>
   Oh, they show movies, too.
</P>
<P>
   _ SESAME STREET. OK, everyone knows it's been a great children's
show for years. But it took having a daughter of my own to make me
realize how many other good children's programs are out there.
``Blues Clues,'' ``Dragon Tales,'' ``Between the Lions,''
``Zoboomafoo'' _ you can name enough quality kids' programming on
one hand to make a pretty good argument for TV as baby-sitter. Not
that any right-thinking person would do so, mind you. Sure keeps
her attention, though.
</P>
<P>
   _TECHNOLOGICAL ADVANCES. Many people argue that there is far too
much sex and violence on TV for kids. And it's true - you can't
reasonably argue the point. What you can do, however, is take
advantage of a high-tech marvel that allows parents to prevent
their children from seeing things on television they shouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   It's called an off button. Even with so many things to love
about TV, sometimes it's the best of all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-00 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
