<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- May 7, 2000 -- NY-SURFERS-3 -- Although New
York has not been the breeding ground for champion surfers, for
Rockaway Beach locals, the wait for good waves is just as important
and a year-round pastime. (Vincent Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) (NYT4) NEW YORK -- May 7, 2000 -- NY-SURFERS-2 -- While
Rockaway Beach in New York isn't like Southern California, where
surf is almost guaranteed and can persist for weeks, New York City
surfers still take advantage of the waves in the Atlantic. Surfers
along the boardwalk at Rockaway Beach in the early morning hours.
(Vincent Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- May 7, 2000 -- NY-CARDINAL-TRIBUTE-2 --
Bishop Edward M. Egan of the Diocese of Bridgeport, Conn., left
center , who is said to be the most likely successor to Cardinal
John O'Connor, attending a second Mass at St. Patrick's Cathedral,
Sunday, which was said by Cardinal Bernard Law of Boston, a close
friend of Cardinal O'Connor. From the pulpit and the pew, those who
knew Cardinal O'Connor both closely and fleetingly offered more
intimate, personal remembrances of a man who they said retained a
personal touch despite his lofty status as the archbishop of New
York. (Michelle V. Agins/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- May 7, 2000 -- NY-CARDINAL-TRIBUTE -- From
the pulpit and the pew, those who knew Cardinal John O'Connor both
closely and fleetingly Sunday offered more intimate, personal
remembrances of a man who they said retained a personal touch
despite his lofty status as the archbishop of New York. Donald
Dumler, the organist at St. Patrick's Cathedral during the tributes
which came in two public Masses that were followed by an evening
vigil. (Chester Higgins Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- May 7, 2000 -- NY-CARDINAL-MOURNERS --
Cardinal John O'Connor is to be honored Monday in a majestic and
intricately planned Roman Catholic funeral Mass that will celebrate
his anticipated ascension into heaven and eternal life with God. An
estimated 3,500 people, including President Clinton, city and state
leaders and cardinals and archbishops in colorful vestments, are to
gather under the soaring spires of St. Patrick's Cathedral at the
Mass for the cardinal, the eighth man to lead the Roman Catholic
Archdiocese of New York. One of thousands of mourners who have paid
their final respects to Cardinal O'Connor at St. Patrick's
Cathedral, Sunday. (Michelle V. Agins/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. -- May 7, 2000 -- HOUK-CHARITIES
-- J.T. Houk says he does not know why he and his charity, the
National Heritage Foundation, have attracted so much attention and
criticism. Last year, Congress and the IRS put a stop to a
charitable giving strategy promoted aggressively by Houk that
critics said benefited donors more than recipients. Now Houk is
facing a challenge to what he claims is the cornerstone of his
brand of philanthropy: finding ways to have donors and volunteers
pay themselves for their charitable deeds. (Cindy Karp/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- May 7, 2000 -- SCI-PREEMIES-3 -- It has been
more than 20 years since doctors began saving extremely premature
infants, and about a decade since advances in neonatology vastly
improved the survival of babies of very low birth weight. Today,
however, many parents of children who were born prematurely are
discovering firsthand how difficult their lives and their affected
child's life can be, as scientists are begin to document the first
large group of premature babies growing up. Much of the new
research is showing that academic and behavioral problems often
surface in the school years. The Neonatal Intensive Care Unit at
Montefiore Medical Center in New York. (Susan B. Markisz/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- May 7, 2000 -- SHALIKASHVILI-PROFILE --
Gen. John M. Shalikashvili, former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff. Shalikashvili, a man with an intimate knowledge of war,
there is a clear logic to his new assignment to persuade the Senate
to reconsider a treaty ending underground nuclear tests. ``War has
never been something theoretical for me or my family,'' says
Shalikashvili. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) LOS ANGELES -- May 7, 2000 -- CALIF-BOWLING-ALLEY-2 --
Bowlers celebrate one of the last matches at the Holiday Bowl in
Los Angeles which was closed on Saturday, May 6. The Bowl, built in
1958 by a group of Japanese-American businessmen, was so important
to so many of it's regular ethnically diverse customers that in
1992, as scores of other businesses and buildings were being burned
to the ground during the riots after the acquittal of LAPD police
in the beating of black motorist, Rodney King, a group of regulars
stood outside and told looters that the Bowl was ``our place.''
(Jill Connelly/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) LOS ANGELES -- May 7, 2000 -- CALIF-BOWLING-ALLEY-1 --
After 42 years of strikes, spares and brotherhood, the Holiday Bowl
in Los Angeles was closed on Saturday, May 6. The Bowl was so
important to so many of it's regular ethnically diverse customers
that in 1992, as scores of other businesses and buildings were
being burned to the ground during the riots after the acquittal of
LAPD police in the beating of black motorist, Rodney King, a group
of regulars stood outside and told looters that the Bowl was ``our
place.'' Ed Nakamoto, who had been coming to the Holiday Bowl for
36 years, first as an employee, then as a customer, hugs Chaquita
Miller, a 26 year patron on the bowling alley's last night open.
(Jill Connelly/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- May 7, 2000 -- TODD-MUSIC-REVIEW -- Patti
LuPone and George Hearn in the concert version of Stephen
Sondheim's1979 ``Sweeny Todd'' at Avery Fisher Hall in New York.
The New York Choral Artists were prodded admirably by their guest
conductor, Grant Gershon, to march, writhe and generally turn
themselves into actors. It turns out that they also sang very well.
(Sara Kruwlwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- May 7, 2000 -- SCI-PREEMIES-2 -- Dominic
Reyes, 5, who was born prematurely weighing a little more than a
pound, has severe cerebral palsy, with his mother, Jacqueline, at
the Albert Einstein College of Medicine in the Bronx. He still
wears diapers and cannot sit by himself. Parents of disabled
children, particularly the poor, often miss out on services for
their children. For children like Dominic, the future often depends
``on how good an advocate the parent is,'' says Dr. Herbert J.
Cohen, of the Children's Evaluation and Rehabilitation Center at
the Albert Einstein College of Medicine. (Susan B. Markisz/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) RALEIGH, N.C. -- May 7, 2000 -- SCI-PREEMIES-1 -- Hope
Tyndall helps Alex Martin, 11, mount a horse at a therapeutic
riding program for people with disabilities in Raleigh, N.C. It has
been 11 years since Alex Martin was born premature at 1-pound
2-ounces of miniature bones and bright red skin. ``Life,'' his
mother says, ``is overwhelming for him.'' It is also overwhelming,
at times, for his parents, who are discovering firsthand what
scientists are beginning to document about babies born as tiny as
Alex: Their lives often grow more complicated over time. (Karen
Tam/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- May 7, 2000 -- MEMS-INTERNET-2 -- MEMS,
microelectromechanical systems, left, are used in tiny valves,
levers, motors and microphones. They consist of arrays of miniscule
mirrors like the one at the right. These rerout signals from one
set of fiber optic lines to another. Millions of MEMS have already
made their way into products like automotive air bags, ink-jet
printers and disposable blood pressure analyzers.
Telecommunications comapnies are investing heavily in MEMS because
they feel the technology will some day improve Internet efficiency.
(The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MORRISVILLE, N.C. -- May 7, 2000 -- MEMS-INTERNET-1 --
MEMS, microelectromechanical systems, are used in tiny valves,
levers, motors and microphones which operate switches with
lightwaves. Millions of MEMS have already made their way into
products like automotive air bags, ink-jet printers and disposable
blood pressure analyzers. Telecommunications comapnies are
investing heavily in MEMS because they feel the technology will
some day improve Internet efficiency. Robert L. Bratter, chief
executive of Chronos Integrated Microsystems, in a Chronos plant in
Morrisville N.C., where MEMS are made. (Karen Tam/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- May 7, 2000 -- SHEAR-MAEWEST-2 -- Claudia
Shear's new play, ``Dirty Blonde,'' about love, cross-dressing and
Mae West, has just opened on Broadway. Mae West may have been the
last woman before Shear to write her own Broadway play (not a
one-woman show) and star in it: ``Sex'' in 1927. Shear onstage in
``Dirty Blonde'' at the Helen Hayes Theater. Shear as the legendary
Mae West. (Sara Kruwlwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- May 7, 2000 -- NY-SUMMER-WEATHER-2 --
Patrick Pizzini, 2, takes advantage of the shade and a free cone of
ice cream, on 137th street and Amsterdam Avenue in uptown
Manhattan, from Vincent Garcia an ice cream truck driver who has
been serving the neighborhood for more than 27 years. As warmer
temperatures finally hit New York, many people quickly sought
relief from the first signs of summer. (Vincent Laforet/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- May 7, 2000 -- NY-SUMMER-WEATHER-1 --
Children play near an open fire hydrant on Sunday giving passing
cars and pedestrians a free wash in uptown Manhattan. As warmer
temperatures finally hit New York, many people quickly sought
relief from the first signs of summer. (Vincent Laforet/The New
York Times)
