the opening round by New York each of the past two years, will try
for a 2-0 lead in the best-of-seven matchup Tuesday night in Miami.
(Barton Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MIAMI -- May 7, 2000 -- BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-3 -- The Miami
Heat's P.J. Brown taking down a rebound against the New York Knicks
as Miami defeated New York 87-83, Sunday. After a week of hype
leading to the series, the bitter rivals started with a thriller.
The score changed hands 14 times and was tied 11 times. (Barton
Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) MIAMI -- May 7, 2000 -- BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-2 -- The Miami
Heat's Dan Majerle defending against the New York Knicks Allan
Houston as the Heat went on to defeat the Knicks 87-83, Sunday in
Miami. The Heat defense played the Knicks tight and tough
throughout Game 1 and New York didn't make a basket in the final
5:34 of the game. The Heat, eliminated in the opening round by New
York each of the past two years, will try for a 2-0 lead in the
best-of-seven matchup Tuesday night in Miami. (Barton Silverman/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) MIAMI -- May 7, 2000 -- BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-1 -- The Miami
Heat's Jamal Mashburn driving against the New York Knicks Latrell
Sprewell as the Heat went on to defeat New York 87-83, Sunday.
After a week of hype leading to the second-round series, the bitter
rivals started with a thriller. The score changed hands 14 times
and was tied 11 times, including at 79, 81 and 83. (Barton
Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- May 7, 2000 -- SHEAR-MAEWEST -- Claudia
Shear's new play, ``Dirty Blonde,'' about love, cross-dressing and
Mae West, has just opened on Broadway. Mae West may have been the
last woman before Shear to write her own Broadway play, not a
one-woman show, and star in it: ``Sex'' in 1927. Claudia Shear at
Mae West's mausoleum at the Cypress Hills Abbey cemetery in Queens,
N.Y., which is where a scene in ``Dirty Blonde'' is set. (Chester
Higgins/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- May 7, 2000 -- NY-SURFERS-1 -- Fervent city
surfers Carl Friedman, left, and Mark Valenta take the New York
City subway to Rockaway beach in the pre-dawn hours to surf in the
chilly Atlantic. If they're lucky, they may catch a wave. While
California's swells are often higher, the thrills are still the
same for many surfers. (Vincent Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- May 7, 2000 -- PATENTS-2 -- A new kind of top
made by Kurt Przybilla, a 35-year-old English teacher in New York,
who was making experimental models of geodesic domes when he came
up with the idea. To many people, Przybilla's tops might look like
molecular models, or perhaps those clusters of blown-glass grapes
in grandmother's fruit bowl. But when Przybilla looks at one of his
tops, he sees its inner geometric configuration. ``It doesn't have
a single stem like a traditional top, which spins on only one
axis,'' says Przybilla. ``It can spin on any of its spheres.''
(Vincent Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- May 7, 2000 -- PATENTS-1 -- Kurt Przybilla, a
35-year-old English teacher in New York, was making experimental
models of geodesic domes when he came up with a new kind of top. To
many people, Przybilla's tops might look like molecular models, or
perhaps those clusters of blown-glass grapes in grandmother's fruit
bowl. But when Przybilla looks at one of his tops, he sees its
inner geometric configuration. ``It doesn't have a single stem like
a traditional top, which spins on only one axis,'' says Przybilla.
``It can spin on any of its spheres.'' (Vincent Laforet/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) HOUSTON -- May 7, 2000 -- E-COMMERCE-COLUMN -- E-commerce
companies have turned to an old retailing standby, private-label
manufacturing, to give them higher profit margins and better
control of inventory. Items like dog food, cosmetics, diamonds,
toys and golf clubs, to name a few, now wear dot-com labels, and
more are joining every week. Courtney Merrick checks an order at
Ashford.com in Houston, a jewelry retailer, before shipping it to a
customer. (Phillippe Diederich/The New York Times)
</P>
