   (NYT14) MORRISVILLE, N.C. -- May 7, 2000 -- MEMS-INTERNET-1 --
MEMS, microelectromechanical systems, are used in tiny valves,
levers, motors and microphones which operate switches with
lightwaves. Millions of MEMS have already made their way into
products like automotive air bags, ink-jet printers and disposable
blood pressure analyzers. Telecommunications comapnies are
investing heavily in MEMS because they feel the technology will
some day improve Internet efficiency. Robert L. Bratter, chief
executive of Chronos Integrated Microsystems, in a Chronos plant in
Morrisville N.C., where MEMS are made. (Karen Tam/The New York
Times)
