<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-07 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8585 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-TORSO-MWOODY-AZR &LR;      05-07 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORSO-MWOODY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTIM'S WIFE HAD BOUGHT POWER SAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY CHRISTINA LEONARD AND BETH DEFALCO  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Scottsdale) - When investigators examined the smooth, straight
cuts left on a torso found in a trash bin in January, they thought
somebody must have used a powerful electrical saw to dismember the
man's body.
</P>
<P>
   So detectives searched Ira Pomerantz's bar, trying to find what
they initially figured was a meat-cutting instrument.
</P>
<P>
   Although they found nothing there, they did find evidence in his
wife's purse that she bought a reciprocating saw late last year,
according to a source close to the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Pape, a 47-year-old former Scottsdale beauty salon
owner, faces first-degree murder charges in her husband's death,
and the saw could be a key link in proving premediation, the source
said.
</P>
<P>
   She told police that she found 60-year-old Pomerantz shot to
death in their Scottsdale home and then dumped his headless,
armless, legless torso into a Mesa trash bin Jan. 27 because she
feared she would be blamed.
</P>
<P>
   Pape has refused to tell police how the body was dismembered,
and investigators have yet to find a saw, or Pomerantz's head and
limbs.
</P>
<P>
   Officials plan to test a reciprocating saw on a cadaver, or
perhaps directly on bones, hoping to produce markings that match
those left on Pomerantz's torso, said the source, who declined to
be identified.
</P>
<P>
   If they do, prosecutors may be able to show premeditation
because the evidence is said to show that Pape purchased the saw
from a Scottsdale hardware store weeks before Pomerantz's death.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have bought several types of blades designed to
cut different materials.
</P>
<P>
   Reciprocating saws are generally used in demolition work to cut
through pipes and other strong materials, said Chase Westerman, a
tool department manager at a Phoenix area hardware store.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can cut through any material with it,'' he said, adding
that the saws range from $100 to $250.
</P>
<P>
   The motor is typically 18 to 20 inches long and has a blade, up
to a foot long, that moves back and forth to shred material.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're awkward and are hard to control,'' Westerman said.
``If someone doesn't have a lot of muscles in their arms, or if
they've never done it before, it can be really hard to use. It can
kick back at you.
</P>
<P>
   ``A normal-sized person who just used for the first time
wouldn't be able to control if they didn't have a lot of strength
in arms,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, officials believe that because of the saw's strength,
Pape could have acted alone in cutting up Pomerantz's body, the
source said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pape is 5-foot-4 and weighs 105 pounds, friends say the
Frenchwoman exercised vigorously. She is being held in a Maricopa
County jail without bail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-00 2334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
