<HEADER>
A8589 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-SIDE-LADN     05-07 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOPPING SHAQ IS NO SMALL MATTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Excuse Shaquille O'Neal during the Lakers playoff
series against the Suns if his eyes have a way of growing as large
as his game. O'Neal has oceans of ability, but concealing his
eagerness is not one of his practiced arts.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what is an unstoppable 7-foot-1, 335 pounds of pure
basketball force supposed to think when he turns around and feels
like he's being guarded by the munchkins?
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital)Gimme the ball.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   And so they did Sunday, O'Neal overcoming a sluggish first
quarter to power the Lakers to a 105-77 victory over Phoenix in the
opener of their best-of-seven playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   One game down, one thing already obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' said Lakers coach Phil Jackson, ``Shaq looks real
dominant.''
</P>
<P>
   No one in the league has a good answer for O'Neal, but the Suns
- coached by his ex-Magic teammate Scott Skiles - elected to play
him straight up. Or as it's known in most NBA circles: basketball
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   After a physical series against the Sacramento Kings that
included frequent double-teaming, O'Neal must have thought he'd
just earned an invite to Club Med.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was he often opposed by a single defender, but for most
of the night, it was a center in miniature.
</P>
<P>
   With Luc Longley in early foul trouble and playing just 17
minutes, O'Neal most often had to power over ex-Laker Corie Blount
(a forward outweighed by about 100 pounds), Cliff Robinson (a
forward who weighs 20 pounds less than Blount) and Rodney Rogers (a
forward a half-foot shorter).
</P>
<P>
   The results were what might be termed predictable. O'Neal
finished with 37 points, 14 rebounds and four blocked shots - all
game-highs.
</P>
<P>
   This after a miserable first quarter that saw him shoot 1 for 7
with three rebounds and a block.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four minutes into the first quarter, I thought Shaq was
struggling to get up and down the court,'' Jackson said. ``The pace
was elevated, and we had to bring it down. I asked him how he was
doing out there, and gave him a little rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Seems it didn't hurt - he was 14 for 21 with 11 rebounds in the
29 minutes he played after the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I got too much rest last night,'' O'Neal said. ``I
haven't gone to bed before 11 in about eight years.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it didn't hurt his turnaround that he was being
guarded by all those little people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to play as physical as I can without getting in
foul trouble,'' Blount said. ``I mean, there's a way to stop him,
it's just not legal.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's biggest problem in this series could be to restrain his
eagerness when he turns and sees who's guarding him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a little bit antsy, but I have to be careful because I
know they're probably going to do some flopping,'' O'Neal said. ``I
just try to go straight up.''
</P>
<P>
   Skiles figures there's no way to stop O'Neal, so it's better to
contain him as best one can in single coverage, and try to stop
everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   For one game, it was left as a nice idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq is Shaq,'' Skiles said. ``I know him as well as any
player in the league. He's the MVP. It's up to us to do something
now to slow him down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
