r s BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX     05-07 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITCHCOCK SAVES LEHTINEN FOR AVS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD AND MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Stars winger Jere Lehtinen was again scratched from the
lineup last night because of his injured right ankle.
</P>
<P>
   It likely was the last time.
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said if there had been a Game 6,
Lehtinen would have played. Since the Stars dusted off the San Jose
Sharks, 4-1 in Game 5 last night, Lehtinen should be ready to play
in Game 1 of the Western Conference Finals against Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said Lehtinen wasn't held out because of
overconfidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do is eliminate any gray area of the
injury coming back on the table again,'' Hitchcock said. ``I guess
the best way to describe it is there is comfortable soreness and
uncomfortable soreness. Our view is if he plays a hockey game
today, could he get up and play another one in two days?
</P>
<P>
   ``And we're not able to say yes to that yet. But we're at the
verge right now where we could say yes in 24 hours or 36 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen again skated in the warmup before the game. He did so
in Game 4 as well, but said he was ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know, pretty much, my ankle,'' said Lehtinen, who has
battled the injury since Oct. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's another player added to our club and we need a lot of
things to go our way. I don't think we're fooling anybody about
that.''  &QL; 
A vote for teammates
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Jere Lehtinen missed 65 of the Stars' 82
regular-season games likely ensured that he wouldn't win his third
consecutive Selke Trophy this season.
</P>
<P>
   So who does Lehtinen think should win the award for the NHL's
best defensive player?
</P>
<P>
   He likes a group of guys named Guy Carbonneau, Mike Keane and
Mike Modano.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of them should be considered,'' Lehtinen said.
``All the injuries this season and still our system pretty much
worked, and those guys did a pretty good job there.''
</P>
<P>
   The finalists for the award are Detroit's Steve Yzerman, St.
Louis' Michal Handzus and San Jose's Mike Ricci.  &QL; 
Playing with pain
</P>
<P>
   Neither Guy Carbonneau nor Jamie Langenbrunner practiced
yesterday morning, but both played last night.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau rarely skates on game day, but he took a hit to the
back of his head at the end of Game 4. He had tests done on
Saturday but was cleared to play. Langenbrunner is still feeling
the effects of a hit he absorbed in Game 2. He missed Game 3 but
played in Games 4 and 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a practice-only player,'' Hitchcock said. ``I really
doubt that he'll practice \Rfor the rest of the postseason\S.''  &QL; 
Muller tries singing
</P>
<P>
   Stars forward Kirk Muller returned from San Jose on Saturday
afternoon like the rest of his teammates. He didn't get a nap like
most of his teammates did, though.
</P>
<P>
   His twin daughters were having a birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   So Muller spent his day with 20 9-year-olds doing karaoke.  &QL; 
Familiar faces
</P>
<P>
   When Stars winger Kirk Muller is elavated from the fourth line
to the third line with Mike Keane and Guy Carbonneau, it will be a
reunion of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Near the end of the games in Montreal, Carbo, Keane and I
would play in the last minutes so it's kind of a reunion,'' Muller
said.
</P>
<P>
   The trio all played for the Canadiens from 1991-94. Not that
Muller has ever been a regular on the checking lines _ he's
normally been an offensive forward _ but the adjustment isn't
drastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only difference is who you are actually playing against,''
Muller said. ``You try to be a little more defensive-minded and
maybe not take too many chances.''  &QL; 
Praising the Avalanche
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Stars had much time to watch the other Western
Conference semifinal, where Colorado disposed of Detroit in five
games, but they know the Avalanche are patiently waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you beat a good team in five, you're doing something
right,'' Muller said. ``They've got a really solid team. They are
playing well defensively, and they've got guys who can capitalize
when there are opportunities on offense.''  &QL; 
Tickets available
</P>
<P>
   Dates haven't been set for the Western Conference finals, but
the Stars will play Games 1 and 2 against the Colorado Avalanche at
Reunion Arena. There are 1,100 tickets available for each game.
Tickets can be purchased by calling 214-GO-STARS or at
www.tickets.com.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
