<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Pitcher Justin Thompson, still bothered by
some soreness in his left shoulder, is scheduled to undergo an MRI
today. Thompson was able to play catch in the outfield yesterday
without problem, but said he still feels ``something grab me'' when
he pitches off a mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in the dark about this as much as anybody,'' said
Thompson, who was examined by Dr. John Conway yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson underwent arthroscopic surgery last Aug. 27 to repair a
torn labrum in his shoulder. The Rangers had hoped he would be back
in their rotation by now, but his 30-day medical-rehabilitation
assignment was brought to a halt 10 days ago after three starts
because of the soreness.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers keep insisting this is a bump in the road. The MRI
will determine that.  &QL; 
Gold Club strikes again
</P>
<P>
   Rangers center fielder Ruben Mateo has been having problems with
the windows in the newly built Gold Club behind home plate. The
problem occurred again yesterday on Jason Giambi's eighth-inning
line drive that Mateo misplayed, allowing Terrance Long to score
Oakland's seventh run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's happened a couple of times,'' Mateo said. ``I saw the
ball, but then I lost it for two or three seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Mateo turned toward right field, but the ball went toward left
field and he never had a chance to catch it.  &QL; 
First-base meeting
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates met before yesterday's game with trainers
Danny Wheat and Ray Ramirez and first basemen Rafael Palmeiro and
David Segui to determined a course of action to deal with their
injuries. Palmeiro has a strained hamstring, and Segui has a
strained hip flexor.
</P>
<P>
   Both should be limited to designated hitter, but Segui was at
first base yesterday for the second consecutive game even though
he's having as much trouble running as Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   Oates wanted assurances from the trainers that having them both
continue to play won't get them hurt and won't keep them from
healing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we can't keep going like this all season,'' Oates
said. ``I left the meeting having been told, No. 1, they can't hurt
themselves any more and No. 2, they can get better. I'll just watch
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Segui went 1-for-3 yesterday to extend his hitting streak to ten
games. He also made a nice diving stop of Terrance Long's grounder
in the third inning.  &LR; subheds:Left-handed schizophrenia
</P>
<P>
   Rangers right-handed starters have been tougher on left-handed
hitters than their left-handed starters, one of the bizarre twists
early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing left-handed hitters are batting .179 against
right-hander Esteban Loaiza and .203 against right-hander Rick
Helling. But they are hitting .342 off left-hander Darren Oliver
and .353 off left-hander Kenny Rogers.  &QL; 
Rangers face Griffey-less M's
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers begin a three-game series against the Seattle
Mariners tonight. It will be the first time the Rangers have faced
the Mariners since they traded Ken Griffey Jr. to the Cincinnati
Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey played 11 years for the Mariners. In that time:
</P>
<P>
   He hit .315 against the Rangers with 30 home runs and 101 runs
batted in. It was his second-highest batting average against any
American League team, surpassed only by the .317 he hit against the
Toronto Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   He hit .382 at The Ballpark in Arlington, his highest at any
park in the major leagues. He has nine home runs at The Ballpark,
tied for the fourth-most by an opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were 61-77 against the Mariners.  &QL; 
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Palmeiro's home run yesterday was the 371st of his
career, moving him past Gil Hodges into 46th place all-time.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Mateo has an 11-game hitting streak, tied for the
third-longest by a Rangers rookie. George Wright hit in 15 in a row
in 1982, and Jerry Browne matched that in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have committed an error in six consecutive games.
nn
</P>
