<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-DEVILRAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX TEE OFF ON DEVIL RAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Last year, Jeff Fassero had a slugging Junior Griffey
on his side. This year, he has a dancing El Guapo. Who can predict
the things that will improve the quality of a man's life?
</P>
<P>
   Fassero, the Red Sox lefthander who won four games in Seattle
while spending most of the summer as Griffey's teammate, improved
his record to 4-1 Sunday at Fenway Park with a 9-7 win over the
Tampa Bay Devil Rays. He was abetted by three home runs and another
summons from the bullpen for Rich Garces, who has pitched in each
of Fassero's last four starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was a miserable year _ there was nothing good about
it,'' said Fassero, who lasted six full innings for the first time
this season before departing with an 8-3 lead. Carl Everett's
three-run home run in the fifth put the Devil Rays five runs in
arrears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if I pitched good, something went wrong,'' Fassero said.
``The whole year was miserable. It's something I lived with and
tried to forget about, all at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   With a wide lead, Fassero gave way to a wider body: Garces,
whose importance to the Sox is expanding at the same rate his
uniform appears to be shrinking, judging by the way the fabric is
stretching. The spotlight in the Sox bullpen is justifiably upon
Derek Lowe, who was called upon to claim the last five outs after
lefthander Rheal Cormier gave up two-run homers in the eighth to
Vinny Castilla and Bubba Trammell.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe, who sent designated villain Jose Canseco back to the bench
with his fourth consecutive strikeout after Canseco had doubled
home Tampa Bay's first two runs in the first, survived errors by
Jose Offerman in the eighth and Wilton Veras in the ninth to record
his seventh save while lowering his earned run average to 0.93,
best among American League relievers.
</P>
<P>
   But while Lowe has been nearly unhittable _ he has yet to allow
a run in nine innings over six appearances at Fenway _ the closer
was the one who suggested that the floodlights should be on Garces,
who has been a Longfellow-sized bridge between the Sox starters and
Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been loose this year,'' Lowe said of El Guapo, who also
hadn't allowed a run at Fenway in five appearances until he was
charged with one Sunday when he gave up a double to Greg Vaughn,
who scored on Castilla's home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's even put out a couple of dances for us this year in the
bullpen,'' Lowe said, claiming that Garces gets down to the sounds
of the music blaring over the PA system. ``He's a pretty good
dancer. You'd be amazed. He's got quick feet, he really does.''
</P>
<P>
   Those were cat's feet that Garces showed when he struck out
Canseco, the last batter he faced, with a curveball that made a
statue out of the Tampa Bay strongman.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd figure Pedro was pitching with the four strikeouts I had
today,'' Canseco said, alluding to Pedro Martinez's 17-K
masterpiece Saturday in a 1-0 Boston loss.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is a swizzle stick, of course, compared to Garces, but
the reliever, who plays a vital role on a staff on which Martinez
is the only starter certain to go more than five innings on any
given night, is beginning to feel some of the same love that
Martinez gets from the Fenway faithful.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in Boston have been very nice to me everywhere I go,''
said Garces, who has allowed just three hits and a run in 6 2/3
innings on the days Fassero has pitched, and in 11 appearances
overall has a 2.70 ERA. ``There are a lot of people out there
cheering for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the mall, people call, `Hey, Guapo, how's it going?' I'll
take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game was still for the taking until sore-legged Nomar
Garciaparra got off the bench after Jose Offerman's two-out double
in the eighth and rifled a pinch single off the elbow of reliever
Roberto Hernandez, the ball hit with such force that it caromed
over the head of third baseman Castilla, allowing Offerman to
score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it hit him,'' Garciaparra said. ``I was thinking Vinny
Castilla was going to catch it and I'm thinking, `Oh, great.' I was
concerned when I got to first base. You don't want to see anybody
hurt. I wasn't trying to hit him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez appeared as if he were in a daze as he left the
premises. Did he see Garciaparra's liner coming?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt it,'' said Hernandez, who planned to have X-rays
upon the team's arrival in New York Sunday &UR;  &LR; night. ``I hope it's
not broken. My first move was to get in the dugout as soon as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Offerman scored the last run for the Sox, who have scored 40 in
Fassero's four starts. With that kind of support, the 2-0 deficit
he faced in the first after an infield hit, his own throwing error,
and Canseco's double didn't figure to last.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we score early it makes it nice,'' said Fassero, who got
the lead back after Veras singled home a run in the second, Trot
Nixon homered with a man aboard in the third, and Troy O'Leary
homered two batters later. ``The guys came right back. (Pitching
coach) Joe Kerrigan told me, `A lot of bad stuff is happening, but
keep them close and we're going to score, and that's just what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's enough to make the 37-year-old Fassero click his
heels himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-00 2352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
