</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-GARCIAPARRA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOMAR HELPS OUT IN A PINCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ You can talk to him about the football he used to kick
between goalposts or the futbol he used to kick past goalies. You
can talk to him about popular music he finds interesting (he likes
a singer named Macy Gray). You even can joke with him, as some Red
Sox certainly did in Cleveland when _ before entering their hotel _
they looked to the valet stand and saw his image gracing the cover
of GQ.
</P>
<P>
   Pick a subject and Nomar Garciaparra probably won't be stumped.
But if you want to have a conversation that lasts more than five
seconds, don't mention baseball statistics. The game's most
versatile great player hates talking numbers, especially when they
apply to him. Maybe that's a good thing because, after looking at
those numbers, you'll find that there really isn't much to say
beyond, ``You the man, Nomie.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Carl Everett said Sunday when he passed the
shortstop in the clubhouse. He didn't say it because of the
staggering numbers, numbers that show Garciaparra hitting .400 this
season with runners in scoring position; .500 when there are two
outs and runners in scoring position; and more than .400 after the
seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   Everett said it because of Nomar The Pinch Hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra began his Fenway Park afternoon as a spectator,
resting a sore left hamstring. The Sox were thumping the Devil Rays
in the eighth inning, 8-3, and it didn't appear that Garciaparra
would be needed. But that was before Rheal Cormier turned Fenway
into a green-tinted Coors Field. The reliever gave up two home
runs, transforming an easy win to a shaky, 8-7 Sox lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, Garciaparra had begun stretching and taking
swings, just in case something happened. So he was ready in the
bottom of the eighth when Jimy Williams told him he'd be batting
for Darren Lewis. He approached the plate with two outs and a
runner (Jose Offerman) on second. It was the third pinch-hitting
situation of his career, and his second against pitcher Roberto
Hernandez. Last year, Hernandez struck him out to preserve a 5-4
Devil Rays win.
</P>
<P>
   But those are just numbers, and you know how he feels about
them, right?
</P>
<P>
   This is what Garciaparra was thinking when he stepped in against
Hernandez: ``Just trying to get a good pitch to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   This is what 32,336 fans (plus Everett) were thinking: You the
man, Nomie.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as he began his walk toward the box, Garciaparra heard
the cheers. He was getting a standing ovation. He noticed that
there seemed to be 30,000-plus in the park even then, with two gone
in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love playing here,'' he said when reminded of the ovation.
``The fans don't leave. They could have easily left when we had a
good lead, when it looked like we were in control of the game. They
stuck around . . . we appreciate it.''
</P>
<P>
   The first pitch Hernandez threw Garciaparra was a fastball. The
shortstop fouled it off to the right. On the next pitch, you would
have thought you were in Jacobs Field. Hernandez threw another
fastball inside to back Garciaparra off the plate. It was a good
pitch. It was a ball. But some fans booed, thinking it was a cheap
brushback. Garciaparra smiled about it later and said he didn't
have a problem with it.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't have a problem with the third pitch, either. He hit it
up the middle, where it ferociously ricocheted off the right elbow
of Hernandez. The ball wound up at third base, and by the time
Vinny Castilla got it, Offerman had crossed the plate. Manny
Alexander then pinch ran for the unlikely pinch hitter and, again,
there was an ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Everett jokingly offered to vacate his locker so more
media members could talk to Garciaparra. ``You all want me to
move?'' the outfielder said with a grin. And he said that without
knowledge of even more staggering numbers. Asked what he knew about
Garciaparra before coming here, Everett said, ``I knew he had 30
home runs as a rookie.'' He didn't realize that, last May,
Garciaparra hit 10 homers, drove in 33 runs, batted .355, and had
two grand slams in one game.
</P>
<P>
   But, remember, those are just numbers. What Everett and everyone
else wanted to talk about was production.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun to see a guy go up there with an ache and still get a
hit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before Garciaparra left the park, he asked about Hernandez. ``Is
he OK?'' he said. The pitcher had to leave the game after being
struck by the ball. He talked after the game and said he was all
right, although he was to have precautionary X-rays.
</P>
<P>
   As for Garciaparra's health, he was able to run and field _
pain-free _ during Sunday's pregame routine. Everyone agrees that
he needs to be in the lineup Monday against the White Sox. Of
course, there are agreements for different reasons. Garciaparra
needs to play because sitting irritates him. Numbers-lovers will
tell you that he needs to play because of his 1999 assault on
Chicago: .571, 3 homers, 12 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Again: Those are just numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra has batted leadoff in his career. He's been a No. 3
man. He's been a cleanup man. He's won a batting title. He's been a
productive pinch hitter. One day, someone will challenge him. They
will ask if he can be the next Babe Ruth and be great at all
aspects of the game. They will ask this man if he can pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Can he?
</P>
<P>
   He smiled and answered, only half-jokingly, ``Yeah, if called
upon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-00 2354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
