<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-KENTUCKYDERBY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK ON DRYSDALE OPTING FOR PREAKNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Neil Drysdale is nothing if not reserved, and
the trainer displayed his customary caution Sunday when he refused
to commit Fusaichi Pegasus, winner of Saturday's Kentucky Derby, to
the Preakness at Pimlico May 20, the second leg of the Triple
Crown.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is the little matter of the $5 million bonus
that goes to a Triple Crown winner to consider. So, cautious or
not, you can bet Drysdale and Fusaichi Pegasus will arrive in
Baltimore next Wednesday, barring a disaster. Fusaichi Pegasus will
stay at Churchill to train before being shipped to Pimlico.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was fine this morning,'' said Drysdale. ``Somebody dropped
something and he bounced. So, he was nice and bright this morning.
We have to see how he comes out of this race first before we go on
to the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're fragile animals, and sometimes something shows up in
the wash. So, literally, we'll just go one step at a time. We've
got to just see how he is the next few days. We've got to watch
him, and monitor him, and make sure he's training well. He's fine
this very minute in time, but all he's done is go for a walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus, the 2-1 ($6.60) choice, put on one of the more
impressive runs in the 126 years of the Derby, coming from 15th
place to score under a hand ride in the rapid time of 2:01 for the
1 1/4 miles. Ridden by Kent Desormeaux, he broke a 20-year jinx as
no favorite had won the Derby since Spectacular Bid in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   The Preakness is run over a track notorious for tight turns, and
Fusaichi Pegasus is a big horse. But why worry?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's pretty handy, and you can do what you want with
him,'' said the English-born Drysdale, 52. ``I mean, it was quite
obvious Sunday there was going to be a cracking pace. There was no
concern for him lagging along in the back. He's got natural speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very satisfying. This is a very talented horse, and he
looks like he's got a very bright future in front of him. It was
very rewarding to watch that talent come through. So, we'll keep
our fingers crossed, and go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There were more than 150,000 people at Churchill Downs, and only
one thought Aptitude should have won the Derby: Aptitude's trainer,
Bobby Frankel.
</P>
<P>
   Aptitude ran a terrific race to finish second at nearly 12-1,
beaten just a length and a half, but Fusaichi Pegasus was under a
hand ride, and to suggest he could have been beaten is laughable.
Frankel was miffed that rider Alex Solis came off the rail and let
Desormeaux and Fusaichi Pegasus through. However, that happened
just a half-mile into the race. What was Aptitude's excuse for the
rest of the journey, which brought him practically even with
Fusaichi Pegasus at one point in the stretch?
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong, Alex rode a good race,'' said Frankel.
``But Desormeaux took the gamble, and that was the difference of,
maybe, winning or losing. I'm not saying I would have beaten him. I
take my hat off to him. Desormeaux rode a great race, and Neil did
a great job with him. I feel real good for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Aptitude, a closer, will be held out of the Preakness, go back
to California to train, and point toward the Belmont Stakes June
10. ``He's fine,'' said Frankel. ``I'll just train him up to the
Belmont.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Deputy, whose future lies on the grass, was a major
disappointment, finishing 14th as the 9-2 second choice. He's going
back to California to race on grass, and will head for the Del Mar
Derby on the turf Sept. 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to give him a month to kick back,'' said trainer
Jenine Sahadi. ``His temperature was normal, and he scoped clean
after the race (no bleeding in the lungs). I don't have any
excuses. Maybe that last race (a win in the Santa Anita Derby April
15) took a little more out of him than we thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't look dead or wiped out. He didn't do any running.
He got a lot more dirt kicked in his face (Saturday). In his last
two races (including the San Felipe, when he ran second to Fusaichi
Pegasus March 19), there had been smaller fields.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most trouble in the Derby came when Wheelaway, at 20-1,
crossed over in front of Captain Steve, an 8-1 shot, and herded him
to the inside while the field was turning for home. Captain Steve,
who had just taken the lead at the quarter-pole, was completely
shut off. The incident didn't help either horse, as Wheelaway fell
back to finish fifth and Captain Steve faded to eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``My horse was running big at the five-16ths pole,'' said John
Kimmel, who trains Wheelaway. ``Richie (rider Richard Migliore)
called on him a little too hard a little too soon. Otherwise, we
might have gotten a solid third . . . The winner stamped himself as
exceptional. He made no mistakes and got the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Wheelaway (who had run third in the Blue Grass April
15) was just one performance short of a good effort. When I have
him ready, he'll really unleash a big one. He is going to be a
force in this division. He may not be up to Fusaichi Pegasus, and I
was also impressed with Aptitude's run, but it's a long year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting how the performance of Fusaichi Pegasus put the
word ``maybe'' on the lips of opposing trainers. Only powerhouse
trainers D. Wayne Lukas, who will send High Yield (15th in the
Derby), and Bob Baffert, who will send Captain Steve, would commit
to the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   Those who hedged were Todd Pletcher, who is considering sending
More Than Ready (fourth) and/or Impeachment (third); Kimmel, who is
pondering Wheelaway's future, and Hal Rose, the 88-year-old trainer
of Hal's Hope (16th). The rest of the Derby field appears headed
home.
</P>
<P>
   Of the new faces for the Preakness, Red Bullet, trained by Joe
Orseno, is a legitimate contender. He won the Gotham and ran very
well when second to Fusaichi Pegasus in the Wood Memorial, both run
at Aqueduct. Red Bullet, a son of Unbridled, did not race as a
2-year-old and was held out of the Derby to wait for the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   Also expected to give it a try are Snuck In (trained by Steve
Asmussen), who won the Rebel and was second in the Arkansas Derby,
and Kentucky Derby trial runner-up Sun Cat, trained by Lukas. It is
unlikely the Preakness field will number more than 10 . . . Derby
2000 established wagering records across the board. A total of
$9,726,912 was bet on-track; off-track wagering was $55,606,088.
Wagering on-track for the 10-race card was $19,967,162, while the
off-track handle was $81,386,383. The total for the race was
$65,333,000, and for the program $101,353,745.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-07-00 2355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
